<HEADLINE>
`OTHER GUY' LEADS CYCLONES PAST COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-OKLAHOMA STATE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Iowa State proved itself to be more than
Marcus Fizer and a cast of hangers-on with a 68-64 victory over
Oklahoma State during Saturday's semifinals of the Big 12 men's
basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Fizer, the league's Player of the Year and a 30-point scorer in
five of his past seven games, did not make a field goal in the
final 13:34 against Oklahoma State. Nor did he score a point during
the Cyclones' comeback from a four-point deficit in the waning
moments.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the biggest crunch-time contributions came from the
team's ``other'' forward. That would be Stevie Johnson, a senior
known for defense and rebounding. Johnson arrived Saturday in
Kemper Arena with the fewest attempts (5.3 per game) and lowest
scoring average (8.3) among the Cyclones' starters.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Johnson who scored nine of the Cyclones' last 11
points in helping Iowa State (28-4) erase a late 61-57 deficit and
earn a berth opposite Oklahoma (26-5) in Sunday's 2 p.m. title
game. With the victory, the Cyclones advanced to their first title
game in a postseason conference tournament since 1996, their final
year in the Big Eight.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's stretch run began with 2:20 remaining, when Oklahoma
State's Desmond Mason hacked Johnson and became the first of three
Cowboys' starters to foul out before the final buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Johnson responded in less-than-heroic fashion. He
missed his fifth consecutive free throw. But on his second attempt
after the Mason foul, Johnson hit nothing but net. He would not
miss again, converting consecutive three-point plays on the
Cyclones' next two possessions and sinking a pair of clinching free
throws with 17 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to talk about Marcus because of all his points,''
said Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy, referring to Fizer's
league-best scoring average (23.3). ``But Stevie is a special guy.
He does a lot of things that don't show up in the box score. He's
the heart and soul of our team, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamaal Tinsley, the Cyclones' point guard, said Johnson's
domination down the stretch ``shows people that we've got other
guys than just Marcus ... We're a true team. We don't need Marcus
to score 30 (points) every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Fizer had just 19 against the Cowboys. But he was
instrumental in drawing fouls on Oklahoma State's three inside
starters: Mason, Brian Montonati and Fredrik Jonzen. All three
fouled out in the final 2:20, as the Cowboys frittered away a 61-57
advantage. Their collective absence, said Cowboys guard Joe Adkins,
helped pave the way to the basket for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some younger guys were in and they didn't do what they were
supposed to do on defense. Anytime you have three front-court
players foul out, you're in trouble,'' Adkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were the Cowboys helped by a season-low shooting percentage
of 33.9. OSU missed 16 layups, including five by point guard Doug
Gottlieb.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's enough to get you beat, right there,'' said OSU coach
Eddie Sutton He complained after the game about a technical foul
assessed to the Cowboys' bench midway through the second half but
conceded the call had no bearing on his team blowing its 61-57
advantage over the final 2:20.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, crunch time belonged to Iowa State's ``other'' forward:
Stevie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I needed to redeem myself after missing all those
free throws early in the game,'' Johnson said. ``The opportunities
were there and I took advantage of them.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
