<HEADLINE>
STARS CENTER JOE NIEUWENDYK HOPES TO MAKE UP FOR LOST TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Hockey didn't exist for Joe Nieuwendyk. Not for long
stretches of this season.
</P>
<P>
   He simply couldn't allow himself to think about the game he
wasn't able to play.
</P>
<P>
   As January quickly faded into February, and the Stars began
playing like a legitimate Cup contender, Nieuwendyk instead passed
his time e-mailing friends and tracking his stocks online. He
didn't feel comfortable in his own locker room, coming for rehab
when no one was around and leaving before anyone could see him.
He'd go to Stars games, but he didn't stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get away,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``It's just hard because
you're not really a part of it, but you are.''
</P>
<P>
   A separated shoulder on Jan. 19 created this dichotomy. Doctors
told him another six to eight weeks loomed before he would play
again. So Nieuwendyk returned from that West Coast swing, retreated
to his house, and soaked in his disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   This, he thought, wasn't the way it was supposed to be. He was
coming off a Stanley Cup playoffs where he played maybe his best
stretch of hockey, and these next couple of years were supposed to
be his years. He had just signed a three-year, $15 million contract
extension, which, with the year he had remaining, could take him to
the end of his career. He's 33, and these next four years would
likely define his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   But time was running out on the first year.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled in October and into November and finally, just as
playing began to be fun again, he couldn't. He physically couldn't.
A rib injury sidelined him for 10 games. He played three before
separating his shoulder and missing another 21. He has missed as
many games this season (34) as he has played.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really understand what's so hard about not playing
until you are not playing,'' said Stars captain Derian Hatcher, who
missed 24 games with a lacerated calf. ``I think you get frustrated
and the best way to deal with that is try to get away. You just
have to come out of the first couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk emerged from his sabbatical. Swinging.
</P>
<P>
   He played on Friday, only his fourth game in the Stars' past 35.
He played 18-plus minutes, getting four shots, scoring one goal and
winning 61 percent of his faceoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happens when Nieuwendyk gets disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointment from missing the Stars' 1998 playoff run with
an injury turned Nieuwendyk into the player he was during last
season's Stanley Cup stretch. As a parting gift, he was awarded the
Conn Smythe Trophy as playoff MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, that's the player we need. Only we don't need it in
the playoffs. We need it now,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``If ever we've needed it, we need it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have spent the season putting fingers in the dykes.
Every time one is plugged, another busts open. They were awaiting
someone's return or for this group _ quite different from last
season's Cup team _ to jell in time for the playoffs. Now, with the
status of goalie Ed Belfour in doubt, the Stars are looking for
someone to plug that hole.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are hoping Nieuwendyk is that someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has he played, 30 games this year?'' Stars winger Jamie
Langenbrunner said. ``I think Joe plays well when he wants to play
well. Not that he turns it off and on. But when he gets focused and
wanting to play _ like he did last year in the playoffs _ where
he's focused to that goal, he can dominate play to a point where
you forget other people are on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A, Langenbrunner says, has to be an eight-week stretch
in the playoffs last season.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk had an NHL-leading 11 goals, including six
game-winners, with another 10 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Bryan Marchment? He, in some way, had something to do
with this.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk didn't make it through the first period of the first
game of the first round of the playoffs in 1998. Marchment made
sure of that when his hit from behind sent Nieuwendyk into the
Reunion Arena boards. He emerged with a season-ending tear to the
anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee _ his good knee.
</P>
<P>
   He went through the same withdrawal from hockey then.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't watch the playoffs. He didn't show up until the
third round, only to watch the Stars lose to the Detroit Red Wings
in the Western Conference Finals. He tried not to think about what
could have been during those long summer days in Dallas where he
stayed to rehab.
</P>
<P>
   But when he came back last year, you could tell he had thought
of nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mission,'' his teammates described him being on last season.
He sucked every ounce of marrow out of the playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think I really seized the opportunity,'' Nieuwendyk
said. ``It was a long time since I got that far in the postseason.
You just put all your heart and soul into it and you get rewarded
in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what made the beginning of this season so frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk didn't find the form he displayed on the way to the
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was just tough for him at the beginning of the year
to get that focus back,'' Langenbrunner said. ``He wasn't the only
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk couldn't accept that.
</P>
<P>
   The thinker in him went looking for reasons. He talked to
friends, a couple of teammates, but mostly he thought. That's what
thinkers do, sometimes to their own detriment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely got that from my mother, no doubt about it,''
Nieuwendyk said. ``A worrier and a thinker.''
</P>
<P>
   The worry now is: Did he leave himself enough time to make up
for the time that has been lost?
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said before,'' Nieuwendyk said, ``ultimately you get
judged on how you do in the end. That's what everybody is going to
write about when the season is over with. How did the Stars finish
up? Not how did they start.''
</P>
<P>
   As March quickly turns into April, and the Stars begin their
defense of the Cup, hockey once again exists for Nieuwendyk. Just
in time for the Stars, too.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
