<HEADLINE>
SPITTING OUT THE SEEDS WILL BE DIFFICULT TASK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ This is Illinois' schedule for today's Big Ten
Conference championship game:
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m. _ Wakeup. 10:30 a.m. _ Breakfast. 11 a.m. Walk through.
Noon _ Tape. 1 p.m. _ Bus leaves. 2:30 p.m. _ Play for
championship.
</P>
<P>
   That last entry has the NCAA Men's Tournament committee reaching
for the antacid pills. An Illinois upset of Michigan State today
would pose just another problem for the committee to solve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonkers. I think they're going absolutely bonkers,'' CBS
analyst Billy Packer said between Illinois' 94-84 semifinal victory
against upstart Penn State and Michigan State's 55-46 defeat of
Wisconsin. ``This will be by far the toughest tournament to select
and seed. I think the committee will have to make more subjective
selections than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee faces this question: Is Michigan State a No. 1
seed regardless of today's outcome? The committee might have to
prepare an ``A'' bracket (Michigan State wins, No. 1 seed), and a
``B'' bracket (if the Spartans lose). Had top-seeded Ohio State
reached the final against the Spartans, the committee could have
given the title game winner a No. 1 and the loser a No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it's just not that easy.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's deadline is 5:30 p.m. today when the 64-team
field is announced on CBS' national telecast. Sometimes in the
past, before the committee improved its organizational skills,
there was a mad dash to achieve a finished product. But never
before has there been so much doubt and uncertainty with the No. 1
seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my best guess: Duke is a the strongest lock to be a No. 1
seed, probably in the East. Michigan State, if it beats Illinois,
would be a No. 1 in the Midwest. Stanford is probably headed to the
No. 1 seed in the South, although a strong case could be made that
Temple deserves a top seed.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, which gained the Pacific-10 Conference's automatic bid
yesterday, probably deserves the top seed in the West. Loren Woods
has suffered from a bad back and might not play again this season.
The Wildcats are down to six scholarship players. Word out of
Tucson is that Arizona coach Lute Olson has imposed a news blackout
on Woods' status in order to protect his team's possible No. 1
seed.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati, with a 28-3 record, no doubt feels it deserves a No.
1 seed, but might not get it without player of the year Kenyon
Martin, who broke his leg during the Bearcats loss to Saint Louis
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Each committee has its own personality and philosophy. This
year's committee wants to select and seed the field based on how
teams play on Selection Sunday, and what specific teams can bring
to the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be more subjective than it's ever been,''
Packer said, noting the myriad of player injuries and suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12 Conference presents a similar problem. If Iowa State
follows its regular-season title with the tournament crown, the
Cyclones deserve top seed consideration. But, if Iowa State loses
to Oklahoma today, do the Cyclones fall to a No. 2? If so, does the
committee prepare a ``C'' bracket and a ``D'' bracket?
</P>
<P>
   Saint Louis' unexpected Conference USA championship means a team
not expected to make the field has an automatic bid. If Arkansas
wins the Southeastern Conference title today, there will be two
unexpected automatic bids in the field. That has teams like St.
Bonaventure, Missouri and Notre Dame listening to their stomachs
churn.
</P>
<P>
   Told that an Illinois victory today would probably send objects
flying around the basketball committee room, Illinois sophomore
guard Cory Bradford got a crooked, wicked little grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, man,'' he said. ``I guess we do sort of hold the key to
some things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
