<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREER IS WILLING TO HIT SECOND, BUT WOULD LIKE PERMANENT SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Manager Johnny Oates' main goal with his Texas
Rangers lineup is to get Rusty Greer, Rafael Palmeiro and Ivan
Rodriguez to the plate as often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   For Greer, that appears to mean batting second. That comes after
batting third for the past four years and after Oates flirted with
the idea this off-season of using him in the leadoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you know my attitude,'' Greer said. ``I've proven I
can hit third and I like hitting third. But if I'm best suited for
this team to hit second, I'll do that. If I'm best suited to hit
leadoff, I'll do that. It's just whatever Johnny thinks will help
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer's only request is to hit in one spot as often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a hitter you grow accustomed to one spot,'' Greer said.
``You feel comfortable doing that and not moving around. That's not
to say I can't be moved. Earlier in my career I was moved all over
the lineup. That doesn't matter. But as a hitter, if you had one
thing on your list, it would be a certain spot in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now Oates is using Royce Clayton as his leadoff hitter,
followed by Greer, Ivan Rodriguez and Rafael Palmeiro. Oates has
also talked about eventually moving Ruben Mateo to the No. 3 spot.
PITCHING ON MEND
</P>
<P>
   The latest on the Rangers' injured pitchers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Closer John Wetteland is over the strained calf muscle that
sidelined him for the first week of the exhibition season. The
Rangers are waiting for him to get over a strained groin muscle but
Johnny Oates said, ``we're not even close to being at the critical
stage. They tell me he's close to rejoining us.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rangers are encouraged by the progress pitcher Mike
Venafro (strained ligament of his left middle finger) has made the
past four days and think there's a chance he could get ready for
Opening Day. Trainer Danny Wheat said, ``I'm afraid to get excited
because it could go the opposite way just as quickly. But if he
continues to improve next week like he has this week, he's got a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rangers continue be excited about the progress of
left-hander Justin Thompson, who is coming off shoulder surgery.
General manager Doug Melvin said the first week of May is still the
target. Oates watched Thompson throw Friday and said,
``Mechanically, he looks flawless. It doesn't look like he's
favoring (the injured shoulder) at all.'' YOUNG PITCHERS DISAPPOINT
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates still isn't happy with what he's seeing with his
young pitchers. Jonathan Johnson, the Rangers' rapidly fading No. 1
pick from 1995, was particularly disappointing last night.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson took over in the eighth with a 5-2 lead and couldn't get
out of the inning. Instead, he gave up three runs and allowed the
Reds to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not getting anybody out,'' Oates said. ``He's up in the
strike zone and his curve ball is rolling around. He's not making
quality pitches around the knees. Everything is up at the belt.''
</P>
<P>
   R.A. Dickey, a first-round pick in 1996, got the Rangers out of
the eighth but gave up a game-winning home run in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our last four pitchers threw more pitches above the belt than
below the belt,'' Oates said, referring to Danny Kolb and Francisco
Cordero, as well. ``They can't pitch up. They've got to do
better.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Second baseman Edwin Diaz, trying to win a spot as a utility
infielder, had a double in three at-bats and is 5-for-12 on the
spring. He also made a nice catch on a pop-up in short center field
to save a run.
</P>
<P>
   _ Right fielder Jason McDonald, trying to win a job as a fifth
outfielder, threw out Sean Casey trying to stretch a single into a
double in the fifth. Said McDonald, ``I'm the type of player who
has to do the little things to have a chance to make this team.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Clark, Matt Perisho and Ryan Glynn are scheduled to pitch
against the Minnesota Twins on Sunday at Port Charlotte. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
