<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-FERNANDEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS BACKUP GOALIE MANNY FERNANDEZ TRIES TO SHORE UP CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Manny Fernandez's demons have never been a product of
his talent. Yet they terrorize his mind like a hurricane battering
the shoreline, ripping apart his confidence like fragile limbs of
trees trapped in the raging storm.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez's mind, not his ability, has served as his past
undoing in his previous stints with the Stars. The Stars' backup
goalie, unexpectedly thrust into the starting role by virtue of Ed
Belfour's arrest and ongoing evaluation, is desperately fighting an
internal struggle of mind over matter.
</P>
<P>
   The demons are still there, gnawing at the security he has built
this season as a quality backup. They are there in even greater
force now, emotionally whipping him since the Stars tied Vancouver
and lost in overtime on Friday to the lowly New York Islanders. The
loss was not solely his fault, they never are, but the demons have
always told him otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the confidence I built in the first part of the
season ... I need to get that back, I need to start thinking about
the good things that I did before and stop thinking about what
happened the last two games,'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys expect certain saves, and if something bad happens, I
can see I start panicking. So in a sense, I put a little bit on my
back, actually quite a lot, but it's the way I'm going to come out
of that. If I come out, I'm going to make myself a lot stronger. I
think it's going to be a good challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge of his brief NHL career begins at 2 p.m.
today when the Stars face the Western Conference-leading St. Louis
Blues. Just as one defensive breakdown can sabotage a goalie, he
knows one mental breakdown can doom the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take the mental aspect right now, I think I can play in
this league,'' Fernandez said. ``The thing is, I care for these
guys as much as anybody else and you don't want to let them down.
</P>
<P>
   He says that ``when a bad goal happens,'' he gets so upset,] ``I
seem to lose control for a couple minutes. I don't think I'm
helping the team as I am right now, so I better get my head on
straight and calm down out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, 25, finally recognizes his self-destructive patterns.
His success this season has worked as therapy. In 19 games, he has
a 2.06 goals-against average and .922 save percentage. Today, he
tries to snap a three-game winless streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manny's been at the top of the stats all year. His
goals-against, save percentage are right there. He's been
rock-solid,'' rookie Brad Lukowich said. ``I played with him in
Kalamazoo, he was our No. 1 there. I know he's capable of the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Belfour returns, coach Ken Hitchcock has no choice but to
trust in Fernandez. But, trust has never been an issue. Hitchcock
coached Fernandez on the team's minor-league affiliate and
continues to believe in his ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always go the extra mile for talent,'' Hitchcock said.
``Our focus is having Manny play well and play strong and that's
our primary focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Fernandez knows that is up to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing about not putting in 110 percent because I've
given everything I have,'' Fernandez said. ``A hockey game is one
thing to give all you've got, but it's another thing to just calm
down and play the game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
