<HEADLINE>
BELFOUR'S STATUS REMAINS UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN AND JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas Stars general manager Bob Gainey on Saturday spoke with
the doctor in charge of the substance-abuse program evaluating
Stars goalie Ed Belfour. Gainey said the evaluation is ongoing and
he hopes to have the program's final report and any recommendations
before the team leaves for New York after Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who play host to St. Louis on Sunday, open a
three-game road trip tomorrow against the New York Rangers. Gainey
said that ``I doubt he will be traveling with us tomorrow, but
nothing is firm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no final evaluation and no recommendations as
yet, but (the doctor) has given me an indication that I could
expect to hear something from him later in the day (Sunday) before
the team leaves town,'' Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   The league-sponsored substance-abuse program is evaluating
Belfour's actions from early Wednesday morning, when he was jailed
on misdemeanor charges of assault and resisting arrest. The police
report said Belfour was intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL requires that any player arrested in an incident
involving alcohol or drugs be evaluated by the substance-abuse
program so that it can recommend treatment for the player or action
by the team. A player cannot practice or play in games while under
evaluation. Gainey said Friday that Belfour would not face
suspension by the NHL or the team. HATCHER, HULL TO RETURN
</P>
<P>
   Not only will the Stars get winger Brett Hull back for Sunday's
game, captain Derian Hatcher also will return. They both missed
Friday's game against the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher thought he had a strained Achilles' tendon. An MRI
showed that he didn't, which is good news because it would've put
him out three weeks. He did have the fluid that had built up in his
Achilles' tendon drained. The time off definitely helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the best it's felt, and I'm really excited about it,
to be honest,'' Hatcher said. ``We know it's weak, but it's going
to be weak until next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull missed Friday's game with a hip flexor injury. Ken
Hitchcock said three days of a strenuous off-ice exercise program
designed to strengthen the muscle has paid off. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Winger Scott Thornton will be a game-time decision Sunday. He
is still feeling the effects of the flu, which forced him out of
Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Stars reassigned left winger Jamie Wright to their
minor-league affiliate, the Michigan K-Wings, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ ABC has decided to drop the Stars-Blackhawks game next
Saturday in Chicago as one of its regional telecasts. That leaves
no local television coverage of the game because of the network's
exclusivity during that three-hour window. The 2 p.m. game can be
heard on WBAP/820 AM.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
