<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-SIMMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMMS HOPING TO SHOW RANGERS HE CAN STILL RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ One at-bat consumes the thoughts of Rangers
outfielder Mike Simms.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch for that at-bat remains to be thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's with a week or 10 days left in spring training,'' Simms
said. ``I want to hit a long single, bust out of the box, slide
into second and get a double out of it. Then, I want to have some
guy smoke the next pitch right at an outfielder _ a one-hop base
hit _ and score from second and have people go: `Oh, wait a second.
He's running again. Look at that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Simms emerged as one of the Rangers' unheralded heroes from
their 1998 American League West championship season, but his health
deserted him throughout the 1999 season and leaves him battling for
a roster berth this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what those last two spots will be,'' manager
Johnny Oates said. ``We've got to have a backup catcher, a couple
of infielders and you know Chad Curtis is going to be on the team.
That leaves only a couple of spots. It just depends on what we
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates expects catcher Bill Haselman, infielder Frank Catalanotto
and outfielder Chad Curtis among those on his bench. Catalanotto,
though, cannot play shortstop, which likely presents a roster berth
for either Scott Sheldon or Edwin Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Simms and outfielder Jason McDonald as the most
likely candidates to earn that one available roster berth. The
Rangers, though, remain concerned about Simms' health.
</P>
<P>
   Simms suffered a partial tear of his left Achilles' tendon while
running during spring training a year ago. The injury limited him
to four September appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Achilles' is fine,'' Simms said. ``I don't even worry about
my Achilles'.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Simms struggles to run. His legs, hip, groin and muscles in
those areas make the process one of labor after a year of
inactivity. Simms signed a two-year contract before the 1999 season
that will pay him $1 million this year, but that will not play a
factor in whether he will be on the Opening Day roster, general
manager Doug Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers rewarded Simms with that contract after the
outfielder/first baseman hit .296 with 16 home runs and 46 runs
batted in as a reserve. Simms joined Eddie Robinson and Bob Thurman
as the only major-league players to hit as many 16 home runs with
fewer than 200 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show them that their faith in me from '98 did not go
all to waste,'' Simms said. ``I want to prove that they were right
and I was worth giving this contract. I don't want to glide
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Progress gives Simms reason for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do what I did today two weeks ago when camp
opened,'' Simms said. ``That's how far I've come in two weeks. I
think if I can progress that way over the next two weeks, then
hopefully that little dream I have will come true.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
