<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FLOYD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL, BLUES BETTER OFF WITHOUT EACH OTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The St. Louis Blues come in to Reunion Arena on Sunday with the
best record in the NHL. Former Blues winger Brett Hull comes in
with his first Stanley Cup ring won last season, his first with
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't have done it with each other.
</P>
<P>
   No typo there. Hull wasn't going to win a Cup in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Hull disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   OK, he doesn't exactly disagree. He just doesn't know whether
they would have or not. He certainly doesn't want to hazard a
guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to say,'' Hull said. ``Obviously not, because
we didn't while I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   The history suggests it wouldn't have happened if he had stayed.
It didn't in his 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The good-but-not-quite-good-enough Blues finally reached a
decision. The Golden Brett had to go. So, they didn't sign him. The
Stars did.
</P>
<P>
   Both organizations are better for it, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues' success has come with the younger group that Hull's
departure allowed them to develop and play. The Stars' Cup finally
happened when in triple overtime of Game 6 Hull banged a puck past
Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   As he pointed out the other day, who's to say if he had stayed
in St. Louis that the Cup-clinching goal wouldn't have come from
somebody else. If he had been playing for St. Louis, who's to say
the Blues wouldn't have beat the Stars in the second round of the
playoffs and he wouldn't have scored the Cup clincher for the
Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Hull doesn't believe in the wonderful world of what if. He
refuses to go there.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no question that both St. Louis and Hull are better
off without each other.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the Blues this season. This isn't Hull's team. They're
allowing something like a shot a game against them. They look like
the Stars' version of ``Mini-Me.'' The Blues that Hull played for
were just a bit more wide open, which, of course, is why everybody
wondered if Hull would fit in when he brought his game to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Hull has benefited from the split. Not only did he prove
that he was capable of winning the Cup, the one jewel in hockey
that he lacked. He also proved that he was capable of being a part
of the team and not ``the'' team.
</P>
<P>
   He has been able to do it because the Stars didn't need him to
be the team.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he had spent his entire career in St. Louis. He was
every bit as popular as other St. Louis sports icons like Ozzie
Smith. The way he played there made hockey fun. He was like
watching the highlight reel every night.
</P>
<P>
   And, if things happen as they're supposed to, he would've won
his Cup there. It's like Ray Bourque now. You basically spend your
entire career in one city amassing personal records and then move
to another town to win your Cup.
</P>
<P>
   So does Hull ever think about what it would've been like to win
his Cup with St. Louis?
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed my years in St. Louis and really loved playing there
and the people and the players,'' Hull said. ``But, you know what,
I'm not there anymore so I don't think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   What's to think about? Hull has his ring, and it appears as if
the Blues could get theirs.
BOURQUE FINALLY IN CUP CHASE
</P>
<P>
   Not seeing defenseman Ray Bourque in a Boston Bruins uniform is
like the president not living at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Just doesn't seem right, does it?
</P>
<P>
   Don't feel bad. Bourque said his first game in a Colorado
uniform since being traded to the Avalanche on Monday felt weird
for him too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down for a little nap just before I left for the game.
Seemed like once I woke up from the nap, it was really weird, it
was like reality: I was going to the rink and playing with another
club,'' Bourque said. ``Warm-up was probably the toughest part.
Seemed like I was just skating around, not really knowing what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of his 21 NHL seasons, Bourque has known exactly what to
do. He played for the Bruins. He was their best defenseman for
season after season. In none of those seasons did Bourque win a
Stanley Cup. He wasn't going to win one with them this season
either. The Bruins were already out of the playoffs. That fact led
to a coy conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said he didn't want to leave, but he might ...
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins said they didn't want to trade him, but they would
...
</P>
<P>
   And then as quickly as you can say rent a player, Bourque was on
a plane to Colorado in pursuit of the one thing he couldn't get in
Boston. This wasn't about money. This wasn't about playing time.
This was about doing the one thing in hockey he hadn't done. Just
the pursuit of the Cup has energized him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the biggest positive that's going to happen,''
Bourque said. ``I think it's a really exciting situation for me.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Avs played the Edmonton Oilers and won with
Bourque scoring two goals. The teams are battling for the best
record in the Northwest Division and the No. 3 seed in the playoffs
that is likely to come along with it. These are the types of games
that Bourque hadn't been playing a lot of lately in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   No, it doesn't seem right to see Bourque in anything except a
Bruins uniform. But, it sounds good. Bourque talks like a rookie
called up to the big club just before the playoffs when he talks
about his new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much talent here. I've never played with a team
that has as much talent up front as we have here,'' Bourque said.
``You could go up and down that lineup. There are so many guys that
are so talented. I think it's going to be real enjoyable to play
here.''
ROAD TO THE STANLEY CUP
</P>
<P>
   The start of the Stanley Cup playoffs is four weeks away. Here's
a look at who's who and what's what on the path there:
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S HOT
</P>
<P>
   Montreal: Going into last night's game, they have the seventh
seed in the East with 70 points. Despite being the most injured
team they're now a playoff team
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver's Alexander Mogilny: Entering last night's game, he
had scored goals in the Canucks' past five games. He has helped
edge the Canucks back into the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S NOT
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Coyotes: One point away from dropping to third in
the Pacific Division. Don't look now, but isn't that the LA Kings
knocking at the door?
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's Vincent Damphousse: Quiet like the rest of Sharks in
the second half. What happened to the guy we saw earlier in the
season?
</P>
<P>
   CUP FRONT-RUNNER
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Blues: OK, OK, so what happened to the part where
they were supposed to struggle at some point?
</P>
<P>
   CUP DARK HORSE
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Canadiens: OK, so they're a really long shot, but
just getting to the playoffs proves they're made of something.
</P>
<P>
   THE TOP 3
</P>
<P>
   The top three reasons to expect something big to happen between
now and Tuesday's NHL trade deadline:
</P>
<P>
   3. The Red Wings haven't done anything yet. And you know they're
going to do something.
</P>
<P>
   2. The St. Louis Blues still don't have depth on the blue line,
and they don't want to go into the playoffs without it.
</P>
<P>
   1. Don't the Philadelphia Flyers still need a goalie?
</P>
<P>
   HE SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, we have to be pleased where we are right
now considering the number of injuries this year. If we go on all
of our cylinders, we'll be a tough team to beat. I think our game
is pretty solid all the way through right now.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dallas Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk nn
</P>
</TEXT>
