<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-BUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE GEORGE W. HIGH MARKS FOR BEING A GOOD GUY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Reeves, known to be a proud Democrat, dancer, shuffleboard
shooter, horseman and sports-page columnist, was having a chat one
day last summer with a high-level politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you think I'm doing?'' asked George W. Bush, referring
to the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just fine,'' answered Revo. ``Just be yourself, and that will
be good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, this is extremely scary: the thought of one of us
giving advice to a man who could be president of the United States.
Molly Ivins, a newspaper hero of mine, is also sure to pounce on
that point about George W seeking an opinion from a what? A
sportswriter? Molly may never stop laughing, or drilling ``Shrub.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Revo also couldn't tell you the name of four world
leaders, he would serve, if asked, as Bush's running mate. Another
scary thought.
</P>
<P>
   Political affiliation aside, George W is still George W to any
local sports media rodents who covered the Rangers during the
baseball phase of Bush's life (1989-94). As the ownership frontman,
or managing general partner, of the Rangers, there was nothing
unusual about George W's relationship with us, meaning plenty of
disagreements and anger surfaced at times. But, along the way, a
case of trust developed, then something else. The very area that
Bush currently scores lowest in the political polls _ likability _
I'd say he topped out at 100 percent with any of us.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 or so local sportswriters (beat writers and
columnists) who dealt almost daily with Bush on baseball, the guess
is that at least eight tend to vote Democratic. But I don't know of
one who to this day doesn't label Bush as a ``good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that make for a good president? I doubt it, but it is
ironic that with Bush and Al Gore headed for a November showdown,
the political analysts keep coming back to how Bush is being
perceived, personalitywise.
</P>
<P>
   What does that little bemused smile mean? Is that arrogance? Is
he being snide?
</P>
<P>
   We saw the same thing, but it meant something different to us.
That smile came before he would nail you on a disputed baseball
point. Or after you had just nailed him. That smile was good.
</P>
<P>
   One day in the early '90s, Bush and his fellow owners announced
``The Ballpark in Arlington'' would be the name of the dream yard
being built just south of old Arlington Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and fellow owners Rusty Rose and Tom Schieffer walked into
the press box that night and Bush said, ``OK, how do the geniuses
like the new name?''
</P>
<P>
   Some did, some didn't. I was in the ``didn't'' category. ``OK,
Galloway,'' said Bush, briskly, ``exactly what would you have named
it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann Richards Field,'' came the reply. And Bush laughed the
loudest. He had, of course, just announced he was running for
governor against the popular Richards.
</P>
<P>
   George W truly liked the give-and-take game with the media. Now,
however, it's on a much bigger scale, against the heavyweights in
the national political media. The stakes are a tad higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, there's no doubt the baseball part of George's life was
great preparation for the governor's race, and now for all this,''
said Schieffer, who replaced Bush as managing general partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so much like holding public office. You have to develop
a public trust and there is the constant media pressure. It's
certainly not in the same league as being president, but it gives
you a taste of it. And George handled it well.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer also remembers the rocky start in 1989, beginning with
the media. Several different groups were bidding to buy the team
from Eddie Chiles, including one of Chiles' partners, Edward
Gaylord, who was the media's choice. But the commissioner's office
awarded the buying rights to the Bush group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a general feeling of maybe George didn't deserve to
be an owner of the Rangers,'' said Schieffer, ``and that he was
nothing but a rich kid with a powerful daddy who made it happen. A
wariness from the media was evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as everyone got to know George, and dealt with him, that
did change. By the time he left to be governor, we all could see
George had been accepted by the media as being a genuine person who
loved baseball. Anyone who gets to know George will say he's a good
guy, and I think that will eventually come across nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   This column was not meant to be political commentary. I leave
that to Molly. It's just that there's some pride involved, seeing
George W in the national arena with the media, knowing it was some
of us who once hammered at him on such things as, ahem, deficit
spending.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, that idea of Revo for veep has some appeal, don't
you think? {Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.}
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
