<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-IOWA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA STATE ROLLS PAST TEXAS TO WIN BIG 12 CROWN
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-TEXAS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A night of scattershooting ended Texas'
improbable journey one step short of a championship at the Big 12
women's basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Longhorns, who rarely found an open jumper they
couldn't make while knocking off two teams that shared the
regular-season title during the early rounds of the tournament,
could not extend that streak Saturday night against top-seed Iowa
State. The Cyclones' zone defense put the brakes on Texas' zone
busters, 75-65, at Municipal Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Texas turned in its worst shooting half in more than a month,
connecting on just 25.6 percent of its attempts before
intermission, and never recovered. It proved to be the Longhorns'
poorest shooting stretch since connecting on 24.1 percent in the
first half of a 73-44 loss at Texas Tech on Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Longhorns began finding the range in the waning
minutes, they found themselves down by as many as 24 points in the
second half and were behind, 74-54, when Iowa State coach Bill
Fennelly pulled his starters en masse with 1:48 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the victory, the Cyclones (25-5) earned the
league's automatic berth in the NCAA Tournament. Texas (21-12), an
NCAA bubble team when the week began, will meet today with
expectations of being selected as an at-large team when the 64-team
women's bracket is announced at 4 p.m. on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played hard, but a better team won,'' said Texas coach Jody
Conradt, whose team played its fourth game in five nights. ``I'm
sure our legs were a little tired and that may have come into play
on some of the easy shots we missed. But that's not the reason we
lost. Their zone defense threw us off-stride. They shot the ball
well and we didn't. That's the reason we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Cyclones connected on 50.9 percent, including 59.3
percent during a second half in which Iowa State stretched a
10-point halftime lead to 74-50 behind the inside work of center
Angie Welle (17 points, 10 rebounds) and forward Desiree Francis
(19 points, 5 rebounds). Arguably, Welle and Francis did their best
work on the defensive end, keeping the clamps on Texas' leading
scorer, Edwina Brown, until the outcome was decided.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who finished with a game-high 23 points, connected on
just 2-of-13 shots in the first half. She scored 15 of her points
in the final seven minuts, when Iowa State was busy protecting a
20-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make her do everything off standstill jump
shots,'' said Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly. ``We tried not to let
her drive to the basket. I think we did a good job of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the tournament's most valuable player, mirrored her
team's 36-percent shooting night (9-of-25). She termed the outcome
``frustrating'' because the Longhorns fell short in their quest to
knock off all three league tri-champs in consecutive nights.
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas forward Edwina Brown was selected as the most valuable
player of the Big 12 women's tournament. Brown finished four games
with 88 points, 42 rebounds, 27 assists and 11 steals.
</P>
<P>
   _ The women's championship game drew a crowd of 9,130, a
single-session record for the Big 12 tournament. Big 12 officials
said all tickets were sold and the turnstile count reflected 570
no-shows.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
