<SLUG> BC-BKC-SELECTION-SUNDAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST EXCITING DAY IN SPORTS? INCLUDE SELECTION SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seventh game of the World Series. Sunday at the Masters.
Churchill Downs on the first Saturday in May. A heavyweight fight
at Caesar's Palace in Las Vegas. The NCAA Tournament's Final Four
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   All are worthy candidates for the best day in sports, a moment
in time where the palms sweat, the skin tingles and the heart races
with excitement and anticipation. It's why we're sports fans.
</P>
<P>
   All of the scenes mentioned above are fit for mental snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   But the following is submitted as evidence that today is one of
the most entertaining and exciting days in sports. This argument is
made even though this event isn't a competition.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 p.m., from a hotel room in Indianapolis, the NCAA will
announce its 2000 men's tournament bracket. From hoop heads to the
casual fan, it's a 30-minute made-for-TV production that has more
drama and excitement than the average mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a finite announcement,'' said Mountain West Conference
commissioner Craig Thompson, chairman of the NCAA men's basketball
tournament committee. ``The first everybody hears about the bracket
and the selections is when the announcement is made on CBS. In
essence, the entire college basketball world is tuned in and
waiting to hear what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It says here that staring at a blank, pristine NCAA Tournament
bracket can be an exhilarating experience. The opportunity to fill
in the blanks with 64 teams is an annual rite of spring. The
anticipation of who's in, who's out and who plays who provides the
same tingles that come seconds before tipoff for the championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget the Kentucky Derby, this is the most exciting two
minutes in sports,'' said Steve Weiberg, ``USA Today's'' college
writer, referring to the time it takes to scan a filled-in bracket.
``TV stretches it to 30 minutes. I don't think there's anything
else in sports where you have all the discussion and speculation
leading up to something _ who's in, who's out. There is nothing
like the week leading up to Selection Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the excitement from two areas _ who makes the field,
who doesn't and then who's playing who, which teams got sent
where.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, maybe the excitement of Bracket Day has been
overdramatized by television. ESPN's saturated coverage of college
basketball has heightened interest in the sport. In 1982, when CBS
gained the rights to the NCAA Tournament, it started televising a
selection show.
</P>
<P>
   CBS analyst Billy Packer remembers when he was working for NBC,
which televised the NCAA Tournament before CBS took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing a game in 1979 at the end of the season,'' he
recalled. ``Dick Enberg said, `Hey, let's call and find out who's
in the tournament.' During the course of the game, Al McGuire was
saying, `Well, so and so got in and this team didn't.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went over to CBS, I told them that we could make a show
out of the bracket announcement. It's really taken on a life of its
own.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's another reason why Bracket Day has its own brand of
excitement. Once all 64 teams are assigned their lines, it's time
to start playing What If. ``Hey, what if Indiana and Duke make the
regional final, it'll be Knight against Krzyzewski. Wow, do you
think Princeton might be able to beat UCLA? Hmmmmm, Rhode Island's
guards might gave Kansas some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a year, you know it's coming and you spend weeks trying to
figure it out ahead of time,'' said Blair Kerkhoff, who covers
college sports for the ``Kansas City Star''. ``And yet, when it
happens, there's drama, you're still intrigued and surprised. After
you've scribbled all the teams down, you really have to catch your
breath and try to figure out what it all means.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since 1985, when the field expanded to 64 teams, the NCAA
bracket sings with symmetry. No messy first-round byes. Just four
regions of 16 teams, sub-divided in eight first-round sites. Win
two games the first weekend, two games the second and two at the
Final Four and you're a national champion.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country this afternoon, Blue Devils from Duke and
Central Connecticut State, Bulldogs from Butler to Fresno State
will gather to wait and watch the 2000 NCAA Tournament bracket
appear on their television sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day the bracket comes out is an exciting time if you're
having a good year,'' said Big 12 director of basketball operations
Kim Anderson. ``If you know you're in, you've got the excitement of
where you're assigned, who you'll play, who else is in your region.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a bubble team, it can be jubilation or devastation.
You're sitting there waiting to see your name called. It can be
bittersweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, bittersweet. We like that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
