<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4489 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-BUZZER-BEATERS-TE     03-12 1635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BUZZER-BEATERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NCAA TOURNAMENT, FINAL SHOTS CAN LEAVE LASTING IMPRESSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five. Four. Three. Two. One. Swishhhhh.
</P>
<P>
   It is a scene that is played out every day throughout America.
For almost any kid who takes a basketball to the neighborhood
playground, the dream of the last-second shot to win the national
title is a constant.
</P>
<P>
   The buzzer-beater has become the signature of a tournament that
has become the signature of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you envision is catching the ball out on the
perimeter and making a shot like that,'' former North Carolina
State player Lorenzo Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles is living proof that the shot that beats the buzzer in
an NCAA Tournament game can come from anywhere and in any fashion.
With Charles, it was a rebound and follow of a missed shot. But
they can be set up by a length-of-the-floor pass or a layup
following a length-of-the-floor dribble.
</P>
<P>
   Though such heroics sometimes are the result of well-designed
and practiced plays, the number of ways to produce a last-second
shot are limitless.
</P>
<P>
   From Charles' putback at the buzzer for N.C. State to Ulyesses
Reed's halfcourt shot that defeated Louisville, there's no formula
for game-winning heroics. Below are some of the most memorable:
A CHRISTIAN PRAYER
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Christian Laettner against Kentucky in the 1992 East
Regional final at The Spectrum in Philadelphia. It's the
buzzer-beater that everyone remembers.
</P>
<P>
   And here are a few things that should not be forgotten:
</P>
<P>
   _ Grant Hill threw the inbounds pass from his own baseline
three-quarters of the length of the floor. No one was guarding him,
double-teaming Laettner instead, a decision that invited media
debate toward Kentucky coach Rick Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   _ The game was so emotional that forward Thomas Hill cried
uncontrollably on the court after Laettner's shot. Thomas Hill
played for the winning Duke team.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laettner was the ``perfect'' person to get the ball for the
final shot. He finished the game 10-for-10 from the field and
10-for-10 from the free-throw line. THE GARBAGE MAN
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzo Charles was an unlikely person to make the final shot
for North Carolina State in the 1983 national championship game
against Houston at Albuquerque, N.M. His job on the team was to
gather loose balls and missed shots around the basket _ ``garbage''
_ and put it back in.
</P>
<P>
   If any tall man was going to standout in this game, it figured
to be Houston's Hakeem Olajuwon or Clyde Drexler _ who, while not
being big, jumped as if he were. Charles would never match the
future stardom of Houston's ``Phi Slamma Jamma,'' but his moment of
fame arrived when NC State guard Dereck Whittenburg's desperation
shot was an air ball.
</P>
<P>
   Charles snatched the ball in the air short of the basket, while
Olajuwon watched almost flat-footed, and jammed the ball through
the hoop to seal the title as time expired and Wolfpack coach Jim
Valvano ran, stunned, back and forth across the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job on the team that year was as a role player,'' Charles
said. ``My job was to bang the boards and put missed shots back in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach V \RJim Valvano\S had diagrammed a play for one of the
perimeter players to penetrate to try to force Hakeem or one of
their big guys to commit,'' Charles said. ``I was battling for
position'' underneath the basket.
</P>
<P>
   It was a battle he would lose. Someone _ Charles doesn't
remember who _ pushed him underneath the basket. It turned out to
be incredible luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing directly beneath the basket, and I could see
the ball was going to be short,'' Charles said. ``I saw the ball
better than anybody else. If Hakeem \ROlajuwon\S had the angle I
had, he wouldn't have been standing there.'' FATHER AND SON
</P>
<P>
   Indiana has Bobby Knight and the Hoosiers. Purdue. Notre Dame.
Even the legend of Larry Bird. And then there's tiny Valparaiso.
</P>
<P>
   The Crusaders lack tradition and power. But they made up for it
with possibly the craftiest buzzer-beater in NCAA Tournament
history. It was a play named ``Pacer'' designed by a father _ Valpo
coach Homer Drew _ for his son _ guard Bryce Drew.
</P>
<P>
   The Crusaders trailed by two points with less than five seconds
on the clock in an opening-round game against Mississippi in 1998.
The ball went inbounds to a Crusaders player, and Bryce Drew cut to
the ball. When he received it, he made a running 3-point shot at
the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't lead to a national title. Valpo was eliminated after
advancing to the Sweet 16. But it allowed Valparaiso to join its
bigger Indiana brothers in NCAA Tournament lore. LENGTH OF THE
COURT, I
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if Brigham Young's Danny Ainge was about to have a
streak of 110 consecutive games of double-figure scoring come to an
end in a second-round game in 1981. Finally, late in the second
half against Notre Dame, he scored his 10th point.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cougars trailed 50-49 with less than 10 seconds
remaining when the Irish's Kelly Tripucka scored on a jump shot.
Ainge took the inbounds pass and hurriedly worked it down the floor
without passing to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge first took the ball past John Paxson, who had guarded him
so well for most of the game. Ainge switched hands and cut across
midcourt. He slid through Tripucka and Tom Sluby. He went around
Tim Andree and finally reached the lane where Orlando Woolridge was
waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up at least 6 inches in height, Ainge still was able to
get the shot off and over Woolridge's outstretched arm. It went in
with 2 seconds left, and time expired with a 51-50 BYU victory.
LENGTH OF THE COURT, II
</P>
<P>
   This was almost like Ainge revisited. But this was a game that
would send one team to the Final Four in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA was a first-round failure earlier in the decade with losses
against Penn State and Tulsa. And Missouri was ahead by a point
with 4.2 seconds remaining in a second-round game in the West
Region.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins inbounded the ball to Tyus Edney. At not even
5-foot-11, Edney drove downcourt. He went into the heart of the
Missouri defense and scored on a falling, off-balance jump shot
over Mizzou interior defenders near the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did UCLA advance to the Final Four, the Bruins won the
championship. HALFCOURT, U.S. STYLE
</P>
<P>
   The days of accurate outside shooters such as Sidney Moncrief,
Ron Brewer and Marvin Delph were over at Arkansas by 1981. In their
place was U.S. Reed and Darrell Walker, who led the Razorbacks into
the second round against defending champion Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had won 19 of 20 games heading into the tournament
and had four starters back from the national championship team. And
they led Arkansas 73-72 with 5 seconds left after Derek Smith's
fall-away jumper.
</P>
<P>
   The best shot Arkansas could get off was one from past the
midcourt line. Reed took it, and it went in at the buzzer. Arkansas
won 74-73 (it was the days before the 3-point shot).
</P>
<P>
   Though an improbable shot, this was nothing new for Reed. He had
made a similar shot from near halfcourt against Texas earlier in
the season. TWICE IS NICE
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 tournament game pitting Syracuse against Georgia, the
Orangemen needed two buzzer-beaters to keep moving toward the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   Their first one came when Jason Cipolla nailed a shot from the
corner at the buzzer to send the game into overtime. But the Orange
didn't finish this one off until John Wallace put down a 3-pointer
at the buzzer of the extra period for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse and coach Jim Boeheim advanced to the championship game
before losing to Kentucky. BEFORE THERE WAS LAETTNER
</P>
<P>
   UConn used to be the Boston Red Sox of college basketball. Make
the playoffs, then fold.
</P>
<P>
   Things were going swimmingly in 1990 when the Huskies reached
the Sweet 16. It looked even better when things went UConn's way
against Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   UConn trailed by 2 points to the Tigers with 1 second on the
clock. Scott Burrell threw a length-of-the-floor pass to Tate
George, who nailed a 3-pointer to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies turned back into the Red Sox in their next game,
losing to Duke in the East Regional final when Christian Laettner
hit a last-second shot for the victory. RO BEFORE DALLAS
</P>
<P>
   Before the Dallas Mavericks stockpiled all those first-round
draft picks in trades with the Cleveland Cavaliers, Rolando
Blackman was a star at Kansas State. Maybe the shot he made in the
second round of the 1981 NCAA Tournament caught the Mavs' eye, and
that was the reason Dallas eventually drafted Blackman with their
second first-round pick of the upcoming draft (Dallas took Mark
Aguirre with the first choice).
</P>
<P>
   K-State was the ninth seed in the West Region playing top-seeded
Oregon State. The Wildcats were behind the entire game until Ed
Nealy drew the fifth foul against OSU's Steve Johnson. Nealy made
both free throws to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State missed a free throw on the other end, and the
Wildcats got the ball to Blackman, who madea 16-foot jump shot at
the buzzer to give K-State a 50-48 victory. WHERE'S ESPN WHEN YOUR
NEED IT?
</P>
<P>
   Though many buzzer-beaters have been caught live by telecasts,
there's at least one notable buzzer-beater in the era before
constant TV. In 1962, no tournament games were covered live. The
final game was shown ``condensed'' in same-day coverage on ABC's
``Wide World of Sports.''
</P>
<P>
   So not many people saw a Final Four semifinal game between UCLA
and Cincinnati. The Bruins blew a 20-point lead and lost the game
when Cincinnati's Tom Thacker put up a line-drive outside shot that
won the game at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati went on to win the title game over an Ohio State team
that was without an injured Jerry Lucas, but still had John
Havlicek and Bobby Knight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 0059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4490 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     03-12 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ONE NIGHT, ALL WAS RIGHT AT REUNION ARENA ONCE MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For one night, Reunion Arena was rowdy again.
</P>
<P>
   Rolando Blackman, this was your life.
</P>
<P>
   As his number ``22'' was raised to the rafters Saturday night,
Blackman wanted to thank them all, which was so typically Ro
Blackman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make it here alone,'' said the man whose style and
smile were the Dallas Mavericks' beacon for 12 seasons from
1981-92. ``I had help all along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   To honor Blackman and retire his jersey, the franchise had
staged a nostalgic reunion. There was former coach Dick Motta,
whose wisdom seems to grow with each passing losing season. There
was the original owner, Donald Carter, who had the selfless
patience to let the basketball people run the show.
</P>
<P>
   There was Norm Sonju who, as general manager, helped build what
was once, yes, a model NBA franchise.
</P>
<P>
   And there were the old Mavericks themselves _ Mark Aguirre,
Derek Harper, Brad Davis, James Donaldson, Tom LaGarde, Scott Lloyd
and Randy White.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best of times,'' said Donaldson, who still plays
professionally in Grenada, Spain. ``I have carried these memories
of Dallas throughout the years. We had something special here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a classy, 20-minute ceremony, during which Blackman was
presented with gifts that ranged from a bag of Hogan golf clubs to
a Kawasaki motorcycle. The NBA, represented by Hall of Famer Bob
Lanier, presented Blackman with a $10,000 donation in his name to
the Children's Medical Center of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   To his wife Tamara, a local grocer presented a $1,000 shopping
spree. Blackman's children received passes entitling them to free
Big Macs and Slurpees for one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved this,'' Aguirre said after the halftime ceremony. ``I
loved every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was smooth _ about as smooth as Ro.''
</P>
<P>
   In a somewhat stunning coincidence _ some might say it was
simply the karma of the night _ the current-day Mavericks held off
the Phoenix Suns to win, 104-99, as Erick Strickland put on a
Blackman-like shooting spree and tallied 36 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they won the game,'' Blackman said, ever gracious.
``It helped make the night special.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no. To longtime Mavericks fans, the walk down
Memory Lane had to be depressing. Donaldson, let me suggest, is
still the best center that the franchise has ever had. The three
guards _ Blackman, Harper and Davis _ helped carry the team to 55
victories in 1986-87 and regularly challenged the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   New owner Mark Cuban told the crowd, announced as a sellout,
that he remembered coming to watch the 1980s Mavericks and sitting
in the $5 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were an inspiration to us then, and you're an inspiration
now,'' Cuban told Blackman. ``I was a fan then, and I'm a fan now.
We will honor you forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Motta told a story about the first time that he saw Blackman
play. He drove from Kansas City to Manhattan, Kan., in a snowstorm
to watch Ro's Kansas State team play Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me this guy could really shoot,'' Motta recalled.
``They won by 18 points, and he took one shot. But there was
something about the gleam in his eye and the way he moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever he walked out of that tunnel, I knew what I was going
to get. Ro was the epitome of consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Over 11 seasons with the Mavericks, Blackman averaged 19.2
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that anybody would argue that he has been just a
tremendous person, on and off the basketball court,'' his old
backcourt mate, Harper, said. ``Ro is one of those guys that you
pick as someone you would want your son to be like.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said what he remembers most about Blackman was his
eternally positive spirit. ``He was always up, always optimistic,''
Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Reunion replay board, a tape of Blackman highlights
scrolled by. The memories, the cheers, the Reunion rowdiness,
seemed such a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Cuban jokes with me and says that he has a plan to get
everything back, and that the new guys are going to put the '80s to
shame,'' Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuban's dreams, perhaps. But whatever happens, Blackman's No.
22, now high in the rafters, will serve as a reminder. Once upon a
time, it reminds, this was a proud franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Like the old song, they made Reunion Arena really want to shout.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
