<HEADLINE>
FINLEY 3-POINTER LIFTS MAVERICKS PAST SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CALVIN WATKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Michael Finley made a 3-point basket and for a change,
Reunion Arena became real loud.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when the fifth sellout crowd of the season _ 18,187 _
was here to celebrate the retiring of Rolando Blackman's jersey, it
was two current Mavericks players stealing some cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Finley's crucial 3-pointer and Erick Strickland's career-high 36
points led the Mavericks to a 104-99 victory against Phoenix on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended a season-high six-game losing streak for the
Mavericks. And it couldn't have come at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise honored Blackman at halftime by lifting his
jersey, No. 22, to the rafters in a moving halftime ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally inspired by Rolando when I went to his dinner
(Friday night),'' said Strickland, who made 11 of 19 field-goal
attempts. ``I just watched. It kinda broke me down to see how he
came through in this league. It gave me a newfound focus.''
</P>
<P>
   In a closely played fourth quarter, the Mavericks were able to
overcome four missed free throws in a 20-second span as they led
102-99.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how we won this one,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson
said.
</P>
<P>
   They won it despite shooting 41 percent from the field and
having their two main scorers, Finley and Dirk Nowitzki, shoot a
combined 12-for-27 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   But Finley provided the big 3-pointer when needed.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 99-99, Strickland missed a 15-foot jumper.
But Nowitzki grabbed the offensive rebound and found Finley
unguarded at the 3-point arc. He nailed the shot to give the
Mavericks a 102-99 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we rode Strickland on offense and
(Shawn) Bradley on defense,'' Nelson said. ``We played as hard as
we could. I don't think we played very well offensively, we
sputtered again, but it was one of those games that it really
didn't seem to matter.''
</P>
<P>
   After Finley's basket, both he and Strickland each missed two
free throws on consecutive possessions.
</P>
<P>
   But when Greg Buckner blocked a 3-point shot from Anfernee
Hardaway, the Suns were forced to foul, and this time Finley made
two free throws with 6.6 seconds left to seal the victory. CEBALLOS
PLAYS
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks forward Cedric Ceballos didn't start but did play
despite a broken pinkie on his left hand. Ceballos scored 11 points
in 31 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos was listed as questionable before the game. He has
missed only four games this season because of the flu or the finger
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke it in two places,'' Ceballos said after the game. ``I
have a bone that's floating in there and its also cracked right
down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos said he broke his pinkie about six weeks ago and has
been playing in pain. But a pass from Steve Nash in a game last
week made the pinkie worse.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos said he's not sure if he will need surgery after the
season. BRADLEY IS ALL-TIME SHOT BLOCKER
</P>
<P>
   With his five blocked shots Saturday night, Mavericks center
Shawn Bradley became the team's all-time leading shot blocker with
616 blocks. He surpassed James Donaldson's mark of 615. GUGLIOTTA
OUT FOR SEASON
</P>
<P>
   The Suns lost forward Tom Gugliotta for the season when he
injured his left knee in Friday night's loss to Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta had complete ruptures of the anterior cruciate
ligament and the medial collateral ligament and damage to the
meniscal attachment.
</P>
<P>
   For the season, Gugliotta averaged 13.7 points and 7.9 rebounds
per game. nn
</P>
