r s BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-T     03-12 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FORCING REALIGNMENT FOR 2002
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite winning three American League West titles in four years,
despite having the AL MVP three of the past four years, the Rangers
barely create a blip on the national radar.
</P>
<P>
   Rare is a Rangers game that is televised nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Rarer still is a member of the national media making an
appearance at the Rangers' spring-training camp. Many make the trek
to Sarasota, Fla., and Fort Myers for the obligatory Ken Griffey
Jr. and Pedro Martinez stories, but apparently few realize the
Toledo Blade Boulevard exit, about halfway between the two cities
on Interstate 75, would lead them to Port Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than five weeks, though, the Rangers will
command the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's owners meet in Houston on April 18, and are almost
certain to approve a realignment plan for the 2001 season that will
clear the way for an unbalanced schedule to allow teams to play
more games against divisional foes.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force behind realignment is the local major-league
baseball club.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, baseball doesn't need to realign to implement an
unbalanced schedule. Morally, though, it must.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were put at a geographical disadvantage in 1994,
when the expansion Florida Marlins and Colorado Rockies entered the
majors and the sport realigned. The AL West went from a seven-team
division that included the Chicago White Sox, Kansas City Royals
and Minnesota Twins, to a four-team division with the Rangers,
California (now Anaheim) Angels, Oakland Athletics and Seattle
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rangers president Tom Schieffer lobbied hard to move the
Rangers out of the division, logically arguing that when an
unbalanced schedule was implemented the club would be damaged
financially. The number of late-night games on the West Coast, two
time zones away, would mean lower TV and radio ratings, and thus
lower broadcast-rights fees.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer was promised the Rangers would be moved, but it didn't
happen when the Arizona Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay Devil Rays
necessitated realignment when they joined the majors in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's time to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we can get to an unbalanced schedule is to
resolve the problem of the Texas Rangers,'' said Boston Red Sox
chief executive officer John Harrington, chairman of the
schedule-format committee.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers will move to the AL Central, with the
Diamondbacks replacing them in the AL West by moving from the NL
West. To keep the current 16-14 breakdown, Tampa Bay goes to the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks owner Jerry Colangelo doesn't want to change
leagues because he fears the financial repercussions. Fan surveys
have shown the paying customers prefer the Senior Circuit. But he
has no choice. Arizona and Tampa Bay both agreed when they were
awarded franchises that they could be moved without their
permission.
</P>
<P>
   Some elements remain to be worked out. Commissioner Bud Selig
said the eventual realignment may contain ``some surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise, though, already has been revealed. The
oft-ignored Rangers are the engine powering the whole thing.
SPOTLIGHT ON: DOC GOODEN
</P>
<P>
   Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker was trying to explain how
his team could trade 22-game winner Mike Hampton and still have a
solid rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds, he said, is as solid as any pitcher in baseball.
It's no fluke that Jose Lima won 21 games last year. Scott Elarton
has ace-type stuff. Chris Holt is more than a year removed from
shoulder surgery and should be much better.
</P>
<P>
   And the fifth starter?
</P>
<P>
   ``Doc Gooden is our sleeper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden indeed was a sleeper going into camp. He signed a
minor-league contract after going 3-4 with a 6.26 earned-run
average for the Indians last season.
</P>
<P>
   But after giving up only four hits and three runs in his first
seven spring innings, he might be emerging from his hibernation. He
retired the first 12 batters he faced, but the Dodgers got to him
for three runs in three innings Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's written him off, and at age 35 he hasn't shown much
to suggest there's a whole lot there,'' Hunsicker said. ``But
knowing Doc, seeing the shape that he's come into camp, knowing the
competitive fire is still there and knowing that he's fighting for
a job and maybe his career, I like those kind of intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking him to come in here and be the ace and win 15
games. We're asking him to be the fifth starter and win eight to 10
games, and I think that's doable.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, manager Larry Dierker is asking a bit more. He
realizes Gooden isn't the same pitcher who looked like a future
Hall of Famer when he went 24-4 with a 1.53 ERA for the Mets in
1985, his second season in the majors. But he challenged Gooden not
to be content to be the No. 5 starter, but to be the No. 3 guy
behind Reynolds and Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what he's accomplished in his career, we know he's not
going to go out and get shook up,'' Dierker said. ``He's been a
starter all of his career, so we know he's going to have some
poise.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely accept the challenge,'' he said. ``I feel good,
and the shoulder feels fine, so it should work out.''
WELCOME TO DEION
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Sean Casey became a Deion Sanders fan the first
day the former Cowboys cornerback arrived at the Reds' camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion's great,'' Casey said. ``He brings instant respect as
soon as he walks into the clubhouse, but also he's just a great
guy. His humility and his faith in God really shows in the way he
carries himself in his life. He's a special person.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a different person than Casey expected, given Sanders'
public persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Casey said. ``You see two different things. You
see Prime Time, and then you see just Deion. He has his flair when
he gets out there on the field, and he's the best at what he does,
whether it's baseball or covering the best receivers out there.
When you get to know him, he's a little different from some of the
interviews you've seen over the years.'' AROUND THE HORN
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cubs want Kerry Wood to abandon his slider, the pitch
responsible for most of his 20 strikeouts against Houston two
seasons ago, to lessen stress on his surgically repaired elbow.
Wood doesn't necessarily agree. ``They think I can get people out
with fastball, curve and changeup,'' he said. ``But I don't think
the slider is a pitch I can abandon. We will shorten it up and make
it less stressful on the elbow, but I can't throw it out the
window.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John Smoltz's season-ending elbow injury reduces the
once-formidable Braves rotation to three solid pitchers. Greg
Maddux, Tom Glavine and Kevin Millwood are as good as anyone's top
three, but now there's a huge drop off. Terry Mulholland, who was
supposed to pitch out of the bullpen, becomes the fourth starter.
Bruce Chen, Steve Avery and Derrin Ebert are the fifth-starter
candidates. General manager John Schuerholz said he and manager
Bobby Cox will evaluate the rotation and decide whether to pursue a
trade for another starter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cubs manager Don Baylor assigned Jeff Huson to the minors when
both were with Colorado in '97, and Huson asked Baylor if he had a
future in the game. ``If he would've said, `No, I don't think you
can play anymore,' I would've been done,'' Huson said. ``That's how
much I value his opinion.'' Three years later, Huson is reunited
with Baylor in the Chicago Cubs' camp and has a good chance to win
a job as a utility infielder.
</P>
<P>
   _ Red Sox reliever Rod Beck did not look ready to claim the
closer's job during his first outing of the spring. He threw 12
fastballs and, according to one scout's radar gun, topped out at 85
mph (four times). The other eight were measured at 84.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free-agent-to-be Manny Ramirez evidently won't be signing a
contract extension with the Indians anytime soon. GM John Hart told
agent Jeff Moorad they would sign Ramirez to a Ken Griffey-like,
below-market deal if he wants to stay in Cleveland. Moorad, who was
in camp last week, indicated it will take more than the $14.5
million per season the Dodgers are paying fellow right fielder (and
fellow Moorad client) Shawn Green to keep Ramirez in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Expos plan to leave the small-market blues behind. They
expect to break ground for a new ballpark in April and expect it to
open for the 2002 season. By then, they hope to have their payroll
in the $50 million range.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Giants have set an attendance record before playing a game
in their new, 40,800-seat, Pacific Bell Park. As of Tuesday, only
50,000 reserved seat tickets remained for the season, not counting
the 500 bleacher seats set aside for walk-up traffic every game.
Attendance easily will exceed 3 million. The previous mark was
2,606,354 in 1993. THE FINAL WORD
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of interleague play revolves around the
geographical rivalries. The two Chicago teams, the two New York
teams, Anaheim-LA. I would welcome that opportunity with the
Rangers. I think it would be great for the state of Texas.'' _
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker, on the possibility of the
Rangers going to the AL Central and playing Houston in interleague
play nn
</P>
</TEXT>
