<HEADLINE>
KINGS HOLD OFF FLAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This time of year, the Kings only care about games
won, not opportunities lost.
</P>
<P>
   But as the opponents get tougher in the final month, it might be
hard to forget their slumping power play, which could have made
Saturday night's 3-1 victory over the Calgary Flames a whole lot
easier.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd of 18,118 at Staples Center saw the Kings
complete a four-game sweep of the Flames and solidify their sixth
spot in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But for the third consecutive game, the Kings did not score with
the man advantage. Four times during that span, including twice
against Calgary, the Kings had a five-on-three advantage and didn't
score.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, who close out their season-long seven-game homestand
Monday night against Vancouver are 3-2-1 in the first six games.
That could be better if they weren't 0 for 16 and 2 for the last 32
with the man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play is what wins playoff games,'' captain Rob Blake
said. ``It just has to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   They did get first-period goals from Ziggy Palffy and Craig
Johnson, who beat Flames goaltender Grant Fuhr in his first start
since mid-November when he went out with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   But when Jarome Iginla scored midway through the second, it
became anyone's game. Aki Berg gave the Kings a little room when he
scored with 11:28 to go in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames entered the game just three points behind San Jose
for the eighth and final playoff spot in the Western Conference,
but were coming off dismal losses against Colorado (8-3) and
Toronto (6-2).
</P>
<P>
   They cut the Kings lead to 2-1 midway through the second period
on a goal by Jarome Iginla, who was NHL Player of the Month for
February.
</P>
<P>
   Iginla, who had a league-high 16-game scoring streak stopped by
the Avalanche, took a long pass in front from Phil Housley and
poked it past Jamie Storr for his 24th goal of the season. Iginla
had 28 all last year.
</P>
<P>
   Again the Kings power play failed them from holding off the
Flames. With 4:03 remaining in the second and Derek Morris already
off for cross checking, former Duck Bobby Dollas was whistled for
holding the sti ck.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Kings a five-on-three advantage for one minute and
31 seconds. They didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, who outshot the Flames 38-25, emerged from a physical
start (seven fighting penalties in the first 11 minutes) with a 2-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr was making his first start after missing 25 games with a
knee injury and faced 14 shots in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy scored first at 12:19 when he skated across the Flames
crease as Rob Blake fired from the slot. The rebound popped out and
Palffy slipped it under Fuhr's right pad for his 26th goal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Palffy, Johnson rarely gets to show off his offense. But
with less than two minutes left in the period, he and Ian
Laperriere converged in front of the Calgary goal. The puck landed
on Johnson's stick and he slid it between Fuhr's legs for his ninth
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But without the power play, the Kings could not pull away. The
first five-on-three came at 14:04 of the first when Eric Charron
went off for roughing. Darryl Shannon already was in the box from
cross checking , but the Kings couldn't capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, they limited the Flames to just three shots in the
period, but the lost opportunity could have been more critical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
