<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-B     03-12 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BAD NEWS BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Good game. Great guys.
</P>
<P>
   The catchy marketing phrase that ushered the Bruins into the
1999-2000 season with such promise could be summed up best this
morning by a forlorn Charlie Brown, dragging behind him a tattered
black-and-gold pennant:
</P>
<P>
   Caption: Good grief!
</P>
<P>
   Something not so funny happened on the way to the Stanley Cup
finals _ Boston's destination, as forecast in an August issue of
Sports Illustrated. Not only was there no playoff berth, but the
Bruins so badly lost their way, their play so thoroughly inept and
hopeless, that their revered team captain traded his sweater last
week for a devil-may-care flyer with the temptress that is Lord
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades-plus later, Ray Bourque finds himself a proud member
of the Colorado Avalanche, working with the best surrounding cast
he's ever had, beyond his Canada Cup and Olympic dalliances. On his
way out of town, he also fired the heaviest shot of his career,
labeling Boston a city in which few NHLers would want to play,
expressing his frustration with both management and ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The step-back view here is not pretty. For the second time in
four seasons, the Bruins will miss the playoffs, leaving them with
but one postseason series victory since 1994. In an interview at
his Buffalo office last week, club owner Jeremy Jacobs said there
soon will be changes in the way his team operates, and, based on
the rising rhetoric he detects from the fan base, he worries about
a possible downturn at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   It's all somewhat hard to believe for a team that less than a
year ago was poised for takeoff, looking young, vibrant, and
strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry (Sinden) and I, we both have said to each other
recently, `Who would have thought we'd be talking about these kinds
of things?' '' said Jacobs, sorting through the pitfalls and
disasters this season. ``We never saw this hit on the radar screen
coming. I think we are still a very talented team. I think the kids
we have have really underperformed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs is right. The young, talented players, almost without
exception, have been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   The key question is, why?
</P>
<P>
   It is clear from what Jacobs says and how management has acted,
specifically in recent weeks, that Pat Burns will not be back to
fulfill the fourth year of his contract as head coach. The blame
almost certainly will fall to him. The parts should have performed
better, management will say. Another Boston coached sacked. From
Rick Bowness (one year), to Brian Sutter (three years), to Steve
Kasper (two years), and now to Burns, most of the past decade has
brought little fortune to Causeway Street and an abundance of hasty
adieus for the men who have stood behind the Boston bench.
</P>
<P>
   As in any game, the coach is always an issue. But to implicate
Burns as the root cause of most, or even much, of what has gone
wrong with the Hub's hockey team would be, at the very least,
shortsighted. Three years ago, he was viewed as part of the
solution. Now he's looked upon, by ownership and management, as
most of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Burns has his foibles, just as he has his strengths. He clearly
needed to vary the game plan when it became painfully obvious in
the first nine games of the season (0-5-4) that too much was made,
said, and written based on last year's postseason victory over the
Carolina Hurricanes. When another bout of the blahs hit in late
November _ this time with no antidote _ it was some six weeks
before Burns attempted a more up-tempo game. His approach, so
successful for two seasons, wasn't working. September's blue skies
had given way to a horizon full of funnel clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the new scheme would have improved results. However, by
the time it was rolled out, far too much else was blowing up.
Disruptions began on a near-daily basis, ranging from an array of
season-ending injuries befalling key players _ Jason Allison, Anson
Carter, and Byron Dafoe _ to the bizarre firing of Joe Murphy and
the season-ending suspension of Marty McSorley for his two-handed
chop on Donald Brashear's head.
</P>
<P>
   But the footprint for much, if not most, of what has gone wrong
this season was laid last summer, when the state of semi-euphoria
following the playoffs led Sinden and Mike O'Connell to
overestimate the team's talent base and do next to nothing to add
to the roster. The offseason shopping began and ended with the
acquisition of 36-year-old Dave Andreychuk. When it was obvious the
talent was not what was billed, there were hurried acquisitions of
rent-a-wrecks Murphy and McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk, after a sensational start, turned into a nonfactor
by early December and was cashiered in last Monday's trade that
shipped Bourque to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who appeared troubled and agitated in his short time
here, produced little and was discharged after showering Burns with
one too many expletives.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley, a congenial but tired warhorse, earned marks of
willingness but displayed little effectiveness. He now faces jail
time, if convicted of assault charges brought last week by the
Crown Counsel in British Columbia. Brashear was left with a
concussion. The league was left with a black eye. The Bruins, once
more, were left with nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, Sinden and O'Connell went 0 for 3 in the
player-acquisition department. On top of that, they also lost
center Tim Taylor, their defensive specialist, to free agency and
became the first franchise in NHL history to exercise free agency
``walkaway'' rights, opting not to pay Dmitri Khristich a $2.8
million arbitration award. He packed for Toronto and the Bruins got
a draft pick _ whose goals and assists may not be a factor for
another three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   Also during the summer, veteran winger Ken Baumgartner and
defenseman Dave Ellett were released, the last years of their
contracts bought out.
</P>
<P>
   The total on all those comings and goings: four veterans out,
three brought in _ and not a single one left in uniform today.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all that wouldn't add up to disaster if the remaining young
base, including returnees as well as farmhands and draft picks, was
enough to recharge the product. Obviously, that wasn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Carter and Allison remained healthy the entire season,
the point production up front was challenged. Joe Thornton's
numbers improved, but his overall game plateaued. Sergei Samsonov
(Jacobs: ``There's a better player in there'') showed only bits and
pieces of the sensational style that made him Rookie of the Year in
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque turned 39 in December and his game, for the first time,
grew gray around the temples. So bad were the club's fortunes that
Burns was still playing Bourque 25-30 minutes a night, a cruelty
printed in black-and-white for all to see in the game summaries. In
the midst of Bourque's struggles _ or perhaps contributing to them
_ the games of Kyle McLaren and Hal Gill fell down around him. One
of the few bright lights of the year _ perhaps the only one _ was
the tough, determined, and consistent play of backliner Don
Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   In net, Dafoe, after a one-month holdout, only briefly showed
reliable shot-blocking after returning in November. In a game plan
as simple as the one employed by Burns, with top defensive play and
netminding a must, too many holes add up to too many losses and
ties.
</P>
<P>
   The season that went nowhere is first and foremost about talent
_ rather, the lack of it.
</P>
<P>
   Good game. Great guys.
</P>
<P>
   Just not enough of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
