<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN SWEPT AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One night they were embattled St. John's teammates
who had plunged their team into turmoil on the eve of the Big East
tournament final. But Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, all was well with Erick
Barkley and Marvis ``Bootsy'' Thornton, the combatants of a
reported locker room altercation during halftime of Friday night's
semifinal victory over Miami.
</P>
<P>
   One night they were trading fists, angry glares, and angrier
words.
</P>
<P>
   The next it was nothing but love and high-fives.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a night and one team meeting make.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who opted not to follow through with his plan to take a
leave of absence from the team, and Thornton combined for 41 points
to lead third-seeded St. John's to its first Big East title since
1986 with an 80-70 victory over No. 4 seed Connecticut in the
conference tournament final at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, voted the tourney's Most Outstanding Player, led the
Red Storm (24-7) to their third victory over UConn (24-9) this
season by scoring a team-high 22 points on 9-of-14 shooting,
including 4 of 6 from 3-point range, while Barkley added 19 points
(6-for-10 shooting), 3 rebounds, and 3 assists. Anthony Glover,
whose two clutch free throws clinched Friday night's win, had 15
points, while Lavor Postell, who joined Barkley and Thornton on the
all-tournament team, had 14 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never fell apart,'' Thornton said. ``We had an argument,
but it was nothing. It was just between two competitive guys.
Tonight we just sucked it up and we won.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I got a lump in my throat, but I'm not gonna cry,'' said
Barkley. ``It feels great, going through what I've been through.
I'm just trying to play basketball for St. John's.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Red Storm never lost focus in a season rife with
distractions served as a testament to the amazing job done by coach
Mike Jarvis, the former Boston University and Cambridge Rindge &AMP;
Latin mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed in my heart that all would be resolved,'' said
Jarvis as he stood on the Garden floor and proudly watched his
players cut down the nets. ``I have a bracelet with the initials
W.W.J.D. It stands for, `What Would Jesus Do?' We had a team
meeting today before practice and I wrote those intials on the
chalkboard and I asked each player `What would Jesus do?'
</P>
<P>
   ``When it got around to Anthony Glover, the kid who made the two
free throws (against Miami), he said, `Jesus would forgive.' Then
when it got to Chudney Gray, he said, `All is forgiven now. Let's
go out and be a team again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely what it took for the Red Storm to avenge an
82-63 loss to UConn in last year's championship game. St. John's
denied the Huskies, who were playing their fourth game in as many
nights, their third straight Big East title and snapped UConn's
nine-game winning streak in tourney play.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Mouring led UConn with 22 points on 7-for-16 shooting,
including 6 of 11 from 3-point range, while foul-plagued Khalid
El-Amin added 13 points and freshman guard Tony Robertson had 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies trailed by as many as 12, 36-24, in the first half
when Thornton drained a 3-pointer with 2:38 to go. The Huskies, who
made only two field goals in the final 6:38, ended a scoreless
drought of 4:22 when Mouring hit two free throws to make it 36-26.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's held a 37-28 halftime lead, so there was little
concern that Barkley and Thornton would be at each other's throats
again. But if UConn had any intention of winning its third straight
title, the Huskies were going to need a better showing in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was, unlike Friday night's game when he was three
minutes late for the second half, Barkley showed up on time and
scored St. John's first two baskets, including a 3-pointer that
gave the Red Storm a 42-33 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies managed to pull within 46-41 on Robertson's jumper,
but UConn unraveled when El-Amin picked up his fourth personal with
12:27 left. Thornton and Postell combined to score 9 in a 10-2 run
that enabled St. John's to build a commanding 15-point lead, 58-43,
with 10:41 to go. But UConn refused to go away, using a 15-4 run to
rally within 64-58.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's, though, staved off the Huskies for a title that did
not seem probable the night before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
