<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'CONNELL CONCEDES MISTAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There are a million and one reasons the Bruins went
south this season. No one factor has been overwhelming. There have
been wrong decisions, wrong personnel, wrong chemistry, wrong
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jeremy Jacobs has been publicly critical of coach Pat
Burns and players such as underachieving Sergei Samsonov while
supporting the job that president/general manager Harry Sinden and
assistant GM Mike O'Connell are doing. But, truth be told, there's
plenty of culpability on their part.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to rate the job management has done this season,
O'Connell paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough question,'' he said. ``But I think you'd have
to say we failed. We haven't done very well. It's easy to sit back
now and look at it. We thought we'd have as good a chance as anyone
to make another step in the right direction and it didn't work.
Going into the season, we all had such high hopes. It didn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell doesn't understand the perception that he is the one
who would like to get rid of Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why that's been portrayed that way,'' he said.
``I've been away. I haven't been around the team. That's not the
truth. It's odd. If I'm around the team too much, I'm meddling, and
if I'm not around the team, I'm sour on the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connell, who soon will take over the GM title and has
already assumed most of the duties, wouldn't endorse Burns, who is
in the final year of his contract. Even Jacobs said he thought
O'Connell was more ``reactionary'' than Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he felt that was true, O'Connell said, ``I'm a
pretty patient guy. I don't know if reactionary, if I am that or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said he understands the fans' anger and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up watching this team,'' he said. ``I know what it
means to the community and how the town reacts to the team. I feel
for the fans. As bad as this season has gone, if you look back at
the start of the season, I don't think anybody thought we'd go
through this. We didn't think so, either. I think we were realistic
about our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people picked us to go to the Stanley Cup finals. We
thought that would be nice but there are a lot of things that would
have had to happen. Going forward, we have every bit of a chance
next year to have the success people thought we'd have this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, said O'Connell, this season is worse than 1997,
when the Bruins missed the playoffs for the first time in 30 years.
In other ways, he doesn't think it's as bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``From '97 to the end of last year, (the turnaround) happened
pretty quick,'' he said. ``No one ever expected us to turn it that
quick, to have an old team that looked like it had nothing. To turn
it around to one of the top teams in the league in a matter of 18
months, it startled a lot of people, and maybe it was too much, too
soon. Maybe these are growing pains we need to live with and
hopefully players and coaches and management will learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   When management was preparing for this season, it had great hope
that everything would come together. Instead, things blew up in
their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems like no matter what was done, it didn't work,''
said O'Connell. ``Whatever was said, it didn't work. Whoever was
quoted, it seemed like it worked against everything. It hasn't been
an easy season. There have been fires here and fires there and it's
taken its toll. You look at (Joe) Murphy and (Marty McSorley) and
that just didn't work. And Dave Andreychuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you looked at the team at the start of the year, we
showed some promise. Then, bang, one thing led to another. How
Byron (Dafoe's) holdout affected the psyche of the team. All of a
sudden, he gets back and John Grahame was playing well and we send
him down, how that affects the team. We bring in Murphy and
McSorley and how that affects the team and then injuries. The
difference between winning and losing in this game is so close. It
just seemed like we were always on the wrong side of it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell acknowledged the team was adversely affected by the
number of players who missed training camp, but because of the
players' salary demands, it couldn't be helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does make a difference, especially for goaltenders,'' he
said. ``It's hard, but the players have to make the decision as
well as us. The easiest thing for us to do is to just pay whatever
they want. We've never made unrealistic offers to people. I think
they're very fair, very well thought out. We research almost
everything we do extensively. If both parties are realistic, a deal
will get done.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, O'Connell said, the Bruins are trying to re-sign
right wing Anson Carter, who had wrist surgery Friday. O'Connell is
trying to get Carter's agent, Pat Brisson, to cut to the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got an initial introduction to the area,'' said O'Connell.
``I still haven't seen any hard numbers. I'm going to call him back
and thank him for that and say please get to the numbers. I know
Anson as well as his agent does and who makes what and where he
should fit. So, we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Another player they'd like to keep happy is veteran defenseman
Don Sweeney, who was the Bruins' most consistent player. Sweeney is
due to become an unrestricted free agent at the end of the season.
O'Connell said Sinden is talking to Sweeney's agent, Mark Witkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to keep him,'' said O'Connell. ``He's a great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fallout from a dreadful year that, mercifully, is
almost over, O'Connell said he's looking forward to taking over the
GM's title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more difficult it is, the greater the challenge,'' he
said. ``I'm not ready to play bingo yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Sabres were busy last week bolstering their lineup.
In addition to acquiring center Chris Gratton from Tampa Bay
Thursday, the Sabres picked up Chicago center Doug Gilmour Friday.
Gilmour knew he was going somewhere, but it was difficult waiting
for the other shoe to drop. ``It's hard knowing all they want to do
is move you,'' said Gilmour, who is sidelined with bruised ribs. He
will be paid $6 million this year and next, and the Blackhawks will
pick up a good portion of that . . The McSorley incident continues
to raise questions. Should he be punished outside the realm of the
NHL? Will he be found guilty in a court of law? Former Islanders
great Denis Potvin and two-time Lady Byng winner Marcel Dionne
weighed in. ``When you enter the NHL, you know if a guy
sucker-punches me on the ice, I have to deal with that in my own
way,'' said Potvin. ``The game deals with it in its own way. If a
guy sucker-punches me on (the street), that's a totally different
thing. Where do you draw the line? I think the NHL did the right
thing and I'd rather not see it go any farther.'' Dionne thought it
was a tough call. ``I really believe McSorley is paying a dear
price,'' said Dionne. ``You always worry about what's next. I'm
sure it has happened before, when I was playing in the 1970s, but
we didn't have the coverage and media attention we have now. From
what I saw on TV, if I'm not a hockey fan, this is criminal
assault. No different than if it were in the stands and someone
hits you with a baseball bat.'' Brad Marsh, a former NHL defenseman
now coaching teenagers, thinks McSorley could make a contribution,
warning youngsters of dangerous behavior. ``I would like to see him
do some public service announcements geared at minor league players
across North America, trying to get them on the straight and
narrow,'' said Marsh. Former player Rob Ramage, who coaches kids in
St. Louis, echoed those sentiments. ``It's something I had to
explain to them,'' said Ramage. ``What went on there is not part of
the game. But what a spokesman he could be to the kids. `I didn't
play because this is what I did. I lost my chance to play.' What a
powerful message.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We think things are weird here, but how about the goings-on in
Dallas? The defending Stanley Cup champions have a big problem with
goaltender Ed Belfour. Belfour was arrested Wednesday morning for
assaulting a security guard and resisting arrest. The Dallas police
had to Mace him twice, once while he was in custody. Belfour
refused to cooperate and was placed in a restraining chair. He is
being evaluated by officials from the NHL's substance abuse program
and is expected to miss at least two games, including Sunday's
contest against the St. Louis Blues. Belfour said the incident was
a big misunderstanding, a position coach Ken Hitchcock rejected.
``That's the worst attitude you can have,'' said Hitchcock. ``This
is not about a misunderstanding. Eddie's a good person and he's got
a heart of gold. We want him to have a successful career but also a
successful life. You can't close your eyes in these situations.''
Belfour is going to have to be accountable to his teammates. ``Our
concern is that people stand up and explain themselves and do it
honestly,'' Hitchcock said. ``Because this isn't a
misunderstanding; this is a big mistake and we need to correct
it.'' . . . Former Bruin Shawn McEachern could have become an
unrestricted free agent at the end of the season but is thrilled in
Ottawa and recently signed a three-year deal believed to be worth
$6 million-$7 million. ``I wanted to stay in Ottawa,'' said
McEachern, a native of Waltham. ``My wife enjoys it, our kids enjoy
it, and I enjoy the small community feeling. I've been in other
places and I know the grass isn't always greener on the other
side.'' . . . It appears Long Island billionaire Charles Wang, CEO
of Computer Associates, is interested in buying the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He got off to a slow start, but Washington Capitals center Adam
Oates, at 37, is having a tremendous season. Coach Ron Wilson is
pushing Oates for the Selke Trophy, awarded to the best defensive
forward. ``Adam contributes so much defensively,'' said Wilson.
``He is such an extension of the coach's arm on the ice and he
bought into a defensive system that's difficult for offensive
players to buy into. He had to be the guy to give up some of his
responsibility offensively, but not at all in terms that hurt the
team. As far as I'm concerned, there isn't a guy who is even close
when it comes to the Selke.'' . . . Even when Rick Tocchet was
toiling in his brief and unsatisfying tenure in Boston, he would
have rather been in Philadelphia. He was happy in Phoenix, a team
loaded with talent, but to say he's ecstatic about being back with
his beloved Flyers is an understatement. ``It's a great situation
for me,'' said Tocchet, who was dealt for Mikael Renberg. ``Philly
was No. 1 on my list. I'd like to think I've got something to
offer.'' Tocchet, a terrific guy and respected leader, will be
missed in the dressing room. ``He's taught us and me a lot about
what it means to play this game,'' said the Coyotes' Keith Tkachuk.
``It's a sad day around here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
