<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX VISIT TO DOMINICAN IS SYMBOLIC 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS-2   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ You know how somebody looks
familiar but you just can't quite connect the man and the moment?
That's how it was at the very nice pregame reception thrown by
United States ambassador to the Dominican Republic Charles Manett
and his staff Saturday. In the middle of the hubbub, there was this
very impressive-looking middle-aged gentlemen with a familiar look
wearing a Houston Astros cap.
</P>
<P>
   And then someone says to you, ``Would you like to meet Rico
Carty?''
</P>
<P>
   You kidding? Rico Carty? A man who might as well have the name
Senor Line Drive to commemorate all the bullets he knocked out in
both leagues?
</P>
<P>
   We are kind of used to the idea that in modern baseball
Dominicans rule. But it wasn't always thus. First, there were the
Cubans, followed by the Mexicans, and then the Puerto Ricans. The
San Francisco Giants came down here in the mid-'50s and came away
with the great Juan Marichal, not to mention an entire Alou family.
And right there in the forefront of this Dominican-friendly
takeover of baseball was Rico Carty, a righthanded masher of the
first degree.
</P>
<P>
   Marichal got himself into Cooperstown without the bother of
buying a ticket. He is now the Dominican's Secretary of Sports and
in that capacity he represented his country's administration at the
embassy ceremony. Carty was present to help promote the idea of a
Dominican sports Hall of Fame, which in this country basically
means a Dominican baseball Hall of Fame. Toward that end, an
18-item Baseball Hall of Fame exhibit featuring artifacts connected
with some of the great Dominican ballplayers is on display at the
American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not have the slightest idea when I came up that there
would someday be this many Dominicans in the big leagues,'' Carty
said. ``If you had asked me if it would ever come to this, I would
have said no.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Sutton was once famously quoted as saying that he robbed
banks because ``that's where the money is,'' and that's the basic
reason the Red Sox, along with the Astros, are part of this two-day
major league excursion to Quisqueya Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at it as great exposure for us,'' said Red Sox vice
president John Buckley. ``This is a chance to promote the Red Sox.
We were the first ones to raise our hands and say, `We'll go,' when
Major League Baseball was looking for volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dan Duquette joined the Red Sox five years ago, the
organization had, by his estimation, ``1 or 2 percent Dominican
players.'' And now? ``It's near 30 percent,'' he said, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   At the big league level, the prominent Red Sox players of
Dominican extraction thus far have come via trades or free agency.
That would mean the likes of Tony Pena, Pedro Martinez, Ramon
Martinez, and Jose Offerman. We are just getting a glimpse of this
regime's Dominican harvest when we look at impressive young third
baseman Wilton Veras and promising righthander Juan Pena.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox now have a baseball academy in the Dominican, and
with Pedro as a marquee signing, they have strengthened their
influence in this most critical of all baseball venues. And
speaking of Marichal, Duquette said every Red Sox fan owes him a
great deal of thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Marichal was one of the key advisers when Pedro decided
to sign with us after we made the trade,'' Duquette explained.
``Pedro respects him greatly, and he signed with us on that
recommendation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone forget Marichal, known in his prime as the Dominican
Dandy, passed through the Red Sox portals as he was making his way
out of the big leagues. He was once even part of a memorable 1974
Sunday doubleheader pairing with Luis Tiant. Whoever would have
thought that this brief Red Sox experience one day would prove so
significant in the history of the organization?
</P>
<P>
   After years of neglect in the area of Caribbean recruitment,
Duquette has the Red Sox as proactive as anybody. Doing so was a
major priority when he took the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew from our experience in Montreal how important
international recruiting was to anyone's developmental program,''
said Duquette. ``If you're a good team, year in and year out, this
is what you have to do. This is a good time for the Red Sox to be
in the Dominican.''
</P>
<P>
   For any serious baseball organization, any time is a good time
to be in the Dominican. If you can also play a ballgame here on a
nice sunny afternoon, so much the better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
