<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE PLAYS TOUGH GAME _ WAITING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU - The last place anybody wanted to be on a gorgeous day
like Saturday was indoors.
</P>
<P>
   But while the rest of civilization, seemingly, was at the beach
across Pacific Coast Highway, members of the Pepperdine basketball
team were working away inside Firestone Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Waves aren't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Life still remains in their season, and today they'll find out
what the future holds - whether they'll be readying for the first
round of the NCAA Tournament or sulking with the rest of the bubble
clubs who felt they got snubbed.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, the Waves (24-8) will gather today at the home
of Andy Benton, an athletic department official, to watch the
tournament selection show. By 4 p.m. they'll know their fate.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Pepperdine went through a two-hour workout, then
scrambled to watch some conference tournament games on television.
But that's been their routine since they concluded the regular
season in a 69-65 loss to Gonzaga on Monday in the West Coast
Conference tournament championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all getting pretty antsy,'' said forward David
Lalazarian. ``We just waiting to find out what's going to happen. I
mean, you watch some of these (conference tournament) games and you
see a few upsets and you wonder how that's going to affect our
chances of getting in. It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The anxious wait could have been avoided had Pepperdine defeated
Gonzaga in the WCC final. A win would have ensured the Waves one of
the 29 automatic bids. Instead, they'll sweat out the last few
hours hoping to get one of the 35 at-large berths in the 64-team
field.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves would seem a lock to get in after compiling an
impressive list of ''tournament-friendly'' achievements. For
instance:
</P>
<P>
   -Of the 60 teams in the current College RPI report, the Waves
rank fourth in most road wins with 13, tying a school record.
</P>
<P>
   -They rank second with the most games played on the road (20)
and second for least amount of home games with 12.
</P>
<P>
   -All 24 wins were against Division I opponents. Ten of its 15
nonconference games were on the road, and they finished 10-5 in
those games.
</P>
<P>
   -They recorded ``quality'' nonconference wins over Colorado
State, Detroit, Fresno State, Long Beach State and
Louisiana-Layette.
</P>
<P>
   -Their losses were to quality teams that reached the tournament
last year - Auburn, Kansas, UCLA, UNC Charlotte and Gonzaga, which
beat Pepperdine twice (and lost once).
</P>
<P>
   -In a conference that yielded five teams that won at least 19
games, the Waves were the regular-season champions at 12-2.
</P>
<P>
   Taking all that into consideration, and the fact that Pepperdine
advanced to the WCC tournament championship game and lost in
overtime, the Waves are on solid ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we keep telling ourselves and we feel like we've
done everything we could do and that we deserve (a bid),''
Lalazarian said. ``But again, you see some of these upsets and you
wonder how it's all going to play out. So you get a little
nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolff felt the Waves clinched a
bid by reaching the WCC tournament final after winning the
conference regular-season crown. Still, he too is anxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the so-called experts and the various Web sites have
Pepperdine in the tournament, but I'll be nervous about the whole
thing until I see our name flash on the television screen on Sunday
afternoon,'' said van Breda Kolff.
</P>
<P>
   The wait is almost over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 0153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
