u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      03-12 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN DIDN'T GO DOWN REBUILDING 76ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three years ago, Larry Brown boldly walked into a
minefield known as the Philadelphia 76ers. He inherited a team that
had won 18 games, three more than the Celtics, and richly deserved
its 64 losses.
</P>
<P>
   He made no bold predictions about quick turnarounds or
guaranteed playoff appearances. He and henchman Billy King went to
work and, despite a couple of glaring gaffes, they have assembled a
team that comes to Boston Sunday having lapped Rick Pitino's boys
in green.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers come in as contenders, not pretenders. They don't
talk about trying to make the eighth spot in the playoffs, they
talk about getting home-court advantage. They have the league's
leading scorer in Allen Iverson, but according to the old-school
Brown, if you concentrate only on Iverson, you're missing the
essence of his club.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a knock on Allen,'' Brown said, ``but our team is
all about Tyrone Hill, Theo Ratliff, George Lynch, Aaron McKie, and
Eric Snow. When Allen went out, we were 6-4 without him. But with
these guys, we have competed in almost every single game. They
defend their positions as well as anyone in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino talks wistfully about defense, and his team pays lip
service to the concept. The Sixers go out and play defense.
Opponents shoot 43 percent against Philadelphia, the
seventh-stingiest mark in the league. They are near the top in
forcing turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch may be the embodiment of the team, coming in as a free
agent (apparently not good enough to play for Vancouver) and
earning a starting spot through sheer tenacity. Brown says Lynch
reminds him of Adrian Griffin, a player who is utterly selfless and
``brings it on every single possession.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch also happens to be the only guy on the team to have
started all 60 games. Brown has had injury woes all season, yet the
team is right in the hunt for the division crown. Brown has
outstanding depth up front, thanks to three huge deals.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months into his first season, Brown saw the
Iverson/Jerry Stackhouse thing wasn't working and dealt Stackhouse
to Detroit for Ratliff and McKie. He saw Tim Thomas wasn't working
out, either _ he basically traded Keith Van Horn and cap space for
Thomas _ and sent Thomas to Milwaukee for Hill. Then, he deep-sixed
Larry Hughes, who couldn't coexist with Iverson (and who was
drafted ahead of Paul Pierce) for Toni Kukoc.
</P>
<P>
   The Kukoc deal helped all involved, but it really helped the
Sixers because they now have another legitimate scorer. Brown says
Kukoc is better defensively than he thought _ Kukoc will never be
an All-Defensive Team candidate _ and, needless to say, has been
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's won,'' Brown said. ``He understands what it takes to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Sixers. Finally. They broke through last season, not
only making the playoffs but getting to the second round. They're
ready for more.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the success, Brown is, of course, worried. He wouldn't
be a coach if he weren't. He's worried about Iverson's sore
shoulder, although, as he noted, with the arrival of Kukoc,
``There's more ball distribution than we've ever had. It used to be
one guy taking 30 shots'' _ guess who? _ ``and the next guy taking
six.''
</P>
<P>
   He's worried about Hill's sore Achilles' tendon and what looks
like a tough schedule the rest of the way. The Sixers haven't
played the Utah Jazz but they will meet twice in the next 18 days.
They have a brutal Western swing (Minnesota, Utah, Lakers,
Sacramento) and still have two games left with both Miami and
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've managed to hang on,'' Brown said. ``I'm thrilled. I
think this season we've lost eight games by 10 or more points and
we've been out of only one of them. That's an amazing thing to me.
But we've got a tough schedule ahead, especially out West. But
that's what's fun for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are justifiably getting kudos as they rampage through
the league, but guess who's quietly coming around? Yup, it's the
Jazz. They come east this week having overtaken the Spurs for the
top spot (and critical No. 2 seed) in the West. They had won six
straight and 9 of 10 heading into Phoenix Friday. So, are the Jazz
just being the Jazz, ready to make a serious run? Or is it a
fruitless chase the way the Lakers are playing? ``We're not
conceding anything,'' said center Olden Polynice. ``The Lakers are
an abdominal strain away. Shaq gets one of those and they're done.
You can't count us out. I saw what Denver did to Seattle (in 1994)
but we know we have to do it ourselves. To me, it's important to be
playing well, now.'' Polynice is finishing his first year with the
Jazz and thinks the team isn't getting the proper respect. ``We
have two guys here who play hard every night, who are going into
the Hall of Fame, and yet they get nothing,'' he said, referring to
John Stockton and Karl Malone. ``It's like the league is focusing
on all these young guys. I don't think John and Karl get enough
credit. The NBA is supposed to be this great image maker. Well, how
about finding a way to market these guys?'' . . . The NBA is trying
to find a way to boost sagging television ratings. Coaches have
been miked for some NBC games, although most abhor the idea. Then,
starting April 1, the league will allow cameras into locker rooms
at halftime so viewers can get a ``feel'' of what it's like. No one
likes that idea. Said Indiana coach Larry Bird, ``I'll just have my
players sit there naked. That won't last very long.'' . . . Alvin
Gentry won't stay unemployed for long. Brown, who had Gentry as an
assistant at Kansas and in San Antonio, said he'd like to see the
deposed Pistons coach on the Philly bench. (There will be an
opening with John Calipari heading to Memphis.) The Gentry firing
was, basically, a preemptive strike by management because his
contract was up and he wasn't going to be rehired. The more
important question here is, of course, Grant Hill. If the Pistons
can't crack the playoffs, what incentive is there for Hill to stick
around? Interim official taster George Irvine is Hill's fourth
coach in less than six seasons and the new guy will be the fifth.
Names popping up include Bill Laimbeer and Rick Mahorn, who, by the
way, was just named CBA Coach of the Month in Rockford, where he
succeeded Darrell Walker. Another ex-Piston, Isiah Thomas, has put
his Detroit-area house up for sale and is building in the Atlanta
area. Without jumping to conclusions, one would surmise that the
Hawks will be in for some serious redecorating after the season.
Isaiah Rider was late, again, for Thursday's loss at home to the
Spurs. Meanwhile, Dikembe Mutombo looks totally uninterested in the
events around him . . . Speaking of the Pistons, they retired Joe
Dumars's number Friday and will soon celebrate the 10th anniversary
of their second title team. (Can you imagine if the Celtics or
Lakers did that with their title teams?) And to think the Pistons
took immense heat in 1985 after drafting the obscure Dumars out of
McNeese State ahead of East Lansing/Michigan State legend Sam
Vincent, who went to Boston. (If Dallas had drafted Malone and
Dumars, how many flags would it have?) By the way, to illustrate
how wild that draft was, the final two players taken in the first
round are not only still around, they're thriving: A.C. Green and
Terry Porter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves may look back on this year and kick themselves
for their play at home against some of the league's flotsam and
jetsam. Their latest lapse: a loss Wednesday to the pathetic
Wizards. Minnesota also has lost at home to the Clippers, Warriors,
Mavericks, Magic, Nets, and Nuggets and is only 7-7 at home against
sub-.500 teams . . . How's this for a sure-fire draw: The Warriors
are offering free admission to Sunday night's game with the
Clippers to anyone who will submit to a buzz-cut from one of 20
Marine Corps ``hair stylists'' at the arena. Good thing the Celtics
would never stoop to a cheesy thing like that. Those in attendance
will see Lamar Odom playing the point. That's where
soon-to-be-fired coach Jim Todd has decided Odom will play, and the
rook averaged 16 points, 9 rebounds, and 5 assists over a five-game
stretch . . . The silly Dennis Rodman sideshow came to an
all-too-predictable conclusion last week. It wasn't Rodman's fault.
He was just being himself. The Mavericks discovered they could lose
just as easily without him. Said Phil Jackson, ``There wasn't
enough of the drama that Dennis likes, or the showcase perhaps that
he needs.'' Dallas's first Worm-free home game Wednesday drew only
13,435, two-thirds capacity . . . When the league switched Sunday's
Toronto-Seattle game to prime time on NBC, it did so despite
freezing out most of Canada. The game was supposed to be on CTV _
the Canadian cable giant _ but the switch means viewers must settle
for local news, ``Felicity,'' and a show called ``Charmed.'' CTV
already had made commitments to sponsors in those time slots . . .
The Miami Heat have added another suit to the coaching staff. (They
have four assistants already.) Keith Askins, one of Pat Riley's
favorite players, has hooked on as a volunteer assistant. Askins
will be well compensated for his volunteerism; he's still
collecting the remainder of his $1.75 million contract. The Heat
waived Askins prior to the season and he heard from a few teams. He
decided to relax before getting back into it: He had not been to a
single Miami game or even to the new American Airlines Arena since
being released . . . One of the great stories of this or any season
may unfold this week in San Antonio. On Tuesday against Atlanta,
Sean Elliott is scheduled to make his season debut, seven months
after a kidney transplant. It is a debut that many figured might
never happen. Elliott has been determined to make it back _ he
originally targeted mid-February _ even as coach Gregg Popovich
told his team to forget about it. San Antonio has been having
internal woes of late _ Avery Johnson didn't appreciate being
mentioned in trade stories _ and needs all the help it can get in
the cutthroat Western Conference. The Spurs could use anything
resembling the Elliott of old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
