<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS MUST WIN ON ROAD TO STAY IN PLAYOFF HUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Celtics don't like to see box scores in their
locker room, but there is no mistaking the Eastern Conference
standings on the wall. They are updated daily, and they show where
the Celtics stand and where they have to go.
</P>
<P>
   The last two playoff spots in the East are up for grabs, and six
teams, including the Celtics, are in the mix. (We're eliminating
the Hawks, who seem to have tanked the season.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the teams ahead of you,'' coach Rick Pitino said
Saturday. ``It's also the teams right with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino wants the last week of the regular season to mean
something and, with all these teams in a scrum, there's a good
chance it will. ``Every game for us is monumental,'' the coach
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic clearly have the best schedule, with only one-third of
their remaining games against winning teams. Orlando is finished on
the road in the West and plays eight games against the other
pretenders. The Magic have a good home/road split, but they've been
a tough team to peg.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest schedule? Detroit by a mile. The Pistons have the
most road games and start a five-game Western swing next Sunday.
And the game before that? A homer against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who are playing above .500 since their 2-15 start, are
making noise and should have Jayson Williams back next Saturday.
Williams is working out and was told by one teammate that he looked
better than Gheorghe Muresan. ``I don't know how to take that,''
Williams said. The Nets, like the Magic, have the most games
(eight) against the Eastern contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee has an excellent April schedule, with 9 of 11 games
against teams with losing records and only six games overall
against winning teams. But the Bucks still have to go out West, and
they are playing horribly right now, as evidenced by their 28-point
home loss to the Nets Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics? After Sunday, they have only seven games left
against teams with winning records. But they've got to do it on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we're behind the 8-ball,'' Pitino said. ``After
(Sunday's) game, we have 10 of 13 on the road. We have to take care
of business at home and get lucky on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Kenny Anderson, ``It's going to be tough. It might come
down to the last week of the season. The main thing we can do is
try to win each game we play, one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitino on John Calipari's move to Memphis: ``Memphis is a town
of scoundrels and he's a scoundrel. Seriously, it's a great
opportunity. It's sort of like the UMass situation in that it needs
enthusiasm, recruiting, and to be built from the bottom up. And he
has more resources for recruiting there than he did at UMass.
Amherst is not exactly a basketball hotbed.'' . . . Pitino on the
Sixers: ``They go back door more than any team in pro basketball.''
He also said the Sixers start four ``great'' defensive players
along with Allen Iverson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
