<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER GREAT MARINO PASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If Dan Marino retires as expected Monday, he will not
be remembered for the sad way his career ended or the fact that he
never won a Super Bowl. He'll be remembered as the most prolific
passer in pro football history.
</P>
<P>
   That is as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   It is too bad that Marino never experienced the excitement of a
Super Bowl victory as his contemporary John Elway finally did at
the end of his brilliant career, but he is making a wise choice not
to chase the game on to Minnesota, as he was thinking of doing.
</P>
<P>
   Marino belongs in a Dolphins uniform or none at all. To do
something else at this late stage of his football life would be
courting disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Wise, and also rare, is the athlete who knows when his time has
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Marino's arm is not what it used to be, and he is immobile
because of an Achilles' tendon injury suffered a few years back. He
also has a serious case of the yips, his nerve sometimes deserting
him in large part because he knows his receivers are not as good as
the ones he used to have.
</P>
<P>
   Marino threw some horrendous interceptions last year, the only
season in which he threw more picks than touchdowns. Yet he still
got his team into the playoffs and had a brilliant game in Seattle
before his string ran out.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets out now, Marino will not be remembered for the last
few games in which he struggled. If he stays too long, he will
become another hump-shouldered Johnny Unitas, misplaced in a pale
blue San Diego Chargers uniform, or a limping Joe Namath, as a Los
Angeles Ram pretending he was still Broadway Joe of the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   If Marino announces his retirement Monday, he will be remembered
not for small weaknesses born of age and infirmity at the end of
his career but for the brilliance that allowed him to pass for
61,361 yards and 420 touchdowns, including seasons in which he
threw 44 and 48 touchdowns. There will be much to remember about
him when Miami retires his uniform next season, and none of those
memories will be the sad ones he could be carrying if he chose to
play on.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino doesn't need a gaudy ring to prove that he is a
champion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Slade's decision to restructure his contract does not make
him a candidate for firing a year from now, as Bruce Armstrong was
this year. Unlike the Armstrong situation, New England would
actually cost itself cap room if it cut Slade in 2001 when his cap
number accelerates to $4.1 million. Armstrong's disappearance saved
the Patriots cap money because the bulk of his income was in
salary, not a pro-rated bonus. But cutting Slade would cost New
England $2.1 million on the cap, including an additional $780,000
as part of his pro-rated bonus. Slade's willingness to restructure
his deal gave the Patriots an additional $860,000 of cap room at a
time when they reportedly were down to $80,000 . . . Willie
McGinest, who was in attendance at the Felix Trinidad-David Reid
fight in Las Vegas last week and looking fit and ready to play,
will be back in New England this week to join the bulk of his
teammates for Bill Belichick's offseason workout program. The
program ends June 16 and training camp will open around July 17,
two weeks before the Patriots play the San Francisco 49ers in the
Hall of Fame game in Canton, Ohio. The only mandatory minicamp runs
June 2-4 . . . Although Patriots wide receiver Sean Morey will play
in NFL Europe this spring, quarterback Michael Bishop will not.
Bishop was always reluctant to go overseas despite the recent
success of NFL Europe alums such as Kurt Warner and Jon Kitna.
Belichick decided it might be counterproductive to send him because
it would mean asking Bishop to learn his fourth offensive system in
less than two years. Bishop ran the Kansas State offense two years
ago, tried to learn Ernie Zampese's timing offense last season, and
now must adapt to Charlie Weis's ideas . . . By contrast, the
Kansas City Chiefs have assigned 11 players to NFL Europe,
including two quarterbacks and college football's all-time leading
rusher, Brian Shay. At Emporia State in Kansas, Shay gained 6,958
yards and scored 88 touchdowns but he went undrafted last year. He
was on the Chiefs' practice squad for five weeks last year before
being cut . . . Tedy Bruschi is expected to make a decision on his
future this week. He has offers from Green Bay, Oakland, and
Cleveland, but no one is offering the $3 million signing bonus he
wants on a five-year deal. He won't get that from New England,
either, because of its cap situation. The best the Patriots could
do would be a $2 million bonus or a longer contract over which to
spread the money . . . Old friend Scott Rehberg is back in the
news. The ex-Patriot lineman made headlines last year when he said
he could not play in a Browns game because of the flu and was
ripped by teammate Lomas Brown. ``Things got ugly up there,''
Rehberg said after signing a two-year deal with the Cincinnati
Bengals as an all-purpose backup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Big-time agent Tank Black may be going down in flames. On top of
allegations that he violated NFL rules governing agents, the
Securities and Exchange Commission is alleging that he defrauded a
number of NFL players of millions. He reportedly took $400,000 from
Tampa wide receiver Jacquez Green's signing bonus and deposited it
in a Cayman Island bank account that the SEC claims was a front for
a Ponzi scheme. Black also allegedly cost another client all of his
$3 million signing bonus . . . Among the players who benefitted
most from the recent NFL combine workouts was Boston College
defensive tackle Chris Hovan, who impressed the scouts by doing 35
reps with a 225-pound bench press . . . Trent Dilfer never expected
to be in the position he finds himself in today. He was supposed to
be leading the Buccaneers into the Super Bowl by now. Instead, he
is backing up Tony Banks in Baltimore after signing a $1 million,
one-year deal. Dilfer started 76 games for the Buccaneers in his
six seasons there but lost the job to rookie Shaun King late last
season. Tampa could have extended Dilfer's contract but refused to
gamble any more money on its former No. 1 draft choice. Meanwhile,
King has become the toast of Tampa after the way he carried them
into the NFC title game. ``We're winning, so they like me now,''
King said. ``But your time in the spotlight isn't always that long.
You never know how long it will last into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Interesting dynamics in the brewing quarterback battle in Denver
between incumbent Brian Griese and newly signed Gus Frerotte.
Frerotte is used to such battles, having engaged in them in
Washington with John Friesz, Heath Shuler, Jeff Hostetler, and
Trent Green before moving on to back up Charlie Batch in Detroit
last year. Now he has signed a one-year deal with Denver to compete
with a player who has the same agent he has. He publicly has
conceded the job to Griese, but privately the 31-year-old Frerotte
is going to Denver looking to play. The only fly in the ointment
would be if the Broncos sign Steve Young, as some speculate head
coach Mike Shanahan will. Frerotte was told of that possibility
before he agreed to terms, but he believes there is no more than a
10 percent chance of that happening . . . Rumors abound that
Keyshawn Johnson has been offered to the Redskins, Buccaneers, and
Ravens as the Jets attempt to find a way to parlay their No. 16 and
No. 18 picks into one of the top four drafting slots in pursuit of
Penn State defensive end Courtney Brown. But sources in Washington
say there is little likelihood the Redskins will trade either the
No. 2 or No. 3 spot because personnel director Vinny Cerrato
believes there are only four sure-shot players in this draft _
Brown, Penn State teammate LaVar Arrington, Florida State wide
receiver Peter Warrick, and Alabama tackle Chris Samuels _ and he
is in position to grab two of them . . . One guy in New York has a
unique take on the Jets' decision to shop their best player around.
Mets catcher Mike Piazza, who was traded to New York in 1998
because of brewing contract problems, said, ``Nobody's beyond
getting traded if the team can try to prove that they feel it's the
best for the team. I never thought of myself as untouchable. I
think a lot of guys shouldn't think of themselves as untouchables.
That's the business of sports. It's not personal. Even (Wayne)
Gretzky was traded. You have to realize one door closes and another
opens.'' . . . The belief throughout the league is that Dallas
cornerback Deion Sanders will end up in Washington once the Cowboys
finally dump his salary and endlessly sore toe. The Redskins hope
to team him with Champ Bailey on the corners, with Darrell Green
coming off the bench . . . Bob McNair's new Houston team broke
ground on its state-of-the-art stadium. The $350 million palace is
supposed to be ready for the 2002 season and will have the NFL's
first retractable roof. When the Astrodome was built in 1962,
officials fired off .45s into the dirt to break ground; this time
they drank coffee in china cups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's the essence of what's wrong with free agency. Cleveland
loses Lomas Brown to the New York Giants, then turns around and
signs the guy Brown is replacing, Roman Oben, the Giants' ex-left
tackle. What did Brown have to say about that? ``Oben is a good,
young guy, but it just would've been a little while before I took
his job.'' . . . Bill Walsh met with Jerry Rice's agent, Jim
Steiner, Friday in California to try to break the deadlock on the
Hall of Fame receiver's contract situation. Rice is under contract
until 2004, but the 49ers want him to take a pay cut that will
reduce his cap number from its present $5.49 million. They want to
put much of his future money in incentives at a time when his
skills are beginning to erode. Rice is reticent, and faces being
fired if he doesn't agree to some sort of reduction. San Francisco
is $1.75 million under the cap but must clear another $250,000 by
April 15 to have enough money for its draft selections. Word is,
many of the parameters of a new deal have been worked out but not
the one that counts most _ money . . . The Oakland Raiders lost
another round in court in Sacramento last week but the NFL still
hasn't seen the last of Al Davis. A Superior Court judge ruled the
Raiders cannot leave Oakland, as Davis had threatened, but left the
door open for Davis to sue for damages. You can bet he will . . .
The Rams' Charley Armey has his team in an interesting draft
position this year _ last in every round after winning the Super
Bowl. In each of the Rams' previous five seasons in St. Louis, they
entered the draft in the same spot (No. 6), although they traded up
to No. 1 in 1997. ``It doesn't change what we do,'' said Armey.
``The philosophy you take is you start your draft with Round 2 when
you're drafting 31st.'' . . . Look for the Steelers to trade backup
fullback Richard Huntley to the Dolphins for draft choices and then
open negotiations with starter Jerome Bettis on a contract
extension. Bettis has one year left on his present deal. Pittsburgh
hopes to land at least a fourth-round choice for Huntley, plus a
conditional pick in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
