<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBB'S START HAS BEEN PERFECTLY SPLENDID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ While we were caught up in that pretty impressive run
by Tiger Woods, another storm of success started to percolate. It
has grown louder and more impressive with each swing of her club,
to the point that Karrie Webb is now the one stalking history,
though she preaches caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Nancy has to start worrying yet,'' said Webb, in
reference to the LPGA Tour record of five straight wins by Nancy
Lopez in 1978. Webb, 25, has won all three of her starts this
season, but is not playing in this week's Welch's/Circle K
Championship in Tucson. She will try to make it 4 for 4 when she
defends her title next week at the Standard Register Ping in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   She has been a serious presence on the LPGA Tour since her
rookie season in 1996 when she won four times. Webb triumphed three
times the next season, then twice more in 1998 and seemingly was a
logical choice as the Tour's best player. But nowhere in that mix
was there a major championship, a shortcoming that Annika
Sorenstam, Laura Davies, Juli Inkster, and Dottie Pepper _ among
other notables _ did not have to explain.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, that changed. Webb, after finishing second, 27th, and
14th in the first three majors of the season, came from behind to
win the du Maurier for her first major triumph. That it was one of
six victories in 1999 and contributed to her $1,591,959 windfall
for the season was not as important as the fact that it relieved
her of the burden of explaining to reporters why she had never won
a major. Never mind the fact she was still just four seasons into
her career; the question followed her like a dark cloud.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Now Webb is asked: When will you not win again?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, like Woods, the answer is simple. She won't win every
week. That goes without saying. But for now she is as close to a
sure thing as there is in golf. In her three wins this year _ the
Office Depot, Australian Women's Masters, Takefuji Classic _ Webb
has played 11 rounds and shot higher than 71 just once. Six rounds
have been 69 or better and twice she has fired a 65. And, as Woods
outplayed Ernie Els, Phil Mickelson, and Davis Love in his streak
of six straight wins, Webb has beaten Sorenstam, Inkster, and Lorie
Kane in her stretch. In other words, she's proven her talents
against the best.
</P>
<P>
   When she beat Sorenstam in a one-hole playoff at the Takefuji,
it reinforced the belief that Webb had replaced the 29-year-old
Swede as the game's queen. At the start of the 1998 campaign,
Sorenstam had won 12 times, with two majors, compared with Webb's
seven and zero. The last two seasons, however, have been advantage
Webb _ eight wins, including that major, compared with Sorenstam's
six and zero. Webb now has 19 career wins, Sorenstam 18, and if
last week's playoff in Hawaii signals anything, it is perhaps that
Sorenstam doesn't like the landscape as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want another chance,'' she said. ``I want another chance
against Karrie. I'll be there again and I'll be on top again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has not been the friendliest of weeks in state golfing
circles, as 15 local players were stripped of their amateur status
for violating US Golf Association rules against playing for prize
money. There is passion on both sides of this issue, but what comes
through loud and clear is a
``they're-doing-something-wrong-too-so-why-can't-we?'' mentality
that makes me feel like I'm refereeing a fight over the Nintendo
controls between my sons. That some very good people are involved
makes it even more unpleasant, but the worst part of all is that
the game of golf _ to which many of these gentlemen owe a lifetime
of thanks _ is a careless afterthought to many of them.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction between wagering and playing for prize money is
a gray area, some claim, which tells me they aren't sure on the
issue. So, I wonder, why not pick up the phone and call the USGA
and ask? Why take a chance? If you interpret a rule one way, and
the USGA interprets it another way, guess who wins?
</P>
<P>
   The issue isn't whether calcuttas (the mere mention of the word
makes me want to vomit) exist. They regrettably do. The issue isn't
why someone reported this particular tournament to authorities. The
issue isn't whether the USGA should revisit its rules on amateur
status. (It should.) The issue isn't about shades of hypocrisy that
exist in the game and some people who rule it. No doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a code of conduct that any legitimate golfer lives
by, a code that acknowledges that the Rules of Golf, as interpreted
by the USGA, are supreme and the one voice that matters. Notice I
said ``legitimate golfer,'' which has nothing to do with how well
one scores. It has everything to do with how well one treats the
game. Unfortunately, there are more and more people treating the
game poorly, thumbing their noses at it, using it as nothing more
than a vehicle to satisfy their thirst for what is commonly called
``action,'' which should never, ever be confused with what golf is
all about.
</P>
<P>
   The thrill of winning _ at the expense of honesty, integrity,
and fair play _ is all that matters to more and more people who
play golf. (Let's not call them ``golfers.'') So they play 200
rounds a year but hand in a dozen scores. So they carry a 10
handicap but can make a half-dozen birdies in any given round. So
they hustle some young, naive kid into playing in a member-guest,
where the parimutuel betting is huge, not because they like the kid
_ heck, they just met the week before _ but because the kid can
whip a 3-iron 210 yards off a tight lie.
</P>
<P>
   Golf is not fair, which means it mirrors life, a dangerous
reality that leads all of us to bend rules to suit our particular
need at the moment. Words can be twisted, rearranged, and taken out
of context in such an easy manner that believers can be easily made
disbelievers. But during a week in which many people have expressed
their outrage on both sides of the issue, one man's comment has
stuck with me: The game is always better to the player than the
player is to the game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Appleby, still fighting a daily battle to come to grips
with the tragic death of his wife following the 1998 British Open,
is hoping 2000 takes him into the upper echelon of his profession.
No one disputes his talent (he's won a tournament in each of the
last three seasons in the US), but ``it's time to get to another
level and figure out the buttons to get there and be able to do
it,'' said Appleby, who will be defending champ at the Shell
Houston Open next month. Of course, that road to the next level
goes through the major championships, at which Appleby has failed
miserably. He missed the cut in all four of them a year ago and in
12 career starts in the majors, he has made it into weekend play
just five times, a T-10 at the US Open in 1998 his best finish . .
. Call it penance for his ill-advised criticism of Arnold Palmer at
last year's Masters, because Mark Calcavecchia will not be in the
field at Augusta National for the first time since 1986. He could
not crack the Top 50 in world rankings, nor make it on any of the
other criteria. Brad Faxon and Olin Browne are two others who will
not be at Augusta, despite having won PGA Tour events last year.
(Tournament officials last year stopped a longtime practice of
exempting winners of PGA Tour events, leaning instead on the world
rankings.) Among those who held on to their Top 50 positions to
make it into the Masters: Paul Azinger, Shigeki Maruyama, and Kirk
Triplett . . . That infamous celebration at The Country Club's 17th
green during last September's Ryder Cup is still a sore spot. The
main characters _ Jose Maria Olazabal and Justin Leonard _
reportedly discussed the situation when they met at the American
Express Championship in Spain six weeks after Brookline, but they
were faced with more questions last week after being paired in the
third round of the Dubai Desert Classic. ``I accepted the apology
and everything is fine now,'' said Olazabal, who had to wait on his
birdie attempt while Leonard and teammates celebrated wildly
following the American's improbable birdie putt from more than 40
feet that all but wrapped up the victory. ``It's all in the past,''
said Leonard, who has been stung by criticism. Greg Norman, for
one, suggested that Leonard should have shown better sportsmanship
and conceded Olazabal's putt. ``I don't think it's any business of
Greg to get involved,'' said Leonard. ``What's done is done and
cannot be changed now. I certainly don't intend to say whether I
believe he's wrong or right.'' . . . In the final round of the 1999
Masters, Olazabal was faced with a testing birdie putt on the 13th
hole just moments after his playing partner, Norman, had drained a
dramatic eagle. Olazabal let the noise die down, then made his
birdie, a key to his victory since ``it stopped his momentum,''
said the Spaniard, who makes no comparison with the putt he
attempted just after Leonard's heroics. ``Different format,
different situation. They weren't the same at all.'' . . . From Chi
Chi Rodriguez, on why he is still grinding away on the Senior Tour
at age 64: ``When you retire, your wife gets twice as much husband
and half as much money.'' . . . As for Sergio Garcia, the young
Spaniard was asked if he had a girlfriend in the US or back home.
``Not yet. Too busy,'' he said . . . Johanna Head was all set to
make her debut on the LPGA Tour at the Takefuji Classic when she
got sick and had to be rushed to the hospital. Diagnosed with a
severe bladder infection, Head withdrew from the tournament,
rejecting a plan by her identical twin, Samantha. Seems Samantha,
who was going to caddie, offered to play and let Johanna carry the
bag. ``But she said she was in too much pain,'' said Samantha,
``and people would get suspicious. We could do it, though. There's
no way to tell us apart.'' . . . Lost in the glare of Webb's streak
has been the steady play of Janie Moodie. She has three Top 10
finishes already and seems poised to break through any week with
her first LPGA Tour triumph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
