<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TRADE STRENGTH FOR YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ This is not standard operating procedure for
a general manager of a team that won 95 games and its second
straight division title, to trade a two-time American League MVP
and count on kids to come through at three positions (third base,
center field, and right field).
</P>
<P>
   But Doug Melvin, the general manager of the Texas Rangers, made
the tough choices, trading slugger Juan Gonzalez a year before he
could have walked as a free agent, and pointing to the Red Sox as a
reason to trust in young players such as third baseman Mike Lamb
and outfielders Ruben Mateo and Gabe Kapler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we're a little bit younger,'' Melvin said last week while
sitting in his box at Charlotte County Stadium in Port Charlotte,
Fla., ``but look at the Red Sox. They came into the spring last
year and took a chance on Trot Nixon and Jason Varitek and Brian
Daubach. They gave them a chance, and they did the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season ended for the Rangers when they were swept in the
playoffs for the second straight time by the New York Yankees, a
shocking disappointment for owner Tom Hicks, whose hockey team, the
Dallas Stars, won a Stanley Cup but whose baseball team has scored
a total of two runs in six consecutive playoff defeats to the
Bombers. Overall, the Rangers have lost nine straight postseason
games, the fifth-longest streak in baseball history. (The Red Sox
are No. 1, having lost 13 in a row until Pedro Martinez beat the
Indians in Game 1, 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the year,'' Melvin said, ``we had eight free
agents. When you have eight free agents, you pretty well know your
roster will turn over. We were trying to manage the roster and give
ourselves some payroll flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Series had been over barely a week when Melvin dropped
the bombshell, trading Gonzalez, reliever Danny Patterson, and
backup catcher Gregg Zaun to the Tigers for five players:
lefthanded starter Justin Thompson, outfielder Kapler,
closer-in-training Francisco Cordero, backup catcher Bill Haselman,
and lefthanded pitching prospect Alan Webb.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing we did was trade Juan even before we got
involved with free agents,'' Melvin said, ``so we knew what kind of
players we would be getting for Juan and to help us make better
choices for what we still needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would have been more certainty in keeping Juan for this
season, but the larger risk was to let Juan go to free agency while
still trying to fill holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's intention was to keep third baseman Todd Zeile and
pitcher Aaron Sele. He balked initially at Zeile's request for a
three-year deal with a no-trade clause, eventually relented on both
counts, and thus was shocked when Zeile elected instead to sign
with the Mets, who didn't offer no-trade protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told his agent a year from now the Mets will be trying to
trade him to open $6 million or $7 million on their roster,''
Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Sele also turned down a three-year offer at $24 million and a
four-year package for $28 million from the Rangers, Melvin said.
Sele thought he'd landed a better four-year deal from the Orioles,
but when Baltimore pulled out at the last moment because of
concerns about his arm, Sele had to settle for a two-year, $15
million deal with Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd signed Sele, I don't think we would have had the money
to sign Kenny Rogers and Darren Oliver,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Those lefties, along with Thompson when he comes back from
shoulder surgery, will give the Ranger rotation a radically
different look. The last two seasons, Texas had an all-righty
rotation. In the AL West, Melvin sees Mo Vaughn, Darin Erstad, Jim
Edmonds, and Garret Anderson on the Angels, the A's stacked with
lefties (Ben Grieve, Matt Stairs, Eric Chavez, Jason Giambi), and
the Mariners adding John Olerud. Having some lefties with which to
counterpunch should help the Rangers, especially if another October
rematch with the Yankees is in the cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope Justin is ready by the first week of May,'' he said.
``We don't want him rushing back to justify the Juan trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Melvin said, is not to win down the road. With closer
John Wetteland able to become a free agent after this season _
Texas has no plans to offer him a new deal _ the idea is to make
another run this year, while being in good position to challenge
with the kids in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think we can win with this club,'' Melvin said. ``The
main thing is pitching good at the start of the year, to give our
positional guys a chance to get some at-bats on the big-league
level. Rogers, Darren Oliver, Rick Helling, Esteban Loiaza, and
Mark Clark are all established guys. And we're counting on our
bullpen, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez may hit 50 home runs in Detroit's new Comerica Park.
Melvin will gladly trade those bombs for the Rangers' first trip to
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but Worcester is becoming a cradle of baseball
scouting. J.P. Ricciardi (A's), Ted Lekas (Blue Jays), Joel
Grampietro (Rangers), Stan Saleski (Giants), Paul Turco (Giants),
Tom Clark (A's), Jack Gillis (Devil Rays), Bill Livesey (Devil
Rays), and Ray Fagnant (Red Sox) all have Worcester ties. Livesey,
a special assistant to Devil Rays GM Chuck LaMar, attended
Worcester Academy, and Fagnant is an Assumption College alumnus . .
. Why did the Red Sox lose bench coach Grady Little to the Indians?
Because Cleveland gave Little a two-year contract with an option
for a third year. The Sox offered only a one-year deal . . . Are
the Yankees Derek Jeter's team? ``He won't admit to it, but yeah,''
said Sox first baseman Mike Stanley, a former Yankee teammate of
Jeter. ``He's very humble, but I think he's just a great player. He
was a little more vocal the second time I was there with the
Yankees, in 1997. There's a core group there of Jeter, Tino
(Martinez), and Bernie (Williams). Those three guys, if there's
something going on, or somebody needs to say something in a
meeting, it'll be one of those guys. They're good friends, hang out
together. Take the age out of it with Derek. Look at the ability,
the leadership qualities. When he steps off the bus, it's like the
Beatles walked off the bus.'' Will Nomar Garciaparra ultimately
assume the same role for the Sox? ``Nomar does not have that
outward expression,'' Stanley said. ``He's not someone who's going
to yell and scream. And it's tough for a young guy to speak up when
there are so many older guys on the team, guys like (Bret)
Saberhagen. Nomar kind of sits back. He likes to lead by example,
the way he prepares for a game and goes about his business.'' . . .
Count Stanley among those Red Sox who believe Darren Lewis can
still play a vital role for this club. ``He's the best outfielder
on our team and one of the five best outfielders in our league,''
Stanley said. ``And he's worked incredibly hard with Tommy Harper
this spring to learn more and more about stealing a base, for when
he comes into a game as a pinch runner.'' . . . Twins GM Terry Ryan
has been giving the same answer to every GM who calls: He's not
trading pitcher Brad Radke, at least not during spring training . .
. Catcher Ben Davis was one of the Padres' most highly touted
prospects when he was promoted last season, but he ticked off
manager Bruce Bochy and veterans like Tony Gwynn when he refused to
go to the bullpen and catch. ``Looking back on it, it was a stupid
thing to do,'' Davis said. ``But I was just so frustrated at the
time. I didn't care what was going on. I just wanted to play. I
didn't want to go sit down there in the bullpen and catch. That's
just the competitive spirit that got the best of me that day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former PawSox regular Jon Nunnally, who spent a brief time with
the Sox before being traded last winter to the Mets for Jermaine
Allensworth, went on a tear last week, hitting four home runs in
three games . . . Former Sox reliever Lee Smith, the majors'
all-time leader in saves, is back in the game as a coach for the
Giants. He'll spend the season as pitching coach for Double A
Shreveport, his hometown. ``I just want to get back in the game and
work with kids,'' Smith said. ``I've been doing little things with
high schools and colleges where I live. I've thrown batting
practice, but I wear those high school kids out. They aren't used
to looking at forkballs.'' . . . The Cubs have pushed pitching
prodigy Kerry Wood's first spring start back to next weekend, which
means he'll likely open the season on the disabled list. ``When I
said we are going to be cautious with him, I can't state that
enough,'' manager Don Baylor said. ``It could mean May 1, who
knows? Any type of pain, and he is off the field.'' Wood plans to
abandon his slider, which put too much stress on his surgically
repaired elbow . . . With Reds GM Jim Bowden saying the club has
been rebuffed in its attempts to deal for Radke or Jose Rosado of
the Royals, former Sox pitcher Mark Portugal has emerged as the
leading candidate to become the team's fifth starter. Portugal's
abrupt release by the Sox at the end of the season was not
baseball-related, the club's denials to the contrary . . . The
Braves will have a decision to face this offseason regarding John
Smoltz, who is to undergo Tommy John tendon-transplant surgery on
his pitching elbow. The Braves hold an $8 million option on Smoltz
for next season. The guess here is they will exercise it. . .
Florida's Josh Beckett, the 19-year-old righthander who was the No.
2 pick overall in last June's draft, put on a show in his spring
debut, topping out at 96 miles an hour while showing terrific
composure during two perfect innings against the Royals . . . Jeff
Frye, whose future seems a dead end in Boston, would love to return
to the Rangers and play in Arlington, where he lives, but that
isn't going to happen. He's being paid too much ($2.5 million) and
manager Johnny Oates hasn't forgotten the time Frye went on a radio
show and ripped him for a lack of playing time. Frye may have more
hope that the Phillies take an interest. The Phillies' faith in
Marlon Anderson appears shaky, and they could be in the market for
a second baseman . . . An agent on Garciaparra's $23.5 million
contract, with two option years that could make the package worth
$45 million: ``Dan Duquette and the Sox absolutely stole
Garciaparra. I give Dan credit. Nomar should have posters made up
saying, ``Hi, my agent cost me $36 million.' '' . . . Maury Wills
is in Expos camp as a base-running instructor . . . The Angels'
proposed starting rotation of Ken Hill, Tom Candiotti, Kent
Mercker, Ramon Ortiz, and Jarrod Washburn were a combined 22-30
last year. Maybe that's why Hill isn't talking to the media now . .
. Clip and save: After a series of meetings with franchise anchor
Alex Rodriguez, Mariners CEO Harold Lincoln proclaimed the club
would not trade the star shortstop this season, even though
Rodriguez can walk as a free agent after the season. Said Lincoln,
who is head of Nintendo USA: ``This decision is part head and part
heart. I'm as comfortable with it as any decision I've ever made as
a businessman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
