<SLUG> BC-BKC-ATLANTIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNGRY OWLS CAPTURE CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
 10-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Four consecutive defeats to the University of
Massachusetts. A heartbreaking loss to Rhode Island last season on
a buzzer-beating trey by Lamar Odom. To say Temple had had enough
of losing in the Atlantic 10 championship game is like saying Santa
Claus could stand to lose a pound or two.
</P>
<P>
   It is also an understatement to say St. Bonaventure entered its
first A-10 championship game in 16 seasons with a monumental task
on its hands.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth-ranked Owls grabbed the first 16 rebounds of the game;
hit 8 of their first 10 3-pointers; held the Bonnies to .077
shooting from the floor over the first 11:30; and raced to a
28-point first-half lead on their way to a 65-44 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Temple was too deep, too talented, and too determined to lose
another title game. With the chance of gaining a No. 1 seed in the
NCAA tournament, the Owls put together one of the most dominant
first-half efforts in A-10 tournament history, making the second
half a formality.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament most outstanding player Quincy Wadley scored 16
points and Mark Karcher added 15 to lead Temple (26-5), which won
its first title since 1990 and is now tied with UMass for the most
A-10 titles (five).
</P>
<P>
   With No. 1-ranked Cincinnati and No. 2 Stanford losing last
week, the No. 3 Owls will most certainly earn a No. 1 seed.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph culminates a dominant season for Temple, which lost
just two conference games. ``I think in the first half we executed
real good. That was the key,'' said coach John Chaney, whose team
led, 37-12, at halftime and maintained control in the second half
despite allowing the Bonnies to cut the lead to 50-36 with 6:08
left.
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure (21-9) was the only team to beat Temple this
season after trailing the Owls at the half. Saturday night, the
Owls' first-half binge was too large to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like they were waiting for this one a long time,''
said St. Bonaventure coach Jim Baron, ``and they showed it
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in recent title defeats Chaney made his team watch the
victors celebrate before retreating to the locker room. Even before
the tournament, players said memories of Odom's winning shot
haunted them all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was heartbreaking what happened to us last year,'' said
Wadley. ``We didn't want to go through that again.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what St. Bonaventure was stacked up against. To make
matters worse, Bonnies power forward Caswell Cyrus battled a
stomach virus and didn't start. He entered with 16:34 left in the
first half but wasn't much of a factor.
</P>
<P>
   That and a solid Temple defensive front led to the Bonnies
missing 12 of their first 13 shots. The Owls, meanwhile, sank seven
consecutive treys, including one by Wadley with 6:24 left that gave
Temple a 32-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, we were playing good defense, too,'' said St. Bonaventure
senior guard Tim Winn (9 points). ``They were just making shots.
When you look up and it's 23-2, all you can think is `How do you
get back in it?' And you start taking desperation shots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who will play them in the tournament better be really
guarded,'' said Baron. ``They're a difficult team to prepare for in
a week. They played like this, and we get them twice a year in the
regular season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
