r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     03-12 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREWERS: LOPES JUST WHAT WE NEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX, Ariz. - Milwaukee Brewers general manager Dean Taylor
says he and player-personnel vice president David Wilder went into
their job interview with Davey Lopes last October ``with no
preconceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: They decided to ignore everything they'd heard
about Lopes, the former Dodgers All-Star who'd been interviewed and
turned down for major-league managing jobs by seven clubs in seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   They'd heard Lopes, 53, was gruff and grumpy, honest to the
point of verbal brutality, bitter about never getting the chance he
sought. In short, a bad interview.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brewers CEO Wendy Selig-Prieb, daughter of the baseball
commissioner, was committed to bringing in a long and diverse list
of applicants, so what could Taylor and Wilder do with Lopes but
listen?
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Lopes had nothing to lose after so many
disappointments, so what could he do in the Brewers' office but
relax and be himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out of it asking ourselves why nobody had given Davey
Lopes the opportunity to manage before,'' Taylor said this week as
he watched Lopes manage the Brewers in a Cactus League game against
the Arizona Diamondbacks. ``He convinced us he had the
communication skills, the motivational skills and the teaching
skills that we were looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopes supposed the answer to ``why?'' wasn't because he's a
minority - the Rhode Island native has Portuguese, African-American
and Irish heritage - but ``maybe because of my style of play
(scrappy), because I'm outspoken, because I'm too honest.''
</P>
<P>
   In his office at Maryvale Baseball Park, Lopes let out a
staccato laugh at the notion he could be (begin ital)too(end ital)
honest.
</P>
<P>
   Too honest for some general managers, who prefer acquiescent
diplomats in the manager's office? Possibly.
</P>
<P>
   Too honest for his players? Never.
</P>
<P>
   It's turning out that Lopes' blunt talk is exactly what the
Brewers players wanted to hear this spring as the team of Jeromy
Burnitz and 24 other guys tries to reverse seven straight losing
seasons under Phil Garner.
</P>
<P>
   Garner raised eyebrows in 1998 when he yanked Jose Vina from a
game and chewed him out in front of the team after the second
baseman failed to run out a ground ball. It was the first time the
Brewers had seen the manager do that.
</P>
<P>
   Lopes won't wait seven years to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy's honest and tells you what to expect, I don't
think you can ask for anything more,'' said Marquis Grissom,
Milwaukee's 32-year-old center fielder and leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to sit there wondering, `What's this guy
thinking about me?' '' said relief pitcher Jim Bruske, the former
Dodger who was a Padre when Lopes was the San Diego first-base
coach from 1995-99. ``Davey's the kind of guy who doesn't care what
people think of him. He'll tell you what he thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one way to motivate a clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we don't have to see him ticked off,'' said third
baseman Jose Hernandez, who first encountered his new manager in
1991 when Lopes was the Texas Rangers' first-base coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers' bus broke down on the two-hour drive back from a
game in Tucson the other day. Lopes later remarked to a club
executive that he was surprised the inconvenienced players stayed
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The executive said he wasn't surprised at all. After all, Lopes
was on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should rename it the Straight Talk Express. The name
is available again.
</P>
<P>
   Lopes breaks the manager mold. He wears a graying goatee, giving
him a vaguely menacing Lenny Bruce look. He showed up for a
post-hiring appearance in Milwaukee wearing a beret. He listens to
jazz in his office.
</P>
<P>
   But why is straight talk from a baseball manager considered
remarkable?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess guys are reluctant to tell (players) something they
might not want to hear,'' Lopes said before batting practice the
other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be a politician. They might not like what I say, but
they'll appreciate that I'm telling the truth. That's all I
expected as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopes was the Dodgers' second baseman and base-stealing leadoff
hitter for parts of 10 seasons, spanning Walter Alston and Tom
Lasorda, appearing in four World Series and capping his L.A. career
with the 1981 victory over the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came along, the guy in charge had a lot more power. If
the manager told you to do something, you did it,'' Lopes said.
``Today you get asked, `Why?' You've got to be a psychologist.
You've got to be able to talk to these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of Lopes as a screamer instead of a talker puzzles
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe people thought I was going to come in with an iron fist,
you know? They don't know me,'' he said. ``If I'm what a lot of
people think I am, I'm setting myself up for failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am outspoken on issues. I believe we, as minorities, have to
speak out on certain issues, because if we don't nobody will. (But)
I'm not going to do anything to embarrass the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Embarrass the Brewers? Embarrass them worse than seven losing
seasons in a row?
</P>
<P>
   Something different, like a little straight talk, couldn't hurt
in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some people thought he was too outspoken, too brusk, too
brash,'' said Taylor, the GM. ``But that's exactly what we were
looking for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
