<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARKLEY'S SEASON A STORM OF CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The circus generally comes to Madison Square Garden
in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But this year it came a few weeks early, cleverly disguised as a
basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   How else can you explain the bizarre atmosphere that surrounded
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's Big East tournament championship game between the
University of Connecticut and St. John's?
</P>
<P>
   Normally, a game between the Huskies and Red Storm in March
would offer enough entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. Not with St. John's and its traveling soap opera
involved. The spin around the Garden centered on St. John's guard
Erick Barkley, who has had an ongoing dispute with the NCAA over
eligibility issues ranging from the type of car he owned to how his
education at Maine Central Institute was financed.
</P>
<P>
   That was nothing compared with what happened in St. John's
semifinal against Miami Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Storm came out for the second half, Barkley wasn't
with them. And when he reemerged three minutes into the second half
of a game St. John's won, 58-57, the campus minister to the
athletic department, Rev. James Mahrrer, accompanied him and was
holding his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's trainer Ron Linfonte then wrapped Barkley's left
wrist and he returned to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? ``Upset stomach,'' was the official team response
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, Barkley and teammate Bootsy Thornton had a shouting
match that turned physical at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Long after the game, an explanation of sorts emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I put this?'' said Barkley. ``Tomorrow's game, I don't
think I'm going to be attending it. I'm taking a leave of absence
from the team. I don't know if I'll be here. That's all I've got to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, we come to Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's episode of the soap opera.
Thornton scores 22 points and is named the tournament's Most
Outstanding Player. Barkley adds 19. St. John's wins its first Big
East tournament title since 1986 with a solid 80-70 victory.
Everyone smiles and says, ``What problem?''
</P>
<P>
   All of this, of course, after St. John's spent Saturday morning
trying to minimize the damage. Reportedly, the Red Storm had two
statements prepared _ one with Barkley back, one without him.
</P>
<P>
   After the celebrations and dances on the court, the Red Storm
were all one big, happy family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a day, quite a week, quite a month, quite a year,'' said
St. John's coach Mike Jarvis. ``This team is a family. We had a
little family dispute (Friday) night. One of our family members
probably redefined what a leave of absence is. This is a family.
When we fight and when we have arguments we have a passion that
sometimes carries over. But we care about each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what next week will bring? The NCAA is pouring through
the St. John's records and reportedly talking to people.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Jarvis's future? He has never hidden that fact that
his goal is to coach in the NBA, preferably with the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   With the NCAA continuing to probe St. John's, don't be surprised
if Jarvis takes a hard look at NBA openings this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The end result is hard to determine. St. John's, much to
Jarvis's credit, played better than expected during the regular
season despite the turmoil. The Red Storm developed a
circle-the-wagons mentality.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm have proven they can beat any team in the country.
As proof, just look at their victory over Duke at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   But what must worry Jarvis is the uncertainty in his own locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first round between Thornton and Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   With the stakes much higher, it will be interesting to see how
St. John's conducts itself.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's game was a dress rehearsal for the NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The media attention will increase and the questions will not go
away.
</P>
<P>
   How St. John's deals with it will determine just how long its
season will continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
