<HEADLINE>
CORNELL OUSTS HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ITHACA, N.Y. _ Facing a big, physical team in the playoffs . . .
on the road . . . before probably the most hostile crowd in
college. Harvard knew it was in for a rough time _ and that's what
it got.
</P>
<P>
   The pounding, hitting, and pushing finally got to the Crimson,
as the Big Red erased a 3-2 third-period deficit with two quick
strikes to win, 4-3, Saturday &UR;  &LR; night and sweep the best-of-three
ECAC quarterfinal series at Lynah Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell (15-12-2) is off to Lake Placid, N.Y., for an ECAC
semifinal match; Harvard can start making plans for spring break.
</P>
<P>
   The Crimson, who lost the opener, 4-3, here Friday night,
concluded their first season under coach Mark Mazzoleni at 11-17-2.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Prestifilippo, in playing his final college hockey game,
came up with a solid 20-save effort, but the two third-period goals
by Cornell will linger in the senior's memory for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the third period tied, 2-2, Harvard grabbed the lead at
4:41 when Chris Bala scored on a wrist shot from the left circle.
</P>
<P>
   But in lightning time, the lead and the season were gone. Denis
Ladouceur tied the game at 6:29 when his shot along the ice beat
Prestifilippo on the right. Just 25 seconds later, Krzysztof
Wieckowski gained control of the puck in front of Prestifilippo and
lifted a backhander into the net for the winning strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out in two, but we could have won this thing in two,''
said Prestifilippo. ``Forget about three games, we could have won
this in two games. I'm proud of how we played, a couple of plays
were the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzoleni lifted Prestifilippo with 1:27, but Harvard couldn't
beat goaltender Ian Burt (23 saves).
</P>
<P>
   Prestifilippo blamed nobody but himself for the tying and
winning goals. ``(The tying goal) went in, it was a problem,'' he
said. ``But the last one was a back door play, and I'd like to have
it back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Crimson, playing aggressive from th opening faceoff, struck
first. Bala, skating along the right boards, tossed a centering
pass in front of the net that Jeff Stonehouse deflected past Burt
at 5:26.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell tied it, 1-1, when Doug Stienstra's wrister from behind
a screen on the left side beat Prestifilippo at 11:38. Dave Kozier
assisted on the power-play strike.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard regained the lead at 17:32 when Brett Noval deflected
Tim Stay's wrist shot from the right side into the net.
</P>
<P>
   But Cornell evened it, 2-2, just 22 second later on defenseman
Rick Sacchetti's second goal of the season. Ladouceur and Stienstra
had the assists.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzoleni liked the strides Harvard took during this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well enough to win, but we broke down in crucial
times and they capitalized on them,'' said Mazzoleni. ``Our team
played our hearts out for six periods, and a lot of teams could not
have hung in there, it's not an easy environment to play, but we
kept our focus from the beginning to the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
