<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 OPENER HARDLY VINTAGE FOR AYALA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The 1999 Fighter of the Year didn't get much of a
start on 2000 or much of a payday for the night he earned that
honor.
</P>
<P>
   World Boxing Association bantamweight champion Paulie Ayala
recently was accorded the same honor once won by the likes of
Muhammad Ali, Joe Louis, Rocky Marciano, Marvin Hagler, Thomas
Hearns, Ray Robinson, Ray Leonard, and many other legends when Ring
magazine presented the Texas bantamweight with the belt it has been
handing out yearly since 1928. Ayala was named Fighter of the Year
in large part for the night he upset Johnny Tapia to win the title
last June, a fight for which he was paid the princely sum of
$60,000 _ before taxes and his manager's cut.
</P>
<P>
   That was supposed to be the start of something big for the
soft-spoken Ayala, who is a fighter only on the nights he is paid
to be one. The rest of the time, he's a quiet family man,
son-in-law of a minister who says, ``He is what a father prays and
dreams his daughter will marry.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, that's not a fighter, but in Ayala's case an
exception can be made because he is what promoter Bob Arum calls
simply ``a really nice guy.'' Not to mention a nice little boxer.
</P>
<P>
   But boxing is a business for really nasty guys. Or really
maladjusted guys. Or really aggressive guys. Normally, it is not
considered a business for really nice guys _ not if those nice guys
want to stay in one piece.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ayala is all Arum says he is as a man, and if he turns into
all the promoter hopes he'll be as a fighter, he has the potential
to be the next hot Hispanic property in Arum's stable.
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to be the case after Ayala eschewed the
opportunity to take batting practice on an unqualified opponent in
his first title defense after beating Tapia. Instead, Ayala put his
new title on the line last October against No. 1-ranked Saohin
Sorthanikul, a fighter most bantamweights had been trying to avoid.
It was a tough fight, but that was expected, and Ayala gutted it
out, winning a clear decision.
</P>
<P>
   What was not expected was what happened last weekend in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala was heavily favored to defend his title against a kid from
Denmark named Johnny Bredhal, who admittedly was 45-1 but had
fought outside of Denmark only twice, once in a loss to Wayne
McCullough in 1995 in Belfast. So it was expected that the 1999
Fighter of the Year would launch his 2000 campaign with a bang.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was nearly a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   After 12 tough rounds, Ayala was still bantamweight champion but
by the slimmest of margins, winning a majority decision that was
not popular. Ayala had been cut under the right eye and on his
lower lip by a guy who had been paid only $10,000 to challenge for
a world title. Ayala's status as 1999 Fighter of the Year seemed to
have meant little to Bredhal but a bit more to the two judges who
voted for him.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Ayala was a winner in the end, and unlike many
boxers, he was able to keep his disappointment in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``At home, it's still the same and I'm still the same,'' said
Ayala (30-1) of his status as a world champion. ``I'm still daddy
and husband. I'm more recognized now wherever I go, but I was very,
very surprised to even be nominated for Fighter of the Year, let
alone win it. Getting that belt was overwhelming because of the
people who have won it before me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala wins the hard way in boxing, by going the distance and
exchanging flurries. He has registered only 12 knockouts in his 30
victories. For a guy who can't really punch, that is not
necessarily the wisest course of action, but it is Ayala's style
and it is what has made him an exciting attraction and a fighter
Arum believes can make big money despite being a little man.
</P>
<P>
   It is also why a rematch with Tapia is much anticipated this
year, as is a unification fight against International Boxing
Federation champion Tim Austin, because in both cases promoters
know Ayala will come to do one thing: swap punches.
</P>
<P>
   Against Bredhal, Ayala tried much the same tactics that worked
so well against Tapia but with considerably less success, though he
did drop the challenger in the second round. Though many in the
crowd at Mandalay Bay felt the underdog had put the bite on the
champion, Ayala reacted to the decision the way he does to most
things, with calm acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied with the win,'' Ayala said. ``The knockdown was
very substantial but I wasn't able to catch him to the body the way
I wanted. I felt I landed the heavier blows but I take my hat off
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of catching him to the body, Ayala caught Bredhal at the
wire, winning the final three rounds on one card and the final six
on another to pull out a slim victory. For 1999's Fighter of the
Year, it was a win that made clear what he already knew about the
boxing life he has chosen.
</P>
<P>
   The Ring belt was for last year. Last weekend was the dawning of
a new year with new fights, and he found a way to win the first of
them. Maybe not the way he or Arum would have liked, but he did
what counts for a prizefighter. The Fighter of Last Year won his
first fight of the new year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Boxing Writers Association of America originally named
Evander Holyfield its fighter of the decade, but a second vote was
demanded by Thomas Hauser, Ali's biographer and an admirer of Roy
Jones Jr.'s. Somehow, Jones nosed out Holyfield, 6-4, by a vote of
the association's executive committee. I'm on that committee but
don't ask me how it happened. Don't you have to beat a formidable
opponent sometime in 10 years to be Fighter of the Decade? . . .
Veteran trainer Teddy Atlas is again preparing Junior Jones for an
April 29 shot at the IBF featherweight title held by Paul Ingle.
Atlas originally signed on to prepare Jones for what they thought
would be a shot at Prince Naseem Hamed Saturday &UR;  &LR; night for $500,000
but that negotiation collapsed and Atlas planned to return to
ESPN2's broadcast booth and leave Jones alone. But the former world
champion was persistent, calling Atlas several times a day until he
finally agreed to prepare him for a fight that could get Jones back
on track for a big payday down the line. ``I forced myself to get
back into it a little bit,'' Atlas said. ``But Junior is a good
kid. He knows this is it. He understands my way of thinking and
that made it easier for me. He knows that when it's all said and
done, all that counts is what he did. All that counts will be his
record.'' In Atlas's opinion, Hamed was beatable if Jones had
anything left, and he believes the same applies to Ingle, who gave
Hamed hell for 11 rounds before being stopped. ``This is a winnable
fight,'' Atlas said. ``Ingle wastes a lot of movement from too far
away. You've got to sniper him. You've got to potshot him and then
feint him and run him into a punch. Junior can do that.'' He's more
likely to do it with Atlas in his corner . . . The Jones-Ingle
fight is on the undercard of the Lennox Lewis-Michael Grant
heavyweight showdown at Madison Square Garden . . . Atlas will be
in a unique situation March 24 when he not only broadcasts ESPN2's
fight card from the Blue Horizon in Philadelphia but also works the
corner of his young fighter, Elvir Muriqui, while miked. Atlas will
commentate from the corner as the fight is in progress as well as
advise his fighter between rounds. ``I'm a little worried about
this,'' Atlas said. ``It will get a lot of attention for my
fighter, but if it don't go perfect, that puts me on the spot.''
Don't bet against Atlas or his Albanian prospect . . . Felix
Trinidad and David Reid drew a disappointing 200,000 buys on
Showtime Event Television, leading Trinidad's rival promoter, Arum,
to say, ``What happened demonstrated that Trinidad is a
non-attraction. From the standpoint of marketability, he gives a
promoter a license to lose money. That card will lose $6 million-$8
million and it did nothing to help a Trinidad-(Oscar) De La Hoya
rematch.'' That's because there won't be one right away. De La Hoya
and Shane Mosley will fight June 17 at either the Staples Center in
Los Angeles or at Mandalay Bay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ex-light heavyweight champion Virgil Hill gets yet another title
shot April 8 in Paris when he squares off with World Boxing
Association cruiserweight champion Fabrice Tiozzo. On the same
card, WBA super middleweight champion Byron Mitchell defends vs.
Bruno Girard for the Acaries brothers, France's biggest promoters .
. . Here's some perspective for you. Remember that war Erik Morales
and Marco Antonio Barrera put on Feb. 19 on HBO? They earned
$200,000 each, while the big-name heavyweights split millions for
doing nothing but look at each other for 12 rounds. You might want
to ask if there is no justice, but you already know the answer if
you've been around boxing for long . . . Speaking of Morales and
Barrera, don't expect a rematch soon. Morales says he has fought
his last fight at 122 pounds and Barrera insists he's not moving up
to chase him. ``I think the public deserves a rematch from us but
it will have to be at 126,'' Morales said. ``I can no longer make
the weight in this division.'' Morales will move up to
featherweight while Barrera retains his World Boxing Organization
portion of the super bantamweight title because only Morales's
World Boxing Council portion was at stake. The WBO made an
intersting move several days after the fight by declaring it would
not vacate its title because, ``This kid was screwed,'' according
to Francisco Valcarcel, president of the WBO. Valcarcel called it a
``miscarriage of justice.'' So Barrera remains the WBO champion
despite losing and says he has no interest in moving above the
122-pound limit to face a guy he just beat . . . Morales hopes to
land a shot with WBO featherweight champion Hamed, who fought
ex-junior featherweight champion Vuyani Bungu Saturday &UR;  &LR; night . . .
Thomas Hearns claims he'll make his last appearance in the ring
March 25 at Joe Louis Arena to defend the International Boxing
Organization cruiserweight title against Crawford Ashley. At 41,
it's long been time for the Hitman to stop getting hit, but he
wanted to go out a champion, and with the proliferation of belts
these days, he found one he could win. Now he says he'll defend it
one time in his hometown, where his boxing career began decades ago
in the basement of the Kronk Gym. Hopefully, Hearns (59-4-1, 46
KOs) will go out with one last knockout to remind the world he was
once one of the most feared punchers in the sport . . . Rumor is
there's a new power struggle going on for control of Mike Tyson,
with adviser Shelly Finkel being undermined by James Prince, the
rap music mogul who took over the career of Floyd Mayweather Jr.
and a half-dozen other fighters, including WBA welterweight
champion James Page.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The John Ruiz-Holyfield title fight will not be May 20. It also
won't be May 27, as Don King told the Globe weeks ago. Now it's
been put off until June 3 and will likely have the WBA portion of
the heavyweight title at stake because that organization is poised
to strip Lewis for refusing to fight its No. 1 contender . . . New
Bedford super middleweight Scott Pemberton is rated No. 13 by the
WBA . . . Word is, Dana Rosenblatt returns to the ring next month
at Foxwoods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 0211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
