<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN READY FACES TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The bloom came off More Than Ready's rose in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a cinch to be 1999 2-year-old champion _ and Kentucky
Derby winter book favorite _ after winning the first five races of
his career, More Than Ready finished third, beaten just a
half-length, in the Belmont Futurity Sept. 19. He then flopped in
the Champagne Oct. 9, finishing fifth as the choice, beaten 14
lengths. More Than Ready was then pulled out of training. In the
span of three weeks, he lost the 2-year-old crown (which went to
Breeders' Cup Juvenile winner Anees) and prominent status for the
2000 Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But More Than Ready is fighting back. He gained a dead-heat for
first (with Summer Note) in the 7-furlong Hutchinson Stakes Jan. 29
at Gulfstream, and he gets an acid test Sunmday in the $750,000
Louisiana Derby at Fair Grounds. Trainer Todd Pletcher shipped More
Than Ready out of Florida for Sunday's event, and, surprisingly,
the race came up far tougher than Saturday's more prestigious
Florida Derby. Both Captain Steve, winner of the Hollywood Futurity
and trained by Bob Baffert, and Exchange Rate, winner of the Risen
Star at Fair Grounds and trained by D. Wayne Lukas, were entered in
Louisiana. Baffert also intends to start promising allowance horse
Tribunal at Fair Grounds. Tough crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be more pleased with the way the colt has
trained,'' said Pletcher via conference call Tuesday after
witnessing More Than Ready drill 5 furlongs in 1:00 3/5 at Hialeah
Monday. ``He's literally push-button. He's an easy horse to train.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was delighted with his effort in the Hutchinson. Ultimately,
we decided on the Louisiana Derby, instead of the Florida Derby,
because it's a mile and one-16th, not 1 1/8 miles (the Florida
Derby distance). It's a more gradual progression from his first
race.''
</P>
<P>
   More Than Ready is by Southern Halo, out of a Woodman mare.
While he has distance breeding, he has high speed and has looked
like a sprinter on the track. Whether he can handle the 1 1/4 miles
of the May 6 Kentucky Derby is a major question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like everyone else, I'm waiting to find out,'' said
Pletcher. ``Surely, he's a gifted sprinter. He's a natural speed
horse. He's been so brilliant sprinting that people are skeptical
he can go long. But his pedigree says he can handle a distance,
maybe even a distance on grass. He definitely has the pedigree.
What makes me think he can go long is that he is a kind horse. You
have to place him forwardly, but he's not a one-dimensional speed
horse, he doesn't need the lead, and that will allow him to stretch
out.''
</P>
<P>
   More Than Ready, who is regularly ridden by John Velazquez,
needs a good showing Sunday to progress toward the Kentucky Derby,
but he doesn't have to be sensational.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to the Triple Crown,'' said Pletcher, who
trains More Than Ready for owner James Scatuorchio. ``The Louisiana
Derby will do him more good than another 7-furlong race. He doesn't
have to win it to make it to the Blue Grass (at Keeneland April 15)
or Wood Memorial (at Aqueduct the same day).
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a two-turn race under his belt. He's not going
to be too far off the pace, unless somebody goes crazy. I don't
want to take him out of his natural style. To me, it's an
advantage. He has rateable speed, and I'm not going to take away
the natural speed that he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've left what appears to be an easier race in the Florida
Derby to come to a tougher race. It's too early to rate the Triple
Crown horses. No one knew about Charismatic last year, and he came
within a length of winning the Triple Crown, and became Horse of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a solid crop. They've been running fast races, and
taking turns winning. We're not ducking anybody, and we're not
chasing anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   More Than Ready was put on the shelf after developing a fever.
By the time the Breeders' Cup rolled around in November, the former
star had become an afterthought. But if he can regain the form he
displayed early in his career, he can become an exciting player in
a 3-year-old campaign that sorely needs one. It should also be
remembered that no Breeders' Cup Juvenile winner has ever won the
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been an advantage to not run in the Breeders'
Cup,'' said Pletcher. ``I don't know exactly why he didn't run his
race in the Champagne, but we have a fresh horse now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rockingham Park has added two stakes to its 2000 schedule, and
will introduce the Brass Monkey starter handicap series. Rock has
beefed up the racing schedule over the July 4 weekend, adding the
Rockingham Park Derby, to be raced at a mile and one-16th July 2,
and the Rockingham Park Distaff Handicap, at 6 furlongs July 3. In
addition, the Lilac Stakes, run at a mile and one-16th on the turf,
has been renamed the Rockingham Park Oaks, and will be run July 1.
The schedule is designed to build toward the $75,000 Rockingham
Breeders' Cup, at a mile and one-16th on the turf for fillies and
mares July 4. The highlights of the 100-card meeting, to be held
June 11-Sept. 24, remain the Grade 3, $200,000 New Hampshire
Sweepstakes June 24, and the $100,000 Spicy Living Sweepstakes Aug.
6. The Brass Monkey series, named for a popular New England horse
of yesteryear who was known for his late charges to victory,
consists of seven races, open to claiming horses, and will begin at
a mile and one-16th, for a purse of $8,500 on June 24. The distance
and purse will grow with each race through the final on Sept. 23,
to be contested at a grueling 2 miles and 40 yards, for a purse of
$12,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
