<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NORTHRIDGE-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N. ARIZONA HOLDS OFF NORTHRIDGE IN OT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSOULA, Mont. - It was one final amazing, stomach-twisting run
in a hard-to-believe season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge men's basketball team gave it a go in
its second serious bid to make the NCAA Tournament in the last four
years, but the Matadors just didn't have enough in an 85-81
overtime loss to Northern Arizona in the Big Sky Conference
tournament final Saturday night at Dahlberg Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The last of the 3,316 fans who stuck around to see the wild
finish had to collect their breath when it was over. The teams, who
tied at 70 in regulation, combined for 16 points in the final
minute, and NAU had to make two free throws in the last three
seconds to secure its second tournament title since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad somebody has to lose a game like this,'' CSUN coach
Bobby Braswell said. ``I'm very, very proud of this team ... not
only for the way (the players) fought back, but the way they fought
back this whole season.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Matadors must wait until tonight to see if their season
is over. They are hoping for an NIT bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all anticipating going to practice on Monday, getting
ready for the next (game),'' Braswell said.
</P>
<P>
   NAU had the tournament savvy, playing in its third consecutive
tournament final, but it was the Matadors who showed grit down the
stretch. Northridge (20-10) scored the final nine points of
regulation to force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   And CSUN had a chance to win in the final seconds, but Markus
Carr's running jumper in the lane bounced off the back of the rim.
</P>
<P>
   The shot was similar to one Carr made in CSUN's 69-66 win over
NAU at Northridge in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I about had a heart attack,'' said NAU guard Adam Lopez. ``I
thought it was going in.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ross Land, NAU's all-time 3-point shooter and the school's
second-leading scorer all-time, thought his career might be over
when the ball left Carr's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just froze,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting, because Land had the night's most magic moment.
He sank an 85-foot shot at the halftime buzzer to give the third-
seeded Lumberjacks (20-10) a 38-29 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Land, the tournament MVP, was 5 of 9 on 3-point attempts and had
20 points. He played all 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I happy to see (Land) gone? You bet,'' said CSUN forward
Brian Heinle. ``I wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinle, who made the all-tournament team, had 14 points.
However, he did not make a shot in overtime. The Matadors were
lifted in the extra period by Carr, who had the team's last eight
points.
</P>
<P>
   Carr played 42 minutes. Sure, he regretted missing the final
shot in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same play. This time it didn't drop for me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell: ``There was no question whether we were going to run
(the play). This doesn't come down to Markus winning or losing the
game. Northern Arizona won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   NAU coach Mike Adras also thought the Lumberjacks made a
statement after they started conference play 0-4 and rallied to win
14 of their final 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the best team in the Big Sky,'' Adras said. ``I'm
convinced of that. We proved it. (We) did it on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks set a tournament single-game record with 16
3-pointers. They made an amazing 49 percent of their attempts from
beyond the arc in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona, which shot 62 percent in its semifinal win
over Eastern Washington, made 53 percent of its shots against
Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping they wouldn't be able to shoot the ball well two
nights in a row and they did,'' Braswell said. ``You have to give
them a lot of credit. Ross Land, (Dan) McClintock, those guys are
veteran guys who have been to the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Adras thinks Northridge belongs in the postseason, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our conference should do the best it can to get (CSUN) an NIT
bid,'' he said. ``That team deserves it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
