<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN'S INJURY IS A CHILLING REMINDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the best player in college basketball, Cincinnati's Kenyon
Martin, went down in a heap the other day shattering his right
fibula and ripping several ligaments in the leg one immediately
thought of the widespread impact of such an untimely injury.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it probably wipes out any chance of the Bearcats
winning the national championship and even figures to deny the team
a No. 1 seeding in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   And for another, it reaffirms once again what agents and
advisers are constantly telling talented college underclassmen and
even a select group of high school seniors that they should turn
pro and take the money rather than risk a serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Martin himself had benefited from staying at
Cincinnati, improving dramatically as a senior and enhancing his
status to the point he might have been the first player selected in
this year's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   He still might be, or at least might be a lottery pick, but
there also is a possibility that he might go lower because teams
might be fearful of his now uncertain physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Guys who have torn up their legs and stand 6-foot-9 and weigh
240 pounds aren't exactly sure bets to retain their former skills,
much less be able to withstand the demanding rigors of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of Kenyon Martin serves as a chilling reminder of the
risks that can curse an extraordinary athlete who, for one reason
or another, decides to remain in college and pass up an opportunity
to become an instant multi-millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Those who favor jocks finishing their college education will
tell you that the four years spent in the halls of academia will
give them the opportunity to grow mentally, physically and
spiritually and also will prepare them for a vocation to fall back
on when their athletic careers are finished.
</P>
<P>
   And, certainly, in some cases this is true maybe even in the
case of the ill-starred Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But did Magic Johnson make the wrong decision opting for the NBA
season after his sophomore season at Michigan State? Did Michael
Jordan ruin his life not completing his senior season at North
Carolina? Have Kevin Garnett and Kobe Bryant, both of whom have
become fabulously wealthy, hurt their financial standing joining
the NBA out of high school?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   It long has been the strong feeling here that an athlete should
forgo college or at least depart prematurely if he has a chance to
earn the type of wages far beyond the reach of the rest of us mere
mortals.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if the heralded 7-foot center at Dominguez High in
Compton, Tyson Chandler, finds out next spring that he will be a
certain NBA lottery pick, can anyone with even the faintest
financial acumen blame him if decides to skip college?
</P>
<P>
   Why should Chandler spend a couple of years at, say, UCLA
earning tons of revenue for the Westwood university and for the
NCAA when he can be earning tons of money for himself?
</P>
<P>
   Why should any of the college athletes do anything for the NCAA,
a nit-picking, narrow-minded, tyrannical organization that seems to
spend all its time these days busting athletes for loans they
received in high school?
</P>
<P>
   Wow!
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the NCAA, which receives more than a billion dollars for
its basketball TV contracts and shamelessly exploits athletes, is
out trying to purify amateur sports with its ridiculous edicts and
unctuous snooping makes me sleep calmer at night.
</P>
<P>
   Why, it turns out only this week the NCAA, the reigning model of
Lord Acton's fabled
power-corrupts-absolute-power-corrupts-absolutely aphorism,
perpetuated still another petty act when it informed basketball
star Rebecca Lobo she couldn't work its women's tournament for
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   What heinous crime had Ms. Lobo committed to deserve such a
blackballing?
</P>
<P>
   Why, of course, she happens to be a professional athlete,
drawing a paycheck these days from the New York Liberty of the
WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   No way the NCAA wanted any of its telecast besmirched by such a
wretched soul!
</P>
<P>
   As you watched Kenyon Martin writhing on the floor against St.
Louis, you felt a sense of sorrow for him.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to determine how much money the injury will cost
him, but it could be plenty.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure youngsters like Tyson Chandler around the
country are looking at Martin, and thinking that such a tragic
injury also could happen to them.
</P>
<P>
   What if Kenyon Martin's leg is permanently damaged?
</P>
<P>
   What if he no longer has the spring in it that made him the most
menacing defensive player in college basketball this season?
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure that any NBA team that now decides to draft
Martin will make sure he's 100 percent healthy before giving him
the standard four-year, $11 million contract that a player of his
caliber normally would be able to command?
</P>
<P>
   You also can be sure a lot of young basketball players who can
generate seven-figure contracts are now more anxious than ever to
join the NBA rather than stay in college and be savagely
scrutinized by a dictatorial governing body that should have been
forcibly disbanded by its members long ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
