<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4592 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LEWIS-BEHAVIOR0313-CO     03-12 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-BEHAVIOR0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Predictably, accounts of Lewis' behavior vary
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nothing is more predictable in a case like the one
involving football star Ray Lewis than this: Eyewitness accounts
will vary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the problem with a chaotic, dimly lit scene,'' said
defense attorney Jack Martin. ``It would be more suspicious if
everyone had the same story.''
</P>
<P>
   And the stories do vary widely in the case of the street melee
that occurred in the early morning hours after the Super Bowl near
a Buckhead nightclub, leaving two men, Jacinth Baker and Richard
Lollar, stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, Reginald Oakley and Joseph Sweeting have been charged
with murder.
</P>
<P>
   In some versions, Lewis is described as a ``peacemaker'' who
tried to stop the fight. In others, he's an angry bystander, unable
to ``control his boys.'' In another, he's an assailant, throwing
punches.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen people saw part or all of what transpired that
morning. But finding witnesses and getting them to speak has been a
daunting task for both the prosecution and the defense. One of
Lewis' attorneys, Ed Garland, has resorted to buying an ad in the
free metro Atlanta paper Creative Loafing. Prosecutors have begun
offering grants of immunity to those who may have played some role
in the altercation.
</P>
<P>
   Through interviews, court hearings and investigative records,
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution has obtained statements from nine
witnesses who were in Buckhead the morning Baker and Lollar were
stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
   There are certainly other witnesses who will testify at trial,
now scheduled for mid-May. Neither the prosecution nor the defense
is necessarily building a case solely around these witnesses. But
these nine have all been interviewed by either the prosecution or
the defense and are expected to be on the witness list for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
