<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4595 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WEB-PHONES0313-COX     03-12 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-PHONES0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    iPhone helps simplify confusing online navigation
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Not everyone who wants to use the Internet wants
to own a computer, but just about everybody wants to own a phone.
</P>
<P>
   InfoGear Technology Corp. of Redwood City, Calif., offers the
iPhone, a telephone with a 7.4-inch touch-sensitive screen that can
bring consumers most of the benefits of the Internet without the
complexity, expense and space-hogging bulk of a full computer.
</P>
<P>
   The iPhone occupies an area on a desk about the same size as an
office telephone, and it performs all the functions of a phone. It
has caller ID with call blocking, a digital answering machine with
remote message access, a built-in directory for storing phone
numbers and other information and a log to store a list of incoming
and outgoing calls.
</P>
<P>
   The iPhone also has programmable speed-dial keys and speaker
phone functions and is compatible with network voice mail systems.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to its voice line for the telephone system,
iPhone has a separate data line and all the equipment to access the
Internet even while talking on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   The iPhone has a full-size keyboard that slides into a
compartment at the bottom of the phone when not in use. The
keyboard can be used to write e-mail or type Internet addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The screen of the iPhone is touch-sensitive so the users doesn't
have to use a mouse to point and click icons on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the controls are one-touch buttons, so it's easy to call
up and use the phone's various functions. The device has a built-in
56k modem, and Internet access is fairly fast.
</P>
<P>
   InfoGear says iPhones also are easy to install. They are simply
plugged into phone lines and a power supply. Software included with
the phone helps the user register the product and access InfoGear's
iPhone Web site. From there the user can use InfoGear Network
services.
</P>
<P>
   InfoGear supplied iPhones to the media during the International
Consumer Electronics Show in January, and they were a big hit.
Their best feature is probably ease of use; even novice users were
able to master them quickly without instruction manuals.
</P>
<P>
   The main limitation of iPhone is its relatively small,
black-and-white liquid crystal screen. It's fine for e-mail, but it
doesn't deliver all the colorful excitement of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The iPhone, which won a Best of Show award at the Consumer
Electronics Show, is available through several online retailers.
Check www.infogear.com for more information and links to retailers.
The product's suggested retail price is $399.
</P>
<P>
   Big Planet sells iPhone by phone. Call (800) 487-5200 and refer
to item number 468 645 4001.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
