<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 1433EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4603 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UNCONVENTIONAL-PROFES     03-12 1650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNCONVENTIONAL-PROFESSOR0313-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Professor out to put 'learning' back into education
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a late-winter day of blue skies and crisp, dry air,
Roger Shattuck poses for a photographer on the faux-Gothic campus
of Oglethorpe University. He is a thinker, so she asks him to sit
with his hand to his 76-year-old face. He amiably complies. One can
be a contrarian without being contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck is an unconventional thinker, as resistant to academic
fashion as he is gentle in manner. Principled disagreement he can
accept, but not the dogmas he finds seeping into the ground water
of American cultural life. One is that there can be no common
literary heritage in a country built on the banishment of the red
man, the enslavement of the black man, the exploitation of the
working man and the suppression of women of whatever color.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that children learn little from old-fashioned
memorization and step-by-step drills, but would be eager to
discover entire worlds on their own if only the teacher would get
out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   From all such notions Shattuck dissents, and he had come to
Oglethorpe to say why.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, he was there to present the plenary address at a
symposium whose theme was ``Celebrating the Liberal Arts: Making a
Life, Making a Living,'' part of Oglethorpe's inauguration of its
new president, Larry D. Large. His address, titled ``The Phony War:
Rote Learning vs. Critical Thinking'' and delivered to an audience
of about 200 faculty members and alumni, had none of the rancor
that often attends debates about American education. Indeed, its
quiet good sense could have fooled a person into thinking Shattuck
was an accommodationist.
</P>
<P>
   But a man willing to divide books into the good and the bad does
not accommodate easily. Shattuck, in fact, has set out to practice
what he preaches _ this at a time when others would be enjoying
retirement. Professor emeritus of modern languages and literature
at Boston University, he is running for the school board in
Lincoln, Vt. (population 974), all because he thinks public schools
in the United States have put the cart before the horse _ or, to
park the cliche, have abandoned a subject-centered classroom for a
child-centered classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``In talking to friends, the idea of running for the school
board came up,'' he says. ``There was no opening at the time, and
now there is. I felt I should follow up in the real world what I
had been saying in the academic world.'' The election is in April.
</P>
<P>
   CURRICULUM HARD TO FATHOM
</P>
<P>
   A man who has critics does well to have credentials. Shattuck
has been elected a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and
Sciences and honored by the American Academy and Institute of Arts
and Letters. One of his eight books, ``Marcel Proust,'' won a
National Book Award in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   So here is this well-laureled scholar in his retirement poring
over thick volumes of educationese churned out by Vermont's
curriculum experts. ``I wanted to know what they believed a proper
curriculum should be,'' he says. ``But it's impenetrable. In all
those pages upon pages,'' he says, ``the words `to study,' `to
learn' never appear. Nor does the word `fact.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's no mystery to Shattuck that American high school students
do poorly on achievement tests when compared with students from
Japan and Korea, the Czech Republic and Singapore. ``They've never
been taught anything,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   They've been doing paper-and-scissors ``projects'' and all
manner of busy work, but nothing that furnishes the mind with a
coherent understanding of the world or hones it to think with
discrimination. That's why Shattuck thinks the debate between rote
learning and critical thinking is bogus: Memorization of the
multiplication tables, the capitals of the states and the
succession of American presidents does not by itself make one
educated. But you can't very well think ``critically'' if you don't
know anything _ and public education in the United States has
de-emphasized rudimentary knowledge of fact for ambiguous knowledge
of self.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our schools fail, we just scatter in all directions,''
Shattuck says. ``The function of an education is to transmit a
heritage, not to undermine it. But we've being doing it backward.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CANDID AND PERVERSE
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck does not separate the two, education and literature,
education and the arts. They are all part of a web that defines how
we make a living and how we make a life. Which is why he is willing
to say there are books whose influence has been morally harmful,
and others whose moral influence goes by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   This being the case and this being the United States _ home of
Top 10s in everything from college football teams to summer
vacation spots _ why not make a list? When his book ``Candor &AMP;
Perversion: Literature, Education and the Arts'' came out last
year, Shattuck amiably complied in this, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Bob Weil's idea,'' he says, referring to his editor at
W.W. Norton &AMP; Co. ``He wanted me to do it because he said it would
help interest people in the book. Maybe it does, maybe it doesn't _
I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   A smart publicist might say that the book's title was not one
conceived with high sales in mind. If a sweetener would pique
curiosity, a Top 10 list of ``candid'' books and ``perverse'' books
would seem to fit the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I originally did 12,'' Shattuck says, ``but Bob wouldn't have
it. `Nope,' he said, `it must be 10.'''
</P>
<P>
   Evil being more interesting than good, the eye turns first to
the side of Shattuck's ledger that says ``Perverse.'' Among its
entries: ``Sexual Behavior in the Human Male,'' by Alfred Kinsey.
The pioneering sex researcher ``was a charlatan twice over,''
Shattuck says. He not only made false claims about the scientific
nature of his work, but argued for the moral equivalence of all
sexual behavior. And of E.O. Wilson's widely reviewed, much praised
``Consilience: The Unity of Knowledge,'' he says: ``The world's
greatest authority on ants has written a book that seeks to make
ants out of all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't much use for Friedrich Nietzsche, Karl Marx or Michel
Foucault, either.
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck would rather see college students reading Albert Camus'
``The Stranger,'' Helen Keller's ``The Story of My Life''
(``Combined with Annie Sullivan's remarkable letters, 'The Story of
My Life' gives a double account _ inside and outside _ of how a
profoundly disadvantaged child learns to learn, to speak, to love
and to respect others.'') and Tolstoy's ``War and Peace'' (``How do
we learn about life? The media distort life so often and rely so
heavily on stereotype that we live with a caricature of ourselves
... (From) Tolstoy's great bear hug of a book ... we learn about
life at its fullest.'')
</P>
<P>
   Top 10 lists are fun, but the real point of ``Candor &AMP;
Perversion'' was a critique of easy assumptions and the pursuit of
knowledge that only debases life. He encapsulates much of that
critique in 19 theses that form the bases of both it and an earlier
book,
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbidden Knowledge: From Prometheus to Pornography.'' Among
them:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Across millions of years we have evolved a fairly stable
human nature, which contains an elusive element of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Works that have survived for centuries cannot be dismissed
out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Like our terrestrial environment, our literary, intellectual
and moral environment needs to be wisely cultivated and
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Let us eschew the freestanding word text. Let us take
advantage of terms like novel, poem, play, essay.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We teach what we hope to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Reliance on methodology tends to eliminate the experience
and the love of literature.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``In a free society, the primary role of education is the
transmission of a heritage, not its primary subversion.''
</P>
<P>
   `CULTURAL CONSERVATIONIST'
</P>
<P>
   You can size him up rather easily _ or you think you can. He is
a Great Books man, and he is a conservative. Shattuck smiles,
knowing the latter word is often an epithet, and says: ``I'm a
political liberal and a cultural conservative _ no, what I'd really
say is that I'm a cultural conservationist. I don't know how you're
going to explain that to your readers, though.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, some would say, a man who doesn't know which way the wind
blows. ``I've debated with Roger on this subject, and I think he
exaggerates the importance of the texts we teach,'' says Gerald
Graff, a literary critic and associate dean of curriculum and
instruction at the University of Illinois at Chicago. ``What I
tried to persuade Roger of _ unsuccessfully, I guess _ is that the
problem is not which books we teach but books themselves. Because
American students grow up in an anti-intellectual environment, any
kind of reading poses a challenge. When this is the case, it
doesn't make much difference whether you're teaching Shakespeare or
Alice Walker. There is a deeper problem here and that's the problem
of literacy itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Graff ready to join in Shattuck's criticism of public
education _ that it is more concerned with how something is taught
than what is taught. ``I'm a content man myself,'' he says, ``but
we've all had bad teachers ... people who know the subject but
didn't know how to teach. So I think the education people have a
point.''
</P>
<P>
   In his little township of Lincoln, Shattuck knows very well
which way the wind blows and he intends to walk directly into it.
``That's why I'm running for the school board,'' he says. ``If
people don't try to change things, they're just going to get
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point, the practical and the intellectual must meet.
``It comes down to how you view the world,'' he says, ``and what
you believe about human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
