<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4619 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CARSEATS0313-COX     03-12 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSEATS0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents have gotten the message about car seats for babies, but
many older children still face terrible risks
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Theresa Driscoll-Miller pulled her Chevy Suburban into
the car pool line outside Atlanta's New Century School.
</P>
<P>
   In minutes, her 8-year-old son, Frankie, climbed into the
spacious back seat next to the family dog, Moe, snapped on the seat
belt and started playing his GameBoy.
</P>
<P>
   It's a daily routine played out every day in cars all across the
nation. And it puts thousands of children at risk for serious
injury or death
</P>
<P>
   Too big for most child car seats and too small for standard seat
belts, children from preschoolers to third-graders are literally
being put in harm's way. Too many sit in the front seat, where an
exploding air bag could kill them if a crash doesn't. Others sit in
the back, where it's safer, but have shoulder belts rubbing against
their necks, lap belts stretched across their delicate stomachs, or
both.
</P>
<P>
   That's despite recent pediatric and highway safety
recommendations that children who are under 9 years old and weigh
less than 80 pounds use either a booster seat or a ``youth'' seat _
a step up from a car seat _ when riding in a car. Experts say that
at least half of the approximately 500 children a year who died in
auto accidents from 1994 to 1998 might have survived if they had
been properly restrained.
</P>
<P>
   Most people have gotten the message about properly restraining
babies in cars, says James Nichols, director of research at the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. But many parents
are still unsure about the best way to buckle up older children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear we haven't done a very effective job in
getting the message out,'' Nichols said. ``Parents have no idea how
important this is.''
</P>
<P>
   Seat belts were designed for people weighing at least 80 pounds
and at least 4 feet 8 inches tall. That's tall enough to sit
squarely against the back of the seat and have the knees bend at
the end of the seat. The lap belt is meant to go across an adult's
lap, and the shoulder belt to fit over the chest. In an accident,
the force of impact is spread out over the rib cage and the pelvic
region as the belts tighten down and across.
</P>
<P>
   But because of a young child's size, the lap belt falls across
the abdomen _ one of the softest and weakest parts of the body. In
a wreck, the force of the crash can be concentrated in the lap
belt, causing it to squeeze the child like a rope wrapped around a
pillow. As a result, the child can sustain internal injuries and a
broken back.
</P>
<P>
   Children in the front seat are also at risk. They tend to be
more active than adults, playing with the dashboard or radio. In a
crash, they can be propelled forward, improperly restrained by a
loose-fitting seat belt designed for adults. If the car has a
passenger-side air bag, the 200-mph force of the deploying bag can
break their necks.
</P>
<P>
   As of December 1998, almost 70 children had been killed by
passenger air bags, according to National Safe Kids. And statistics
show that, very often, when a child has been killed riding in the
front seat, law enforcement officers have found the back seat clear
_ meaning the youngster could have been sitting in a more safe
position. ``In over 90 percent of the cases, there is an available
seat in the back,'' said Dr. Kyran Quinlan, a pediatrician and a
medical epidemiologist at the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials also remind parents _ especially those
who have bought, in Driscoll-Miller's words, ``mondo-tank''
sport-utility vehicles _ that the dynamics of a crash don't change
much, regardless of the automobile's size.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents said they haven't bought into the child-booster
advice because they wonder if they make that much difference. Some
flinch at the cost of paying $25-100 for a booster or ``youth
seat,'' after shelling out $35-100 for a child safety seat.
</P>
<P>
   Others simply remember when children tumbled about in the
station wagon _ without seatbelts, car seats or boosters - when a
youngster's greatest protection was a mother's arm thrust across
his or her chest as the car came to a sudden stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the `In my day' argument,'' Quinlan said. ``Well, in those
days, the death rates were significantly higher than they are now.
And to be honest, I could never understand why any of us would
reject new ideas about safety that clearly saves lives just because
that's not what we're used to.''
</P>
<P>
   State legislators have been slow to follow the science. Although
the American Academy of Pediatrics and the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration has outlined booster seat guidelines for
children older than 3 years old, not a single state requires that
kids be restrained in such seats.
</P>
<P>
   All states do require that children under the age of 4 be
restrained. And 25 require that children up to 16 be restrained _
that is, wearing a seatbelt at all times.
</P>
<P>
   But many child-safety experts believe the letter of the law is
too narrowly drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the first battle line is most likely to be drawn
between parents and their kids. Nichols, of the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration, has a 6-year-old and an 8-year-old.
The 8-year-old is not happy at all about his dad's beliefs on
booster seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a lot of problems with him about this,'' said
Nichols. ``There isn't a child in his class who's in a booster seat
and he's embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   But like another child safety issue _ bicycle helmets _ experts
say parents need to stick to their guns and explain why it is
important that their child do this. And eventually, what was seen
as odd becomes routine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
