u e BC-DANGELO0313-COX     03-12 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANGELO0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retro soul man D'Angelo back in fine form
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amazing what a newly chiseled chest can do.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, R&AMP;B singer D'Angelo bared his soul on his debut,
``Brown Sugar.'' The album was centered around a Hammond organ and
other instruments the then-20-year-old actually played _ unlike so
many R&AMP;B acts who filter most sounds through a computer. And by
covering Smokey Robinson's classic ballad ``Cruisin''' and speaking
well of his ``Lady,'' he was lyrically much more accessible than
his peers.
</P>
<P>
   What the casual listener might not know is that ``Brown Sugar''
is widely credited in the industry for launching the retro soul
trend for which rapper/singer Lauryn Hill received so much praise.
Her album, ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' won five Grammys
and has sold more than 7 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2 million-selling ``Brown Sugar'' didn't win any Grammys
for which it was nominated, and it never hit No. 1 on the pop
charts.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, D'Angelo is baring more than his soul for his
second album, ``Voodoo.'' His well-defined body _ no longer
slightly pudgy or hidden by bulky leather jackets _ is showcased on
both his album cover and new video. He's moved from behind the
keyboard to center stage. And if he is wearing a stitch of clothing
in the ``Untitled (How Does It Feel)'' video, the sleepy, early
Prince-sounding first single from his album, the director sure
doesn't want you to think he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people think I did that for shock value or something,''
D'Angelo says of the video, in which he claims he does have
``something mini'' on. ``And don't get me wrong, I wanted to get
the people's attention. I want to entertain. But I don't want the
exterior to overshadow the music that's coming out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at a lot of treatments for that single,'' the
25-year-old Richmond native continues, ``and the only suggestion
that I really liked was the one that had just me and the song. And
I think it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Powered by the anticipation over a five-year hiatus and heavy
rotation of ``Untitled'' on Black Entertainment Television and MTV,
``Voodoo'' debuted at the top of the Billboard pop charts Feb. 12.
And D'Angelo _ unlike many of his fellow R&AMP;B singers _ covers a
broad swipe on the radio dial. He can be heard on an Atlanta
hip-hop' station in the morning, a pop station during the day and
on R&AMP;B and adult urban contemporary stations at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and Maxwell are throwbacks to that era of Marvin (Gaye),''
says longtime DJ Youngblood.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as long as he can keep the music outfront _ I mean Marvin
got into that sex symbol thing, too _ if D'Angelo doesn't let that
nakedness lead him, I think he'll go far.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and about that: If D'Angelo's earlier shows are any
indication, he won't take his shirt off tonight until the end of
his almost three-hour performance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
