<SLUG> BC-FLESH-EAT-BACTERIA0313-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Man with flesh-eating strep in critical condition
</P>
<P>
   By Mara Lee
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON _ A 42-year-old man remained in critical condition
Saturday with a Strep A infection that has evolved into its most
severe type, known as ``flesh-eating'' bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, health officials continue to investigate an outbreak
of 23 cases of strep throat infections in the Cincinnati area that
led to two deaths. The Ohio Department of Health and Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention are examining the cases for a common
link.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, about 500 cases a year of life-threatening strep
infections occur. About 100 die from those diseases. Only 5 to 10
percent are of the ``flesh-eating'' variety.
</P>
<P>
   But while milder strep infections, and even asymptomatic
carriers of strep bacteria, are somewhat common, there is no reason
to worry, according to Dr. Sherman Alter, director of infectious
diseases at Children's Hospital. ``It usually does lead to critical
infection,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strep is not that easy to transmit,'' he said. Someone's
sneeze or cough would have to land directly on a cut for someone to
get the flesh-eating variety.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of patients with the flesh-eating infection
will die, partly because the early symptoms are similar to the flu
or a muscle strain. By the time black blisters form, the disease is
advancing rapidly, and amputations are often necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Alter said the best way to prevent the infection is through
standard hygiene practices _ plenty of handwashing, covering one's
mouth when coughing or sneezing, and putting anti-bacterial salve
and adhesive bandages on small cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Strep can cause several life-threatening diseases: scarlet
fever, rheumatic fever, a virulent strain of pneumonia, a form of
toxic shock syndrome, and a flesh-eating type that attacks deep
layers of skin and muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
