<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS0313-COX     03-12 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Captivating colorful wildlife and dark waters of Brazil
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE RIO NEGRO, BRAZIL _ ``Bubbles, bubbles. Big fish, big
fish,'' hissed Samuel the guide. They weren't really bubbles, but
hundreds of tiny peacock bass flicking on the water's surface.
</P>
<P>
   This was no time to argue over semantics, though, because where
there are baby peacocks, there usually are adults. The sun, blocked
much of the week by the beginnings of the Amazonian rainy season,
had just come out and illuminated the movements of the fingerlings.
</P>
<P>
   The parents, often outsized Goliaths with attitudes to match,
tend and care for their young to protect them in a river system
where everything, even other peacock bass, is out to eat them. Any
intrusion upon their offspring's space is greeted with enthusiastic
anger. To paraphrase Robert Ruark's description of Cape buffalo,
the parent peacocks act as if that lure owes them money.
</P>
<P>
   Something was herding this shoal of baby fish across a hidden
lagoon watered by the Rio Negro, and before Samuel could point, the
big orange and black Woodchopper was in the air. It landed smack in
the midst of the school.
</P>
<P>
   Half a dozen heavy rips failed to produce a strike and it seemed
the trick might fail this time. But a second cast had hardly hit
the water before the earth literally opened up in a flash of red
and green and the Chopper disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Even though you know what's coming and even though it may have
happened dozens of times before, no one can be completely prepared
for the explosiveness and pure savagery that is the strike of a
trophy peacock bass. It actually isn't a bass at all, but a giant
cichlid, a cousin to aquarium fish such as tetras, known to
Brazilians as tucunare.
</P>
<P>
   With its brilliant green sides, black bars, red and orange gills
and red eyes, the peacock has become a target fish for trophy
anglers worldwide. They are willing to brave the heat of the
Equator and the threat of yellow fever, Dengue fever and malaria _
not to mention terminal heat rash _ for the chance to catch a giant
peacock.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-pounders are common. Twenty pounds is rarer but they're out
there. All of them strike with a ferocity and fight with a power
the average bass fisherman just is not prepared to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Janes, on his first peacock trip, caught a 15-pounder
during our vacation trip on the Amazon Clipper. The 80-foot
houseboat sleeps 14 anglers, plus crew and cooks. Fishing is out of
17-foot bass boats equipped with 60-horsepower engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never experienced anything like that big fish,'' Janes
said. ``They are unbelievably strong. You land the fish and you're
just drained.''
</P>
<P>
   Janes caught his big fish by casting into a group of baby
peacocks being herded along by an adult pair. ``They move them from
place to place to protect them,'' said Gilberto Castro, a veteran
river guide who oversees the operation aboard the Amazon Clipper.
``The adults tend them, maybe eat the ones that have a fungus and
could infect others.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro said no one actually knows a great deal about tucunare.
``We know they breed all year and we know they must grow very
quickly because the growing season never stops. But nobody knows
how old they are or how quickly they reach trophy size,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Castro said he keeps a thermometer at his house that measures
minimum and maximum temperatures each day. ``In 26 years on the Rio
Negro, it has never read lower than 72 degrees and never higher
than 90 degrees. That's perfect for the fish,'' Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   The fish are perfect for the environment, too. They compete for
space with piranhas and pink dolphins, electric eels and freshwater
sting rays. In the seemingly placid, black waters of the Rio Negro,
the going is always tough and the tough better get going _ or get
eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, peacock bass are not active at night. They sleep in
their favorite spots, making them vulnerable to the spears and gigs
of native fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the topwater strike that is the drug of choice for
non-resident anglers. They come during two fishing seasons, January
into early March and late August to early October.
</P>
<P>
   Anglers begin their trip by flying to Miami, then taking a
five-hour flight to the historic city of Manaus. From there, it's a
one-hour plane ride to Barcelos for the Rio Negro trip. The
houseboat that serves as home for the next week docks at Barcelos
to start the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of choice that provokes the strike is the Woodchopper,
a nearly seven-inch-long, cigar-shaped stick of wood with a
propeller at the rear end and three sets of giant treble hooks in
the middle. Heavy rods, 60- to 80-pound braided line and top-dollar
reels with smooth drags are necessary equipment for handling the
first powerful runs of the largest fish.
</P>
<P>
   So many things can go wrong landing a peacock bass that actually
catching a 20-pound-plus fish is a combination of luck and
providential attendance. The fish that slammed my Woodchopper was a
whopper, which was evident the first time it rolled to the surface
and made itself visible. ``Big fish,'' Samuel said.
``Twenty-pounder.''
</P>
<P>
   The fish had spent most of its power deep in the waters of the
lagoon and was just lolling on the surface. I was already adding up
the money I was going to collect from everybody else on the boat.
That's a stupid thing to do with peacock bass.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel and I both saw the iffy hookup at the same time, a single
hook lodged up under the outside of the tough bone on the fish's
lower jaw. ``Careful,'' the guide said. ``Not hooked good.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the fish could hear the words, because at that
moment he (it was a giant male) turned his belly toward the boat to
enter the net. But that move gave the slightest bit of angle to the
hook, which was only looped over his jaw. The Woodchopper popped
out and the fish disappeared again into the black water from which
it came.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel was more shocked and more rubbery-legged than I was. He
let out a huge sigh and sank back onto his cushion. ``That was a
big fish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
