<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECRET PRINCESS DI BOOK DEAL; FORBES CELEBRITY ISSUE; READING AND
THE WWF  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than a year, the literary agent Michael V. Carlisle
struggled to achieve something unheard of in the publishing
industry, where secrets are made to be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   He managed to conceal efforts to develop and find a publisher
for ``The Bodyguard's Story,'' Trevor Rees-Jones' 336-page account
of the events surrounding his own survival of the 1997 Paris car
crash that killed Diana, princess of Wales, and her companion, Emad
Mohamed al-Fayed, who was known as Dodi.
</P>
<P>
   The secrecy came from fear that Fayed's father, Mohamed
al-Fayed, would squelch the effort if he knew that his son's former
bodyguard intended to publish an account that conflicted with his
own view that a conspiracy led up to the car crash.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, Fayed did try to halt the sale of the book this
month in England, although he failed. The book is scheduled for
publication in the United States this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gambled a lot,'' Carlisle said. ``If people had betrayed us,
the book would have been stopped. The gamble of all our time and
expectation of success would have been lost, and Fayed would have
been litigating my client.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of months, Carlisle arranged for Moira Johnston, a
writer who is one of his clients, to meet secretly with Rees-Jones
and to research the first three chapters and an outline for a book.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to approach publishers in London, the
recognizable former bodyguard _ with a face scarred by the crash _
met in the St. James Club hotel conference room with executives
representing seven companies.
</P>
<P>
   The representatives signed a confidentiality agreement and were
not allowed to take the proposal out of the room, Carlisle said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that several British publishers rejected the project
because of fears that Fayed might mount a court battle against it.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, three publishers made offers and the winning bidder,
Time Warner Inc.'s Little, Brown &AMP; Co. unit, continued to conceal
the incendiary topic, even keeping it secret from its own sales
representatives until earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I have more white hair than I did before,''
Carlisle said. ``Keeping a secret in publishing _ it's
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORBES USES 4 COVERS FOR A CELEBRITY ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Forbes magazine had a pair of firsts last week. Not only did the
magazine showcase its first cover to feature a pierced navel _
belonging to the pop star Britney Spears _ but it printed four
different covers, becoming part of the latest trend in magazine
publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The March 20 issue of the magazine featured Kobe Bryant, Anna
Kournikova, Regis Philbin and Spears on separate covers under the
headline ``The New Stars of Money.'' The covers were sent to
subscribers and newsstands at random and were not aimed at specific
regions, as is often the case, according to Lewis D'Vorkin, the
executive editor. (Last year, Fortune sent a cover featuring the
Nascar driver Jeff Gordon to the South and Midwest and an alternate
cover featuring a woman clad in tight Levi's jeans to the
presumably more relaxed West and East Coasts.)
</P>
<P>
   D'Vorkin said the magazine chose four covers ``because we had
four different stories to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he noted: ``We've gotten a lot of attention. We did four
nights on CNBC, each night focusing on a different person. It's
more bang for the buck. Celebrities sell, and we've got four of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes joins several magazines that have run multiple covers the
last year. To celebrate its 15th anniversary, Spin's current issue
has four different covers. TV Guide has gone so far as to run 26
different covers for a football issue. Last year, Sports
Illustrated even ran 50 covers _ one for each state _ for a
year-end issue.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with the Forbes cover, said Samir Husni, a
professor of media at the University of Mississippi and a close
observer of the magazine industry, is that Forbes does not
prominently indicate that the four covers are all the same issue
inside. This might confuse readers at the newsstand, causing them
to buy the same magazine twice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Vorkin said he had not heard any complaints and pointed out
that the headlines are almost identical on each cover. D'Vorkin
said that the only drawback had been the cost of shooting the three
additional photographs _ ``and doing these kinds of people, well,
they bring along a fair amount of entourage, although it was not as
bad as some of them get.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI &QR;
</P>
<P>
   PROFESSIONAL WRESTLING VS. HARRY POTTER
</P>
<P>
   Think Harry Potter has a stranglehold on children's best
sellers? Think again. When Barnes &AMP; Noble recently convened a focus
group of boys aged 11 to 14, the one hardcover each boy had bought
in common was about a character named Mankind.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the World Wrestling Federation's Mankind (aka Mick
Foley), whose autobiography ``Have a Nice Day!'' was published in
October by ReganBooks, a unit of News Corp.'s HarperCollins, and
now has 700,000 copies in print.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``The Rock Says ...,'' a ReganBooks offering by the
wrestling icon the Rock (actually Dwayne Johnson), joined Foley's
book on the New York Times best-seller list in January. There are
600,000 copies in print. Both books also weigh in on best-seller
lists in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of the books has not been lost on the American
Library Association, which is about to feature the Rock, Mankind
and the female wrestling star Chyna on a poster to encourage young
people to read. When Johnson was at the Bookends store in
Ridgewood, N.J., for a signing on a Sunday in January, 6,000 people
lined up outside the store, among them school bus loads of 8- to
12-year-olds with chaperones, the store's proprietor, Dana
Gilligan, said.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is by no means limited to boys. Half the fans
hoping to catch an autographed Rock collectible were women and
girls, Gilligan said. The next title to appear in the five-book
contract the WWF negotiated with ReganBooks is about Chyna, to be
published in August.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is getting into the ring with ``I'm Next,'' a
memoir by Bill Goldberg, star of Ted Turner's rival World
Championship Wrestling, which will be published by Crown, a unit of
Bertelsmann's Random House Inc. in November.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble's vice president for merchandising, Bob Wietrak,
called the books ``the new celebrity bios.'' He predicted sales
would remain strong if professional wrestling's television ratings
keep up. And all signs indicate that they will.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ GAYLE FELDMAN &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
