<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PSI-NET-ART-2TAKES-NY     03-12 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSI-NET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PSINet'S BILL SCHRADER, INTERNET ICONOCLAST  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 2 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphics
are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider it a classic Bill Schrader moment.
</P>
<P>
   At a big telecommunications convention in Geneva last October,
William L. Schrader, chairman of PSINet Inc., the biggest
independent Internet service provider, announced that PSINet had
just struck a deal to offer high-speed Internet access in Europe.
The partner, he said, was Winstar Communications Inc., an American
wireless carrier, allowing PSINet to bypass the Continent's
traditional phone systems.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, Winstar's top executives in New York knew nothing
about a deal with PSINet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Bill was predicting the future,'' William L. Rouhana
Jr., Winstar's chairman, said lightheartedly in an interview last
week, noting that his company never announced such an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   All Schrader would say, by way of explanation, was that PSINet
had indeed negotiated a European deal with Winstar. ``The fact that
Rouhana didn't know isn't my problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Odd? Bizarre even? From another chairman at another company,
perhaps. But for Schrader, it was simply business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   In building PSINet from its modest roots in upstate New York to
international Internet powerhouse with a stock market value of $7.3
billion, he has never been afraid to get a bit ahead of himself _
or to risk alienating a potential partner. In fact, PSINet and
Winstar are now in preliminary discussions about working together,
according to executives close to those talks.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader, whose hobbies include target shooting, is an executive
who often fires from the hip, so to speak, aiming verbal shots at
allies and enemies alike and establishing a reputation as perhaps
the most iconoclastic executive of his stature in the
communications industry.
</P>
<P>
   PSINet, with fiber-optic lines around the globe, some of the
world's most advanced Internet systems and a fast-growing customer
base, looms as a highly attractive acquisition candidate _ one
whose shares are up nearly 300 percent since October, as investors
have noted its potential takeover value. It is the biggest of the
Internet access providers not already snatched up by telephone
companies looking to expand into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   But PSINet has been valuable for years. And Schrader, who owns
7.45 percent of the company, has always refused to sell, sometimes
leaving prospective buyers to walk away wondering if he is shrewd
or headstrong _ or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the real reason PSINet is still independent is Bill
Schrader,'' said Richard G. Ellenberger, chief executive of
Broadwing Inc., the former Cincinnati Bell. Broadwing recently
filed to reduce its stake in PSINet to about 11 percent but would
still be its largest shareholder. ``He has built it from the ground
up, and he's not through. He believes he's one of the new age of
executive leaders, and he's not ready to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrader, 48, may not be ready to quit because he has already
come so far. A biologist by training, he was a co-founder in 1985
of one of the first Internet operations, called Nysernet, which
initially linked academic computing centers in the cold reaches of
upstate New York. In 1989, when for-profit activity was still
ostensibly banned from the government-financed Internet, he founded
what was then called Performance Systems International Inc., moving
it to northern Virginia to be closer to the Federal agencies then
overseeing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   PSINet was not only one of the first providers of Internet
access service but one of the most innovative. In 1995, for
instance, PSINet was a pioneer in offering unlimited Internet
service at a fixed monthly fee to consumers across the nation. The
pricing was set in typical Schrader fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I asked him how they chose what to charge for
the flat fee,'' Ellenberger said. ``And he said, `Well, it was 1995
so we chose $19.95, and $19.95 sounded good to us.' And I asked
him, `You didn't do any economic modeling?' And he said, `Nope.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, PSINet's tactical focus has changed; the company got
out of the consumer Internet business in 1996, selling its consumer
unit to Mindspring Enterprises so it could focus on serving
business customers and acting as a carrier's carrier for smaller
Internet service providers. More recently, instead of merely
providing raw Internet links, PSINet has begun to add more advanced
and lucrative services by managing Web servers and computer systems
that deliver corporate software applications across networks.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's ultimate goal has remained constant. ``I would
like to build a system,'' Schrader said, ``that can deliver all the
media to all the customers on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold S. Wills, PSINet's president and chief operating officer
and a former executive at IBM and Xerox, first met Schrader in the
spring of 1996. ``I thought he was crazy,'' Wills said, recalling
his job interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill said, `We're going to kill the phone companies and we're
going to be bigger than AT&AMP;T, and it will be a lot of fun.' And I
said, `How much revenue have you got?' and he said, `Well, last
year we had $35 million.' And I said, `Well, how are you going to
do what you want to do?' And he began to explain in ways that I
hadn't understood before the power of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other people did not understand either. PSINet's stock
traded below $10 throughout 1996, 1997 and 1998. It was not until
last year, when PSINet generated more than $550 million in revenue,
that investors began climbing onto the PSINet bandwagon as a way to
play the growth of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And to ride the PSINet bandwagon is to hear none of the bland
modulations of boardroom-speak.
</P>
<P>
   One recent day, as he drove his silver-gray Lincoln Town Car (he
also owns a Porsche Boxster) from PSINet's headquarters in Herndon,
Va., to one of the company's nearby network centers, Schrader was
asked about one of his competitors, John W. Sidgmore. Sidgmore runs
Uunet, the No. 1 Internet carrier, which is now part of MCI
Worldcom Inc. and is also based in northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of where the market's going, we see eye to eye,''
Schrader said. ``But John is a typical executive who will say what
he thinks people want to hear and I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   (In an interview later, Sidgmore said, ``I'm willing to bet that
on Bill's report card in sixth grade it said something like,
`Doesn't play well with others.''')
</P>
<P>
   And do not even get Schrader started on Stephen M. Case,
chairman of America Online Inc. and another Virginia neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Case is a perfect example of someone who misrepresents the
truth for his own interest,'' Schrader said as he drove.
</P>
<P>
   He cited what he saw as America Online's about-face, after it
agreed to acquire Time Warner Inc., on the need for the government
to regulate the delivery of Internet data over cable television
systems. Before the deal, America Online had called for a
government role; after hooking up with Time Warner, the nation's
second-largest operator of cable systems, many people in the
industry perceived America Online as changing its stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like hypocrites, and Case is a hypocrite,'' Schrader
said. He peered over the wheel, then added: ``He is a self-serving
businessman who's into hypocrisy and I'm not. That's why he decided
to stop competing against us as an Internet service provider and
get into the content business.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement responding to those comments, America Online
said, ``Mr. Case's position on open access has been consistent from
day one.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Schrader reserves his deepest ire, however, for local telephone
incumbents, which he says are monopolists holding back the digital
future. Bashing the Bell companies is hardly unusual among smaller
communications carriers, but Schrader's company must also deal with
the Bells on a daily basis, renting their local communications
lines in order to reach customers.
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly outspoken about Bell Atlantic, the East Coast
giant with which PSINet does a significant amount of business. ``I
call them `Bell Atlantis,''' Schrader said, still dishing as he
drove. ``Bell Atlantis is dead. They cannot exist in tomorrow. We
know the customer better than they do and they can't keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   Why lash out at a such an important supplier?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm honest,'' Schrader said. Referring to Bell
Atlantic's chairman, he said, ``It's not in my best interest to
tell you that Ivan Seidenberg is a poor manager of a
multibillion-dollar company, because they're our major supplier.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for a corporate response, Susan Kraus, a Bell Atlantic
spokeswoman, replied: ``This is not even worth commenting on but
I'll say this. Consider the source. It's hard to take anything he
says seriously. This guy has a long history of making irrational
statements and taking gratuitous potshots at his competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most remarkable aspect of Schrader's blunt style is
that it has not prevented him from garnering the deep respect of
his peers, even those he does not treat gently. As someone who
spoke up for and invested in the Internet early and often, Schrader
is often considered one of the handful of true Internet
visionaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has enormous courage and he's as smart as a fox,'' said
George H. Conrades, chairman of Akamai Technologies Inc. and former
chairman of BBN, one of the big three early independent Internet
companies, along with Uunet and PSINet. ``I admire him,'' Conrades
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sidgmore, of Uunet, also offered a compliment of sorts. ``I'm a
big supporter of Bill's, as wacky as he is,'' Sidgmore said.
``Whatever else you say, good or bad, he is steadfastly committed
to his vision for the company.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sidgmore said, ``I would not be surprised if you read
soon that we will do some investments together.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of all he has built, Schrader has been reluctant
to sell it, despite the hundreds of millions or billions of dollars
such a deal could bring him, considering his personal 7.45 percent
stake in PSINet.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, Internet providers of all size and
description have been snatched up by more traditional
communications companies. Uunet agreed to be acquired by MFS
Communications in 1996 just before MFS itself was acquired by
Worldcom Inc. In 1997, BBN was acquired by GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   That has essentially left PSINet as the last of the Mohicans,
holding out against assimilation with the communications giants.
Deutsche Telekom, for instance, has explored acquiring PSInet, but
those discussions were strictly preliminary. Far more likely
suitors are the new breed of communications carrier in the United
States, companies like Level 3, Qwest, Broadwing and Nextlink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to buy PSINet at least 10 times over the last few
years,'' Sidgmore said. ``Right after MFS bought us we tried to buy
him. I tried after Worldcom. I tried a bunch of times and he would
never sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, it comes down to Schrader being Schrader. ``He
always had the opinion that PSInet is worth 10 times whatever his
stock price is,'' Sidgmore said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that other Internet companies have sold out _ beyond
the financial incentives _ has been their executives' notion that
integrating into a bigger company can give them access to a broader
set of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Wills, PSINet's No. 2 executive, takes a slightly more pragmatic
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some day, they will buy us and we will be sold, and my job is
to make it more expensive for them every day that they wait,''
Wills said. ``What they could have bought for $200 million, they
will now probably have to pay $20 billion for.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Schrader about selling his company _ well, maybe it's better
not to ask. ``Why should I sell the company?'' he said, bristling.
``Tell me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 1703EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
