</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JOURNALISTS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST-SOVIET RUSSIA, TOO, INSISTS ITS JOURNALISTS FOLLOW THE FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two news reports out of Moscow last week _ one probably false,
one sadly true _ served as reminders of the rise of Russian
journalism in the years just before the collapse of communism, and
its paradoxical retreat these days.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a small plane carrying the journalist and media
executive Artyom Borovik crashed soon after takeoff from Moscow.
Borovik's burial over the weekend was laced with eulogies by
Russian officials recalling the path-breaking reports that he wrote
in 1987, at age 27, on the faltering, brutal campaign in
Afghanistan for the magazine Ogonyok.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, word came that the Russian procurator's office had
filed criminal charges against Andrei Babitsky, a Radio Liberty
reporter, for aiding the enemy while covering the war in Chechnya.
The procurator's office denied the report, carried by the Interfax
news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Babitsky, who was captured by Russian soldiers
as he left Grozny, the Chechen capital, and held incommunicado more
than a month, still seems a government target. In an interview
published on Friday in the newspaper Kommersant, the acting
president, Vladimir Putin, said, ``What Babitsky did is much more
dangerous than shooting a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   One war correspondent declared a hero, one reviled. Why the
difference? The kind of government involved? The kind of war? And
is Russia different from other societies in not being objective
about the people killing its sons? Peter Arnett's CNN reports from
Baghdad during the Persian Gulf War starting in 1990 did not endear
him to many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the adulation of Borovik, a son of the Soviet elite, and
the demonization of Babitsky, who covered Russian setbacks from the
Chechen side, both reflect journalism's fragility in Russia. They
underscore Moscow's willingness, then and now, to control
journalists and journalism. Whether the instrument of control is
permission or punishment is less relevant than the raw willingness
to exercise control.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Gorbachev permitted Borovik's reporting, which touched a
popular chord and prepared the country for the army's withdrawal
from Afghanistan. Putin, or perhaps rogue soldiers, punished
Babitsky for reporting that contradicted the government and could
have undermined support for the second Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chechnya is a popular war in the eyes of most Russians,'' said
Emma Gray, European program coordinator of the Committee to Protect
Journalists in New York. The apartment bombings in Moscow, linked
in the popular mind to Chechen terrorists, helped make it so, and
Chechen kidnapping of Russian journalists in their region provided
little incentive for enterprising reporting.
</P>
<P>
   With notable exceptions, Gray said, Russian coverage of this war
was dominated by ``self-censorship'' by journalists who felt ``they
would be branded unpatriotic traitors'' if they contradicted the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Masha Lipman, deputy editor of the Moscow newspaper Itogi, one
of the few news outlets to offer critical war coverage, distrusts
comparisons between Borovik and Babitsky, in part because of their
different audiences. Borovik's Soviet audience numbered in the
millions. The programs of the U.S. government-sponsored Radio
Liberty, she said, are heard by a small group of listeners in the
big cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was reading Borovik,'' she said in an interview last
week. ``Who is listening to Babitsky?'' His obscurity and his
Western ties, she said, made him an easy mark. What happened to
Borovik _ and his later success as a television correspondent in
Russia and on the CBS program ``60 Minutes'' _ was a reflection of
his talent, his connections and the government's needs. ``What
happened to Babitsky,'' Lipman said, ``was the result of a system
with bad instincts and poor operations'' and a visceral fury at
reporters who contradict the military.
</P>
<P>
   She points to her own publication, and to some programs on NTV,
the independent television network, as proof that not all news
outlets parrot government pronouncements. Gray agreed, but added
that the treatment of Babitsky, who spent more than a month in
captivity, might be a harbinger of more trouble for contrary-minded
reporters. Borovik's fame did not deter the government television
network from canceling his program, ``Top Secret,'' last year,
after it looked into possible Kremlin corruption.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to Chechnya, contrary-mindedness was relatively
rare. ``In the main, journalists were content to be a mouthpiece of
their government,'' Gray said. ``It's a tragedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
