<SLUG> BC-GM-FIAT-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIAT WEIGHS SALE TO GM OF A STAKE IN ITS AUTO LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Fiat is close to selling a minority stake in its car
operations to General Motors after apparently failing to sell the
entire division to DaimlerChrysler, auto industry officials and
investment bankers said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat's board is scheduled to meet on Monday to review the
proposed transaction with GM and is fairly likely to approve a
deal, industry executives and bankers said Sunday after insisting
on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting could last into Tuesday, and the board might ask
its negotiators to continue working beyond then, especially if
DaimlerChrysler comes back with a more attractive proposal at the
last moment, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers in Italy, where the troubles of Fiat's car division
have been a long-running national story, reported Sunday that Fiat
would hand over a 20 percent stake in its car operations in
exchange for a 5 percent stake in GM and possibly a seat on GM's
board. The transaction would also involve some sharing of engines
and auto parts and Fiat's use of the Internet buying service for
parts that GM, DaimlerChrysler and Ford Motor are setting up, the
papers reported. But auto industry officials said Sunday that these
and other provisions of the deal were still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Trade Minister Piero Fassino of Italy said that some
alliance between Fiat and a foreign carmaker was ``an inevitable
move.'' He told La Repubblica, a daily in Rome, that ``whoever
wishes to hold on to Fiat in its present form risks marginalizing
it further and further.''
</P>
<P>
   GM, DaimlerChrysler and Fiat representatives declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   If Fiat sells part or all of its car business, it is likely to
focus on its profitable divisions, which make heavy trucks and
tractors. Fiat is considering whether to make a bid for Volvo AB,
the world's second-largest maker of heavy trucks, executives close
to the company said Sunday. Fiat had tried unsuccessfully last year
to buy all of the Swedish company, which decided instead to sell
its car-building division to Ford and focus only on heavy trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission is widely expected to use antitrust
concerns to block Volvo's $7.4 billion acquisition of Scania,
Sweden's other big truck maker. If the commission does so, Volvo
would be a ripe target for a takeover, and Fiat might make an
unsolicited offer, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Volvo has made preliminary contact with several
rivals, including Renault's truck unit, about a possible
combination, the executives said, though talks are not expected to
begin in earnest until the European Commission makes its final
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat, Italy's largest company with investments across many
industries, has been struggling for nearly a year with the question
of what to do with its car operations, which have been gradually
losing market share in Italy and in Europe for years. Having
publicly adopted the General Electric Co.'s management philosophy
of abandoning markets in which it does not hold a commanding market
share, Fiat has courted every big automaker in the world in recent
months in search of an alliance or buyer for its car operations.
Fiat still sells Ferraris in the United States but stopped selling
new Fiat brand cars here in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat's attractions are its strong market share in South America,
its shrunken but still large market share in Italy and its lineup
of freshly redesigned small cars, auto executives have said in
interviews in recent months. While Fiat held 11 percent of the
European market last year, it had nearly 38 percent of the Italian
market last year and 30 percent of the promising Brazilian market.
</P>
<P>
   And while the small-car market around the world is extremely
unprofitable because manufacturers in South Korea and other
recently industrialized countries are producing too many of them,
rising oil prices are beginning to reawaken auto manufacturers'
interest in the market segment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But potential buyers have been leery of Fiat's reputation for
overstaffed, inefficient factories in Italy, with powerful unions
and mediocre quality.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government's recent enthusiasm for a Fiat deal with
a foreign automaker has sparked hope that government money might be
used to help unionized workers retire, allowing Fiat to slim down
its factory work forces, said an American executive who insisted on
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   GM has embarked on a global strategy of tying itself to midsize
automakers with large stakes in their home markets or with valuable
technology. In Japan, it has long had minority stakes in Isuzu and
Suzuki and a technology alliance with Toyota Motor. This winter it
took a stake in Fuji Heavy Industries, which makes Subaru cars and
is a leader in all-wheel-drive technology, and agreed to start
buying six-cylinder engines from Honda.
</P>
<P>
   GM announced in early January that it was exercising an option
to buy the half of Sweden's Saab that it did not already own. And
in a single week in mid-January, the company entered into marketing
partnerships with Sony, America Online and NetZero.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Smith Jr., GM's chairman, articulated the new strategy
in a speech on Jan. 17, repudiating the company's nearly
century-old strategy of self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach is to develop long-term relationships with other
companies that offer a unique advantage to the General Motors group
of brands and businesses,'' Smith said then. ``This alliance
strategy is our major thrust, and it is clearly a different
approach to growth than most people have associated with General
Motors _ or with the rest of the industry, for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   GM has been losing market share rapidly in the small-car segment
in the United States to Korean producers and recently canceled
plans to redesign the small Chevrolet Cavalier because it could not
figure out how to make a profit on it. Even GM's Saturn unit has
been cutting back output because of slow sales.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler has also been looking for alliances and
acquisitions lately, both to penetrate difficult markets and to
respond to regulatory pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Because its Mercedes and Chrysler divisions both make fairly
large cars and sport utility vehicles, DaimlerChrysler faces
difficulties in meeting the tighter fuel-economy requirements
planned by the European Community, and has been looking for ways to
increase its share of the small-car market as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Like GM, DaimlerChrysler also needs to sell more small cars so
as to lure younger, less affluent buyers to its brands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 1717EST &QL; 
