<HEADER>
A4670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ICANN-ASSESS-550&AMP;ADD-     03-12 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICANN-ASSESS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN A NAME? ARCANE INTERNAL BICKERING, INTERNET AGENCY GRIMLY
LEARNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ The battle-weary group of appointees who have
spent more than a year trying to invent a democratic charter for
the Internet's first administrative body arrived here in Egypt last
week eager to finish a major part of their mission _ completing
plans for an election that would choose their successors.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as they were bombarded with calls for delay, 18 months
of setbacks and of frustration exploded into a tense, sometimes
hostile showdown between the group _ the founding board of the
Internet Corp. for Assigned Names and Numbers, or Icann _ and the
people they were supposed to represent.
</P>
<P>
   Icann was created by the Clinton administration to administer
the Internet's address, or domain-name system, and at the same time
produce a plan for turning that responsibility over to a fully
elected successor board.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, it found itself resisting rather than embracing
real consensus among public interest groups over popular election
of the 50 percent of the new 18-member board that is supposed to
represent the global network's tens of millions of users worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the board bowed to the pressure, agreeing on Friday
at the end of a four-day meeting to slow the election process and
study ways to improve it .
</P>
<P>
   But it was clearly an unwelcome extension of terms for the
initial 10 appointed board members who had planned to hand over
Icann's reins on Sept. 30. Appointed late in 1998, the board's
first meeting, in Cambridge, Mass., offered a taste of the acrimony
that lay ahead. The members were greeted by a hostile crowd of
several hundred, some of whom saw Icann as part of a secret
conspiracy to advance big-business interests at the expense of the
Internet's freewheeling traditions.
</P>
<P>
   And since then, the board's every action seems to have evoked
controversy. Last year, the group was summoned before Congress and
forced to open board meetings to the public and to drop plans for
financing its operations through a $1 annual fee on each of the
more than 6 million addresses registered in the popular .com, .net
and .org domains.
</P>
<P>
   Its very first charge _ to break up Network Solutions'
government-sanctioned monopoly in the highly lucrative domain-name
registration business _ got bogged down in protracted negotiations
after the Herndon, Va., company refused to recognize Icann's
authority.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps its biggest trial has been the tug of war between
special interests wanting the board to move quickly to add new
levels of competition in the registration of domain names and those
calling for more attention to getting the process right.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the appointed board members are accused almost
daily, on postings to e-mail lists, of everything from professional
ethics breaches to criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   But such tensions, said Jerry Berman, executive director of the
Center for Democracy and Technology, which led the call for an
overhaul of the general election process, were simply growing
pains. The board's animosity toward his group last week, he said,
amounted to ``shooting the messenger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once everybody calmed down, they made their decision on its
merits,'' Berman said. ``I think they will be surprised at how much
applause they get. I think it will be a unique experience for
them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The showdown had been brewing since March 3, when two public
interest groups, Berman's Center for Democracy as well as Common
Cause, jointly issued a 30-page report criticizing Icann's plan for
letting computer users around the world elect nine of the 18 board
members by Sept. 30. The first nine have already joined the interim
board; they were elected last fall by three so-called supporting
organizations representing different interests: Internet service
providers, domain-name registration companies and intellectual
property interests concerned about protecting their brands online.
</P>
<P>
   Icann's plan called for letting any Internet user 16 or older
with a permanent e-mail and postal address vote for a special
council that would in turn select the nine at-large members. But
the March 3 report said the plan was plagued by conflicting goals,
an unclear mission and a lack of accountability and safeguards
against the election's being captured by special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   It urged the group to put aside deadline pressures and to
instead concentrate on improving the process to ensure that the
election would be legitimate. The report urged Icann to replace the
electoral council system with direct voting, to more clearly define
the organization's role as an Internet administrator and to better
educate the public about its role in administering the Internet's
address system.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the board agreed to hold direct elections for five
new members by Nov. 1, then study how best to elect the four others
and create a permanent process.
</P>
<P>
   Berman's counterpart at Common Cause, Scott Harshbarger, said
the board's compromise set the stage ``for holding open and
democratic elections on an international basis in the new online
world of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear if Icann can set aside the animosities that
erupted here last week and work with the Center for Democracy and
Technology, Common Cause and The Carter Center's election
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   The board's acting chairwoman, Esther Dyson, told her colleagues
on Friday that ``there is a wealth of experience being offered,''
adding, ``I know some people don't appreciate it, but I hope we
will continue to draw on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other board members, however, felt that the Center for
Democracy, Common Cause and some other consumer-related interests
had arrived in Cairo asking for too much too late.
</P>
<P>
   The public interest groups only started attending Icann meetings
last August. And their study of the at-large elections was not
begun until the board had already adopted its two-tier plan.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Kraaijenbrink, a Dutch board member, reacted with hostility
as people lined up on Thursday to oppose the plan, which Icann had
hoped to make final on Friday. He angrily told the crowd, ``I don't
want to be back to square one,'' and emphasized that he was eager
to hand the reins to a fully elected board.
</P>
<P>
   Icann's charge, said Kraaijenbrink and a fellow board member,
Gregory Crew, is to oversee the narrow technical functions of the
Internet. But these functions are not easily isolated from broader
policy issues. One of the first decisions the interim Icann board
made was to prohibit cybersquatting _ the bad-faith registration of
domain names based on others' trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   After a night's rest, the full board decided to streamline and
stagger the elections _ a move that many of those attending saw as
a key test of Icann's legitimacy as a bottoms-up governing body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not persuaded by the arguments,'' Kraaijenbrink said.
``But I observed the reality of the situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
