<SLUG> BC-BERKSHIRE-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERKSHIRE HATHAWAY CONSIDERS BUYING BACK SOME OF ITS OWN SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FlOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warren E. Buffett is not particularly enamored of the stocks
that Berkshire Hathaway owns, even though they have declined
substantially in price. But he has found a stock he thinks is cheap
_ one that Berkshire may begin buying soon: Berkshire Hathaway's
own shares.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a dreadful one for Berkshire. Its major 1998
acquisition, General Re, had poor results and many of the stocks in
the portfolio that brought fame and wealth to Buffett, the
Berkshire chairman and chief executive, lost value even while the
overall market was rising. Overall, Berkshire reported profits of
$1.56 billion, or $1,025 a share, in 1999, down from $2.83 billion,
or $2,262 a share a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Berkshire's Class A stock fell during the year for
the first time since 1990, and it has continued to fall this year,
closing Friday at $41,300, less than half the $84,000 peak it
reached in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to shareholders in Berkshire's annual report,
released over the weekend, Buffett again warned that stock prices
are generally high, reflecting investors' ``wildly optimistic''
expectations. As for the companies in which Berkshire has large
positions, ``the prices of the fine businesses we already own are
just not that attractive,'' he wrote. ``That's why we haven't added
to our present holdings.''
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire has never bought back any of its own shares, and
Buffett said that he thinks that share repurchases are often done
by companies interested in pumping up the price of their shares
even though they are already overvalued and buying back shares
will, in the long run, hurt those shareholders who stay.
</P>
<P>
   But Buffett said that when the share price fell below $45,000 in
February, he considered making purchases, but decided against doing
so until shareholders could be told of the possibility. The
February plunge came on rumors regarding Buffett's health. The
price soon recovered when those rumors were denied, but in recent
days it has begun falling again.
</P>
<P>
   By setting a price below which he deems the shares attractive,
Buffett may have provided some support for the stock even if the
company does not make purchases. ``I view it as an IQ test for
investors,'' said Alice Shroeder, an analyst for PaineWebber. ``If
Warren Buffett is a buyer, would you be a buyer or a seller?''
</P>
<P>
   That comment reflects Buffett's legendary status as an investor.
It is a reputation that has made Berkshire's annual meeting
something of a pilgrimage for thousands of investors _ so much so
that this year's annual meeting is being held on a Saturday, rather
than on a Monday as in past years, because Buffett feared the
crowds would tie up traffic in downtown Omaha if it were held on a
weekday.
</P>
<P>
   But Buffett's recent performance as a money manager leaves
something to be desired, as he wrote in his letter to shareholders.
Buffett has long measured his performance against the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index. It gained 19.5 percent last year, not including
dividends, while Berkshire's book value, largely reflecting the
value of the investments, rose just 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the worst absolute performance of my tenure and,
compared to the S&AMP;P, the worst relative performance as well,''
Buffett wrote in the company's annual report, released Saturday.
``Even Inspector Clouseau could find the guilty party: your
chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the company's seven largest investments at the beginning
of 1999, only one _ American Express _ rose as much as the S&AMP;P did
during the year. Two others, The Washington Post Co. and Wells
Fargo, showed more modest gains, and four declined: Coca-Cola, Walt
Disney, Freddie Mac and Gillette. During 1999, Buffett did not add
to any of the positions. He appears to have sold all _ or at least
most _ of the Disney stake and to have made smaller sales of Wells
Fargo and Freddie Mac shares. So far this year, all of the six
still held have gone down in price, while Disney has recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Buffett has avoided technology investments. ``We
share the general view that society will be transformed by their
products and services,'' he wrote in the annual report. ``Our
problem _ which we can't solve by studying up _ is that we have no
insights into which participants in the tech field posess a truly
durable competitive advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Early last year, Berkshire did invest in Microsoft preferred
stock that was later converted to common stock. If the company
still owns that stock _ and Buffett did not discuss it in his
letter _ it would be worth $19 million now. But that is a small
amount relative to Berkshire's six major equity investments, whose
market value at the end of last year ranged from $960 million for
The Washington Post to $11.7 billion for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Berkshire Hathaway remains very much an ``old economy''
company. Its major business is insurance, as the owner of a number
of companies including Geico, an auto insurer that has been gaining
market share and in the process making life harder for other
insurers with higher cost structures. In 1998, Berkshire Hathaway
bought General Re, which suffered an underwriting loss of $1.2
billion last year. Buffett blamed industry conditions, but said
there were signs that pricing of reinsurance policies was starting
to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett said the company's other operations generally performed
well, with the exception of its shoe business. As the owner of
Dexter and H.H. Brown, Berkshire is now the largest shoe
manufacturer in the country _ a dubious distinction given the
decline of that industry. He said the company was trying to
maintain American operations, but had shifted some production to
other countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
