<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4675 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-12 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ST. PAT'S PREP: THE SAN FRANCISCO READER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, poet  &UR; Dylan Thomas &LR;  described San Francisco in
a letter to his wife,  &UR; Caitlin &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't think that such a place as San Francisco could
exist. The wonderful sunlight there, the hills, the great bridges,
the Pacific at your shoes. Beautiful Chinatown. Every race in the
world. The sardine fleets sailing out. The little cable cars
whizzing down the city hills. ... Seafood is cheap, Chinese food is
cheaper, and lovely. California wine is good. The iced bock beer is
good. What more? And the city is built on hills; it dances in the
sun for nine months of the year; and the Pacific Ocean never runs
dry.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kevin Reilly  &LR; performs ``Dylan in San Francisco'' _ a fictional
re-creation of a reading given by Thomas in San Francisco _ one
Sunday a month at Johnny Foley's Irish House and Pub.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In other local news:
</P>
<P>
   Erotica USA, the ``world's largest erotic consumer trade show''
_ including the show, a lecture series and related entertainment _
comes to the Bill Graham Civil Center Auditorium on April 13.
</P>
<P>
   And the Luk Tung Kuen exercise group, which works out every
morning in Washington Square Park, honored  &UR; Tom O'Connor &LR; , the
park's gardener, at its annual New Year's banquet last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we do our Luk Tung Kuen exercises, we see Tom hauling soil
from one place to another, planting new shrubs and flowers,
clearing paths and mowing the grass,'' said the official tribute.
O'Connor's been on the job for about a year, and member  &UR; Rosalie &LR; 
 &UR; Ross  &LR; says the park ``has never looked more beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Rod McLellan Co. is going to auction off cuttings
from  &UR; Raymond Burr &LR; 's orchid collection, including his prize
``vanilla orchid,'' in Watsonville on March 18.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCHOLARSHIP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, the Smell &AMP; Taste Treatment and Research Foundation
has released results of a survey that determined that people who
smell and eat garlic bread at dinner make fewer negative and more
positive comments about family members.
</P>
<P>
   According to Foundation head  &UR; Alan Hirsch &LR; , business meetings
and political debates might be facilitated by the serving of garlic
bread.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SANTANA AND SMELL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a Rolling Stone interview,  &UR; Carlos Santana &LR;  says that he has
visions and speaks to spirits and that his sense of smell has
played an important role in his life.
</P>
<P>
   He and  &UR; Miles Davis &LR; , for example, often converse. ``He just
seems as cool as ever,'' says Santana. ``I can smell him. Even on
the other side, there is smell. Like, when babies are born, there's
two smells _ one is chicken soup, which is the flesh, and the other
is lilacs, which is coming from the spiritual garden. The spirit
has a lilac smell.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said he could never be attracted to men. ``I mean, the
smell of men, it makes me sick. I'm not into men at all. ... Women
have a different kind of alluring smell.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Lily Tomlin &LR;  is circulating a letter asking every member of a
gay couple to fill out a census form indicating that he or she
lives with an ``unmarried partner,'' thereby standing up to be
counted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Marcia Tanner &LR;  suggests calling those ``suddenly successful
young people'' ``ssyppies.''  &UR; Eric Brizee  &LR; suggests ``chippies'';
 &UR; Mark Burstein &LR;  likes the sound of ``dot-commies.''
</P>
<P>
   - The Washington Monthly whispers that Health and Human Services
Secretary  &UR; Donna Shalala  &LR; _ who used to be president of the
University of Wisconsin _ may become president of Stanford
University at the conclusion of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING HEALED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More magazine cover woman  &UR; Cybill Shepherd &LR;  describes the
heartbreak of her breakup with her most recent boyfriend, for which
she says she was totally unprepared. ``I have to say, I went
through a loneliness that I hadn't before experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   After several months of solitude, she took a role in a movie,
which the magazine says is due out in May and doesn't have a title
yet. ``On the second day of shooting, I felt my heart lift. I was
involved again. I thought, `OK, I'm going to get better.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspired,'' says More, ``she programmed her cell phone to play
the opening notes of Beethoven's `Ode to Joy' each time it rang.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are always more difficult for me than women. I tried Mick
Jagger one time. It did not work for me _ it was not simpatico.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Ennio Marchetti &LR; , whose ``Ennio'' is at the Theatre on the
Square in San Francisco, on his difficulties with same-sex satire.
</P>
