<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-R-REAL-SIMPLE-MEDIA-A     03-12 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-REAL-SIMPLE-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSH FOR NEW MAGAZINE MAY TEST AOL-TIME WARNER SYNERGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT6  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan Wyland, managing editor of Real Simple, a new magazine
from Time Inc. that will arrive on newsstands in two weeks, sat in
her austere office last week and showed off proof pages of the
first issue. She pointed to an artful, stylishly minimalist
photograph illustrating the article ``The Fastest, Easiest Way to
Clean Your Bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet you have never, ever seen such a beautiful picture of a
toilet bowl,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Do beautiful photographs of toilet bowls _ complete with a
toilet brush jutting jauntily from the lip _ make a magazine? The
editors of Time Inc. think so, and so does their prospective
partner, America Online, which has been working with the Real
Simple staff to plan promotion for the magazine since AOL and Time
Warner announced their plans to merge in January.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the affiliation with AOL helps the introduction of Real
Simple will be closely watched at Time Inc. It is, in its
relatively small way, a test run of the larger possibilities for
synergy between America Online and Time Warner, a company that has
had a reputation for preventing the easy meshing of internal
corporate cultures. It will also test how AOL balances the
interests of Time Warner properties against those of other content
providers on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Ann S. Moore, president of the People division of Time Inc. _
the group that includes People, People en Espanol, Teen People and
In Style _ said that the magazine, the first to be introduced after
the merger announcement two months ago, would use AOL as a
promotional platform and also look to AOL members for feedback on
editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   In the first month of Real Simple's arrival on newsstands, for
example, the AOL welcome page, which has some of the highest
traffic on the Internet, will contain a link to a Real Simple Web
site. The site will feature the cover, table of contents, a
sampling of articles, AOL message boards and chat rooms concerned
with Real Simple issues. It will also have a special subscription
offer for AOL subscribers that is now planned to last at least a
year. AOL has more than 20 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Time Inc. as part of a broad arrangement across all its
magazines, will begin to distribute AOL discs.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL and Real Simple have the same mission: to simplify the
consumer's life,'' Moore said. ``We can leverage the Time Inc.
assets to promote the magazine, and when you crank up AOL on top of
that and use the power of their 21 million subscribers _ well, put
it this way, I have not broken out in a sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple is based on what might appear to be a paradox: if
your life is complicated, buy more stuff _ or at least a
subscription to a new magazine that may gather dust bunnies under
the bed along with all the other magazines you have not had the
chance to throw out.
</P>
<P>
   According to the magazine's advertising media kit, Real Simple
is ``about streamlining, refining and distilling your life to the
essence of what pleases you.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a hybrid, combining the lifestyle approach of Martha
Stewart Living, the common-sense housekeeping guidelines of Good
Housekeeping, the shopping opportunities of In Style (with ``800''
numbers and Web addresses in captions so readers can easily buy
featured merchandise) and the Internet service articles of PC
Magazine. An article concerned with bathroom grout _ beautifully
photographed, of course _ mixes with a fashion feature about the
classic white shirt and a guide to paying household bills online.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Sareyan, the magazine's publisher, said Real Simple
was not about ``move-to-the-wilderness kind of simplification.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people who feel that their lives are out of
control, and the idea of simplifying your life is such a wonderful
vehicle for so many advertisers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple's target demographic group _ mostly working mothers
in their 30s and 40s who are fairly affluent and, for the most
part, college-educated _ happens to match up neatly with AOL's
family-oriented approach, Sareyan noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're all about is so close to what AOL's brand equity is
all about,'' he said. ``We both embrace the Internet as a
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolzien, a media analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., said
that while the demographic profiles meshed, it was not yet clear if
the cross-promotional plans would yield results.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the promotional benefits for both companies were
potentially enormous, especially once subscribers to Time Inc.
magazines _ titles as various as Time, Baby Talk, Cooking Light,
Sports Illustrated, Wallpaper, Life, Mutual Funds and Weight
Watchers _ received the free AOL disc.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said one advantage of using AOL as a promotional tool
would be instant response from AOL members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get research back from their membership, and their
members get to tell our editors story ideas, give us feedback on
ideas we may want to do, submit their favorite recipe,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Time Inc., the promotional push has been fierce.
Subscription copies of Money, Entertainment Weekly, In Style and
People went out with cover wrappers offering subscriptions to Real
Simple, and 20 of Time Inc.'s 30 magazines carried ads for Real
Simple.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear how the deal with AOL will affect other Time
Inc. magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Both Stephen M. Case, chairman of AOL, and Norman Pearlstine,
editor in chief at Time Inc., have said that AOL would not depend
on Time Warner alone to supply content and that Time Inc. would not
use AOL alone as a consumer outlet.
</P>
<P>
   One potential source of concern is that AOL has investments in
both iVillage Inc. and Oxygen Media Inc., whose women's Internet
sites are aimed at the same demographic groups as Real Simple is.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Real Simple promotion does raise the specter of being in
a lot of businesses and targeting the same audience and having to
cross-promote everything to that audience,'' said Mark Mooradian,
an analyst at Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Redling, senior vice president of AOL brand marketing who
has been overseeing the Real Simple project, said that while AOL
had always been built on partnerships, there was now a mandate of
sorts to talk about marketing opportunities with the Time Inc.
magazines in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one focus at AOL and that is to deliver the best
content,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Redling pointed out that AOL featured Sports Illustrated's
swimsuit issue on AOL last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most successful promotion AOL has ever done in the
sense of traffic,'' he said. ``So we are talking to all the other
titles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
