 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ST. PAT'S PREP: THE SAN FRANCISCO READER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, poet  &UR; Dylan Thomas &LR;  described San Francisco in
a letter to his wife,  &UR; Caitlin &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't think that such a place as San Francisco could
exist. The wonderful sunlight there, the hills, the great bridges,
the Pacific at your shoes. Beautiful Chinatown. Every race in the
world. The sardine fleets sailing out. The little cable cars
whizzing down the city hills. ... Seafood is cheap, Chinese food is
cheaper, and lovely. California wine is good. The iced bock beer is
good. What more? And the city is built on hills; it dances in the
sun for nine months of the year; and the Pacific Ocean never runs
dry.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kevin Reilly  &LR; performs ``Dylan in San Francisco'' _ a fictional
re-creation of a reading given by Thomas in San Francisco _ one
Sunday a month at Johnny Foley's Irish House and Pub.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In other local news:
</P>
<P>
   Erotica USA, the ``world's largest erotic consumer trade show''
_ including the show, a lecture series and related entertainment _
comes to the Bill Graham Civil Center Auditorium on April 13.
</P>
<P>
   And the Luk Tung Kuen exercise group, which works out every
morning in Washington Square Park, honored  &UR; Tom O'Connor &LR; , the
park's gardener, at its annual New Year's banquet last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we do our Luk Tung Kuen exercises, we see Tom hauling soil
from one place to another, planting new shrubs and flowers,
clearing paths and mowing the grass,'' said the official tribute.
O'Connor's been on the job for about a year, and member  &UR; Rosalie &LR; 
 &UR; Ross  &LR; says the park ``has never looked more beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Rod McLellan Co. is going to auction off cuttings
from  &UR; Raymond Burr &LR; 's orchid collection, including his prize
``vanilla orchid,'' in Watsonville on March 18.
</P>
