<TEXT>
<P>
   (lh) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Monday, March 13. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-APOLOGY (Rome) _ Saying ``we humbly ask forgiveness,'' John
Paul II delivered the most sweeping papal apology ever, repenting
for the errors of his church over the past 2,000 years. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   AETNA (Dateline TK) _ Aetna Inc., the largest U.S. life and
health insurer, said Sunday that it declined a $10 billion takeover
offer from Wellpoint Health Networks Inc. and ING America Insurance
and decided to split itself into two public companies. (Summary
from wires.) By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WINE (Shanghai) _ Red wine is the drink of the moment in
China, and winemakers around the world are feeling the effects.
Demand for wine picked up after the government began promoting
fruit-based alcohol a few years ago, and Western winemakers rushed
in, shipping wine in giant 22,000 liter containers. But now the
Chinese want domestic wine, so much of the Western supply is being
sold at happy-hour prices by Customs after sitting for months in
government warehouses. This isn't doing much for the wine
exporters, and it isn't exactly helping the Chinese develop a taste
for the grape. It's common for Chinese wine drinkers to mix red
wine with Sprite and white with Coke and to drink the concoctions
in gulps. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Dateline TK) _ George W. Bush holds rallies in Florida and
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   HUDSON-VALLEY-INDUSTRY (Undated) _ Decades after smokestack
industries largely disappeared from the Hudson River valley,
leaving behind an environmental and economic mess, plans are afoot
to build more than a dozen industrial plants in the region. Some
welcome the return of manufacturing. Others say it threatens to
undermine years of effort to reclaim the Hudson from industrial
pollution. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-SHOOTING (Beirut, Lebanon) _ A close associate of Iran's
reformist president and one of the main organizers of the
reformers' landslide victory in parliamentary elections last month
was shot and critically wounded Sunday by a gunman who dismounted
from a motorcycle pillion on a busy avenue in central Tehran and
shot him in the face. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA-DRAW (Undated) _ NCAA men's basketball pairings are
announced. By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
