<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-THEATERS-ART-1300(     03-12 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-THEATERS-ART-1300(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIT NERVOUSLY, THEATER ROW PACKS UP 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV:  Photo NYT7  is being sent to NYT photo clients.  Map  is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the late 1970s when Times Square belonged to the
prostitutes and peep shows, a collection of theater companies moved
into a handful of stages carved out of shuttered massage parlors on
West 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   In the years that followed the theaters suffered through
stickups, recessions and aborted development projects and survived
to see a renewed Midtown rise around them.
</P>
<P>
   But now the redevelopment of 42nd Street is altering the
theaters' future. The local development corporation that helped
create the strip now known as Theater Row is closing four of the
playhouses as it prepares to break ground on an apartment tower and
collection of new stages between Dyer and Ninth Avenues. There are
no definite plans for the western half of Theater Row, between Dyer
and 10th Avenues, but the property owners and the theater companies
that make their homes there say development is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Although actors and stagehands are eagerly anticipating working
in the new spaces that will rise on Theater Row, many said they
would miss the idiosyncrasies of their current homes. Others fear
that the most experimental theaters, which are also generally the
poorest, will be pushed out of the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would moan about the lousy dressing rooms, but there is
something that is very actor-friendly and theater-friendly about
these spaces,'' said Anita Keal, who performs in ``The Countess,''
a play about a 19th-century love affair. The show plans to move to
Lamb's Theater on West 44th Street after its current home, the
Samuel Beckett Theater, closes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As Keal spoke, crew members preparing the stage for the next
performance offered their assessments of the theater, with its
slightly-too-small stage, oddly sloping ceiling and unpredictable
heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got its quirks,'' said Juliet King, the assistant stage
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Carhart, the master electrician, added, ``But the quirks
are what give it its charm.''
</P>
<P>
   Playwrights Horizons, a nonprofit theater company, opened the
first stage on the strip in 1975. Three years later the 42nd Street
Development Corp. opened several more theaters in an attempt to use
the performing arts to renew a desolate block. The development
corporation offered inexpensive, often below-market rents to
theater groups, which in return stabilized the neighborhood and
brought in new, paying visitors. Theater Row became one of the
early successes in the continuing effort to reinvigorate 42nd
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight playhouses on Theater Row, Playwrights Horizons has
been the most significant, giving a start to Broadway productions
like ``Driving Daisy,'' ``Sunday in the Park With George'' and most
recently, ``James Joyce's `The Dead.''' Other theaters have also
had success. ``Nunsense'' ran for nine years at the Douglas
Fairbanks Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense of purpose; we were united on this bizarre
block of Manhattan,'' said Andre Bishop, who worked at Playwrights
Horizons from 1975 to 1991 and is now the artistic director at the
Lincoln Center Theater. ``Real estate gentrification was the last
thing on our minds. We were just putting on plays.''
</P>
<P>
   But the theaters did renew the neighborhood, and now the more
recent Midtown boom has opened the way for more lucrative
development. The first theaters to be affected will be the four
owned by the development corporation: the Theater Row, Judith
Anderson, Harold Clurman and Beckett Theaters.
</P>
<P>
   All four will close this month to make way for the redevelopment
project. Although the contracts are not complete, the developement
corporation is planning to rebuild much of the block between Ninth
and Dyer Avenues and create four 99-seat stages, a 199-seat
theater, a 499-seat playhouse co-owned by the Shubert Organization
and an apartment tower. Some theater hands wonder aloud if the
nonprofit theaters that built the row will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theaters held that area together when no one wanted to go
there,'' said Tom Herman, who has directed shows at the Beckett and
at the Pulse Ensemble Theater. ``But it will be difficult for the
small producers to get back into Theater Row.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Papert, president of the development corporation, disputed
that prediction. The proposed theaters will continue to offer
discounted, affordable space to nonprofit theater productions and
will not change what has made Theater Row a vibrant artistic
community, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something that is nice and cozy about Theater Row,
and that is not going to disappear,'' he said. ``It will be just as
it has always been.''
</P>
<P>
   But the current weekly rent for nonprofit groups, $1,800, will
probably rise when the the old, worn stages are replaced with new,
well-equipped performance areas, Papert acknowledged. It is also
unclear how much office space will be available in the new complex
for nonprofit groups to rent.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Theater of New York has until next Monday to move its
offices from Theater Row, and Tuvia Tenenbom, the artistic
director, is desperately hunting for a new home. The real strength
of Theater Row, Tenenbom said, was that it gave small companies
access to a mainstream, suburban audience that the small downtown
stages have a harder time attracting.
</P>
<P>
   ``On 42nd Street you get a different audience, people from New
Jersey and Long Island,'' he said. ``Here we were trying to
convince the general public that pure theater isn't dead.''
Tenenbom said he feared that the Jewish Theater would have trouble
finding the money to rent the new stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be all commercial; it will be Merrill Lynch in the
theater,'' he said. ``It is sad. It is a little bit of the death of
the theater.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. Max Ferra brought the Intar
Hispanic-American Arts Center to Theater Row in 1978, leaving last
year to make way for the renovation. But he said that he had been
promised space in the new complex and that he believed it would
attract a bigger audience and help his organization grow. ``We will
be part of the new 42nd Street,'' he said. ``It will be a complete
uplift of the whole street from east to west.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Sprecher, the Off Broadway theater manager who will run the
new 499-seat theater, said the larger theater would bring a new,
bigger audience to the smaller theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are building an ideally suited playhouse for plays and
small musicals,'' he said. ``Off Broadway is entering into what
people think of as mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no specific plans for the block between Dyer
and 10th Avenues, tenants there are on short-term or month-to-month
leases. William J. Condren, the general partner of Theater Row
Phase 2, which controls the property, said he anticipated
conducting a beauty pageant among developers interested in building
on the land. `` Right hasn't shown up yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the theater companies on the block worry that Right
will come along shortly. Alexa Kelly, the artistic director of the
Pulse Ensemble Theater at 432 West 42nd St., said she feared her
company would lose its space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked very hard to help the community, and now we are
feeling very upset that we are just being ousted,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Krebs, the owner of the John Houseman and Fairbanks
Theaters, said his stages would remain open at least two more
years. He said he hoped that whoever was chosen to rebuild the
block between Dyer and 10th Avenues would create new spaces for Off
Broadway theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is inevitable that the whole block will be changed,'' Krebs
said. ``The only hope is that the Off Broadway need will be met and
the vision will be realized with a string of theaters along 42nd
Street.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
