<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4684 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-RICKMOODY-INTERVIEW-A     03-12 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICKMOODY-INTERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEAK WORKS BELIE WRITER RICK MOODY'S JOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
   
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: ALSO MOVING IN THE ``L'' CATEGORY)
 &UR; Never mind that his novels employ less-than-joyful themes _
electrocution, prepubescent sex, ailing mothers who dribble
``stalactites of drool,'' drug addiction, self-immolation, Richard
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Moody has written such bleak stories as ``The Ice Storm,'' which
became the bleak 1997 Ang Lee-directed movie starring Kevin
KleiDf(K &Cx1f; '',igourney Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   Writing gloom under cover of mirth, he follows a daily regimen
but works only when the spirit moves him. At his home on Fishers
Island in Long Island Sound, he might write by day or he might
write all night, a comfortable schedule that fosters bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hypothesis is that the best way to convey joy to my readers
is if I am joyful when I'm on the job,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Joy brings productivity. At age 38, he's already published three
novels (``The Ice Storm,'' `` Garden State, Purple America''), a
collection of short stories (``The Ring of Brightest Angels Around
Heaven'') and edited a collection of essays titled ``Joyful Noise''
_ and there's that word again.
</P>
<P>
   Although Moody has been variously compared to the greats who
preceded him _ Cheever, Roth, Updike _ he modestly dismisses such
accolades, eschewing public-relations hype while recognizing that
hype and a hit movie have made him a marketable author who so far
can depend on each new work's being accepted by his publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaim also drags him into the Okefenokee Swamp of the book
tour, slogging across America to tout his latest work, leaving
behind his longtime companion, Amy, a computer-software writer who
comes along only to the more attractive cities.
</P>
<P>
   Amy will be coming along when Moody speaks during the Phoenix
Public Library's lecture series, ``Soothing Words,'' a three-month
event that began in January. This month's featured writers include
Moody on Thursday, March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Moody will appear at 7 p.m. at the Burton Barr Phoenix Central
Library to read from his coming collection of stories,
``Demonology,'' due out in January.2001.)
</P>
<P>
   Then he and Amy will head for his father's winter home in
Wickenburg, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Moody is a writer's writer, besotted by the English
language, heir to legendary wordsmiths Hemingway, Fitzgerald,
Joyce, Bellow, Beckett. He loves words as a writer because he loves
words as a reader and sprinkles his conversation with literary
quotations.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's own work is highly stylized _ too much so, some critics
say. But he prides himself on writing that has become denser over
the course of three novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made language exciting again,'' he says, less a boast
than an exaltation in the sheer beauty of well-crafted prose.
</P>
<P>
   Moody has been writing for 30 years. As a boy, he dabbled, but
he was easily distracted by other boyhood occupations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lacked follow-through,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Childhood in suburban Connecticut appeared idyllic from the
outside, but he confesses to harboring ``demons,'' suffering
frequent illnesses and being overly sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   The sensitivity that plagued him in his youth has served him
well as an adult observer of human emotions. He credits his
``finely calibrated compass that picks up what's going on in a
room.''
</P>
<P>
   In his teens, Moody began to write in earnest, producing short
stories and poems.
</P>
<P>
   Son of literary parents, he majored in English at Brown
University and began to write ``Garden State'' in 1986 while living
in Hoboken, N.J., holding down a day job in the editorial
department of the Simon &AMP; Schuster publishing house.
</P>
<P>
   Although the job slowed work on his novel, it taught him the
intricacies of the publishing business _ how to find an agent, how
to write a contract. It did not help sell his book, which was
rejected 22 times in a 15-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Moody despaired of drowning in the seas of rejection. Then, a
small press called Pushcart threw him a lifeline and even awarded
him its Pushcart Editors' Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   Work on his second novel, ``The Ice Storm,'' began in 1990.
Having quit his day job, he was able to write more swiftly,
completing the book in just two years. He was single then,
supporting himself on freelance editing and living hand to mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ice Storm'' was accepted by big-time publisher Little,
Brown and Co., and Moody forged a relationship with an editor who
respects his distinctive style.
</P>
<P>
   Moody became proficient at his craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured out how to tell a story,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Moody tries to do something different with each of his works,
their thread ``fealty to human emotions and human psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Garden State'' is the story of disaffected youth lost in
suburban New Jersey, contemplating life, death and rock and roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purple America'' is a deeply emotional book that examines how
one family's remorse ``trickles down through the generations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Black Veil,'' a non-fiction work due out this summer,
comes from family folklore about the Rev. Joseph Moody, said to
have inspired ``The Minister's Black Veil,'' a short story by
American author Nathaniel Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Ice Storm'' has been his bestseller, thanks in part to
the movie. The grim saga traces a brief span in the life of
Benjamin Hood, a suburbanite bored with marriage who dallies with a
neighbor, struggles to rein in his precocious daughter, Wendy, and
tries to discover himself during the sexual liberation of the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Moody was warned to fear the worst from Hollywood, and ``I DID
fear the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the respected Ang Lee, who also directed ``Sense and
Sensibility,'' allayed those fears. One red flag raised was the
casting of Christina Ricci, who had appeared in such films as ``The
Addams Family'' and ``Casper.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ricci's teen sexpot portrayal impressed Moody, as did the
film as a whole. Now he is waiting to hear about options on his
other works. Buoyed by his positive experiences with ``The Ice
Storm,'' he would happily return to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   With such success comes book tours, not the choicest part of the
profession. One tour took Moody on the road for five grueling
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But he enjoys meeting his readers, most of whom are under age
40.
</P>
<P>
   Writing is an isolating profession, after all, he notes as he
sits alone in his home on Fishers Island, while Amy lives across
the water in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   It is Amy who reads his work first and then filters the reviews,
passing along only those that offer constructive criticism.
Although wary of shaping his style to please critics, Moody says he
sometimes can learn from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust in the possibility that some harsh criticism will give
me an opportunity to improve,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And improvement brings joy. &QL; Reach the reporter at
Barbara.Yost(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at (602)444-7936. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HEADE-PROFILE-ART-2TA     03-12 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADE-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: NATURE CARESSED BY A HUMMINGBIRD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Approaching Thunderstorm,'' which greets the visitor at the
Martin Johnson Heade retrospective at the National Gallery of Art
in Washington, is one of the high points in 19th-century American
painting. It is also the hands-down winner in what might be called
the dark-before-the-storm category, which is saying something,
considering that Heade lived in an era rife with meteorologically
correct landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   The painting achieves this status by being both correct and not:
that is, palpably naturalistic yet dramatically decorative and
artificial. It places us a little distance inland from the edge of
a bay on which a man and dog sit, their backs to us, watching the
approach of a great storm across the water. From bottom to top the
image is a progression of curving bands of color: yellow sand,
eggplant-black water and gray-on-gray sky and clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The progression is divided midway by the bay's sandy outer arms,
which cut into the black water with a pincerlike sharpness that
also suggests twin flashes of lightning. Silhouetted against the
black, the man's red shirt and yellow vest and hat add to the
visual drama.
</P>
<P>
   The stillness of the image is beyond natural. The even, prestorm
light creates the feeling of a stage set, with each band of color
functioning like a separate painted stage flat. And it is a tiny
stage at that. Although a sizable painting, the scene feels small,
as if it were a model rendered at actual size. The man might almost
be a little leprechaun who sits more in our space than the
painting's, transfixed not only by the natural wonder of the storm
but by the abstract wonder of the colors and shapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Approaching Thunderstorm,'' which was acquired by the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in 1975, is the kind of painting that
you give your heart to before you know anything about the artist
who made it. Thus it is a little disappointing that the Heade show
contains nothing else that is quite like it and little else that is
quite as good. Closest in kind and quality is ``Thunderstorm on
Narragansett Bay,'' from 1868, which has the same purple palette
but fewer of the beguiling spatial tics.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first big Heade survey in 30 years and only the
second ever assembled. It has been organized by Theodore E.
Stebbins Jr., a leading Heade scholar and former curator at the
Museum of Fine Arts, Boston, where it was seen last fall. The show
comes with a detailed catalog and coincides with the publication of
Stebbins' magnum opus, ``The Life and Work of Martin Johnson Heade:
A Critical Analysis and Catalogue Raisonne.''
</P>
<P>
   The show and books provide a great deal of information about
Heade (pronounced heed), who was a busy man and turned out not only
hundreds of paintings but dozens of articles for the magazine
Forest and Stream under the pen name Didymus. In the end, one's
disappointment about the seeming singularity of ``Approaching
Thunderstorm'' is diluted by the deluge of fact and art, and the
bizarre tale of hard work, inspiration and obsession that they
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Heade was born in 1819 in Lumberton, Bucks County, Pa., and died
in St. Augustine, Fla., in 1904. He studied painting with the
Quaker preacher and folk painter Edward Hicks in Newtown, Pa., and
then struck out on his own, working as a portrait painter (one of
his subjects was Sam Houston), traveling to Rome, where he painted
street urchins with unmistakable American simplicity, and
exhibiting his first landscape at the Pennsylvania Academy in 1856.
</P>
<P>
   In 1858 he met Frederic Edwin Church. a leader of the Hudson
River School. Contact with Church and his work ignited Heade's
deep-seated passion for nature. ``Approaching Thunderstorm,'' which
he painted in 1859, is the first work of his artistic maturity.
</P>
<P>
   A final fascinating fact suggests a personal innocence that
echoes the professional innocence of his folk art beginnings: Heade
did not marry until 1883, when he was 64. He and his new wife, a
woman 20 years his junior named Elizabeth Smith, settled in
Florida, where his painting continued, unabated, until his death.
</P>
<P>
   Heade's work sank into obscurity after his death, and in the
decades after its rediscovery in the 1940s he was usually
considered a tangential member of the Hudson River School or a
latecomer to the American Luminist style. But this show sets him
apart, in a hermetically sealed compartment of his own creation. He
pursued a finely wrought realism from one interrelated motif to
another: landscapes, flower still lifes, hummingbirds, hummingbirds
chaperoned by orchids or passionflowers and, finally, recumbent
magnolia and lotus blossoms, painted a bit larger than life.
</P>
<P>
   Heade was particularly obsessed with hummingbirds, describing
his lifelong interest as ``monomaniacal.'' He collected them,
dissected them and made three trips to South America, where the
species was abundant, to study and paint them. His Forest and
Stream bibliography lists nine articles on the subject, including
``Hummingbirds as Pets'' and ``More Hummingbird Phantasies.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before his marriage, or for two-thirds of his long career, Heade
was something of a hummingbird himself. He never stayed more than a
year or two in one place, living and working in a string of U.S.
and European cities, summering in different locales and traveling
to Jamaica and South America.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his changes of address, he moved slowly as an artist
and sometimes did not seem to move at all. Whether to please
clients or to satisfy some inner urge, he painted his chosen motifs
again and again, often with very little variation and sometimes
with rotelike results. He was especially devoted to the salt marsh
landscape, painting his first in 1859 and his last in 1904. (The
catalogue raisonne reproduces more than 80.) But it is the birds
and flowers that account for nearly half the catalog's 619
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which runs through May 7, proceeds in clear-cut
chapters, with one subject to a gallery, beginning with the marine
paintings and ending with the magnolia still lifes. As it
progresses, it gets weirder and weirder. With all the hummingbirds
flirting with one another and buzzing about their nests and the
implicitly female flowers, it's hard not to think of procreation,
and not just for the survival of the species. By the final gallery
the reclining magnolia blossoms, whose petals fall this way and
that, seem to exude an aura of postcoital dishabille.
</P>
<P>
   But to a great extent the real tension in Heade's work is
spatial. Each new subject inspired a markedly different treatment
of pictorial space, one that was usually smaller, clearer or more
confined than its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The layered space and bands of color of ``Approaching
Thunderstorm,'' with its suggestion of miniaturization and its
contrast of far and further, was a sign of things to come. In the
marshland paintings Heade carefully takes the measure of
illusionistic space, marking off perfectly flat fields with neatly
conical haystacks as if placing rooks on a chessboard. And
miniature becomes almost microscopic: we see these images as if
through the wrong end of a telescope. The men harvesting the hay
are so far away they register as tiny dots of red and sometimes
yellow.
</P>
<P>
   The red shirt, whether small, as in the marine paintings, or
infinitesimal, as in the salt marsh landscapes, almost amounts to a
Heade signature.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With his hummingbird paintings, which began to proliferate after
his trip to Brazil in 1863-64, Heade brings the dots of color
forward as brilliantly colored and plumed birds, setting up a
dramatic contrast of near and far. The birds are depicted up close,
at actual size and in earnest detail. (They sometimes seem stuck to
the surfaces, like decals.)
</P>
<P>
   Behind them is a misty Andean Eden, where the earth, when
visible at all, presents a steep diagonal. When the hummingbirds
are joined by the big passionflowers and orchids, the images become
more real and the painting more windowlike than ever. The tour de
force in this series _ and nearly as good as ``Approaching
Thunderstorm'' _ is a horizontal painting that depicts 10 different
species of hummingbird darting in and out of a network of vines and
bright red flowers that suggest a decorative grille. (It can make
you think of such contemporary decorative naturalists as Philip
Taaffe and Fred Tomaselli.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the paintings of magnolia blossoms, Heade dispenses
with pretense: space itself has become actual size. It is
completely closed off, velvet lined, a little coffin, which turns
the big white flowers from postcoital to embalmed.
</P>
<P>
   The progression toward claustrophobic space is perhaps forced by
the installation of this show, which obscures the fact that Heade
worked on most of his subjects throughout his life. But it's clear
that he tended, with each new motif, toward contraction,
elimination and control. In the end the contained, finite volume,
so transfixingly hinted at in ``Approaching Thunderstorm,'' is made
real. Between the adored exotic birds, the boxlike space and the
prevailing aura of innocence and obsession, you may leave this show
feeling that you have met the Joseph Cornell of the 19th century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-RICKMOODY-INTERVIEW-A     03-12 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICKMOODY-INTERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEAK WORKS BELIE WRITER RICK MOODY'S JOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
   
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: ALSO MOVING IN THE ``E'' CATEGORY)
 &UR; Never mind that his novels employ less-than-joyful themes _
electrocution, prepubescent sex, ailing mothers who dribble
``stalactites of drool,'' drug addiction, self-immolation, Richard
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Moody has written such bleak stories as ``The Ice Storm,'' which
became the bleak 1997 Ang Lee-directed movie starring Kevin Klein
and Sigourney Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   Writing gloom under cover of mirth, he follows a daily regimen
but works only when the spirit moves him. At his home on Fishers
Island in Long Island Sound, he might write by day or he might
write all night, a comfortable schedule that fosters bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hypothesis is that the best way to convey joy to my readers
is if I am joyful when I'm on the job,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Joy brings productivity. At age 38, he's already published three
novels (``The Ice Storm,'' `` Garden State, Purple America''), a
collection of short stories (``The Ring of Brightest Angels Around
Heaven'') and edited a collection of essays titled ``Joyful Noise''
_ and there's that word again.
</P>
<P>
   Although Moody has been variously compared to the greats who
preceded him _ Cheever, Roth, Updike _ he modestly dismisses such
accolades, eschewing public-relations hype while recognizing that
hype and a hit movie have made him a marketable author who so far
can depend on each new work's being accepted by his publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaim also drags him into the Okefenokee Swamp of the book
tour, slogging across America to tout his latest work, leaving
behind his longtime companion, Amy, a computer-software writer who
comes along only to the more attractive cities.
</P>
<P>
   Amy will be coming along when Moody speaks during the Phoenix
Public Library's lecture series, ``Soothing Words,'' a three-month
event that began in January. This month's featured writers include
Moody on Thursday, March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Moody will appear at 7 p.m. at the Burton Barr Phoenix Central
Library to read from his coming collection of stories,
``Demonology,'' due out in January.2001.)
</P>
<P>
   Then he and Amy will head for his father's winter home in
Wickenburg, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Moody is a writer's writer, besotted by the English
language, heir to legendary wordsmiths Hemingway, Fitzgerald,
Joyce, Bellow, Beckett. He loves words as a writer because he loves
words as a reader and sprinkles his conversation with literary
quotations.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's own work is highly stylized _ too much so, some critics
say. But he prides himself on writing that has become denser over
the course of three novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made language exciting again,'' he says, less a boast
than an exaltation in the sheer beauty of well-crafted prose.
</P>
<P>
   Moody has been writing for 30 years. As a boy, he dabbled, but
he was easily distracted by other boyhood occupations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lacked follow-through,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Childhood in suburban Connecticut appeared idyllic from the
outside, but he confesses to harboring ``demons,'' suffering
frequent illnesses and being overly sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   The sensitivity that plagued him in his youth has served him
well as an adult observer of human emotions. He credits his
``finely calibrated compass that picks up what's going on in a
room.''
</P>
<P>
   In his teens, Moody began to write in earnest, producing short
stories and poems.
</P>
<P>
   Son of literary parents, he majored in English at Brown
University and began to write ``Garden State'' in 1986 while living
in Hoboken, N.J., holding down a day job in the editorial
department of the Simon &AMP; Schuster publishing house.
</P>
<P>
   Although the job slowed work on his novel, it taught him the
intricacies of the publishing business _ how to find an agent, how
to write a contract. It did not help sell his book, which was
rejected 22 times in a 15-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Moody despaired of drowning in the seas of rejection. Then, a
small press called Pushcart threw him a lifeline and even awarded
him its Pushcart Editors' Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   Work on his second novel, ``The Ice Storm,'' began in 1990.
Having quit his day job, he was able to write more swiftly,
completing the book in just two years. He was single then,
supporting himself on freelance editing and living hand to mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ice Storm'' was accepted by big-time publisher Little,
Brown and Co., and Moody forged a relationship with an editor who
respects his distinctive style.
</P>
<P>
   Moody became proficient at his craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured out how to tell a story,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Moody tries to do something different with each of his works,
their thread ``fealty to human emotions and human psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Garden State'' is the story of disaffected youth lost in
suburban New Jersey, contemplating life, death and rock and roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purple America'' is a deeply emotional book that examines how
one family's remorse ``trickles down through the generations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Black Veil,'' a non-fiction work due out this summer,
comes from family folklore about the Rev. Joseph Moody, said to
have inspired ``The Minister's Black Veil,'' a short story by
American author Nathaniel Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Ice Storm'' has been his bestseller, thanks in part to
the movie. The grim saga traces a brief span in the life of
Benjamin Hood, a suburbanite bored with marriage who dallies with a
neighbor, struggles to rein in his precocious daughter, Wendy, and
tries to discover himself during the sexual liberation of the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Moody was warned to fear the worst from Hollywood, and ``I DID
fear the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the respected Ang Lee, who also directed ``Sense and
Sensibility,'' allayed those fears. One red flag raised was the
casting of Christina Ricci, who had appeared in such films as ``The
Addams Family'' and ``Casper.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ricci's teen sexpot portrayal impressed Moody, as did the
film as a whole. Now he is waiting to hear about options on his
other works. Buoyed by his positive experiences with ``The Ice
Storm,'' he would happily return to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   With such success comes book tours, not the choicest part of the
profession. One tour took Moody on the road for five grueling
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But he enjoys meeting his readers, most of whom are under age
40.
</P>
<P>
   Writing is an isolating profession, after all, he notes as he
sits alone in his home on Fishers Island, while Amy lives across
the water in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   It is Amy who reads his work first and then filters the reviews,
passing along only those that offer constructive criticism.
Although wary of shaping his style to please critics, Moody says he
sometimes can learn from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust in the possibility that some harsh criticism will give
me an opportunity to improve,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And improvement brings joy. &QL; Reach the reporter at
Barbara.Yost(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at (602)444-7936. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
