<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NKOREA-CIRCUS-ART-710     03-12 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-CIRCUS-ART-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-WIRE FEATS RULE NORTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANGJON, North Korea _ It sounded like quintessential circus
hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   Before the performance of the Pyongyang Moranbong Circus, which
is in residence at this tourist village at the base of Mount
Kumgang, an announcer warned the audience of mostly South Koreans
that taking photographs was strictly prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Camera flashes, the announcer said, could cause serious injury
to the performers, who must maintain absolute concentration while
engaged in some of the most dangerous physical feats ever
attempted.
</P>
<P>
   The audience was also reminded that it was in communist North
Korea, one of the most isolated countries in the world. ``Clapping
and cheering are appreciated,'' the announcer said, ``but please
stay in your seats until the end of the performance, and please no
suspicious movements.''
</P>
<P>
   The circus has been a popular form of entertainment in socialist
countries, particularly in the former Soviet Union, because
everyone can easily understand and enjoy it, unlike operas and
classical music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circuses were a medium to criticize the bourgeoisie and praise
the socialist revolution, thereby strengthening the ideological
beliefs of the masses,'' said Choi Dai-seok, a professor of North
Korean studies at Dongguk University in Seoul, South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its function in a communist country, the Moranbong
Circus, which has won international acclaim for its artistry and
acts of skill and daring, lived up to its billing in a recent
90-minute performance of eye-popping acrobatics that seemed to
thrill the audience.
</P>
<P>
   With grace and precision the nimble acrobats soared through
seemingly impossible double and triple somersaults off bars and
seesaws, and majestic flips from flying trapezes. The amusing
juggling and balancing acts evoked standing ovations and tears of
joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was skeptical and thought this circus stuff was
just a bunch of North Korean communist propaganda,'' said Lee
Chung, a retailer from Seoul. ``But it was really impressive, a
real testament to their hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Byung Ha-min, a homemaker from Seoul, said: ``It's difficult to
explain, but this was different from other circuses that I've seen.
It was more artistic. It felt like the ballet, theater and circus
all fused together.''
</P>
<P>
   Since late 1998, when North Korea opened scenic Mount Kumgang to
South Koreans, the Moranbong troupe has been performing in a
620-seat dome theater built by the South Korean Hyundai Group,
which operates sightseeing boat tours.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day tours, which cost about $800 a person and are now
open to non-Koreans, provide the only public access to North Korea,
which is still technically at war with South Korea although an
armistice was signed in 1953. For an extra $25 tourists can see the
Moranbong Circus, one of North Korea's major cultural icons.
</P>
<P>
   ``In North Korea the circus is considered a high form of
entertainment, and performers are held in the same regard as
accomplished actors and dancers,'' said Lee B.H., Hyundai's
entertainment manager. ``The circus performance itself is primarily
physical and contains many beautiful body movements.''
</P>
<P>
   Choi said, ``In a nation like North Korea, which lacks
widespread television distribution and other facilities, circuses
naturally became very significant modes of entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Moranbong Circus, which is operated by North Korea's Culture
Ministry, was established in 1962 and has 500 members, 120 of whom
perform at Mount Kumgang. It also includes a 14-piece orchestra and
a master of ceremonies, a woman with a distinct high-pitched North
Korean accent. The remainder of the Moranbong troupe performs in
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Western circuses, which may include many individual
performers like magicians and clowns, those in North Korea feature
mainly ensemble performances. Five, six or more performers take
part in a single act, and their coordination is amazingly precise,
especially during difficult routines.
</P>
<P>
   For example the Moranbong troupe's seesaw jump involves at least
six acrobats performing four somersaults in the air. According to
the troupe's promotional material, that act won first place in the
Monte Carlo Circus Festival in 1985 and first place in the Chinese
International Circus Festival in 1987.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of the most physically demanding routines, which proved a
big crowd pleaser, was the pole-climbing act in which performers
appeared to defy gravity while scurrying up a network of poles.
During the act, acrobats unfurled a banner that read ``One Korea,''
which brought a roar of applause.
</P>
<P>
   Also popular with the audience was the Snow Fairies act, in
which four women soared above the audience in various acrobatic
feats that produced the effect of snow falling at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This piece of art contains the sincere will and hope of the
people for the well being of the great Gen. Kim Jong Il who always
stays up the entire night for our happiness,'' a promotion sheet
said, referring to the country's leader.
</P>
<P>
   Behind North Korea's skilled circuses is a highly selective and
regimented government training program. Children are taught circus
routines at an early age in primary school. Those under 10 who have
a special talent for acrobatics are sent to circus schools. After
six to seven years of training the top students are chosen to join
the Pyongyang or Moranbong troupes, Choi said, where they are
guaranteed a stable lifestyle as long as they excel.
</P>
<P>
   The most talented are often awarded the highly revered title of
``meritorious'' or ``people'' actor. As a result, Choi added,
circus performers are highly regarded in North Korea, and
performers train hard to maintain their positions.
</P>
<P>
   The acts obviously involve danger to the acrobats, and circus
officials said that at least three or four are injured, either
slightly or seriously, each month.
</P>
<P>
   Park Sae-hwan, a former member of the Dong Choon Circus, South
Korea's premier troupe, said the Moranbong Circus was one of the
best in the world, but he also criticized it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their showmanship is very awkward because they have lived in a
rigid society and their stage attitude reflects that social
atmosphere,'' he said. ``They cannot breathe with the audience.
They cannot draw natural and spontaneous laughter. But their
trapeze act is world renowned.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the performance, as the troupe took its bows, many
South Korean tourists, wiping tears from their eyes, rushed to the
edge of the stage to take photographs and shake the hands of the
performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a moment during the performance, it really did feel as if
we were one nation again,'' said Byung Joo-min, who had accompanied
her cousin Ha Min on the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
