<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AETNA REJECTS TAKEOVER BID AND PLANS TO SPLIT IN TWO
</P>
<P>
   Aetna rejected a takeover bid from WellPoint Health Networks and
ING Group and announced plans to split into separate health-care
and financial-services companies.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna also said it would sell some of its overseas health-care
business and use the money to placate investors who drove its stock
price down and led to the replacement of its chief executive late
last month.
</P>
<P>
   BERKSHIRE MAY BUY BACK STOCK
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to shareholders in Berkshire Hathaway's annual
report, released over the weekend, Warren Buffett warned that stock
prices are generally very high. But he has found a stock he thinks
is cheap _ one that Berkshire may begin buying soon: Berkshire
Hathaway's own shares. Overall, Berkshire's profit fell 45 percent,
to $1.56 billion.
</P>
<P>
   THE FRAGILITY OF RUSSIAN JOURNALISM
</P>
<P>
   Two news reports out of Moscow last week served as reminders of
the rise of Russian journalism before the collapse of communism,
and its paradoxical retreat these days. During a funeral for Artyom
Borovik, who died in a plane crash, officials praised his reporting
on the campaign in Afghanistan. Then came a report that criminal
charges had been filed against Andrei Babitsky, a Radio Liberty
reporter, for aiding the enemy while covering the war in Chechnya.
While officials denied the report, Babitsky is still seen as a
government target. The adulation of Borovik and the demonization of
Babitsky both reflect journalism's fragility in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   A TEST RUN FOR AOL-TIME WARNER
</P>
<P>
   America Online has been working with the staff of Real Simple, a
new magazine from Time, on promotion for the magazine. The
affiliation is in part a test run of the larger possibilities for
synergy between America Online and Time Warner, which announced
their plans to merge in January.
</P>
<P>
   MORE GROWING PAINS FOR ICANN
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months of setbacks and frustration exploded into a
tense, sometimes hostile showdown between the appointees who have
been trying to invent a democratic charter for the Internet's first
administrative body _ the founding board of Internet Corp. for
Assigned Names and Numbers _ and the people they were supposed to
be representing. The board bowed to the pressure, agreeing at the
end of a four-day meeting to slow the election process for a
successor board and study ways to improve it.
</P>
<P>
   A COPYRIGHT THREAT TO THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   The case of a Canadian company that redistributes TV programming
on its Web site illustrates how U.S. media and entertainment
industries, using copyright law, could turn the Internet into a
model like the centralized control of cable television. The Motion
Picture Association of America sued the company, iCraveTV.com,
contending that viewers in the United States could circumvent the
company's barriers to non-Canadians. The company responded by
inventing technology that could create a ``country-area network.''
</P>
<P>
   RETAILERS FOCUS ON SITE DESIGN AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   After being criticized for spending more time creating
entertaining sites than delivering high-quality products, on time,
to the right place, Internet retailers spent 1999 building stronger
fulfillment and customer-service systems. Now that those systems
are mainly in place, many Web merchants are devoting an increasing
amount of time and money to implementing audio and video features.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
