<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-YANKEENETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDE INVESTORS TO HELP FINANCE PURCHASE OF DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The YankeeNets will use outside investors to help finance the
$175 million acquisition of the New Jersey Devils, which has been
pending since late last year.
</P>
<P>
   If the transaction comes to fruition, 12 investors will put up
the majority of the purchase price for John McMullen's Devils. But
the YankeeNets would retain control of the team, a person involved
with the sale said.
</P>
<P>
   The YankeeNets raised $200 million last week by selling
seven-year junk bonds to institutional investors, but the proceeds
back the Nets owners' investment in the YankeeNets, pay off the
first six payments on the bonds and provide working capital. The
initial intention of selling $250 million in the high-interest
bonds was scaled back in the face of investor reluctance.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the higher figure, the offering was never intended to
help finance acquisitions. Another $75 million to be raised by
selling an 8.6 percent stake in YankeeNets to private investors is
also not designated for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the YankeeNets will not pay a $15 million bonus to
McMullen if the Devils win the Stanley Cup, contrary to published
reports, the person said. McMullen intends to use $15 million from
the sale of the team to pay bonuses to his employees.
</P>
<P>
   One employee who will benefit most from the sale is Lou
Lamoriello, the Devils' president and general manager, who owns 20
percent of the team, which would be worth $35 million. His
post-sale future with the Devils has not been determined, although
YankeeNets officials are impressed with his record.
</P>
<P>
   A binding agreement to buy the Devils, which has been slow to
complete, is expected soon, but it is not likely to be announced
until after the National Hockey League playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
