</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-PITCHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENDOZA TRADE AND A POOR YARNALL OUTING CONCERN YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ The Yankees' winter theory was that they could
afford to trade Ramiro Mendoza because they have enough pitching
talent to replace him. The rookie Ed Yarnall would become the No. 5
starter and someone else would fill Mendoza's role in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But after a month of spring training, the Yankees have
ascertained they that they do not have as much depth as they first
thought. No candidate to replace Mendoza in relief has developed,
and Yarnall stunk in his first outing of spring Sunday, as he
acknowledged with more colorful words, allowing 10 runs in one
inning, including three home runs. Toronto crushed the Yankees,
14-3.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall's one horrible inning _ his first after missing two
weeks with back trouble _ will not alter his status as the probable
No. 5 starter, but the Yankees are keenly aware of their fragile
nature of their pitching staff. Allen Watson, one of the Yankees'
two left-handed relievers, has soreness in his throwing shoulder
and his condition will be monitored in the days to come. Scouts
watching Watson's last outing felt he was laboring, as if he could
not throw freely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not concerned yet,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankees'
manager. ``I think it's just something that pitchers get, a cranky
shoulder. If it goes a few more days and it's not getting better,
then maybe it'll be time to be concerned. I have a feeling he's
pitched with this maybe a time or two.''
</P>
<P>
   One person in the organization said that in the course of his
treatment Sunday, Watson may have been sent for magnetic resonance
imaging; Torre said he did not know if this was the case.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall said his back felt fine Sunday, and as he warmed up, the
pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre thought his stuff was good, his
fastball alive. Yarnall had good movement on his fastball against
the first few hitters he faced, and the Blue Jays had two outs and
two on and no runs. Yarnall appeared to be in command, even
dropping a changeup over the plate for a strike with a two-ball,
no-strike count.
</P>
<P>
   But Yarnall fell behind in the count to David Segui, fired a
fastball inside, and Segui blistered it. There was another hit and
then another home run, by Tony Batista, and after the Blue Jays
scored another run and loaded the bases, Raul Mondesi blasted a
grand slam. Yarnall threw 52 pitches, reaching his limit in only
one inning. All in all, the left-hander decided as he mused over
his outing in the dugout, it was the worst outing of his career, at
any level.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall seemed to be able to keep the outing in perspective; he
realizes that Torre and Stottlemyre will continue to count on him
as their No. 5 starter. ``It's just one outing,'' Yarnall said.
``Just one inning. I just can't be making a habit out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said, ``He got here and he's trying to impress, and that's
understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have all but resolved to keep Mendoza, at least for
now, because he provides depth in the rotation and the bullpen at a
time when the organization possesses very little quality, major
league-ready pitching depth. They were reluctant to trade him to
the Oakland Athletics for minor league prospects. They have
declined to swap him in a deal for Anaheim's Jim Edmonds, although
the Angels and Yankees continue to talk; the Yankees want to work
out a trade that does not include Mendoza or Alfonso Soriano, their
top infield prospect, while Anaheim wants players ready to
contribute in the majors right now.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did not want Mendoza to be included in discussions
for Jeromy Burnitz, the All-Star right fielder for the Milwaukee
Brewers. The Yankees offered Soriano as part of a package for
Burnitz, but when the Brewers asked for an outfielder and a pitcher
_ Milwaukee wanted Mendoza _ the talks ended.
</P>
<P>
   Torre spoke obliquely about possible deals today. He did not
specifically mention the discussions regarding Edmonds, but what
Torre told reporters Sunday underscored what others in the
organization are saying: that he and the major league staff, as
well as front-office members in New York, are strongly opposed to
unloading assets like Mendoza and Soriano for someone who could
augment the offense marginally.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, pitching is what our strength has been,'' Torre said.
``Can we become a better offensive team? Possibly. But at the
expense of your strengths? Then you have to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you have a ``gaping hole,'' Torre said, ``I'm a little
reluctant to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Do the Yankees have a gaping hole on their roster? ``No,'' Torre
replied firmly.
</P>
<P>
   Torre undoubtedly remembers that in the first half of last
season, the Yankees' left fielders had the worst production of any
position on any team in the majors, and the Yankees still won 98
games and the World Series, after Ricky Ledee played better in the
second half. The question remains whether the Yankees' front office
_ George Steinbrenner, the principal owner _ will be willing to
give Ledee more time to find himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
