<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOVAK-DANCERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BRATISLAVA DANCE THEATER': FROM SLOVAKIA, A MEDLEY OF SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The year is young, but it is unlikely that New York
will see many companies as charming and savvy as the Bratislava
Dance Theater, which made its U.S.debut on Friday night at Kaye
Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Bratislava Dance Theater was founded in 1997 by Robert
Mesko, a Slovak-American dance impresario. It is the first
modern-dance troupe in Slovakia to be built on corporate rather
than state support, the main sponsors being two mobile-phone
businesses, EuroTel Bratislava and Ericsson Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   The troupe's artistic director, Nora Gallovicova, was a
principal dancer with the Slovak National Theater. In addition to
their folkloric dance training, her wonderfully loose-bodied,
unassuming dancers were schooled in academies supported by the
thriving modern-dance culture of Bratislava. The company's
repertory includes works by Slovak choreographers Jan Durovcik and
Peter Mika, Czech choreographer Jan Kodet, and two Americans,
Daniel Ezralow and Bill Young.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's program opened and closed with bookend dances by
Ezralow that teased one's expectation of an evening of Slavic folk
dance. ``Lady Lost Found,'' set to a gentlemanly score by Percy
Grainger, is a sweet-tempered idyll for loving lads and lasses
dressed in soft, creamy white and a kilt-wearing soloist, Zdeno
Galaba, who tosses off multiple pirouettes as nonchalantly as a
shepherd batting a fly.
</P>
<P>
   Did the world of ``Lady Lost Found'' ever exist? Ezralow and the
dancers manage subtly to suggest both the dream and its
unlikelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Ezralow's closing ``Familia Kalashnikov'' is a wild romp whose
cheerfully battling, lumbering, line-dancing antics match the
nuttiness of Goran Bregovic's folk-tinged score in a kaleidoscopic,
fractured charge through hallmark steps and formations of
Mediterranean folk dancing. Only modern dancers could perform it,
however, and these dancers (Zuzana Herenyiova, Jan Mrnak, Jan
Sevcik, Radovan Vagac and Lenka Vagnerova) sailed through ``Familia
Kalashnikov'' with delicious comic timing.
</P>
<P>
   Young deftly evokes the spirit of popular music texts in ``Bound
To,'' choreographed with Colleen Thomas, set to music by Cole
Porter, and ``Two a T,'' performed to songs sung on tape by Ray
Charles and Betty Carter. Young pours his dancers out onto the
stage in ``Bound To'' and sets them to milling, jabbering,
leapfrogging and even sleeping, interspersed with passages of plain
movement identifiable as jazz and modern dance.
</P>
<P>
   In one highlight, set to ``You Do Something to Me,'' stretchy
red bands link one dancer to another in couples who are then forced
into sleek partnering upheavals and reversals and loving encounters
that are both serene and feisty.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kolar and Katerina Vlnieskova are the lovers of ``Two a
T,'' one moment sparring wittily and the next interacting in ways
that capture the subtle vagaries of romantic love with unexpected
depth. Young's movement vocabulary is full and rich. All in all the
program suggested that these performers _ who also included
Marianna Paulikova, Vlastimil Golias, Roman Lazik and Beata
Geffertova _ can do just about anything. May they return soon and
for a longer engagement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 1903EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
