<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     03-12 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE NBA SHOULD HAVE MORE LOVE FOR DUNCAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I may have made a bad career decision when I agreed
to cover the Knicks-San Antonio game Sunday at Madison Square
Garden, instead of the Knicks-Lakers game next week.
</P>
<P>
   I chose Tim Duncan over Shaquille O'Neal, and that, I suppose,
means fewer readers for me Monday morning than for whoever will be
writing the Shaq column next week.
</P>
<P>
   I'm told that Shaq and his Lakers, as a rule, rate higher than
Duncan and his defending champion Spurs, and while I realize that
ratings rule, I happen to be an unabashed Duncan fan. I admit this
is not fashionably cool or the expedient means of landing in a seat
next to Ernie Johnson in those yuk-it-up sessions on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if I had any vocational sense, I would have bypassed
Duncan and not given Shaq and the Knicks a second thought, and
informed the office that every basketball column from here to
eternity or at least the duration of Toronto's playoff run will
feature Vince Carter.
</P>
<P>
   I would attach myself to Carter, the chosen one, and hang there,
like Jeff Van Gundy on Alonzo Mourning. Like the National
Basketball Association on, well, Vince Carter.
</P>
<P>
   What do I do? I tell my editor, ``Put me down for Duncan,'' the
soft-spoken giant who, it has been said, will single-handedly bring
down all of professional basketball if he is allowed to
methodically work the NBA finals the way he did last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Actually _ and I don't know what the heck is wrong with me _ I
found Duncan's performance in the finals to be riveting. Every
night, he was far and away the most complete player in the house.
The young Michael Jordan didn't have the impact on his team that
Duncan had, but last season's ratings were down, way down, from
those of Air Jordan's climactic flight.
</P>
<P>
   By today's standards, getting a low television rating seems to
be a worse offense than head-butting a ref. A star athlete who
doesn't score well with the commissioner of all sports, His
Excellency, Mr. Nielsen, is sent to a purgatory for the
incorrigibly mundane. And that is part of the perverse message that
provokes John Rocker, encourages Dennis Rodman and brainwashes the
public with the nonsense that a player like Duncan isn't sexy
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all say we want role models but people go out and watch
Rodman,'' groaned Van Gundy, sitting up straight in the posture of
the basketball purist. ``There's a certain segment that wants the
superficial and hopefully a larger segment that wants to watch Tim
Duncan. I don't agree that Duncan isn't sexy enough. I would think
that over a period of time, people will come to appreciate him and,
if not, let's say who we are. We're about selling Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   In his second pro season, Duncan wasted Shaq and the Lakers last
spring and no such dominance has been seen from an NBA neophyte
since the Magic-Bird days, 20 years ago. Anyone who loves
basketball should love Tim Duncan. Does the NBA? Not enough.
</P>
<P>
   I'm told Duncan is not the most cooperative soul with the news
media, but that is pretty much across the board these days with the
young NBA stars. Panicked by the realization that is no more immune
to the fluctuations of the marketplace than is Wall Street, the NBA
is too busy trying to milk Vince Carter and mike its coaches. If
David Stern wants to elevate his league's exposure, he should
forget the coaches and get his players out of the training room for
people who don't have NBA dot.com television on their credential.
</P>
<P>
   The league's ratings are down, and what a shock. It took years
for Magic-Bird to take root, and years for Jordan to become
must-see TV. And there is something else that the NBA _ and every
other mainstream sport used to certain levels of television
viewership _ had better understand. Games are no longer alone as a
means of providing live prime-time entertainment. Contrived human
dramas _ from shock culture wrestling to shows like ``Who Wants to
be a Millionaire?'' _ are successfully competing for target
audiences. Kids are finishing their homework and deciding whether
to go on line or to the television set.
</P>
<P>
   But what the NBA and other team sports should always have going
for them is the legitimacy of competition, the notion that its true
fan base knows game is not based on gimmickry and trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've made money because people wanted to watch
basketball,'' said Van Gundy, not thrilled about being miked for
Tuesday night's game on cable against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the invasion of privacy would soon make it
impossible to have a team meeting, which sounded a bit
sanctimonious. The miking thing is one thing. Not having enough
faith in your core product is another. The NBA needs to embrace the
players who hold up its game, not just those who hang from the
rim. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
