<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FLORIDA0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush attacks Gore's call for campaign finance reform
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANT CITY, Fla. _ Coming just short of calling Vice President
Al Gore dishonest, Texas Gov. George W. Bush repeatedly accused
Gore Sunday of being ``a man who will say whatever it takes to get
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was so astonished by Gore's call Saturday for
campaign finance reform that at first, he thought it was some kind
of ``April Fools joke.'' He said Gore adopted reform this week only
because the vice president's own money raising tactics have come
under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have long memories,'' said Bush who promised that if he
wins the presidency he will ``set a high standard in the Oval
Office'' for personal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his comments during a visit to the Plant City
strawberry festival with his wife Laura and younger brother, Gov.
Jeb Bush. The Texas governor, ill from a head cold, greeted
hundreds of festival goers who eagerly shook his hand, gave him
babies to hold and posed for pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his younger brother then entered the St. Clement
Catholic Church ``make your own strawberry shortcake'' pavilion
where, for $2.50, you can have all the strawberries and whipped
cream you can put on your plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush brothers made their own desserts and ate outside while
scores of people hovered over them. ``I just can't believe they are
here,'' said Judith Archer of Tampa. ``I loved President Bush and I
think Jeb has done a wonderful job.''
</P>
<P>
   The good mood was set aside when Bush held a news conference
after dessert. The New York Times reported Sunday that Gore said he
was taking up the issue of campaign finance reform because of the
``pain'' he felt over his role in raising money for the 1996
Clinton-Gore campaign. Last week, one of Gore's friends was
convicted for excesses in raising money that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a passion for campaign finance reform,'' Gore said,
``that is fueled in part because of the pain of those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush reacted harshly to Gore's statements. ``I'm surprised he is
talking about campaign finance reform,'' Bush said. ``I think he
must think that the American people have been asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush later headed to Knoxville in Gore's home state of
Tennessee, where he was picking up the endorsement of Sen. Fred
Thompson, who had supported Arizona Sen. John McCain until he
suspended his campaign last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, went to church in Houston and later to a health
care forum near Dallas. Gore arrived in Miami late Sunday and will
talk about health care today at Jackson Memorial Hospital. He
leaves Florida this afternoon and will return Tuesday to spend
primary night in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the Associated Press Bush's five-year, $483-billion
tax-cut plan would put Social Security, Medicare and health care in
general at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the words of John McCain, he doesn't put one penny into
Social Security, one penny into Medicare or one penny into
expanding access to health care,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush said Gore's appearance in Tallahassee is another
indication that Republicans should not take Florida for granted in
November. ``This is going to be very competitive here,'' Bush said.
``I don't think the vice president is just going to lay down.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida and five other states hold presidential primaries
Tuesday. With McCain out of the Republican race and Bill Bradley
out of the Democratic race, the results are already clear.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor said that after Tuesday, his campaign will
begin working on the strategy for the November election. ``I think
it's going to be a very interesting election.''
</P>
<P>
   The story includes material from the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
