<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, March 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dry, but colder weather will return to the Northeast as brisk
breezes from the northwest diminish quickly in southern New
England. Sunshine will be abundant, but readings will average 5 or
more degrees below seasonal levels. High pressure crested near the
nation's capital will circulate cool, dry air into the Southeast.
Freezing temperatures will be common inland as far south as the
Florida panhandle. A cold front will move slowly into the Bahamas
so that clouds and scattered showers will persist in southern
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The return of milder air into the Plains and Mississippi Valley
will be marked by increasing clouds. A warm front moving across the
Great Lakes region will promote patches of light snow and snow
showers, mainly in Michigan and northern Ohio. A few sprinkles will
dampen Indiana. A humid air stream from the Gulf of Mexico into
Texas and New Mexico will trigger drizzle and patches of light rain
in southern sections.
</P>
<P>
   Bright and pleasant conditions will dominate the central and
northwest Plains as a ridge of high pressure covers the region.
Advancing polar air will reach the Dakotas later Monday, preceded
by clouds and flurries. Meanwhile, a center of high pressure over
Nevada should control the weather over much of the West. Dry and
warmer winds from the east will bring sunny, mild conditions to
southern and central California. A milder air flow from the south
will be accompanied by thickening clouds and showers along the
Northwest Coast. The interior of Washington and Oregon will turn
dull, but mild.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Spring Snow
</P>
<P>
   The half a foot of wet snow that fell from central Missouri to
northern Ohio on Saturday will be nothing but soggy lawns and
fields Monday. Even though the calendar indicates that it is still
winter, the weekend storm was characteristic of a spring snowfall.
This snow came after an early season warm spell and much of it fell
at readings just below freezing. Spring snows melt rapidly because
of the higher sun angle of March, now similar to September, and the
rapid changes of air masses. In fact, readings may reach 60 degrees
Tuesday in the recently snow-covered areas of the Ohio Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
