<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FLORIDA _ Coming just short of calling Vice President Al
Gore dishonest, Texas Gov. George W. Bush repeatedly accused Gore
Sunday of being ``a man who will say whatever it takes to get
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was so astonished by Gore's call Saturday for
campaign finance reform that at first, he thought it was some kind
of ``April Fools joke.'' He said Gore adopted reform this week only
because the vice president's own money raising tactics have come
under scrutiny. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLESH-EAT-BACTERIA _ DAYTON _ A 42-year-old man remained in
critical condition Saturday with a Strep A infection that has
evolved into its most severe type, known as ``flesh-eating''
bacteria. Meanwhile, health officials continue to investigate an
outbreak of 23 cases of strep throat infections in the Cincinnati
area that led to two deaths. The Ohio Department of Health and
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention are examining the cases
for a common link. (Lee, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-BEHAVIOR _ Nothing is more predictable in a case like the
one involving football star Ray Lewis than this: Eyewitness
accounts will vary. ``That's the problem with a chaotic, dimly lit
scene,'' said defense attorney Jack Martin. ``It would be more
suspicious if everyone had the same story.'' And the stories do
vary widely in the case of the street melee that occurred in the
early morning hours after the Super Bowl near a Buckhead nightclub,
leaving two men, Jacinth Baker and Richard Lollar, stabbed to
death. (Torpy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED in (a) General
News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-WITNESSES _ ATLANTA _ At least nine people have stepped
forward to say what they saw on the night after the Super Bowl,
when a fight in Buckhead led to a pair of fatal stabbings.
Baltimore Ravens football star Ray Lewis and two other men facing
murder charges. Here are the witnesses' statements, drawn from
various sources.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Whitehead was at Cobalt, partying with a friends, and left
around closing time.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead said he and a woman began walking towards Jelly Rolls,
a club just east of Cobalt, when they saw some men arguing and
shouting. (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED Saturday in
(a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY-COMING-CLEAN _ ``God bless you all. I am a innocent
man.'' Those were the words of Ed Johnson before he was hanged from
a metal girder on the Walnut Street Bridge in downtown Chattanooga.
The year was 1906, a time of lawlessness and vigilantism, of mob
violence directed toward blacks often wrongly accused, as was
Johnson, of raping a white woman. Johnson had been tried for the
crime and, despite a dearth of evidence _ even the victim could not
positively identify him as the assailant _ he was sentenced to die.
(Dickerson, Atlanta Journal-Consititution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   UNCONVENTIONAL-PROFESSOR _ On a late-winter day of blue skies
and crisp, dry air, Roger Shattuck poses for a photographer on the
faux-Gothic campus of Oglethorpe University. He is a thinker, so
she asks him to sit with his hand to his 76-year-old face. He
amiably complies. One can be a contrarian without being contrary.
Shattuck is an unconventional thinker, as resistant to academic
fashion as he is gentle in manner. Principled disagreement he can
accept, but not the dogmas he finds seeping into the ground water
of American cultural life. One is that there can be no common
literary heritage in a country built on the banishment of the red
man, the enslavement of the black man, the exploitation of the
working man and the suppression of women of whatever color. (Skube,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
