<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PULSIPHER-NY     03-12 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PULSIPHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRUGGLING PULSIPHER STILL AIMS FOR THE BIG MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Bill Pulsipher is feeling the pressure. The
Mets' left-hander admits it. At 26, his world revolves around
pitching and right now it's on a wobbly axis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at all the scars on your body and all you've
ever done is play baseball, you don't have much to fall back on,''
he said, frustrated about the 6 hits and 4 runs (3 earned) he
surrendered Sunday in 3 innings in the Mets' 9-3 loss to the
Montreal Expos at Roger Dean Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to hurry up and try to make some money,'' he said.
``Then you can let baseball just be baseball. The pressure goes
down, way down.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher has a 1-year, $575,000 contract plus incentives, not
bad for a guy who won't be 27 for another 7 months, but paltry by
the standard of some of his contemporaries. After all, by his
timeline, this is supposed to be his sixth year in the major
leagues, not his fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets first began promoting him - along with fellow promising
pitchers Jason Isringhausen and Paul Wilson _ in 1995, but never
got to see that combination realize its potential. Now, after arm
surgery and a trade to the Brewers, Pulsipher is anxious to make up
for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you came up with all the hype and believe all the
accolades, you want it,'' he said. ``When you have friends sitting
across the clubhouse from you that you grew up with basically and
they're doing it _ Gold Gloves and multimillion-dollar contracts _
you want that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher believes a lucrative contract, with all the security
that brings, would make him a better pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I get money, it's not going to turn me down a notch,'' he
said. ``That's going to turn it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now he is part of a four-way battle for the Mets' No. 5
starting spot along with Bobby M. Jones, Glendon Rusch and Dennis
Springer. Pulsipher is anxious to have the list of candidates
``weeded out,'' but that's not likely to happen immediately, even
though Jones had no joyride either Sunday, yielding 4 hits and 4
runs in 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The first inning was chock full of bad memories for Pulsipher.
Leadoff hitter Peter Bergeron hit a slow bouncer toward Todd Zeile,
making the transition to first base. Pulsipher, making eye contact
with Zeile, stopped his charge to the base for a moment, thinking
Zeile could take it unassisted. It was just enough to allow
Bergeron to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Mickey Morandini, hit a bouncer to second
baseman Edgar Alfonzo, who made a rare fielding error. Pulsipher
struck out Patrick Lennon, but then on an 0-2 pitch, the feared
Vladimir Guerrero laced a curveball for a run-producing single.
</P>
<P>
   That irritated Manager Bobby Valentine, who described it later
as a ``down- the-middle'' pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could say it's spring training and I just felt like trying a
curveball there,'' Pulsipher said. ``But I'm not afforded these
mistakes. You've got to make every pitch and that's the bottom
line. It was a dumb pitch in a dumb situation and I paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher, who realized his goal of not walking anyone, felt he
made just one other mistake in the game - a pitch that catcher
Charlie O'Brien hit for a run-producing double.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, I really kept the ball pretty much where I
wanted to keep it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt this was even better than I threw my last time out,''
he said of a two-inning stint in which he allowed no runs.``But I
don't know what I can take out of this game. I can't be
disappointed with the way I threw the ball, because I covered the
outside corner with consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's aware that the 6 hits _ even 2 of the infield
variety _ and 4 runs make for a messy-looking linescore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say the numbers don't count,'' he said. ``But I think
that's a lot of baloney sometimes. What good is it when you think
you've pitched well, but they're scoring on you anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Mets pitching coach Dave Wallace said his main concern about
Pulsipher is his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got good stuff - there's never a question of that,''
Wallace said. ``The command thing is the question for him and for a
lot of guys. Only a select few have the kind of command where they
can put the ball in the strike zone where they want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with his occasional rough edges, Pulsipher said he is a
much more complete pitcher now than when he made his major league
debut for the Mets in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I hurt my arm, I began working on my mechanics,'' he
said. ``I know now about being able to have your body in the right
position and having your hand in the right position to make the
ball do what you want it to do. I used to have no idea. I used to
just throw it and people would say it had great movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher said he has always been treated warmly by Mets fans,
who he feels are pulling for him in a big way to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been with me a long time,'' he said. ``It would be
especially sweet to get back to where I was before all the injuries
and bad luck.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
