<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-ACC-NYT &LR;      03-12 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ACC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE'S RETURNING PLAYERS KEEP THEIR PROMISES TO KRZYZEWSKI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BARRY JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ The championship run began inconspicuously
last April in the wake of the largely unexpected departure of five
of Duke's top seven players. The holdovers Chris Carrawell, Shane
Battier and Nate James went to Mike Krzyzewski's home to wish their
coach well as he recovered from hip-replacement surgery, and to
pledge their loyalty and reaffirm their resolve.
</P>
<P>
   The trio has made good on its vows, culminating with a decisive
81-68 victory over Maryland Sunday afternoon in the championship of
the Atlantic Coast Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The victory raised Duke's record to 27-4 and earned the Blue
Devils the No. 1 seed in the East Regional of the National
Collegiate Athletic Association Tournament. Friday they will meet
Lamar, the 16th-seeded team, at Joel Coliseum in Winston-Salem,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   By defeating Maryland (24-9), Duke became the first team since
the 1973 and 1974 North Carolina State teams of David Thompson and
Tom Burleson to finish first during the regular season and win the
ACC tournament in consecutive years. Duke has finished first in the
conference four straight times, and captured Krzyzewski's fifth ACC
tournament title in nine tries.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, in which the Blue Devils led for the final 33
minutes, avenged their only ACC loss over the past two seasons, a
98-87 Maryland triumph at Cameron Indoor Stadium in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us at Cameron, celebrated on our court,'' said
Carrawell. ``To come out and win today, we beat the team that beat
us last. That's the first time in two years; my record in the ACC
is 37-1. Yeah, that's proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils reached the final by dispatching ninth seeded
Clemson and fifth-seeded Wake Forest with a barrage of 3-pointers,
converting a sizzling 50.8 percent (30-of-59). With the Terrapins
understandably intent upon stopping Duke's perimeter game, the
nation's top-scoring team (89.1 points a game) went inside.
</P>
<P>
   The tone was set with Duke's first two baskets, both from close
range by Carlos Boozer. The freshman center finished with 21
points, 10 in the first half. The Blue Devils also ran sets and
isolations for point guard Jason Williams, who repeatedly
confounded Maryland's defense en route to a game-high 23 points and
the tournament's most valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I let him get into the lane too much today,'' Steven
Blake, the Maryland freshman, said of his Duke counterpart. ``He
penetrated and made things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, from Ridgefield, N.J., also had six assists Sunday,
and his 27 for the tournament was one short of the tournament
record. He became the fourth freshman to win the most valuable
player award, after North Carolina's Phil Ford (1975), Sam Perkins
(1981) and Jerry Stackhouse (1994).
</P>
<P>
   Maryland achieved its last lead, 9-8, on a Blake 3-pointer just
six minutes and 42 seconds into the game. Williams responded with a
3-pointer half a minute later, putting Duke ahead to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring inside while limiting the Terps' fastbreak
opportunities, the Blue Devils led by 37-36 at halftime despite
missing 10 of 11 3-pointers in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Williams opened the second half with a 3-pointer and Duke pushed
to a 48-40 lead at the 16-minute-52-second mark on a 3 by Battier,
a junior forward who finished with 10 points, 5 steals, 5 rebounds
and a sterling defensive job on the Terps' Terence Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland rallied within 48-44 barely a minute later on a jumper
in transition by Juan Dixon, the darting guard who paced his squad
with 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Duke quickly built the lead to 54-44, capped by a Williams layup
in a halfcourt set with 13:42 to go. Again the Terps rallied,
closing to 56-52 with 8:50 left on a Morris follow.
</P>
<P>
   At that, Krzyzewski called timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted Maryland to stop scoring, that was the first thing,''
Krzyzewski said. ``We got a 10-point lead and we lost our focus. I
tried to stress poise during that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Point made. Over the next seven minutes Duke broke the game
open, keyed by Williams, whose 3-pointer gave the Blue Devils a
74-61 advantage with 1:40 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Handicapped in part by the loss of starting forward Danny
Miller, who sprained his left ankle and did not play in the second
half, Maryland allowed Duke 63.6 percent accuracy in the second
half, including 6 of 9 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils meanwhile held the Terps _ appearing in their
first final since 1984 _ to 33.3 percent shooting in the period.
Morris and center Lonny Baxter combined for 10 of 31 for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we won the tournament because of our defense, not
because of our offense,'' Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   This Duke team does not overwhelm opponents with talent or
numbers like the 1999 group that lost to Connecticut in the
National Collegiate Athletic Association title game. Yet it has won
nearly as often with three freshmen among its top six players.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes this so special,'' said Carrawell, who finished
with 13 points and a team-high seven rebounds, ``is nobody expected
it this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
