<HEADLINE>
ARAB LEAGUE STATEMENT ON ISRAEL'S ROLE IN LEBANON DRAWS BITING
RESPONSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Israel's ties with the Arab world received a
fresh jolt Sunday when a brusquely worded Arab League communique
condemning Israel for its role in Lebanon prompted equally biting
responses from leading Israeli politicians, one of whom called the
Arab countries' attitude ``surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange of polemics came a week after the Israeli cabinet
endorsed Prime Minister Ehud Barak's pledge to withdraw Israel's
1,500-member force from the ``security zone'' it occupies in
southern Lebanon by July, ending a 22-year occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Israeli pledge had been expected to improve the
atmosphere for the Middle East peace talks, it has so far produced
only recriminations from the two countries primarily affected by
the Israeli pullout _ Lebanon and Syria, which maintains 35,000
troops here.
</P>
<P>
   The ambivalent attitudes of the governments in Damascus and
Beirut were reflected in the communique issued by foreign ministers
of the 22-nation Arab League after a meeting here in the Lebanese
capital on Saturday. The meeting, held twice a year, normally in
Cairo, was shifted to Beirut as a show of solidarity after Israel
destroyed three Lebanese power plants on Feb. 8. The Israeli
bombing followed stepped-up attacks on Israeli troops in southern
Lebanon, since attenuated, that killed seven Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab League statement, issued after six hours of
consultations, contained some of the harshest condemnation of
Israel from the league in years. Among other things, it blasted
Israel for its ``continuing aggression'' against Lebanon and for
its ``vicious'' threats to Lebanon, a reference to warnings by
Barak and the Israeli foreign minister, David Levy, who have
promised further retaliation if more Israeli soldiers are killed
before the pullout.
</P>
<P>
   The communique said, in effect, that the Lebanese guerrillas of
Hezbollah, the Iran-backed Party of God, had every right to
continue their attacks on Israel's forces since the Israelis were
an occupying force in Lebanon, in defiance of a 1978 United Nations
Security Council resolution demanding their immediate withdrawal.
``The Arab League fully supports Lebanon in its resistance and its
fight against Israeli occupation until Lebanese soil is fully
liberated,'' it said. ``The resistance is the natural result of the
occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   If this was a well-established Arab viewpoint, it was what
followed that most piqued Israeli leaders. Echoing a demand
previously made by Lebanon's president, Emile Lahoud, the Arab
ministers demanded that Israel pay a price for the right to
withdraw its troops in peace. The communique warned of the
possibility of escalating war if Israel pulls out without first
reaching an agreement over the future of the large Palestinian
refugee population in Lebanon. The Palestinians _ who number at
least 200,000, and more than 360,000 by official Lebanese count _
have mostly been in Lebanon since the 1948 war that led to the
founding of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon, which has denied most civic rights to the refugees, has
repeatedly demanded that Israel agree to their ``repatriation,''
meaning their return to what is now Israel. Israel has rejected the
demand, saying that Lebanon should accept the Palestinians as
permanent residents. But since Israel's pullout announcement last
week, Lebanese leaders have said that failure to settle the issue
now could expose Israel to a resumption, after the Israeli pullout,
of the attacks on Israel by the Palestinians that led to Israel's
original invasion of Lebanon in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab League ministers said the Palestinians, if not assured
of repatriation, ``will remain a time bomb threatening peace in
Lebanon and the threatening the peace process.'' Lahoud, the
Lebanese president, put the point more bluntly in an interview
published on Saturday in Al Hayat, an Arabic newspaper published in
London. If the Palestinians attacked after the pullout, he said,
``How will Israel respond? Will they bomb the refugee camps? Will
they reoccupy the country? A unilateral Israeli withdrawal will not
work, and will lead to another war.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, however, even senior Lebanese military officers
concede that the Palestinian refugees are not in shape to resume
attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said the demand that Israel repatriate the
Palestinians was part of a strategy worked out with Syria, one that
sees Israel, having announced its pullout, as dealing from a
position of weakness. By raising the specter of attacks, Damascus
and Beirut are trying to exact as much mileage from the situation
as possible, the diplomats said. For Syria, the prize would be a
more flexible Israeli position on the return of the Golan Heights,
the issue that led to the collapse of the Israel-Syria talks in
January.
</P>
<P>
   The reactions from Israel Sunday were withering. Barak told his
cabinet, according to a Reuters report, that ``declarations of this
kind do not contribute to the atmosphere required to advance the
peace process, and we do not need any approval from our
neighbors.'' The justice minister, Yossie Beilin, called the Arab
League demands ``surreal.'' Levy, the foreign minister, said that
the Arab states' ``double talk of war and peace casts a shadow on
their real intentions towards the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most telling response came from Shimon Peres,
Israel's former prime minister, who was one of the initiators of
the peace process in the early 1990s. ``In all my life, I've never
heard of a country which wants to put an end to an occupation being
threatened,'' he said. ```Woe betide you if you get out of there' _
have you ever heard of anything like that in history?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
