<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-BIKE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGER, REAL AND AFFECTED, LINGERS AT BIKERS' JAMBOREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JON NORDHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Bike Week 2000 headed for the finish wire
Sunday, leaving a trail of broken bodies and smashed motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just on local roads and city streets. Indeed, the
damage on the track at Daytona International Speedway, where
professional cyclists zip around a long cantilevered track at
speeds well over 100 miles an hour, was nothing compared with the
deaths and injuries that resulted when an estimated 600,000
motorcyclists crowded into this Atlantic resort for 10 days of
racing thrills and full-throttle partying.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday night, 13 bikers had died in traffic accidents,
local police agencies reported, and scores more were injured, the
highest toll in the 59-year history of the popular event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's very alarming,'' Officer Rick Gregory of the
Florida Highway Patrol said about the traffic deaths.
</P>
<P>
   But cyclists said much of the blame for the accidents rested
with motorists who ignored or failed to notice bikers as they made
turns or passed other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   It is a touchy subject for motorcyclists everywhere: accidents
caused by car drivers oblivious to the presence of bikers. It is
also a rationale for the supercharged exhaust blasts that announce
the arrival of the bikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loud Pipes Save Lives'' is a ubiquitous decal plastered on
helmets and leather jackets.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed impossible, however, for unnerved motorists not to
notice bikers on Daytona Beach's sun-washed streets this past
weekend. The bikers hurtled across the city and the Halifax River
bridge connecting the beaches with the mainland, thousands on the
move at any time of day.
</P>
<P>
   Some darted in and out of lines of slower traffic, sped along
highway shoulders and threaded crowded intersections.
</P>
<P>
   Riders can leave behind a cone of noise that rips the air with
ear-splitting thunder, even when accelerating at legal speeds.
Eighty-eight cubic-inch engines, twin Mukini carburetors and Wimmer
velocity stacks have a deep-throated gargle at idle, the pride of
every biker, and the va-va-ROOM is a sweet melody to their ears.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from accidents, the Daytona Beach police said, this year's
crowd was well-behaved and cooperative. ``It's an older crowd who
come here for the weather, and they're not looking for trouble,''
said Sgt. Craig Buth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always some hotheads and some bar fights when people
drink too much,'' he said, ``but this has been the mildest group in
my memory.''
</P>
<P>
   The outlaw image persists more in legend than in the reality of
a conclave like Bike Week, where grandmothers and grandfathers
could be seen checking out exhibits of candy apple Harley-Davidson
Softriders and chrome-laden Fat Boys alongside tattooed younger men
and women wearing cutoff leather vests and fringed riding chaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the bad guys 40 years ago when bikers, for good
reason, intimidated people,'' said Bennie Bauer, a burly man in his
mid-50s with a full sandy beard going gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have mellowed with the times,'' he noted, with only a
whisper of regret, adding that some of Bike Week's participants
showed up riding $40,000 customized bikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything down to the last stud on their saddlebags is done
for them, and they don't know what they're paying for with their
gold credit cards,'' he said in a good-natured growl as he motioned
toward a knot of middle-age men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the do-rag off one of their heads and you'll find a
doctor or a businessman,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The men stood on a sidewalk on Main Street along with thousands
of other spectators, admiring an endless stream of motorcycles and
their riders cruising by in raucous procession. In addition,
thousands of bikes were parked handlebar to handlebar on both sides
of the street, buffed and brushed to a high-polish.
</P>
<P>
   What really seemed to be on parade was a national economy that
fuels weekend extravaganzas like Bike Week, enabling more than a
half-million hobbyists to spend an estimated $300 million on the
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have a Harley unless you can afford one,'' said
Debbie Torpey, a self-described computer networker from Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Bike Week, she added, ``is just a chance for a lot of
middle-class and educated people to dress up and let loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the women here, from outward appearances, seemed to buy
into the dirty fingernail and rowdy image that bikers acknowledge
as a cultural inheritance. There was topless exhibitionism,
beer-swilling and macho swagger on parade, as well as
skull-and-crossbones insignia and Confederate battle flag regalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``But where can you put 600,000 people together for 10 days and
have as well-behaved and peaceful crowd as this group?'' said Tom
Guest, owner of Chopper World, a biker's boutique on Main Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
