<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4740 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HUDSON-VALLEY-INDUSTR     03-12 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUDSON-VALLEY-INDUSTRY-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUDSON RIVER TOWNS DIVIDED OVER PLANS FOR RE-INDUSTRIALIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Decades after smokestack industries largely
disappeared from the Hudson River valley, leaving behind an
environmental and economic mess that took years to reverse, plans
are afoot to build more than a dozen industrial plants in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals _ including a $500 million power plant in the town
of Athens, a $680 million paper recycling and power plant in
Ulster, and a $300 million cement factory in Greenport _ have
sharply divided towns up and down the river that have struggled,
and slowly recovered, since the decline of heavy industry.
</P>
<P>
   Those who oppose the plants say they threaten to undermine the
effort to reclaim the Hudson from industrial pollution and to
rebuild the region's economy through tourism.
</P>
<P>
   But others welcome the return of manufacturing _ particularly
the Pataki administration, which has vigorously wooed the companies
with promises of state-sponsored tax-exempt bonds and local tax
breaks. They say it will lure better-paying blue-collar jobs to a
region where employment has improved markedly in recent years, but
where wages still lag behind those of more prosperous areas.
</P>
<P>
   And they are adamant that the factories will not harm the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought a plant would destroy the natural beauty of the
Hudson River, I would act,'' Gov. George Pataki said in an
interview. ``But it's not got to the point where anyone has told me
this is destroying the scenic beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Pataki said that since the governor took office
in 1995, the state had spent $256 million on cleaning and
protecting the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pro-business, pro-industry,'' said Pataki, whose family
home overlooks the river in Garrison. ``We are also
pro-environment. There isn't any dichotomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and many residents are unconvinced, saying
that the administration has oversold the promise of factory jobs
and tax revenue and underestimated the environmental cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of everyone saying the river's never been cleaner, we
should be saying the river's never been under such threat,'' said
Alan Neumann, president of Hudson River Heritage, a preservation
group established 25 years ago. ``It's been decades since we've
been faced with such a concentrated series of proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed plants, most of which would use the river for some
part of their operation, are early in the approval process. A
spokesman for the Public Service Commission said a decision on
whether to build the 1,080-megawatt Athens plant _ it would be the
largest-capacity power plant in the country _ has been postponed
for the third time, until April 30. But the final approval on air
quality standards has already been granted, as has the draft permit
for water discharge.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with St. Lawrence Cement Co., which plans to ferry
cement along two miles of conveyor belts to the riverfront, say
they hope to conduct public hearings this summer. They filed their
final environmental impact study on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the final decisions are months or years away,
emotions are running high. Twelve New York environmental and
preservation groups, led by Scenic Hudson, wrote to Pataki recently
urging a moratorium on industrial development until the state
issues an overall plan for the development of the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In towns along the river, opposing sides have mounted expensive
public relations campaigns. In Athens, a group collected 4,000
signatures and produced a video lambasting the proposed power plant
there. In Saugerties, a citizens' group gathered 1,500 signatures
against the recycling plant and claims credit for the company's
decision to move to Ulster. And preservationists aligned with
Olana, the Hudson River School painter Frederic Church's
Moorish-style villa in Greenport, have joined in a lawsuit against
the gas-fired electrical plant, which they say will despoil the
view from the property.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective plants even played a role in a handful of
elections last fall, in which voters in Hudson and Newburgh ousted
mayors who had supported factory proposals.
</P>
<P>
   In Hudson, an anonymous group opposing the cement plant only a
few miles away prominently placed eight cinder blocks around town
with one-word labels that together formed the questions: ``Who will
really pay? Who will really profit?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century, the people of the Hudson Valley have
tried to balance industry and the scenic landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Poets, painters and philosophers trumpeted the virtues of the
wilderness and the beauty of the river, and along the way the
industrialists built their railroads and factories.
</P>
<P>
   First came brick factories, iron mines and riverside quarries,
then cement factories and later General Electric, all in search of
cheap, unlimited river water.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, the Hudson River was in trouble. Industries had
been dumping chemicals, and municipalities had been dumping sewage.
Scientists found fish full of PCBs from the General Electric plant
in the Upper Hudson, cadmium from a battery factory near Cold
Spring, diesel fuel from the Metro-North yards near Croton-Harmon.
The authorities banned commercial fishing and advised people not to
eat striped bass caught in the river.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, groups committed to saving the Hudson sprang up, and
by the early 1990s the river was being reclaimed. Billions of state
and federal dollars built state-of-the-art municipal treatment
plants. Chemical dumping was curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the deregulation of the electric industry, and
eager to compete for business, New York state in 1992 created a
board to expedite permits to build environmentally sound power
plants. More recently, with the economy in New York City booming
and demand for cement and computer chips growing, the Pataki
administration began courting more industry.
</P>
<P>
   The administration, aided by local towns, has extended a range
of tax breaks and support dollars to the companies. For instance,
Besicorp Co., which has proposed the paper recycling plant in
Ulster, says it has been promised a $300 million tax-exempt bond, a
$400,000 technical assistance grant and other benefits, including
employment tax credits and utility discounts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration has tried in particular to lure
microchip-manufacturing plants, by creating four ``shovel-ready''
sites near the river, with licenses and environmental permits
completed, so that a plant can move in quickly when a deal is
struck. No companies have yet committed to the sites.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have used different methods of persuasion. In
Athens, for example, the town board initially opposed Athens
Generating, and its promise to pay only modest taxes. But the town
fathers changed their minds after the power company promised the
town a $3 million ``community benefits grant.''
</P>
<P>
   In the neighboring towns of Hudson and Greenport, the dispute
over the St. Lawrence cement plant is a microcosm of the broader
debate.
</P>
<P>
   It has involved young and old, rich and not-so-rich. Dave Eger,
one of 15 children raised to farm the rocky fields here, likes the
idea of the $300 million factory set to be built about a mile from
his spinach and strawberry fields. The new plant in Greenport would
replace a shuttered plant across the river and would produce three
times as much cement as the old one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other industry has all been run out,'' Eger, 43, said.
``People around here need jobs, and frankly, I could use the lime
from the cement dust to sweeten my soil.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door in Hudson, the town that once thrived on the jobs
provided by the defunct Atlas Cement Co., Albert Cook is far less
enthusiastic. Cook, who operated a crane for Atlas for 24 years,
says things have changed since his old company packed up and left.
The glue factory closed down, too. So did the match factory. Even
the junkyards left.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson has been saved over the last decade, he said, by the
people who came up from New York City and turned the
down-at-the-heels town into a hive of antiques shops in restored
brick buildings. He said a new factory would drive the tourists
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be a ghost town without them,'' Cook said. But he knows
that not everyone in Hudson agrees. ``My wife feels the cement
plant is a blessing,'' he said sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One issue the two sides have argued over is the matter of jobs,
and both sides freely admit that unemployment has gone down in
Ulster, Greene and Columbia Counties since the early 1990s. In
fact, the Hudson Valley region enjoyed the state's greatest job
growth _ 5.5 percent _ in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But in Hudson, for example, wages still lag behind the state's
average by almost 14 percent. And St. Lawrence's starting wage of
$15.50 an hour looks good: Deena Pewtherer, the executive director
of the Columbia County Chamber of Commerce, said that most area
industry paid minimum wage or slightly above.
</P>
<P>
   Before opening its operations in Greenport and Hudson, St.
Lawrence will close the plant it still operates in Catskill. Thus,
while people on the east side of the river may snag jobs, the net
effect for the state will be a loss of 25 jobs, St. Lawrence
officials concede.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Eger and others like William First, 54, remain unmoved.
First, who has just sold the family construction business he ran
for 27 years, said the new industry would be a boon to a region
suffering ever since IBM laid off thousands of workers starting in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the taxes,'' First said, ``it's the business
spinoff to the restaurants, the motels, the hotels. The benefits
just go on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The debate over industrialization is fierce, and not apt to end
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's polarizing the community in a really bad way,'' said
Carole Clark, the chef at the Charleston Restaurant in Hudson and a
member of the opposition. ``It's been too easy to portray the
issues in terms of the gentrifiers versus the real people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
