<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE IS DECISIVELY RE-ELECTED IN SPAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Spanish voters gave Prime Minister Jose Maria
Aznar a decisive victory Sunday, opting for another four years with
a leader whose conservative fiscal policies have steered the
country during a sustained period of economic growth and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar's win was far greater than had been predicted in last
week's polls and will give him majority control of the country's
350-seat parliament without having to collaborate with any other
party as he has had to for the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   In giving Aznar such a mandate, Spanish voters appeared to be
voting with their wallets and abandoning long-entrenched patterns.
Polls show that most Spaniards are still left-leaning but that a
significant number crossed over to vote for Aznar, apparently
embracing his record and perhaps still disgusted with the numerous
scandals during the 14-year rule of the Socialists who preceded
him.
</P>
<P>
   With 81 percent of the vote counted, Aznar's center-right
Popular Party had captured 44 percent of the vote, or 183 seats. In
1996, when Aznar wrenched power from the Socialists, his party won
only 156 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spanish people have deepened their confidence in us,''
Aznar said in his victory speech to hundreds of cheering supporters
at his party headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But Aznar, who has worked hard to sell his party as a centrist
organization, also reached out to mend fences. ``The attitude of
the government will be open to dialogue with all political and
social groups,'' he said, ``because everyone will need to see Spain
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote is a particularly sweet victory for Aznar, who was a
virtual unknown when he took office four years ago. At the time
many were doubtful that Aznar, a former tax collector and a
colorless campaigner, would be able to last.
</P>
<P>
   But Spain has flourished under his administration. One of the
few conservatives in power in Europe, Aznar successfully guided
Spain into the European monetary union and set about privatizing
state assets and lowering taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years the country's unemployment rate has
dropped from 23 percent to 15 percent. While the average Spaniard
is still poorer than the average European, the gap is closing.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar campaigned on the strength of this newfound prosperity,
promising that he would continue to trim the state's bloated
bureaucracy, cut taxes and provide a pro-business environment.
</P>
<P>
   The Socialists, who accused Aznar of ``sleight of hand'' and
cronyism, were the major losers in Sunday's vote. Small regional
parties maintained their seats, but the Socialists won only 125
seats, down 16 seats from 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours after the polls closed, the Socialist candidate for
prime minister, Joaquin Almunia, conceded defeat and resigned as
head of the party, saying it was time for the left to come up with
new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not able to motivate the leftist and progressive
voters enough to win this election and take office,'' he said. ``We
were not able to get our message across.''
</P>
<P>
   The Socialists tried a French-style coalition with the
Communist-led United Left bloc to try to bring out more leftist
voters. But the attempt was a failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists, who had 21 seats after the last elections, lost
more than half of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that there is a clear conservative trend in Spain,
economically socially, culturally and politically,'' said the head
of the United Left, Francisco Frutos.
</P>
<P>
   This year's campaign was hardly gripping. With Spain's economy
predicted to grow at a healthy 3 percent this year, neither Aznar
nor the Socialists proposed big changes. Instead, the candidates
squabbled over marginal issues _ a windfall tax and the rights of
pensioners, for example. Many Spaniards complained of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Early evening figures indicated that turnout was slightly lower
than that of 1996, when about 62 percent of voters cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowing the campaign has been the recent resumption of
violence by the Basque separatist group ETA, which has killed three
people in car bombings since late January.
</P>
<P>
   ETA's political allies urged Basques to boycott the polls to
protest the government's refusal to negotiate demands for an
independent Basque state carved out of northern Spain and
southwestern France.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of security officials was stepped up in
anticipation of possible violence. But by late evening no major
incidents had been reported. Some 3,000 police officers were
guarding 2,600 voting stations in the Basque region.
</P>
<P>
   Glue was poured into door locks at several polling places in the
area, and gasoline bombs were thrown at a government office
overnight in the Basque city of San Sebastian. But no injuries were
reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
