<SLUG> BC-POPE-BOYHOOD-HOME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE MEETS A JEWISH LINK TO HIS BOYHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also POPE-APOLOGY) 
(mk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Visiting his boyhood home in Wadowice, Poland, last
summer, Pope John Paul II nostalgically pointed out to followers
the house where he grew up. Explaining that it had belonged to a
Jewish landlord, the pope said: ``I don't know what happened to
him. I think he died.'' The pope went on to explain that many Jews
in Wadowice ``were killed in ghettos and then in camps.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the 79-year-old pope had a private audience with Ron
Balamuth, a New York psychiatrist and the grandson of Yechiel
Balamuth, who rented rooms to Karol Wojtyla and his father before
World War II, and who died in a concentration camp in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Balamuth, whose father survived the Holocaust and moved to
Israel, has been struggling for years to regain his family's title
to the house, which now serves as a papal museum and is curated by
local nuns.
</P>
<P>
   When the pope mentioned Balamuth's grandfather in Poland last
June, the case became public, but Balamuth has yet to formally
regain title to the house.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants a plaque to be placed at its door, explaining
that it was both the boyhood home of the pope and the property of
the Balamuths, most of whom died in concentration camps. ``There
has not been much movement,'' Balamuth said of his efforts to
persuade Polish officials to recognize his claim and put up a
plaque.
</P>
<P>
   Before last summer, Balamuth had written to the Vatican, seeking
the pope's support, but had received letters from Vatican officials
redirecting him to local officials in Poland. He renewed his
efforts after the pope's public mention of his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Sunday, Stanislaw Kotarba, a member of Wadowice's city
council, said he had received Balamuth's proposed text for a plaque
and deemed it ``very good.'' He said it might be attached to the
house next month.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting at the Vatican on Friday, arranged by Aharon Lopez,
the Israeli ambassador to the Holy See, and Jerzy Kluger, a Jewish
boyhood friend of the pope who survived the war and lives in Rome,
did not deal with Balamuth's legal claims. Instead, Balamuth said
he requested the meeting to cull the pope's memories of his
relatives before the war. Balamuth said the pope lit up when he
showed him an old photograph of the storefront beneath the house,
and said he remembered it well, pointing out the local church in a
corner of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him about my father, who died in 1969, whether he got
into mischief,'' Balamuth recalled. ``He looked at me and said,
`No, he was a good boy.' He was almost reproachful, as if saying,
`Don't be disrespectful to your parents.'''
</P>
<P>
   Balamuth said the pope stood and held his hand throughout their
15-minute discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very moving,'' he said. He said he was struck by the
pope's physical fragility, and also by his determination to keep
working. ``When you see him close up,'' Balamuth said, ``he is so
single-mindedly focused on what he seeks to accomplish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
