<HEADLINE>
GREER LEAVES CAMP AFTER INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Left-fielder Rusty Greer joined relievers
John Wetteland and Mike Venafro on the Rangers' list of
exasperating injuries this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Greer returned to Texas yesterday afternoon after aggravating
his injured right ankle during his first-inning at-bat in the
Rangers' 7-5 loss to the Minnesota Twins at Charlotte County
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers plan for Greer to be examined today by Dr. Charles
Cook and do not expect him to play again until Wednesday at the
earliest. Greer hung his cleat in the batter's box when attempting
to run to first base and aggravated his inflamed ankle. Manager
Johnny Oates removed Greer from the lineup after the at-bat and
replaced him with Chad Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in the doctor's hands now,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland continues to be slowed by significant tightness in his
right groin after throwing Friday, and did not throw yesterday.
Venafro (ligament strain, left middle finger) threw off the mound
for the fourth time in eight days. _ Johnny Paul
Catalanotto shines
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Frank Catalanotto hit a home run yesterday and
also made a terrific diving catch on Michael Cuddyer's bases-loaded
line drive in the ninth inning. He realizes the defensive play
might have been more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I can do defensively is only going to help me,''
Catalanotto said. ``I know and I think they know if given a chance,
I can hit. Anything I do defensively is only going to help my
chances of getting playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   Catalanotto, acquired from the Detroit Tigers in the Juan
Gonzalez trade, is a utility infielder who came to the Rangers with
a reputation of being a good hitter but needing to improve
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming down here, I said to myself, I've got to impress
somebody defensively and do a lot of extra work defensively,''
Catalanotto said. ``It's on my mind. I don't put pressure on
myself, but I have to make the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Johnny Oates, ``He can swing the bat, he hasn't
hurt himself defensively and he runs pretty good.''
No platoon at third
</P>
<P>
   Oates acknowledged that third base is up for grabs. He also said
a platoon is not an option even though Mike Lamb is a left-handed
hitter and Tom Evans is right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're locked into playing one position, it's tough to
platoon in today's game when you need 11 or 12 pitchers,'' Oates
said. _ T.R. Sullivan
Early retirement
</P>
<P>
   Minor-league outfielder Antwon Rollins, the Rangers'
fourth-round selection during the 1998 draft, shocked those in the
organization yesterday by announcing his retirement six days before
his 20th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he never really wanted to play baseball,'' said
Reid Nichols, the Rangers' director for player development. ``He
said he never really had a dream of playing in the major leagues.''
_ Johnny Paul
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
