<HEADER>
A4749 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-BIG12-TEX     03-12 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG12-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYCLONES BREEZE BY SOONERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Marcus Fizer snipped the final cord from the
net and waved to a legion of screaming Iowa State fans lingering in
the afterglow of the Cyclones' victory in yesterday's title game of
the Big 12 basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath him, the school's cardinal mascot outfit busily whisked
a broom across the floor at Kemper Arena, symbolizing the Cyclones'
sweep through a tournament field littered with Top 20 teams. As he
peered up at the scoreboard one last time to confirm that his team
had, in fact, beaten Oklahoma, 70-58, to seal the Big 12's
automatic berth in the NCAA Tournament, Iowa State coach Larry
Eustachy had a flashback.
</P>
<P>
   He reflected to last season, when the Cyclones were a .500 team
and not invited to any postseason tournaments, much less
characterized as ``a team that can go all the way to the Final
Four,'' as Oklahoma forward Eduardo Najera suggested yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to put the Cyclones' 29-4 season into historical
perspective, Eustachy offered a nod toward the reigning Super Bowl
champions from St. Louis, who went from worst in their division to
best in the NFL in a one-year span.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a once-in-every 20 years story. We're right up there
with the Rams. I really believe that,'' Eustachy said. ``It's
phenomenal what these kids have done. Even with all they've
accomplished, they keep surprising me at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Add yesterday's title cakewalk to Eustachy's latest list of
pleasant surprises. The Cyclones dominated from the outset,
sprinting to a double-digit lead midway through the first half and
maintaining control thereafter. Eventually, Iowa State built a
51-31 lead before Oklahoma (26-6) rallied to close the final
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a 12-point game, but it was never close. They took it
to us,'' Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson said. ``Iowa State proved
today what they've proved all year. They're the best team in this
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Although both teams were playing their third game in three days,
Iowa State had the fresher set of legs throughout. The Cyclones
outscored the Sooners, 14-0, in fast-break points before
intermission and regularly got the ball inside for layups to Fizer
(22 points, nine rebounds) when forced to run a half-court offense.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma shot just 34.9 percent, which Sampson credited in part
to fatigue from an overtime victory on Friday, coupled with an
emotional triumph over rival Texas on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids aren't lawn mowers. You don't just pull their
string and they start running on horsepower,'' Sampson said. ``It
affects some teams more than others and that definitely affected
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones took full advantage, with Fizer, Michael Nurse (14
points, six rebounds) and Jamaal Tinsley (13 points, six rebounds)
doing most of the damage in helping Iowa State become the first
school in Big 12 history to sweep both the men's and women's
tournaments in the same season. The Iowa State women beat Texas,
75-65, in Saturday's title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's a great weekend to be a Cyclone,'' OU's Sampson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, said Nurse, who did little to downplay the
Final Four hopes seeping out of the ISU locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Told that Sampson had predicted his team would ``be a handful''
for any NCAA opponent, Nurse smiled and offered a correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we're two handfuls,'' Nurse said.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, they're more basketball team than any of their
Big 12 peers could handle. In the regular season or in Kansas City.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
