<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO SAYS OFFENSE STILL FORMIDABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The demise of the Rangers' offense could
be greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers parted company with right-fielder Juan Gonzalez and
third baseman Todd Zeile during the winter, but what remains of the
heart of their order compares favorably to any in the American
League.
</P>
<P>
   Left-fielder Rusty Greer, catcher Ivan Rodriguez, first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro and designated hitter Lee Stevens combined for 443
runs batted in last season, the second most by any four players on
an AL roster this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget that we scored 945 runs last year,'' said
Palmeiro, who accounted for 148 of the runners who crossed the
plate. ``We were so good offensively, and there's a chance that
we'll be as good this year. Even if we're not as good, we're still
going to be very good. We shouldn't lose much.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's bases that statement on this among many other facts:
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the Rangers' order _ left fielder Rusty Greer,
catcher Ivan Rodriguez, Palmeiro and designated hitter Lee Stevens
_ remains among the American League's best.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Cleveland Indians, who scored a major-league-best 1,005
runs in 1999, claimed a more prolific collection of four run
producers. Manny Ramirez, Richie Sexson, Jim Thome and David
Justice combined for 477 RBI last season.
</P>
<P>
   The projected fearsome foursomes in Oakland (Jason Giambi, John
Jaha, Matt Stairs and Ben Grieve), Tampa Bay (Greg Vaughn, Fred
McGriff, Vinny Castilla and Jose Canseco) and Toronto (Carlos
Delgado, Tony Batista, Raul Mondesi and Darrin Fletcher) did not
produce as many runs as the aforementioned Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's expectations appear rather bold considering the
Rangers' lineup no longer includes two significant cogs from the
major leagues' second-most prolific offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers traded Gonzalez to the Tigers in November for fear
of losing the two-time American League Most Valuable Player as a
free agent after this season. Zeile snubbed the franchise during
the 11th hour of negotiations and signed as a free agent with the
New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   What did the Rangers lose?
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez averaged 140 runs batted in per season during his final
four years with the Rangers. Zeile, who served primarily as the No.
6 hitter in his only full season with the Rangers, averaged 100 RBI
the previous four years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the departures of Gonzalez and Zeile, ``there's nobody
in here panicking,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Ruben Mateo and right fielder Gabe Kapler cannot
be expected to replace the run production of Gonzalez and Zeile,
but ``it's important that Ruben and Gabe are able to provide us
with some offensive help, and I'm confident that will be the
case,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers don't expect to be so offensive-dependent this
season with the additions of left-handers Justin Thompson, Kenny
Rogers and Darren Oliver to their rotation, and Oates also
anticipates better defensive play. A significant improvement in the
Rangers' team earned-run average, say approximately a run, would
reduce the offensive burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 162 fewer runs we would have to score,'' Stevens said.
``That's 162 RBI we might not need.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Rangers are expected to score their share of runs with
a lineup that includes Greer, Rodriguez, Palmeiro and Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried at all,'' Palmeiro said. ``Our offense is
going to be good. It's going to be good enough to win.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
