<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RIDICULES GORE ON ISSUE OF CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALCOA, Tenn. _ Declaring that Vice President Al Gore would ``say
anything to get elected,'' Gov. George W. Bush of Texas ridiculed
Gore on Sunday for stating that reform of the nation's campaign
finance system would be a centerpiece of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has repeatedly sought to turn the Clinton
administration's ethical lapses into an albatross around the vice
president's neck, pounced on Gore's decision to champion more
restrictions on the role of money in politics, which Gore disclosed
in an interview that appeared on Sunday in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that when he saw the article, ``I wasn't sure if it
was an April Fool's edition, or not, of the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe that he is going to make campaign funding
reform a cornerstone of his campaign,'' Bush said at a news
conference in Plant City, Fla., where he was campaigning at the
state's annual strawberry festival before flying to a rally in
Tennessee, Gore's home state. Florida, Tennessee, Texas and several
other Southern states hold primaries on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, it was not all that long ago that he went to a
Buddhist temple to raise money,'' Bush said. ``One of his close
friends was indicted and convicted of fund-raising excesses. I
think the vice president is somebody who will say anything to get
elected. At least that's my interpretation of how he handles
things. I look forward _ the more he talks about campaign funding
reform, the better off it will be for my campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, chief strategist for the Bush campaign, in an
appearance Sunday on the ``Fox News Sunday'' program, said,
referring to a fund-raising event at a Buddhist temple in
California: ``This is more than just a little teensy-weensy
mistake. Sometimes Vice President Gore has a big problem telling
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Buddhist temple involved violations of law,'' Rove said.
``Fifty-five thousand dollars in illegal contributions were
funneled through that fund-raiser, and the vice president has
consistently not told the truth about his involvement in that
fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   In the interview in The New York Times on Sunday, Gore said he
had learned from his involvement in past campaign finance problems
and would vigorously try to change the system. He also said that
Bush, who has twice been elected governor of Texas, lacked the
experience to be president.
</P>
<P>
   The sparring over campaign finance reflected the extent to which
Sen. John McCain's candidacy in the Republican primary is affecting
the general election. Both sides are eager to court McCain's
supporters, many of whom indicated that they were attracted to the
Arizona Senator because of his campaign against what he deemed the
increasingly corrupting influence of money in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gore appears to hope that by acknowledging his involvement in
past fund-raising situations and proclaiming that he was redoubling
his efforts to change the system, he can head off Bush's attempt to
portray him as unprincipled. At the news conference on Sunday, Bush
emphasized his response: nothing that Gore proposes _ and no amount
of mea culpas _ can erase the taint of the Clinton administration's
ethics record.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore referred often to McCain in his comments, seeking to
cast himself as a McCain-style reformer, Bush on Sunday did not
mention his former rival once. In fact, Bush promoted his own
campaign finance proposal, which has been greeted coolly by
advocates for tougher rules, only when asked about it by a
reporter. Aides said later that Bush wanted to keep the focus on
the vice president's ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Like McCain, Gore favors prohibiting the largely unregulated
donations to political parties known as soft money. Bush supports a
ban on soft money donations from corporations and unions, but not
from individuals. A soft money ban sponsored in part by McCain has
failed in Congress because of opposition from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   After discussing his campaign finance proposal, which also
includes more disclosure of donations, Bush quickly returned to the
theme of Gore's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaign funding reform starts with having people who are
going to obey the laws that exist,'' Bush said. ``That is the best
campaign funding reform immediately _ is to obey laws that are on
the books and have an attorney general who will fully prosecute the
laws on the books.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also brushed aside Gore's criticism in the Times interview
that Bush was not prepared to be president. Gore cited as evidence
Bush's economic plan, which Gore said was based on a ``risky tax
scheme'' that would ``threaten our prosperity.'' The vice president
also questioned whether Bush was proposing tax breaks for wealthy
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush characterized those comments as typical of someone with a
Washington mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president, I think, is probably going to make the
case that since he spent so much time in Washington, D.C., that
only he can be the president,'' Bush said. ``I'm going to make the
case that there is life outside of Washington. That being in the
business world is part of an experience necessary to become a chief
executive officer. Being the governor of the second biggest state
in the union.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president obviously believes that all wisdom and
knowledge emanates out of Washington,'' Bush said. `` I don't think
that. I think all wisdom and all knowledge emanates from the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas J. Hattaway, a spokesman for the Gore campaign,
contended that Bush would be foolish to campaign on his record as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that George Bush is much of an expert on wisdom
and knowledge,'' Hattaway said. ``Under his so-called leadership,
Texas is one of the most polluted states in the country and one of
the worst places to raise a child. That is not the kind of
experience that America is looking for on the national level.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hattaway also promoted Gore's proposal to Bush to forswear soft
money donations, withdraw all television and radio advertising and
hold debates twice a week. Bush has rejected the offer.
</P>
<P>
   On another issue, Bush said he was considering supporting a move
by some Republicans in Congress to repeal a 4.3-cent increase in
the gasoline tax passed in President Clinton's first term. The
Republicans have sought to put the administration on the defensive
over the recent rise in gasoline prices, which could turn into an
important political issue in the high gasoline-consumption summer
vacation season.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he agreed with Clinton that the government should not
dip into the Strategic Petroleum Reserve in an effort to depress
prices. Still, Bush excoriated the administration for failing to
convince oil-producing countries to export more oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are countries with which we should have enormous amounts
of capital,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, at an airport rally outside Knoxville, Bush
received an endorsement from Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., who had
been among the few congressional Republicans to back McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also took a few geographic jibes at Gore, who moved his
campaign headquarters to Tennessee from Washington last year when
it seemed that he was stumbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that Al is in Texas today,'' Bush said. ``I
wanted to go to his home to campaign today as well, but I couldn't
get reservations to Washington, D.C.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
