<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-SHOOTING-890(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN IN IRAN SERIOUSLY WOUNDS A TOP REFORM FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ A close associate of Iran's reformist
president and one of the main organizers of the reformers'
landslide victory in parliamentary elections last month was shot
and critically wounded Sunday by a gunman who dismounted from the
back of a motorcycle in central Tehran and shot him in the face.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman and the driver escaped aboard the motorcycle into
heavy traffic, but the intelligence minister said later _ without
elaborating _ that the government knew the assailants' identities.
</P>
<P>
   The attack raised new doubts about the ability of reformers to
carry out their program of broader democracy and respect for human
rights in the face of bitter opposition from entrenched stalwarts
of the rigid system of Islamic rule established after the shah's
overthrow in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, Saeed Hajjarian, a 47-year-old newspaper editor who
is a key member of the inner circle of President Mohammad Khatami,
was reported to be fighting for his life Sunday night with a bullet
lodged in his neck. Television reports showed him lying in the
intensive-care ward of Sina hospital, on a life-support system,
surrounded by doctors, relatives and political associates.
</P>
<P>
   News reports gave conflicting reports of Hajjarian's condition,
with some doctors being quoted in Western news agency accounts as
saying he had regained consciousness. But other reports
contradicted this, including one that quoted the senior surgeon
assigned to his care, Dr. Mohammad Reza Zafarqandi, as saying he
remained in a coma.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a serious possibility of brain damage,'' Zafarqandi
said, according to a report by the BBC's Tehran correspondent,
carried on the network's Web site. ``We are hopeful, but his
condition is not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Reformers won about three-quarters of the 290 seats in
Parliament in the election on Feb. 18. But the reform cause faces a
bitter uphill struggle against hard-liners who control the armed
forces, the police, the judiciary and the courts in Iran, a country
with an overwhelmingly young population of 65 million.
</P>
<P>
   The reform movement under Khatami, who is a Muslim cleric, has
registered a series of election landslides since his triumph in the
presidential vote in 1997, encouraging many in Iran and elsewhere
to hope that the Islamic system can be peacefully reformed from
within. But Sunday's shooting is only one in a series of violent
attacks on reformers that have suggested that some in the hard-line
camp would prefer to settle the political future in a test of
force, however catastrophic that might be for Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, who was often criticized in his own camp for treading
too cautiously, abandoned his reserve after being told of the
shooting. During a provincial tour he condemned the attack in angry
terms suggesting that his patience, too, may be wearing thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrorists resort to such acts because they and their cause
have been isolated, and because the people hate them,'' he said.
``Their aim is to wreak vengeance and wreck all hope of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence minister, Ali Yunesi, gave no indication of who
the assailants were or what their motive might be. Elsewhere in the
government, in ministries that have come under the control of
reformers, there appeared to be no doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hajjarian was the target of opponents of freedom,'' the
Ministry of Islamic Guidance and Culture, once headed by Khatami,
said in a statement. ``The blind men who carried out this attack do
not know that democracy in Iran cannot be stopped by bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hospital, crowds held aloft copies of a Tehran
newspaper with a banner headline proclaiming ``Hajjarian
Terrorized!'' A number of reformist politicians, newspaper editors
and intellectuals gathered at the victim's bedside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who chose Hajjarian as an assassination target knew they
would create a crisis in the country by doing so,'' Ali Rabiei,
secretary of the Supreme National Security Council, nominally the
country's top security body, said outside the hospital, according
to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
   ``This attack, whoever is behind it, was organized by those who
are not happy with the election,'' said Mohammad Soltanifar, editor
of the Iran News, an English-language newspaper that has strongly
backed Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   The Iran Islamic Participation Front, the political coalition
that carried the reformers to victory in the parliamentary
election, issued a statement that pointed at conservative leaders
who have made or acquiesced in calls for violence against
reformers. ``Those who have used public platforms to call for
violence and killing must know that they cannot bend the will of
their people to reach their goals,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative clerics who have resisted any diminution of the
system of clerical autocracy bequeathed by Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, leader of the 1979 revolution, struck back with
allegations of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Khomeini's successor as the country's supreme leader, Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei, who has consistently tried to block reforms, sent a
representative to the hospital to offer condolences, but newspapers
controlled by the hard-liners attributed the attempted
assassination on the hard-liners' traditional bogeymen, foreigners
and ``anti-Islamic elements'' out to discredit the system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Hajjarian, a member of the Tehran city council,
came as he entered the municipal headquarters. Witnesses quoted by
the news agencies said they had seen a man dismount from the rear
passenger seat of a motorcycle, approach Hajjarian, and fire twice
at almost point-blank range, aiming at the victim's temple. But the
gunman's hand was shaking, according to Mahmoud Ali Tabatabaei,
another municipal councilor, who was just feet away at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said one bullet had hit Hajjarian's left cheek, while
another had grazed his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Associates noted that Hajjarian, in election speeches and in the
reformist newspaper that he publishes, Sobh-e Emrooz, had been one
of the most outspoken critics of those trying to shore up clerical
authoritarianism. Like many others in Khatami's inner circle,
Hajjarian was himself once an supporter of uncompromising Islamic
rule, and thus came to be seen by the hard-liners as an apostate.
</P>
<P>
   From 1984 to 1989 he was a deputy minister in the intelligence
ministry, one of the bastions of Khomeini's rule. Like other former
hard-liners, he turned to the reform movement when he was excluded
from power during the presidency of Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani,
who curbed some of the worst excesses of clerical rule, but is
widely seen now as an ally of the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not run in the election, Hajjarian had acted
since then as a sort of informal parliamentary whip. Just over a
week ago he urged newly elected reformers to act swiftly on laws to
curb the conservatives. ``If we're not active, the people will say
we were incompetent, or worse, they will say we didn't really want
changes,'' he said. ``In that event, we will lose all legitimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the 1997 election, reformers' concerns about
assassination have focused on Khatami, who is notoriously lax about
his personal security.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998 the reform movement was virtually paralyzed
when five well-known opponents of clerical authoritarianism _
scholars and writers, and a politician and his wife _ were brutally
slain. Under pressure from Khatami, the intelligence ministry
admitted early in 1999 that the killers were ``rogue elements''
from within the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   But the ministry's confession only served to underscore that the
security agencies believe that they can act as they please under
the protection of the hard-liners, who take the position that
Khamenei, and those loyal to him, are above the Constitution and
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the disclosures about intelligence-ministry death
squads, have been published in Hajjarian's newspaper. After the
attack Sunday, some of his associates pointed to the fact that
eyewitnesses described the motorcycle used in the attack as a BMW
of the kind restricted by law to the Iranian army and police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
