<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-SEC-FINAL0313-COX     03-12 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SEC-FINAL0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Improbable SEC run ends in Hog heaven
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The chant began with 6.6 seconds left: ``No-LAN!
No-LAN!'' By then, Nolan Richardson was already beaming, already
clapping his hands. In the giddy afterglow, he embraced his wife,
Rose. And then the Arkansas coach began one of the most improbable
ladder climbs of his career, to cut down a most treasured net.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only thing I haven't won,'' Richardson said after
his young Razorbacks won their fourth game in four days and
Arkansas' first SEC Tournament championship with a 75-67 victory
over Auburn Sunday in the Georgia Dome. The Hogs (19-14) also
earned an automatic NCAA Tournament bid, in the only manner they
could have qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've won everything else,'' said Richardson. ``When we won the
national championship, I was happy. We won the national junior
college championship, I was very happy. We won the NIT, I was
happy. But I don't think I've ever been as happy inside for a group
of guys that young, that went through all the trials and
tribulations of basketball and family death and all the talk. And
then came over here and put all that behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hogs did, in the building where they'd lost the 1995 and '99
SEC finals to Kentucky. With tournament MVP Brandon Dean scoring 22
points, Arkansas joined Auburn's champs as the only SEC teams to
win four games and the conference tournament. In so doing, the Hogs
ended Auburn's own inspirational run.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was proud of our team every time we played,'' said coach
Cliff Ellis, whose Tigers (23-9) lost their last three
regular-season games after Chris Porter was declared ineligible but
upset Florida and survived South Carolina in overtime en route to
the final. ''This weekend was a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   One that should benefit Auburn in the NCAA Tournament, although
the Tigers dropped to a No. 7 seed. One of six SEC teams to receive
at-large bids, Auburn will play Creighton in the first round of the
Midwest Regional at Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas, meanwhile, received a No. 11 seed in the South and
will meet Miami at Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks won't enter the NCAAs as they did the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody wrote us off,'' said Dean, who had 14 of his
career-high 22 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody expected us to be here,'' said Joe Johnson, the
electrifying freshman swingman who had 10 of his 12 points in the
second half and joined Dean on the All-Tournament team. ''We had
nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet enough energy to win for the fourth time in four days. ''I
think a couple of guys, their legs were tired, including myself,''
said Johnson. ''But we just had to suck it up and go.''
</P>
<P>
   With 1:29 left in the half, Auburn led 32-23. Then Arkansas
closed with a rush, beginning in typical Hog fashion. ''It was
created by a turnover,'' said Ellis. ''All of a sudden,
bap-bap-bap! They're back.''
</P>
<P>
   One of 17 Auburn turnovers, it led to four straight Arkansas'
points. The last two came on Johnson's pullup jumper, his first
points of the game cutting it to 32-27 at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the second half, we asked them to get into a streetfight,''
said Richardson. ''We were playing a team that was boxing. We're a
streetfighting team.''
</P>
<P>
   His streetfighting men responded. Johnson scored six of
Arkansas' first eight points after halftime. Dean gave the Hogs
their first lead at 37-36, then jammed over Mamadou N'diaye. Auburn
later regained a 58-54 lead on back-to-back 3-pointers by Jay
Heard. But when Johnson's banked foul-line jumper put Arkansas up
to stay 63-62, it also kick-started a decisive 10-2 run by an
undersized champion that was out-rebounded 41-20.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas has but one senior and ample reasons to rejoice.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy Gipson, who scored 10 of his 14 points in the second half,
lost his father in a Jan. 13 car accident. Backup Charles Tatum's
cousin also died in a car crash and his grandfather recently died.
Dean sprained both ankles this season and also had a stress
fracture in his shin. Johnson was academically ineligible for the
first 10 games, then lost his grandmother a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   All that made this unexpected win that much sweeter for
Richardson and his little piggies. ''I was happy, real happy,'' he
said. ''There's not many coaches in this country that are gonna
walk in here and win four games in a row. Not in the SEC. I've
brought teams over here that were good, real good. So to win the
SEC tournament with a bunch of puppies is unbelievable. I think
it'll go down as one of the all-time things that happened in my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
