<HEADER>
A4756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SOUTHERN-PRIMARIES-NY     03-12 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SIX SOUTHERN STATES, PRIMARIES HAVE NO MEANING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was supposed to be the Southern Super Tuesday, the
day when the South finally muscled its way into the primary
calendar and showed itself as a fearsome voting bloc. But Mike
Francis now has a somewhat different name for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it Stupid Tuesday,'' said Francis, chairman of
Louisiana's Republican Party, referring to this week's Southern
primaries. ``The taxpayers of Louisiana are going to spend about $4
million so that maybe 40,000 people can show up to vote in a
meaningless primary. Isn't that ridiculous?''
</P>
<P>
   The primary season effectively ended last week, when the leading
challengers in the Republican and Democratic parties dropped out
after losing on the real Super Tuesday, leaving a pair of
uncontested races for the nominations. But to the disgust of many
in the South, the already scheduled presidential primaries in
Florida, Tennessee, Mississippi, Louisiana, Oklahoma and Texas will
still go on, even though they no longer serve any practical
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, a formal election is still necessary to select
the delegates the state will send to the national party conventions
this summer. Like a lopsided baseball game that must still be
played to the ninth inning, the voting must go on, even if no one
is watching.
</P>
<P>
   The chances are that Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al
Gore would have won all the primaries anyway, even before Sen. John
McCain and former Sen. Bill Bradley dropped out last Thursday. Both
challengers had essentially written off the home region of the two
front-runners, making little effort to organize in any of the six
states.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, polls already showed Bush and Gore with towering
margins in most of the states, which was one reason the challengers
decided not to embarrass themselves further. A series of
Mason-Dixon polls showed that McCain was behind Bush by 48 points
in Oklahoma, 56 points in Mississippi and 69 points in Texas,
Bush's home state. Gore's margins over Bradley were even larger.
</P>
<P>
   McCain might have done somewhat better in Florida, even though
Bush's brother, Gov. Jeb Bush, had pushed the state party into
overdrive for him. Richard Scher, a political scientist at the
University of Florida, said McCain would have done well in some
sections of the state, such as Pasco County, north of Tampa, which
has a large population of retired military personnel and recently
became mostly Republican for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   But because of Florida's closed primary system, McCain would
still have lost, Scher said. Democrats who might have wanted to
cross over and vote for him would have had to switch their party
registration more than six weeks ago, when the McCain phenomenon
was still young.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern primary day was established in 1988 to increase the
region's clout in the nominating process and give a boost to
conservative candidates, but it has rarely worked out as planned.
In 1992, Georgia moved ahead of the pack by a week, in a successful
attempt by Gov. Zell Miller to assist Bill Clinton. After that, so
many states began leapfrogging the South that the second Tuesday in
March, which once sounded relatively early, became pointlessly late
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana tried to buck the system earlier this year and hold
caucuses before Iowa, but the national Republican Party would not
hear of it. Several Florida state legislators are sponsoring a bill
to move up the state's primary, but there is a logical limit to how
many states can move themselves in front of other states.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, both parties are considering drastic changes to the
haphazard primary system. One popular proposal that has been put
forward by the National Association of Secretaries of State would
set up a rotating system of regional primaries beginning in 2004.
Under the plan, Eastern states would vote in March, Southern states
in April, the Midwest in May and the West in June. In 2008, the
Southern states would go first, and the rotation would continue
every four years. New Hampshire and Iowa would still be allowed to
go first because of tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal would allow smaller states to go first and
larger ones later.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the Southern states will have to sit back and
watch as only the most faithful of party loyalists go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is making a swing through the region, and there are
scattered local races on the ballots that may draw a few crowds.
But the reasons to go to the polls are less than compelling, and
turnout is expected to be microscopic.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jeppie Barbour, the former mayor of Yazoo City, Miss., and
a longtime Republican, has decided he has something better to do
than vote in his party's primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be voting in the Democratic primary,'' he said, a
decision that may come as a shock to his brother, Haley Barbour,
the former chairman of the Republican National Committee and an
adviser to Bush. ``There's somebody I need to vote for in the levee
board election.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
