<SLUG> BC-SWISS-VOTE-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS TOWN VOTES TO REJECT DOZENS FOR CITIZENSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A new citizen review of personal details about
foreigners seeking to become Swiss citizens resulted on Sunday in
the rejection of most applicants, including all those from the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Provided with information about each applicant's salary, tax
status, background and hobbies, voters in an industrial suburb of
Lucerne decided that only four families, all of Italian origin,
were suitable to become Swiss _ eight individuals out of a total of
56. The rest, many from the countries that were part of Yugoslavia
under communism, were voted down, most by considerable margins.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in the town of Emmen drew notice across the country
because it is viewed as a test of strength for the Swiss People's
Party. The anti-immigration position taken by its leader, Christoph
Blocher, has been compared to that of Joerg Haider, whose
right-wing Freedom Party is now part of neighboring Austria's
government.
</P>
<P>
   Elements of the People's Party, which received an increase in
voter support during last fall's federal elections, hope to spread
the popular vote on citizenship to larger cities, such as Zurich
and Bern.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Swiss direct democracy,'' said Urs Ischi, a party
member who promoted the new system, in which voting on citizenship
was conducted with national referendums. But he defended Sunday's
vote, saying, ``It was not only against Yugoslavs but also against
others, including Turks and Hungarians.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanela Omerhodzic, 20, whose parents came here 27 years ago from
Bosnia, saw it differently. ``I'm very discouraged,'' said
Omerhodzic, one of those turned down, upon learning the results.
``I feel Swiss. I was born in Switzerland, I went to school in
Emmen and I live there now. I work in Switzerland. It's not
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Omerhodzic, who is a secretary in an international accounting
firm in Zurich, said she was undecided about whether to try again.
``The details they ask are so personal, so private,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss officials have decided to review naturalization in part
because population growth is dependent on immigration.
Switzerland's current population of 7.2 million people grew last
year only because of an increase in the number of people arriving
to join relatives. The number of Swiss citizens increased by only
.3 percent, according to federal statistics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In other nationwide votes Sunday, the Swiss rejected major
changes, including quotas to ensure that women would hold a certain
percentage of seats in Parliament and other public offices, and
proposals to tighten Europe's strictest laws against artificial
reproduction and to halve the nation's road traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal for political offices for women in traditionally
male-dominated Switzerland received only 17 percent of the national
vote. Commentators called the results the ``death'' of the idea,
which was aimed at redressing the fact that there are only two
women in the seven-member governing body, and only about 25 percent
in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also rebuffed a proposal to speed the process of bringing
referendums to a countrywide vote; that was opposed by the
government on grounds that it would ignite a new flood of such
votes. The Swiss already go to the polls at least three times a
year to vote on a wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   The only referendum measure approved Sunday was one to reform
the country's complex judicial system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
