</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LOUISIANA-DERBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY PUTS NEW TURN IN ROAD TO THE DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ The road to the Kentucky Derby, which took a
dramatic twist Saturday when Hal's Hope won the Florida Derby at
Gulfstream Park over the favored High Yield, took another turn
Sunday when Mighty won the Louisiana Derby in New Orleans over More
Than Ready.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty, owned by the Claiborne Farm and trained by Frank
Brothers, had run second in all three of his starts this year after
winning the Iroquois at Churchill Downs last November. If that was
an omen, so be it. The colt flashed past big-league competition in
the homestretch of the Louisiana Derby and defeated More Than
Ready, a rookie star last year, and Captain Steve, one of the West
Coast's Kentucky Derby favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Does this give Mighty an edge in the sweepstakes for the
Kentucky Derby, which will be run May 6 at Churchill Downs? Not
necessarily, but it does not hurt. The horse lost to Captain Steve
twice and to More Than Ready once last year, but he evened the
score Sunday when he ran the mile and one-sixteenth in 1:43 1/5 in
the Louisiana Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana Derby field was infiltrated heavily with
California stars who had fled the rain that flooded the West Coast
in recent weeks, led by Captain Steve, trained by Bob Baffert, and
Exchange Rate, who finished fourth, trained by D. Wayne Lukas. But
they could not catch Mighty when he flew down the deep homestretch
on the outside to win one for Churchill Downs, where he scored his
only two successes before Shane Sellers nudged him home at the Fair
Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty paid $14 for a $2 bet to win, $6 to place and $3.80 to
show. More Than Ready paid $7 and $4.60, and the 2-1 Captain Steve
$3.20 for third.
</P>
<P>
   So, the traffic headed for Kentucky did not exactly thin out
this weekend. More likely, it became confused. And much of the
confusion was created by Hal's Hope, the unheralded colt bred,
trained and owned by 88-year-old Harold Rose, who has dealt mainly
with claiming horses during his career in racing.
</P>
<P>
   The rags-to-riches elements to his story are irresistible: a
horse with little pedigree, raised in a stable occupied almost
entirely by claimers bred by a trainer who earned a degree in
mathematics at Bucknell and did not get into horse racing until he
retired from business 30 years ago and moved his family from New
Jersey to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Then he set up a stable of about 20 horses, chiefly claimers
that he sold to anybody who would bid on them. He thought one was
special, so he kept him, gave him the name Hal's Hope and watched
him run sixth and fifth in his first two races last year at nearby
Calder Race Course.
</P>
<P>
   But Hal's Hope raised eyebrows in January when he won the Holy
Bull Stakes at Gulfstream Park at odds of 40-1. And he raised
Rose's expectations when he ran a tough second in February to High
Yield in the Fountain of Youth Stakes. The odds were still high,
10-1, and even when he went to the post for the Florida Derby, he
was 6-1. But there he finally won respect when he led all the way
and held off High Yield in a stirring duel down the homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's wife, Elsie, who is 85, is writing a book _ her fourth _
and this one naturally features Hal's Hope. When will Rose retire
from racing for a more sedentary life? ``Retire?'' Rose asked
rhetorically. ``Possibly when I'm 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsie Rose was asked Sunday morning what she and her husband had
done after winning their biggest race and their $450,000 share of
the purse of $750,000. ``Well,'' she replied, in her folksy way,
``the children all went out somewhere and celebrated. We had taped
the race at home and watched the rerun. Harold told me this morning
that Hal's Hope ate up all his feed and he's ready to go on to the
next assignment. We're going to Kentucky, hopefully to the Blue
Grass on April 15. That's the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas paid all proper respect to his senior rivals, and said he
and High Yield would see them again at the Blue Grass in Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with his effort,'' Lukas said of High Yield,
``although I would have liked to have won the race. I thought we
had it won entering the stretch, when Pat Day looked over his
shoulder. But you have to give Hal's Hope credit. He ran a
tremendous race.''
</P>
<P>
   The casualty list from the Florida Derby included Scottish Halo,
who cut both ankles before finishing sixth, and Hades, who may have
flipped his palate before being eased in the stretch. But so far,
at least, the casualty list did not include Harold Rose and his
life's dream. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
