<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN AND CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Coach Ken Hitchcock liked what he saw out of his newest
line that joined wingers Brett Hull and Scott Thornton with center
Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Hull's nagging hip-flexor injury has made it
impossible to reunite him with Mike Modano because that line will
continue to carry two-way responsibilities. Hitchcock believes the
new Nieuwendyk line has the potential to be a second scoring line
behind the No. 1 line of Modano, Jamie Langenbrunner and Brenden
Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to win at the end of the day, we have to have
two lines that can play,'' Hitchcock said. ``Brett Hull hasn't been
strong enough in his five-on-five game to warrant playing him the
amount of minutes that we need from that type of player, but he has
the ability, if we can get him healthy, to come underneath as a
support line.'' _ Jeff Caplan
Back-to-back
</P>
<P>
   The Blues were a different team without Chris Pronger. Pronger,
perhaps the leading candidate for the Norris Trophy as the league's
best defenseman, had back spasms yesterday and did not play against
the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously a major part of our team,'' Blues defenseman
Todd Reirden said. ``He's a good leader on and off the ice.
Hopefully, things will be better \Rtoday\S, and he can be back
playing right away. He controls the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronger is tied for first in the NHL with a plus-42. He also has
38 assists and 48 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Pronger is probably the X-factor here, because he's a
dominant player in his own right defensively,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said, ``but so is \Rinjured Stars winger\S Jere
\RLehtinen\S.'' _ Charean Williams
Back-to-back II
</P>
<P>
   And on the seventh day, Blues goalie Roman Turek rested.
</P>
<P>
   Turek, who has a league-leading 1.97 goals-against average, sat
out the game against the Stars a day after he faced 26 shots,
including seven in overtime, in a 1-1 tie against Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we could have played him, but at the same time,
he gets a day off. He gets a break,'' Blues coach Joel Quenneville
said. ``He's had a lot of work this year. ... I'm sure he'd like to
have played here, but he wants to play all the time, too, so we try
to control and monitor that going down the stretch here.''
</P>
<P>
   Turek was 30-14-4 in three seasons with the Stars, who traded
him to St. Louis for a third-round draft choice after last season.
He is 35-13-8 this season _ second to New Jersey's Martin Brodeur
in victories _ and includes 4-2 and 3-1 victories against the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played here last game, and we won,'' Turek said. ``I played
\RSaturday\S in St. Louis. When we play back-to-back, usually we
play Jamie \RMcLennan\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more interesting the first game I played against the
Stars, but now, it's not different. It's nothing special after a
few games. They're just another team.'' _ Charean Williams
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Sylvain Cote suffered a bruised shin yesterday. Ken
Hitchcock said Cote would play in tonight's game at the New York
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has decided to drop the Stars-Blackhawks game Saturday in
Chicago as one of its regional telecasts. That leaves no local
television coverage of the game because of the network's
exclusivity during that three-hour window. The 2 p.m. game can be
heard on WBAP/820 AM. _ Jeff Caplan
Defending the Cup
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Blues came into Reunion Arena yesterday with
injuries of their own, such as to top defenseman Chris Pronger (48
points, tied for third on the team), and center Pierre Turgeon (58
points, second on the team). And starting goalie Roman Turek took
the day off after playing Saturday against Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Those are tough omissions for any team.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were minus goalie Ed Belfour, center Guy Carbonneau
and forwards Blake Sloan, Jere Lehtinen and Brian Skrudland. Not
too bad, actually. The Stars, who defeated the Blues, 4-2, are _
believe it or not _ at one of their healthier points in the season.
And playing well without all their top players is why they remain a
legitimate threat to repeat as Stanley Cup champions. _ Jeff Caplan
</P>
</TEXT>
