<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4793 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-WHITEWATER-REPORT-150     03-12 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEWATER-REPORT-1500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR'S SUCCESSOR READYING FINAL REPORTS ON CLINTONS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Beginning as early as this week and continuing for
several months, the special prosecutor for Whitewater matters,
Robert W. Ray, will begin filing with a federal court a series of
final reports on his office's investigations involving President
Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton, lawyers who have been informed
of the plan said this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, who are not part of the special counsel's team,
said the first such report, concerning the improper acquisition by
the Clinton White House of about 900 Federal Bureau of
Investigation files, including many dossiers of prominent
Republicans, is expected to conclude that there was no criminal
wrongdoing and that the episode occurred because of a series of
unwitting mistakes initiated by a low-level White House security
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Although the conclusions in that report will probably not pose
any significant problem for Mrs. Clinton, who is a candidate for
the Senate in New York, Ray's office is planning to complete and
file a second report, in July, about how the Clinton White House
came to fire several longtime employees of the White House travel
office.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has maintained that she had little to do with what
occurred, while others have told investigators that she played a
central role. It remains unclear how Ray will reconcile the
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   A third report, about issues stemming from the Clintons'
investment in the Whitewater real estate venture before his
presidency, is expected to be filed with the court in late summer,
said the lawyers familiar with the schedule. That would place its
completion near the final phase of Mrs. Clinton's Senate campaign
against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York. It is unclear what
conclusions this report will reach.
</P>
<P>
   The reports from Ray's office will not immediately be made
public. Instead, as stipulated by law, they will be sent to the
special panel of three federal judges that oversees the operations
of the Office of the Independent Counsel. The three-judge panel is
then supposed to distribute copies of the reports to the many
people who are named in them for comment or rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   The judges may later release the full reports to the public. But
it is expected that when copies are given to individuals named in
them, the reports' substance would make its way into news accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton and her lawyers will presumably be given a copy of
any parts of the reports dealing with her.
</P>
<P>
   The issuing of several reports rather than one final one will
mean that the Office of the Independent Counsel will be commenting
on the behavior of the Clintons and their associates over an
extended period. As a result, Mrs. Clinton may be obliged to deal
with with these issues throughout her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As the reports become public, they could also pose questions for
Vice President Al Gore about the behavior of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the lawyers outside the office say, Ray has not yet
fully resolved the issue of whether President Clinton could be
charged with crimes after he leaves office. The lawyers who are
familiar with the operations of the office said that Ray and his
associates were planning to take yet another look at that question.
</P>
<P>
   The issues that will be covered in the internal debate over
whether Clinton may be indicted after his presidency are the same
issues that were involved in the impeachment drama played out in
Congress in late 1998 and into last year. They include whether
Clinton lied under oath to a grand jury and whether he pressed
Monica Lewinsky to lie about their relationship in an affidavit she
filed in the sexual misconduct lawsuit brought against Clinton by
Paula Corbin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr, who headed the Office of the Independent Counsel
until October, largely concluded that the proper forum for those
charges to be tested was in the impeachment battle and that there
was no need for any separate criminal proceeding, said two lawyers
familiar with the workings of the office. But Ray, who succeeded
Starr, is said to believe the question should be re-examined. Ray
declined to comment for this article.
</P>
<P>
   The third report, to be issued at the end of the summer, is
supposed to involve a host of issues stemming from the Whitewater
real estate venture, which lent its name to the far-reaching
inquiry by the office.
</P>
<P>
   That would include such questions, as yet unanswered, as how
Mrs. Clinton's billing records from her days as a lawyer in Little
Rock, Ark., disappeared for two years while the subject of a
criminal subpoena, only to reappear in the White House. That report
will also deal with her testimony about her actions as a lawyer in
land transactions in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   That report may also deal with the conduct of Nathan Landow, a
Democratic fund-raiser who was being investigated in connection
with accusations that the president had made a sexual advance to a
White House volunteer, Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ray, a former federal prosecutor in New York, took over
the investigation from Starr in the fall, he has been operating
under an informal but firm deadline in which most of the office's
work would be completed by the end of this summer. The main reason
for this deadline, other lawyers who have been involved in the
investigation said, is that the three-judge panel that oversees the
office is obliged to review its work at that time and can issue a
judgment on whether the office should be shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, one of the three panelists, Judge Richard D. Cudahy
of Chicago, wrote in an opinion that he thought the time had come
to end the investigation. Cudahy, a senior judge on the U.S. Court
of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit, said he saw no need for the
office to stay in operation once the impeachment battle was
concluded. But at that time, he was overruled by his two colleagues
on the panel, also from the Court of Appeals, Judges David B.
Sentelle of the District of Columbia Circuit and Peter T. Fay of
the 11th Circuit, in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, said one of the lawyers, is now keenly aware that his job
is to write the final chapters of the investigation that has taken
more than five years and cost more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The law that provides for the appointment of independent
counsels expired in June, but Ray's office is still governed by its
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, an associate of Starr's said that one final report
was contemplated and that it could be ``blistering'' in its
description of Mrs. Clinton's behavior, even though it would be
only a recitation of events and unresolved issues without any
explicitly stated judgments. That still seems to be the approach
the independent counsel's office is about to take, said one lawyer
formerly with the office. The lawyer, who asked not to be
identified, said that the reports would not make any explicit
judgments, except to clear someone of wrongdoing. In other cases,
the lawyer said, the implications will be hard to miss.
</P>
<P>
   The report about the acquisition of the FBI files, which is to
be filed with the court within a matter of weeks, if not days,
involves a problem that first surfaced in 1996. Congressional
investigators learned that the White House's Office of Security had
requested the files of more than 900 people who once worked at the
White House but no longer did. The files included people like Brent
Scowcroft, President George Bush's national security adviser, and
Marlin Fitzwater, his press secretary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno asked Starr to investigate that
matter along with his other chores. The independent counsel's
office appears to have concluded that the files were acquired, as
the White House claimed, through a bureaucratic mistake stemming
from the use of an incorrect Secret Service list of White House
pass-holders by a low-level investigator, Anthony Marceca.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the independent counsel has cleared Bernard
Nussbaum, the first White House counsel, of any crime. Reno asked
Starr to investigate whether Nussbaum lied when he swore to a
Congressional committee that he had not told an FBI agent that the
head of the security office, Craig Livingstone, was hired because
of a connection to Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel's office has struggled for months over
the issue of whether to detail its findings, even though they would
be critical of people who are not indicted. Prosecutors typically
render their investigative judgments by indicting or not indicting
someone.
</P>
<P>
   But the original independent counsel law required special
prosecutors to explain why they chose not to indict someone. The
law, as amended in 1987, deleted that requirement, leaving it up to
the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Ray is quoted in William Safire's Monday column in The New York
Times as saying: ``It's not enough to say `we've issued a report.'
Part of my responsibility is to explain our judgments so the
country can evaluate them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
