A4797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-ACC-FINAL0313-COX     03-12 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ACC-FINAL0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blue Devils' `two kids' too much for Maryland
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Memo to all potential opponents of Duke in the
upcoming NCAA Tournament: The Blue Devils have discovered yet
another way to beat you.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Duke (27-4) beat Maryland 81-68 Sunday for the ACC
Tournament championship was really not a surprise. What should
concern the rest of the NCAA field, however, is that the Blue
Devils got behind a pair of freshmen to beat a very good team.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Jason Williams scored 23 points while center Carlos
Boozer added 21 more to give Duke its second consecutive ACC
Tournament title. Duke became the first team since North Carolina
State in 1973-74 to win both the regular season and tournament
championships in consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two kids really stepped up big today,'' said Duke coach
Mike Krzyzewski, whose team repeated as conference champions after
losing four first-round NBA draft choices. ``We're ecstatic about
winning another championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland (24-9), the only ACC team to beat Duke this season,
figured it would be in position to win if it could control the Blue
Devils' All-American forwards, Chris Carrawell and Shane Battier,
who combined for only 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   But the Terrapins could not find an answer for Williams, who led
all scorers with 23 points while dishing out four assists. Williams
was named the tournament's Most Valuable Player with 53 points and
27 assists in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Williams) got inside our defense and broke us down,'' said
Maryland coach Gary Williams, in the championship game for the
first time. ``We just couldn't stop them when the game was on the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke had won two ACC Tournament games against Clemson and Wake
Forest by making a total of 30 3-point shots. Maryland extended its
defense to handle the long-range shots, leaving room for Boozer to
operate inside. Boozer hit eight of 14 shots from and field and all
five attempts from the free throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to go into Carlos and he responded in an amazing
way,'' said Krzyzewski. ``It's kind of nice when your best game is
in the championship game and this was his best game.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland, which trailed by 12 early in the first half, got back
into the game and was behind 56-52 with 8 minutes, 46 seconds left.
That's when Krzyzewski called time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had lost our focus after having a 10-point lead
(54-44) earlier,'' said Krzyzewski. ``I just wanted us to keep our
poise.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Duke did as Boozer and Williams scored 10
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
