<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-NYT &LR;      03-12 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ASSAILS BUSH'S PROPOSALS AND CALLS RIVAL INEXPERIENCED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Vice President Al Gore ventured into Gov. George W.
Bush's backyard Sunday and hurled spears at him, portraying his
rival as so inexperienced that he would imperil Social Security for
the sake of an unnecessary tax cut if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Governor Bush have the experience to be president?'' Gore
asked a small group of retirees here at an assisted-living
community. ``No. A proposal like that makes you wonder, because
right now we are heading in the right direction with a strong
economy and continued prosperity.'' He said that Bush would take
the nation in ``the wrong direction'' by trying to satisfy the
wealthy special interests that were financing his campaign and
wanted a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that if Bush cut taxes as much as he proposed, he
would be forced to cut Medicare, dip into the Social Security trust
fund or cut money for environmental and education programs. In any
case, Gore warned, Bush would ``take us back to the Bush-Quayle
recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was courting voters in Texas and across the South this week
in advance of a batch of primaries on Tuesday that he will
undoubtedly sweep. Although these primaries are anticlimactic in
the aftermath of former Sen. Bill Bradley's withdrawal from the
Democratic presidential race last week, Gore was trying to drive up
interest in his candidacy and lay the groundwork for the fall
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the election is eight months away, the two putative
nominees are already locked in battle, and Gore is determined to
try to define Bush while Bush is trying to define him. Bush cast
Gore Sunday as galling in his presumption to adopt the mantle of
campaign finance crusader, saying that Gore had in fact committed
ethical lapses and ``would say anything to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with Gore aides saying that one of the chief concerns
that voters harbor about Bush is his lack of experience, Gore is
trying to stoke those doubts by portraying Bush as so unseasoned
that he would ruin Social Security just to give a tax break to his
wealthy contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would take all of the Social Security surplus and
devote it exclusively to the Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush had opened the door to raising the retirement age
for full benefits for Social Security. Gore did not mention that
the age is set to rise over the next few years to 67 anyway. Citing
an article by The Associated Press, the Gore campaign said that
Bush had said in November that raising the retirement age and
creating personal savings accounts might be ``part of a trade-off''
for securing Social Security for the baby-boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that those who were well off might choose to set up
private accounts, but others would be left behind. ``Then you'd
have a two-tier Social Security system,'' he said. ``I say, if it
ain't broke, don't fix it. Shore it up the way we always have.
Social Security is the most popular program and the most successful
program that has ever been enacted in the United States of America.
It doesn't need to be privatized.''
</P>
<P>
   Having congratulated a woman in the audience who was 102 years
old, Gore noted that the average lifespan of Americans was
increasing, so that there are now 75,000 people over the age of
100.
</P>
<P>
   ``But just because lifespans are increasing,'' Gore said, ``that
doesn't mean that someone who works at hard physical labor, whether
it's lifting steel or a waitress carrying a tray, has any less wear
and tear on her skeleton and muscles, on the tendons and on the
body, and that person is ready to retire at the age of 65 and
shouldn't have to wait until the age of 70 to retire. I'm against
raising the retirement age.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore reiterated his proposal to Bush that they both refuse to
take so-called soft money, the unregulated donations to the
parties, that they eliminate all campaign advertising and that they
debate each other twice a week, Tuesday nights and Thursday nights
at 8 p.m. He said this approach would prompt ``a renaissance in our
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   He is making his arguments every chance he gets these days, both
overtly and subliminally. For example, he used to deride the
Reagan-Bush years that he said led the country to economic
disaster. Now, he talks about the Bush-Quayle administration,
which, he said in Houston on Saturday night, led to ``the worst
depression since the Dust Bowl days of the 1930s.''
</P>
<P>
   By invoking the name of Dan Quayle, the former vice president
not known for his experience or substance, and linking it with the
presidency of Bush's father, Gore is trying to conjure the image of
a candidate who is neither ready for the presidency nor capable of
sound economic decisions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gore is trying to pump up his standing with
key Democratic constituencies. He arrived here Sunday afternoon
from Houston, where he rose early to go jogging with Carl Lewis,
the Olympic medalist. He spoke at a black church in Houston, where
he delivered an extended soliloquy on the nature of racism, and
visited a Mexican restaurant before flying to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is courting minority voters, here and elsewhere, because a
high turnout, especially among blacks, is essential if he hopes to
capture any states in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore appears to have no hope of winning Bush's home state
of Texas, he is making a serious foray into that other Bush
territory, Florida, where George Bush's brother Jeb is governor, in
an effort to woo voters in that Republican-leaning state. Gore is
planning to watch the primary returns on Tuesday night in
Tallahassee, a sign that he intends to compete in the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
