<HEADER>
A4801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE0313-C     03-12 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Earnhardt by a bumper
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dale Earnhardt was the first Chevrolet driver to take
advantage of NASCAR's rule change.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, the Intimidator, nipped Bobby Labonte in a
photo-finish in the Cracker Barrel 500 for one of the closest
finishes in Winston Cup history. Earnhardt's crew was so unsure of
the outcome that they waited several seconds for the official word
before celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I did beat him,'' Earnhardt said. ``When we were
getting close to the line, I looked over and his car wasn't really
side-by-side with me, as far as looking into the driver's door. So
I felt pretty good about our chances that we had beaten him out by
a nose.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who was trying to win the second straight Winston Cup
race at Atlanta Motor Speedway, admitted being confused about which
one of the cars would head to victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I had no idea (who won) at first . . . I couldn't
tell,'' Labonte said. ``So yes, there was an element of doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   After three lackluster races to start the 2000 season, NASCAR
was rescued by Sunday's race at AMS. There were 12 cars that left
the race early because of accidents or mechanical problems, plenty
of three-wide racing, and -- most importantly -- 30 lead changes
among 17 drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That race was boring, wasn't it?'' Earnhardt joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew all along if we could just get Dale in an equal car,
the same deal (as the others), we can win races,'' team owner
Richard Childress said. ``It proved it today.''
</P>
<P>
   During the last month, Childress has complained publicly about
the Fords having an ``unfair advantage'' over the Chevys. The
complaints by the high-profile owner apparently paid off.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to make the playing field more competitive, NASCAR
announced last Monday that the Chevy teams could add two inches to
the front-air dam for a more-balanced ride. Oddly enough, that was
just about the margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Three Chevy drivers, including Steve Park and Joe Nemechek,
finished in the top five, giving the Monte Carlos their best
performance of the season. In the three previous races, Ford
drivers had won twice and captured the pole position in all three
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helped, obviously,'' said Jeff Gordon, who had a
season-best finish of ninth in the No. 24 Chevy. ``It's hard to say
what we would've been like at this racetrack without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Nemechek: ``I think the rule change helped us some, but
it's hard to judge it off one race.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the Ford and Pontiac teams complained after the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two inches make a big difference, doesn't it . . . in this
game of inches?'' said Doug Yates, engine-builder for Robert Yates
Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has taken Ford out of picture,'' said Jimmy Spencer,
driver of the No. 26 Ford. ``Chevrolets get up behind you now, and
they loosen up the Fords. Now, you've got to own a Chevy because
you get everything you ask for if you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Legendary driver Richard Petty, who owns the Pontiac teams of
Kyle Petty and John Andretti, was not happy after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevrolet won, didn't they? Wouldn't you say the change made
the difference? It was pretty obvious, I thought,'' Petty said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin, who drove the No. 6 Ford to a third-place finish,
became angry when asked about the rule change. Modifications have
been a sore subject since Martin complained several seasons ago
about the Chevys having an unfair advantage over the Ford
Thunderbirds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't comment on rule changes since Dale Earnhardt sent me a
crying towel at Charlotte four years ago,'' Martin said. ``I'll
never comment on that again.''
</P>
<P>
   When told of Martin's comments on Sunday, Earnhardt replied,
``That was all in fun. Everybody in this sport is competitive. If I
sat here and (was happy) with second, third or last, then Richard
Childress Racing wouldn't want me to drive my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
