<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-DRAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 CONNECTICUT, YAWN, AGAIN GAINS THE TOP BERTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have dominated and decimated nearly every opponent they
faced this season, never so much as slipping from the top slot in
the polls and missing an unblemished record by just 2 points. So it
was understandable why the members of the Connecticut women's
basketball team were slouched in their chairs Sunday night, looking
as if they were ready for naps, as the brackets for the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament were announced. Yawn,
the Huskies are No. 1 again, this time the top seed over all in the
64-team tournament and the top seed in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut (30-1) will play host to the first- and second-round
games at Storrs, Conn., and will face Furman (20-10) _ which earned
an automatic bid by winning the Southern Conference _ in the
opening round. The other top seeds are Tennessee (28-3) in the
Mideast, Louisiana Tech (28-2) in the Midwest and Georgia (29-3),
which was sent to the West for the fifth time in the nine
tournaments, much to the chagrin of Coach Andy Landers, who has
grumbled for the last several days about his team's likely
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers (22-7), the runner-up to Connecticut in the Big East
tournament, is the second seed in the West and will play host to
the first two rounds and open against Holy Cross on Friday. Rutgers
will likely then head to Portland, Ore., for its next two games,
and might have to face a hot Mississippi State team, which upset
Auburn and shocked Georgia in the Southeastern Conference
tournament and nearly upended Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said before the selections that I didn't want to go to
Portland, not because of the teams that are out there but because
of how far we have to travel,'' said Rutgers Coach C. Vivian
Stringer. ``I don't know what we are going to do. Our ultimate goal
is to return to the East to play in the Final Four in Philadelphia.
We know we have a tremendous amount of work to do to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament selection committee arranged the brackets so the
Huskies would face Tennessee in the championship April 2 in
Philadelphia. No. 2 Tennessee not only gets to play host to the
first two rounds in Knoxville, but faces the likelihood of playing
in a home away from home _ Memphis _ for the Sweet 16 and Elite
Eight. Connecticut and Tennessee split their home-and-home series
this season, each team winning on the other's home floor, but if
they are the tournament favorites _ and the objects of anticipation
for a rematch, they still face a tough three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, making its 12th straight tournament appearance,
drew an exceptionally tough bracket. To advance the Huskies will
likely need to defeat fourth-seeded Purdue, the Big Ten champion
and defending national champion, and second-seeded Duke, the
Atlantic Coast Conference champion and last year's national
runner-up. Still, there are generally few early-round upsets in the
women's tournament. Last year, all 16 top seeds advanced to the
Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to convince your players that if we play as well as
we did against Louisiana Tech, Penn State, Tennessee at Tennessee
that we will win,'' said Connecticut Coach Geno Auriemma. ``Ten or
12 teams have a legitimate chance. I like our chances. We had an
unbelievable year. We have beaten everyone we needed to beat. We
have proven we are the No. 1 team in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn State apparently did not. There was speculation that Penn
State deserved one of the top seeds after finishing 26-4. But the
Lady Lions lost to Purdue in the Big Ten final, and the selection
committee chairwoman, Bernadette McGlade, explained that Louisiana
Tech, the Sunbelt tournament champion which remained in the top
four all year, stepped in when Penn State stumbled, even though
Louisiana Tech has declined from its long-time dominance of the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penn State did a great job in the Big Ten,'' McGlade said.
``One thing Louisiana Tech had was a nice nonconference schedule.
They beat Tennessee. It was a very close situation. Had Penn State
won the Big Ten, I think it would have made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty conferences were granted automatic bids for the 200
championship and the remaining 34 teams were selected at-large. The
SEC and Big 12 Conference each had six teams, and the ACC had five.
The Big East got four in: Connecticut, Rutgers, Notre Dame, the
second seed in the Mideast, and Boston College, the fifth seed in
the Mideast. Unlike the men, the women's tournament opens with
first- and second-round games played at 16 campus sites beginning
Friday. The top 16 teams play host, but because of a scheduling
conflict, Mississippi State, the third seed in the West, could not;
so the hosting assignment went to the next highest seed in the
group of four: Oregon, the sixth seed.
</P>
<P>
   McGlade conceded that this was one of the toughest fields her
committee had ever had, and she said the selectors could have used
68 slots. There were a few surprises, especially from conferences
that typically only place one team in the field. Pepperdine, with a
power rating in the 70s, made the field as an at-large with a 21-9
record from the West Coast Conference, along with Maine (20-10),
from the America East.
</P>
<P>
   Left out were Florida, which had a tough schedule and high power
rating, but just 17 victories. Florida, McGrade said, was a victim
of the improvement in women's basketball. There were simply too
many qualified teams to jam into too few slots.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was so much parity,'' McGrade said. ``A lot of very good
teams had only 17 wins. The competition for the at-large spaces was
so tight. This was an extremely difficult tournament. We really had
more than 34 at-large teams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
