<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4811 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETRECORDING-SFCHRON &LR;      03-12 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETRECORDING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET JAM SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   By BENNY EVANGELISTA  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
``EB'' in London beamed his drum solo across the Internet. A few
minutes later, ``Daze,'' sitting in another part of London, sent
over a base guitar track to accompany the drums.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hearing that mix inspired ``Girlie,'' a singer who was logged on
from her home in San Francisco, to contribute her own blues-style
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday morning, oooohhh Monday morning. Can't seem to get it
together,'' Girlie sang.
</P>
<P>
   It was a typical jam session, with the three musicians feeding
off one another's creativity as they would if they sat together in
a recording studio or gathered around a piano.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, the artists _ who were thousands of miles and
several time zones apart _ were brought together in a ``virtual
studio'' to demonstrate a new software program made by a small San
Francisco firm called Rocket Network Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The program, RocketPower, lets musicians and producers
collaborate on songs or other projects without having to travel or
ship audio tapes back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   RocketPower works in conjunction with other software programs
designed to turn a computer into a recording studio with the use of
a microphone, keyboard, electric guitar or other instrument plugged
into the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this week, a free version of one of those recording
programs infused with RocketPower will be available for download
through a musicians' Web portal,  &LR; www.harmony-central.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The program is called Logic Rocket, a scaled-down version of
more expensive programs for music professionals by Emagic Soft-und
Hardware of Germany. The free version will be available for both
the PC and the Apple Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Using Logic Rocket, musicians can record and mix up to four
digital audio tracks and then mix in up to 12 additional tracks
from other artists on the Internet, said Emagic Communications
Director Bob Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site will also have free virtual recording studios.
Similar to Internet chat rooms, the virtual studios provide a place
in cyberspace where musicians and singers from anywhere can drop in
for impromptu jam sessions, as long as they have the same software.
Both Harmony Central and Rocket Network hope to make money by
leasing secure private Net studios for artists who want to work on
and save their creations.
</P>
<P>
   Professional audio and video producers say such Internet
collaborations will have a dramatic effect on their industry. And
Rocket Network executives hope the virtual studios appeal to the
millions of people who play a musical instrument as a hobby, a
market that by one estimate is as much as one-quarter of the U.S.
population alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone should have thought of this earlier, it makes so much
sense,'' said Eric Cody, owner of New Millennium Music, a New York
music and commercial production company. ``It's almost like being
there when the Model-T was invented.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody said he's excited about ``the possibility of being able to
take care of a session with singers or instrumentalists in L.A.
while I'm here in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody was the first to lease an Internet recording studio two
weeks ago when it was introduced by Steinberg Soft-und Hardware
GmbH, another German firm that has cut a deal with Rocket Network
to offer RocketPower online services to its customers. Steinberg
has sold about 1 million copies of its Cubase, an audio production
program aimed at the professional market.
</P>
<P>
   In just the first week, more than 1,000 people registered for
Cubase's online services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in one session with a guy from Belgium, a guy from
Denmark, a guy from Hungary, two guys from the U.S. and three guys
from Japan,'' said Rodney Orpheus, head of Internet services for
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Programs like Cubase and Emagic, known as audio sequencer tools,
aren't well known to the general public, but they have become key
tools used in the music, television and film industries.
</P>
<P>
   The days when songs were created in one studio session
disappeared three decades ago with the advent of multitrack tape
machines, which allow sound engineers to add new instruments and
other sounds long after the original singers and musicians have
packed up and gone.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, songs from Grammy-Award-winning artists like Christina
Aguilera may take weeks or months of post-production work using
digital audio production tools to blend the right mix of
instrumentals and vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, though, producers and artists still had to gather in
studios to record their separate tracks, or tape the tracks and
ship the tape back and forth by overnight mail. Another alternative
was to use expensive high-speed T1 lines or even satellite hookups
to connect studios.
</P>
<P>
   But Rocket Network's program lets musicians and producers meet
online at the same time to send sound samples back and forth to be
fine-tuned into a final product.
</P>
<P>
   Orpheus said the rise of home computers and various audio
recording and mixing software available has also caused an
``explosion of do-it-yourself music in the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Two or three decades ago, ``to make a record cost you $50,000 to
hire a big studio full of big machines,'' Orpheus said. ``Now you
can get the same functionality for $399 (for a music program) that
runs on a home computer.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ability to connect online, ``Now, anybody can make a
record with anybody else in the whole world,'' he said. ``Next
year's Beatles could be living in a basement in Boise, Idaho.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocket Network CEO Pam Miller hopes the company can cash in on
leases for the private Web studios to artists who want to create a
constant, secure spot for online collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   Annual leases for the private studios range from $99 to $599 per
year, with rates that depend on how much the studio is used and how
much computer storage space it takes. Miller said that still
compares well to the $100 to $300 an hour charged by some physical
studios.
</P>
<P>
   Miller believes Rocket Networks can tap a $2.6 billion
professional audio production market, which includes voice-overs
for commercials and post-production work done on movies. But she
said there is a potential $16 billion a year market from amateur
hobbiests and musicians who are now playing in their living rooms
but may want to jam online with their counterparts around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Rocket Network, which has 35 employees, was founded in 1995 in
England by British musicians Willy Henshall and Tim Bran with U.S.
software developers Canton Becker and Matt Moller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got interested in the inefficiencies with the way sound
recording is done,'' said Henshall, who is best known as a member
of Londonbeat, a British R&AMP;B group whose best-selling hit was
``I've Been Thinking About You'' in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been interested in pushing the boundaries
artistically,'' he said. ``This allows music to be created that
could not have been created at all. Your creative options have
expanded because of the people you can reach.''
</P>
<P>
   The company moved to San Francisco in 1998 and attracted
Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen's attention. Allen's venture
capital firm, Vulcan Ventures, owns a 40 percent stake in Rocket
Networks and also sent Miller to the company to steer its business
development.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Palo Alto's DigiDesign, which makes high-end
software and equipment used by about 85 percent of the audio and
video production industry, announced a development partnership with
Rocket Networks. As part of that deal, DigiDesign bought a 20
percent stake in Rocket Networks, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Malcolm Maclachlan of International Data Corp. said
another online firm, mH2O.com of New York, will soon launch its own
Web music collaboration software.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to the point where the Net is ripe to really
start affecting how people make music and allow for more
collaboration,'' Maclachlan said. ``I think there's going to be a
lot of companies competing to be the service provider there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; evangelista &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
