<SLUG> BC-GLOBALTECH-EXPORTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LEADS WORLD IN EXPORT OF TECH PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID LAZARUS  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
The United States solidified its position as tech toy store to the
world last year as exports of digital gear reached a record
$181billion, accounting for 26 percent of all U.S. goods sold
abroad, a leading industry group says in a report to be released
today.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Electronics Association, representing about 3,000
of the nation's biggest technology companies, based its findings on
analyses of more than 65 world markets where the United States
sells at least $50 million in high-tech products.
</P>
<P>
   The report, titled ``Cybernation 2.0,'' was compiled in
conjunction with the tech-heavy Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   It finds that the 15-nation European Union was the biggest
market for U.S. tech and telecommunications hardware, with exports
to the region hitting $43 billion and U.S. manufacturers investing
$31 billion in local facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Among individual countries, tech sales to Canada led the way at
$29 billion, followed by Mexico ($22 billion), Japan ($16 billion),
Britain ($11 billion), South Korea ($10 billion) and Germany ($9
billion).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming almost irrelevant what trade barriers may exist
in each country because companies are still buying technology and,
in many cases, that technology now comes from the U.S.,'' William
Archey, president of the American Electronics Association, said in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that tech products will account for at least a
third of U.S. exports within just a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Computers and computer components are on the shopping lists of
most countries, along with the assorted devices _ servers, routers,
switches and so on _ that provide the plumbing for information
networks. Many developing nations also have active interest in
procuring U.S. medical technologies.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most surprising findings in the association's study,
Archey said, was that while Japan remains America's single largest
tech market in the Asia-Pacific region, it has been surpassed by
Singapore in terms of investment by U.S. manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-tech money tends to flow where it's treated most
warmly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason U.S. tech outfits are turning left at Tokyo
and settling in Singapore is because of Japan's recession, Archey
observed. But he also cited continued barriers to free trade
erected by the Japanese government, as well as a lack of
venture-capital funding and a culture that shuns risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Silicon Valley ethos is something the rest of the
world realizes it will have to adapt to,'' Archey said. ``But in
places like Japan, that ethos flies in the face of government
control and some of the cultural considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   For Japan to return to its former status as an economic
powerhouse, ``there are lots of things that are going to have to
change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   China is another matter. Although U.S. tech exports to China
totaled just $3.3 billion last year, the electronics association
expects the country's appetite for all things digital to surge in
coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a country that's hell-bent on becoming
more technologically advanced,'' Archey said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, cellular phone use in China soared by 3,600 percent
between 1993 and 1999, the association's study finds. And with just
13 personal computers for every 1,000 of its 1.3 billion people,
China has virtually unlimited growth potential for PC and
chipmakers.
</P>
<P>
   However, the U.S. Congress still must grant China most-favored
trade status prior to China joining the World Trade Organization
and opening its market wider to American technology firms. While
President Clinton has pushed hard in recent days for legislators to
act, the outcome is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a close vote,'' Archey said, ``but we think it will
get passed.'' A decision is expected by this summer.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. tech exports to China have climbed by more than 120
percent since 1993, other nations have been even more aggressive in
shopping for the latest gadgetry from Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   According to the association's report, the Philippines tops the
list for fastest-growing major tech-export markets, with sales
nearly quadrupling since 1993. Sales to South Korea, Ireland and
Brazil, meanwhile, almost tripled in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The report forecasts that computer use in Asia will surpass that
of the United States and European Union by 2005, but that America
will remain out front in terms of Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the United States leads the way in per-capita
computer use with 580 PCs for every 1,000 citizens, while Iceland
is tops online with 493 Internet users per 1,000 citizens.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Archey said world markets will remain hungry for ``anything
that's Internet related'' and added that more countries can be
expected to adopt America's high-speed business model.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be the model for a long time to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
