<SLUG> BC-WEBRETAILERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ONLINE OUTPOSTS FLOCKING TO THE BAY AREA  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
When employees of BlueLight.com, the Internet arm of Kmart, stand
on the balcony of their new San Francisco office building, they
will have a view unlike anything they would see from their parent
company's headquarters in Troy, Mich. Instead of overlooking a
Midwestern prairie, BlueLight's new offices at Fisherman's Wharf
face whitecapped waves and the rugged Marin Headlands.
<P>
   Over the past year, many prominent brick-and-mortar companies
from across the nation have established their dot-com businesses
here. Like Kmart, they often select the Bay Area as their Internet
address rather than simply operating from their corporate
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are diverse, including the availability of quality
workers and the proximity to venture capital. Some executives say
being too near the parent company can stifle creativity.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of these online outposts in the Bay Area
appears to contradict the theory that the Internet makes the
location of an e-commerce firm irrelevant. Many out-of-state
companies are so convinced that the Bay Area is the ideal base for
their online businesses that they are willing to pay higher
salaries and real estate costs to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can recruit faster and more effectively in the Bay Area
than anywhere else in the world,'' said Jim Breyer, a director for
Wal-Mart.com, which recently moved from its parent company's
headquarters in Bentonville, Ark., to a temporary home in Palo Alto
and is looking for a permanent headquarters on the Peninsula.
``When you're trying to turbocharge a brick-and-mortar company on
the Internet, moving at light speed is the central challenge to
being successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart.com, which has hired 10 employees and plans to add
another 190 by the end of the year, had considered moving to
Austin, Texas, and the East Coast. But Breyer, who is also a
managing partner at Accel Partners, Wal-Mart.com's major investor,
said the company chose the Bay Area because talented workers were
easier to find and software contractors and investors were nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicon Valley is the center of the Internet,'' Breyer said.
``That can't be said of Bentonville or any other place.''
</P>
<P>
   Luring Bay Area technology workers out-of-state is difficult,
Internet executives say. Many workers prefer the Bay Area to some
less cosmopolitan corporate hometowns. Others want to live where
there is a high concentration of technology companies so they can
easily jump to another job.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Bay Area's reputation as the capital of the
Internet world can also be its curse. David Karraker, a spokesman
for Kmart's BlueLight.com, which moved to San Francisco in
December, said his company must pay higher salaries and may suffer
greater employee turnover because of its relocation to the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may have to pay more, but your site will be better at the
end of the day,'' Karraker said. ``In the long term, it pays quite
well to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   BlueLight.com currently has 60 employees and expects to hire
another 140 to 240.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart moved BlueLight.com to the Bay Area primarily because of
worker availability and easy access to investors. But Karraker
added that being 2,000 miles from Kmart headquarters is also a
bonus, though the two offices are linked directly by videophone and
executives travel between San Francisco and Michigan nearly every
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever starting an Internet venture, it's important to be
slightly removed from a retail parent that has been around since
the 1800s,'' Karraker said, ``even if they've been wildly
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Some out-of-state companies establish their Internet operations
in the Bay Area from their inception. For example, Macys.com, owned
by the Macy's retail store chain from Cincinnati, has been based in
San Francisco at the Union Square offices of its parent company,
Federated Department Stores, for all of its two years.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms like Encyclopedia Britannica, from Chicago, locate
just part of their online businesses to the Bay Area.
Britannica.com's Internet education unit is currently in the South
of Market neighborhood, but will move to the Presidio in June.
</P>
<P>
   The concentration of e-commerce companies in the Bay Area
appears to run contrary to the Internet's early billing that it
would allow people to work on equal footing anywhere in the world.
The reality, according to Rashi Glazer, a marketing professor at
the University of California at Berkeley, is that location still
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Glazer said that technology companies need to be surrounded by
other technology companies to take advantage of what he calls the
``water cooler phenomenon.'' Proximity allows people in an industry
to informally share ideas and keep abreast of the latest
innovations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way to think of Silicon Valley is as one big water
cooler,'' Glazer said. ``So much of what people learn needs to be
done face-to-face. Certain things can be automated or virtualized,
but some things can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Though several out-of-state companies have established Internet
outposts in the Bay Area, the economic impact is probably minimal,
Glazer said. The technology industry is so big locally and real
estate competition so fierce that a few hundred jobs does not make
much of a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether these companies come or not does not make much of an
impact,`` Glazer said. ``We do not suffer from a lack of Internet
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
