<TEXT>
<P>
   Dates for the NCAA dance
</P>
<P>
   By Tony Barnhart
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Both the SEC and the ACC had reasons to howl when the
64-team field for the men's NCAA Basketball Tournament was released
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC joined the Big Ten and Big 12 in receiving six bids. But
when Arkansas played their way in by winning the SEC Tournament,
the NCAA selection committee dropped out Vanderbilt. The Commodores
were 19-10, with two wins over Tennessee and one each against
Florida and LSU.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the only reason the SEC had to be upset. After a
season of being rated as the nation's No. 1 conference, no SEC team
was seeded higher than No. 4. LSU (West) and Tennessee (South) were
No. 4 seeds, while Florida (East) and Kentucky (Midwest) were
seeded No. 5. Auburn is a No. 7 seed in the Midwest and Arkansas is
a No. 11 seed in the South.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC is steamed as well. Once considered the nation's best
conference, the ACC received only three bids for the second
straight year. Duke, its champion, was the No. 1 seed in the East.
Maryland was No. 3 in the tough Midwest and North Carolina received
its 26th consecutive bid as the No. 8 seed in South. Left out,
however, was 19-11 Virginia which had beaten North Carolina (18-14)
twice and Maryland once during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The anger of the ACC and SEC wasn't eased when it saw UNLV in
the field as an at-large team despite not having a win against a
Top 25 team. Craig Thompson, the commissioner of UNLV's Mountain
West Conference, is the chairman of the selection committee. The
Mountain West does not have an automatic bid.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also raised some eyebrows with its No. 1 seeds. As
expected, Cincinnati dropped to a No. 2 seed after the
season-ending injury to Kenyon Martin. Duke was No. 1 in the East
and Big Ten champion Michigan State was No. 1 in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee also gave No. 1 seeds to both both Arizona and
Stanford of the Pac-10. Arizona, which beat Stanford twice during
the regular season, remained in the West while Stanford was shipped
South. Temple (26-5), which many thought had played its way into a
No. 1 seed, is the No. 2 seed in the East.
</P>
<P>
   The last teams to receive at-large bids were St. Bonaventure,
Indiana State, Pepperdine, Dayton, Seton Hall and UNLV. In addition
to Virginia and Vanderbilt, teams that didn't make the field
included Villanova, Notre Dame, Arizona State, Bowling Green, Kent
and Southwest Missouri State.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
