<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4817 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PURPLETIE-NETCLEANERS     03-12 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PURPLETIE-NETCLEANERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEW DRY CLEANING SERVICE SEEKS DOT-COM RICHES  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Some people look at stained suits, crumpled blouses and grubby
slacks and see, well, dirty laundry. Payam Zamani looks at them and
sees a chance to create a nationwide chain of Internet-enabled dry
cleaners.
<P>
   Zamani has founded PurpleTie.com, which will offer dry cleaning
and laundry services to the Bay Area starting in July. Its pitch:
Internet ordering, free pickup and delivery at customers' doors,
next-day service, environmentally sound cleaning practices,
competitive rates.
</P>
<P>
   PurpleTie has plans to open shop in 28 metropolitan markets over
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, it wants to expand into other concierge services:
film processing, shoe shining, maybe diapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will build a convenience portal,'' Zamani said.
</P>
<P>
   But making big bucks from dry cleaning is harder than getting
motor oil out of a white suede Armani, according to industry
research. And it's not clear whether Pleasanton's PurpleTie or any
potential competitors will find the business lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   David Uchic, spokesman for the International Fabricare
Institute, an industry trade group, said profit margins for dry
cleaners ``are in the single digits _ quite modest.''
</P>
<P>
   Zamani disputes that, saying dry cleaners underreport to the
IRS. He said net margins are 20 to 30 percent; gross margins are
over 60 percent. The IFI says annual receipts total $8 billion,
while Zamani says his analysis shows them to be roughly $24
billion, or about $250,000 per cleaner per year, in line with Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet estimates.
</P>
<P>
   PurpleTie is now building a $16 million dry cleaning plant in
Manteca (San Joaquin County) and spending another $4 million on a
fleet of 170 trucks. The plant will eschew perchloroethylene, or
``perk,'' a toxic solvent and possible carcinogen used by most dry
cleaners, instead using hydrocarbon and carbon dioxide as cleaning
agents.
</P>
<P>
   PurpleTie step vans will come to customers' homes and offices
within a 30-minute window. To streamline the long haul to Manteca,
the company will set up five regional hubs, where the step vans
will deliver laundry for tractor-trailer transport to and from the
dry cleaning plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental question is whether the additional costs of
pickup and drop off will (be less than) what they save by not
having to pay for commercial real estate,'' said Ken Cassar, senior
analyst with Jupiter Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The highly fragmented dry cleaning industry has never had a
gargantuan chain on the order of Blockbuster or Starbucks. Most of
the 98,000 dry cleaners in the United States are mom-and-pop
operations _ two-thirds of them are so small that they don't have
employees, according to the U.S. Economic Census.
</P>
<P>
   Zamani isn't the only entrepreneur who looks at the staid
industry and sees a chance to clean up.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Krasnow, a founder of office superstore chain Staples, last
year started Zoots, a dry cleaning chain that offers 24/7 drop offs
and pickups (at storefronts, not customers' homes), drive-through
service, environmentally friendly cleaning and Internet monitoring
of account status. Zoots now has 18 stores in New England, but it
plans nationwide expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Streamline of Massachusetts, partially backed by Nordstrom,
offers home delivery of groceries, plus dry cleaning and film
processing, in Boston and Washington, D.C. It's now expanding into
Chicago and plans to be in 20 markets by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   And other dot-com companies, notably online grocers Webvan and
HomeGrocer, which already come to customers' homes, are expected to
add dry-cleaning services to fatten their bottom lines. Because
Webvan, which premiered in the Bay Area in June, has a distribution
system, customers and a brand in place, it would have a strong
advantage over another startup, said Evie Black Dykema, online
retail analyst with Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the question of whether dry cleaning is going out
of style. ``We have dry cleaners hanging on by their fingernails
due to the casualization of American culture,'' Uchic said.
</P>
<P>
   But Valerie Frederickson, president of a Menlo Park career
management consulting company, thinks that there is still a need.
In Silicon Valley, ``people dress in snappy casual,'' she said.
``That means very expensive knits for women, all-cotton Faconnable
shirts for men. That all needs to be dry cleaned.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one market segment, however, that will never need dry
cleaning. ``Programmers' managers are lucky if they take showers
daily and fold their T-shirts so they're not wrinkled,''
Frederickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Zamani said he expects to spend $400 million for nationwide
expansion, and he hopes each region will turn a profit within two
to three years of launch. So far, he has largely financed PurpleTie
himself (Xoom.com founder Chris Kitzke is also an investor), but is
now soliciting a new round of capital.
</P>
<P>
   This is Zamani's second Internet startup; with his older
brother, Frank, Zamani founded Autoweb.com in 1994. That company
has suffered from a glut of car-buying sites. Zamani owns slightly
under 14 percent of Autoweb, which has a market cap of about $200
million _ down dramatically from $1.2 billion shortly after its
March 1999 IPO.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
