<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WHITE-COLLAR-CRIME-59     03-12 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLLAR-CRIME-590(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A SIDE EFFECT OF ECONOMIC PROSPERITY, WHITE-COLLAR CRIME
FLOURISHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.Y.) (js) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Gary Ahlert, an agent for toy inventors, was
in a financial hole. He had lost $400,000 on a plan to market a
material to cover artificial limbs. So in 1998, when a potentially
lucrative mining deal came up, the pitch, from an apparently
credible businessman, seemed worth listening to: invest in an
Arizona mine filled with ore that could be used to make cellular
telephone batteries.
</P>
<P>
   To get a stake, Ahlert called a Georgia company whose newspaper
advertisements offered ``Hard Money. Financing available. $250K and
Up.'' Ahlert sent the company a $5,000 processing fee for a $3
million capital investment loan, and he and a partner invested
about $200,000 of their own money in the mining project.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, the offer of a loan was fraudulent, the
mining project was a scam and Ahlert and his partner were out about
$300,000, all the poorer for having proved a law enforcement adage
that a booming economy breeds white-collar crime.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, while violent crime has plummeted nationwide,
white-collar crime, against individuals and small businesses, has
skyrocketed, fueled by the economy and made easier by the Internet,
law enforcement officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is a lot of money around, they are going to go
after the money,'' said Robert Morgenthau, the Manhattan district
attorney. ``So, when you look back and you have high activity in
the market, and we have never seen anything like this, you are
going to have a lot of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generalization is that the honey attracts the bears.''
</P>
<P>
   That has created a difficult situation for a criminal justice
system designed to deal, primarily, with street criminals, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   For Ahlert and others like him, the situation adds insult to
injury.
</P>
<P>
   And because it is so hard to track down this kind of scam
artist, prove the case and recover the money, prosecutors and the
police are sometimes reluctant to try, law enforcement officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to securities regulators, law enforcement agencies and
the National White Collar Crime Center, which studies the
phenomenon, white-collar crime has risen 10 percent to 20 percent
in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   And the federal Securities and Exchange Commission, which deals
with investment fraud, reported a 20 percent jump in the number of
complaints from 1995 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said the Internet had complicated the
situation for them by making it easier for swindlers to quickly
steal money and disappear into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne A. Hunt, the chief of the financial crimes section for the
FBI, said in an interview that the bureau was investigating more
than 26,000 white-collar cases, using more than 2,400 agents. In a
decade, bureau officials said, the FBI has more than doubled the
number of agents and resources dedicated to white-collar cases.
</P>
<P>
   But, law enforcement officials acknowledged, that is still not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advent of new technology has really affected us
tremendously,'' Hunt said. ``Traditional white-collar criminals are
now utilizing the Internet to do the same types of crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Leighton, a sociologist and professor of criminology at
Eastern Michigan State University, said it was a difficult
transition for law enforcement to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to keep this image of the street criminal and the idea
of the threat coming from the poor, but we have long had all this
white-collar crime, which is much more likely to affect the average
American,'' Leighton said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ahlert and his partner spent about $220,000 on the mining and
the loan schemes. And, having devoted about another $80,000 to
lawyers and investigators in an effort to recover his losses, he
has lost his business, is considering filing for bankruptcy and is
about to close his office on Main Street here. He and his partner
do not even know if they can afford to hire a bankruptcy lawyer, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most striking about the case is law enforcement's lack
of action.
</P>
<P>
   Ahlert said he had appealed for help from New York to El Paso,
Texas, and had compiled thick files of evidence. In one letter, the
men running the mining project claimed to own more than 700,000
tons of ore in Arizona, ore that really belonged to the Department
of Defense. One Texas police agency considered pressing charges
against one of the men in the mining project, but the El Paso
County district attorney's office dropped the charges because
prosecutors believed they could not make the case, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that a case like Ahlert's was
difficult to investigate because white-collar criminals tended to
be good at hiding their assets, and generally it was not
cost-effective for prosecutors unless they could amass a long list
of victims who had been defrauded of much more than Ahlert and his
partner could reclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials in Texas, Georgia and New York who
have looked at Ahlert's case said that it appeared he had amassed
evidence of fraud, but that it was very unlikely the case would
ever go to court.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that investigating even the simplest
white-collar crime case could take years and often involved sorting
through thousands of pages of documents. Furthermore, jurors often
have a hard time understanding white-collar crime or feeling
sympathy for the victims, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Given those realities, the officials said, prosecutors are
reluctant to proceed with small cases or those that involve few
victims. Arrests for white-collar crime, which peaked in 1995,
suggest that after making a strong push to address the growing
number of people being victimized by white-collar crime, the
authorities pulled back and began focusing on bigger cases, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been told by prosecutors that our case was not sexy
enough,'' Ahlert said. He later added, ``We are just two little
guys who can't do anything for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The increase in white-collar crime is felt most acutely in
financial centers, like the New York region, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What everyone is worried about is that if the market corrects
downward we are going to be swamped with complaints,'' said Eric
Dinallo, a former Manhattan prosecutor who is now chief of the New
York state attorney general's investor fraud and securities bureau.
``Because people will not even know that they are being scammed
until they take their money out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lambiase, the director of the securities division at the
Connecticut Banking Department, said more street criminals were
moving into the world of white-collar crime because they could get
away with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you mug someone in Connecticut I could get you arrested
today,'' he said. ``But if you do white-collar stuff, there are so
many ways to hide and shield yourself, and it is much tougher to
convict you in front of a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambiase said that experienced people like Ahlert were
increasingly being defrauded.
</P>
<P>
   Ahlert was hardly new to the workings of the business world. One
of the authors of a book called ``Selling Your Idea or Invention''
(Carol Publishing, 1994), which included a chapter on how to avoid
scams, he had worked with Hasbro, Mattel and other major toy
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Ahlert saw the advertisement for the loan in The New York Times
classified section in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Leighton, the sociologist, said that people like Ahlert were
easy targets in good economic times because ``people feel more
comfortable about spending on things that sound risky.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ahlert said his experience had left him far from
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's turned my life upside down,'' he said as he smoked
cigarette after cigarette in the conference room of his office last
month.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was living on money borrowed from friends and his
daughter, Noel, 33, a schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am embarrassed,'' he said.  &QR; 
 &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
