<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-MAGIC-NYT &LR;      03-12 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS ENJOY A LAUGH AT MAGIC'S EXPENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Stephon Marbury spent much of Sunday
night's game against the Orlando Magic with a towel over his head
and a smile on his face. The dynamic playmaker was an observer and
cheerleader for 20 minutes, and the Nets were still able to cruise
by the Magic, 129-91, before 13,648 fans at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was a critical one in the Nets' flirtation with a
playoff berth and advanced them a full game in the Eastern
Conference standing. Orlando, which entered the game in the
conference's eighth and final playoff spot, is now tied with
Milwaukee at 30-33. The Nets, who have routed both clubs in the
span of three days, are three games back at 27-36.
</P>
<P>
   In winning their third straight game, the Nets became just the
third team this season to whip the Magic by more than 20 points. It
was the worst beating Coach Doc Rivers' hard-working club has
endured this season.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury played 28 minutes and finished with 9 points and 10
assists, marking the second straight game in which he has scored
fewer than 10 points. He had reached double figures in 75
consecutive games before scoring 9 in Friday's 108-80 blowout of
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury's low scoring is a testament to the Nets' growing depth
and chemistry. For the second straight game, no starter played more
than 30 minutes. Kerry Kittles led the starters with 14 points.
Keith Van Horn had 13 points and Kendall Gill finished with 11. As
Marbury and the rest of the starters watched from the bench, the
Nets' reserves rolled like a boulder down a steep hill.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Newman made 9 of 13 shots to tie his season high with 26
points. Scott Burrell added 16 and Lucious Harris had 11. The Nets'
bench accounted for 80 points Sunday, the third straight game in
which they have combined for more than 42 points.
</P>
<P>
   The end was so easy that Coach Don Casey used Gheorghe Muresan
in the fourth quarter. He responded with 9 points and 3 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets got a break when they learned before the game that Ron
Mercer, Orlando's starting shooting guard, would be absent while
serving a one-game suspension. Mercer, who has been the Magic's
second-leading scorer (13.5 points a game) since being obtained in
a trade with Denver in February, was suspended by the National
Basketball Association for fighting with Denver's George McCloud
after Saturday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   A Magic spokesman said Mercer entered the Nuggets' locker room
to speak to some former teammates and was attacked by McCloud.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando did not seem to miss Mercer early on. It led for much of
the first quarter, including three times by 5 points, before
settling for a 30-28 advantage heading into the second quarter. In
addition to John Amaechi's offense, it was the Magic's hustle that
kept it in front. It repeatedly beat the Nets to loose balls and
outrebounded them, 11-6.
</P>
<P>
   Already fortunate because of Mercer's absence, the Nets received
another windfall when Amaechi bumped heads with Marbury with 26
seconds remaining in the first. The side of Marbury's head collided
with Amaechi's nose, leaving the Magic's main post threat on the
floor. Amaechi walked to the locker room with his face stuffed in a
towel and did not return until 10 minutes 11 seconds had elapsed in
the second quarter. By that time, however, Orlando was trailing by
57-44.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets pulled away with the help of their second unit. The
combination of Elliot Perry, Burrell, Newman, Harris and Jamie
Feick gave the Nets their first lead of the game when Newman made a
3-pointer early in the second.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets led by 39-36 when Van Horn replaced Feick at the 8:29
mark. Van Horn, who played center in the small lineup, and the four
reserves put together a 15-6 run over four minutes that gave the
Nets command for keeps. Burrell led the charge, burying two
3-pointers during the run and scoring 13 points in the quarter. He
made 3 of 4 attempts from behind the arc and 5 of 7 shots over all.
</P>
<P>
   Newman was also hot, scoring 11 in the quarter, to help the Nets
push the lead to as many as 15 points and take a 61-49 advantage at
the break. It was more of the same in the third, as the starters
picked up on the groove set by the reserves. Marbury ran the floor
game tremendously in the period, giving out six assists, including
a couple of sensational no-look feeds that Van Horn finished with
dunks. Gill, Kittles and Van Horn did most of the scoring and gave
the Nets five double-figure scorers at the end of the third.
</P>
<P>
   The balance was especially impressive considering that Marbury,
who was 3 for 8 from the field heading into the fourth, had only 9
points. Orlando cut the lead to 11 twice, but the Nets responded
quickly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
