<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-ARTIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORK ABOUT FREE SPEECH, NOT HOLOCAUST, ARTIST SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)  (js) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hans Haacke, the German-born artist whose work is in
an exhibition that is to open soon at the Whitney Museum of
American Art, responded sharply over the weekend to those who said
the artwork trivializes the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trivializing the Holocaust is the last thing I want to do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The work, which is called ``Sanitation,'' will go on view March
23 as part of the Whitney's 2000 Biennial. It includes a wall that
juxtaposes the First Amendment with statements made by Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and antiart quotations by three conservative
politicians, written in the Gothic Fraktur typeface once favored by
the Nazis and sometimes used by neo-Nazis. Beneath the passages is
a row of trash cans from which blares the sound of marching troops.
</P>
<P>
   Haacke said the work was meant to focus on the First Amendment
and artistic freedom in the wake of last fall's imbroglio over the
``Sensation'' exhibition at the Brooklyn Museum of Art. That show
of cutting-edge British art prompted Giuliani to try to withdraw
city subsidies from the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm very upset about is the attempt to dictate to museums
what they show, and the statements made by politicians in
Washington that have curtailed the freedom of the National
Endowment for the Arts,'' Haacke said. ``The attention to those
issues is deflected by the spin of my supposedly having trivialized
the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Anti-Defamation League protested the museum's
decision to show ``Sanitation,'' saying it denigrated the memory of
those killed by the Nazis. Marylou Whitney, a daughter-in-law of
the Whitney's founder, Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney, also denounced
the museum for showing the work. But the two family members most
active at the museum, Flora Miller Biddle and Fiona Donovan,
Gertrude's granddaughter and great-granddaughter, strongly support
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Haacke said his work ``does not speak of the Holocaust; it
speaks about freedom of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   As an artist whose work deals with social and political issues,
Haacke said, ``it would be impossible to speak about anything if
one cannot speak about historical references.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a German citizen and I live with German history and I see
parallels.'' Though he is not Jewish, his wife of 35 years, Linda,
is. ``He has always been accepted by the Jewish family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Haacke said he had always ``taken the Holocaust very
seriously.'' For example, he cited an installation he made for
Graz, Austria, in 1988 that was included in a 1994 show at the
Jewish Museum here called ``The Art of Memory: Holocaust Memorials
in History.''
</P>
<P>
   Haacke, who is known for his provocative works, is in the midst
of another art furor about his historical references, one that
upsets some Germans. Invited to make a work for a courtyard at the
newly renovated Reichstag building in Berlin, Haacke remembered a
moment in 1984, when he walked through a park filled with Turkish
families having picnics, and he recalled a statement inside the
Reichstag building that reads: ``To the German people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood it to mean that the people I was surrounded by
were instructed to stay out, that they did not belong,'' he said.
So Haacke borrowed an idea from Bertolt Brecht: he designed a
dedication in neon letters, using not the German word ``Volk,''
which he said had connotations of strictly describing Germanic
people, but the more inclusive word for ``population,''
``Bevoelkerung.'' Around that inscription, ``to the population,''
he would place soil from each election district represented in the
Reichstag.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that language difference, angry opponents are waging
a campaign against the work, which was accepted by the
parliamentary committee that commissioned it last fall. The full
Reichstag, Haacke said, was expected to vote on it later this
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
