<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4827 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-12 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TRAGIC CONTINUUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The police intercepted the two teen-age boys who were
running up Broadway, near 138th Street, and opened fire. This was
on the night of Feb. 13, 1997. Robert Reynoso, 18, collapsed to the
ground with a bullet in his chest. Juval Green, 17, fell with a leg
wound.
</P>
<P>
   The police would later say they thought the boys had a gun.
There was no gun. And the boys, who survived the shooting, had not
been involved in a crime. Nevertheless, the police arrested them.
The charge _ incredibly _ was criminal possession of a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a joke.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department tried to keep the shooting under wraps but
I got a tip and wrote about it. When I visited Reynoso at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center, he was handcuffed to his bed.
Breathing and swallowing were so difficult for him, and he was in
so much pain, that he would at times whisper to relatives, ``I just
want to die.''
</P>
<P>
   This shooting typified the over-the-top, overly aggressive
behavior that has become the hallmark of policing under Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani. The cops were responding to a report of shots
fired at Broadway and 135th Street, three blocks away. Not only
were Reynoso and Green shot, but four other innocent people were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The police were shooting and rounding up people without the
slightest clue as to what was happening. Afterward, the department
tried to conceal the extent of the madness. Top officials would not
even confirm the four additional arrests until I let them know I
had obtained a copy of a confidential memo from a police captain,
Robert T. Varieur, to the chief of the department, Louis Anemone.
</P>
<P>
   The memo said: ``During the confrontation in front of 3395
Broadway, four (4) individuals who were initially thought to be
involved in the incident at West 135th Street were taken into
custody. Upon investigation it was determined that there was no
evidence to link them to that incident and these arrests were
subsequently voided. All four (4) individuals were visiting from
Baltimore, Maryland.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Reynoso and Green were dropped. The
Manhattan district attorney's office investigated the shooting, but
no action was taken against the police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the city quietly agreed to pay $1.8 million to Reynoso
and Green to settle a federal lawsuit they had filed. Their lawyer,
Robert L. Herbst, said, ``We claimed the officers had no
justification for shooting them.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Servedio and Jose Borrero were the officers who opened
fire on the teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have never gone on record to explain what they actually
saw and heard that caused them to shoot these kids down,'' said
Herbst.
</P>
<P>
   When the officers were deposed recently in connection with the
lawsuit, they exercised their Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination and refused to answer questions about the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen now is what usually happens. The taxpayers will
foot the bill for a police foul-up and we'll move on. There will be
no acknowledgment from the mayor or the police commissioner that
there is a serious problem with the police that continues to plague
this town and that will result, inevitably, in more bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   We are riding a continuum that leads from the harassment of
law-abiding individuals on the street to the arrest of innocent
people like Alton White, the actor from the musical ``Ragtime,'' to
the nonfatal shooting of teen-agers like Robert Reynoso and Juval
Green, to the choking death of Anthony Baez in a dispute over a
football, to the profound tragedy of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Only a fool could fail to see that New York needs to wake up and
deal with this.
</P>
<P>
   Last week four recent Ivy League graduates filed a federal
lawsuit against the city, claiming they were beaten and terrorized
by Street Crime cops in an encounter in Manhattan two months ago.
The cops mistakenly thought the plaintiffs' car had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   When the graduates, two men and two women, saw three men in
plain clothes with guns drawn coming after them, they thought they
were being attacked by criminals and tried to flee. That, according
to the lawsuit, enraged the cops.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of story is no longer the exception in New York. It's
becoming the rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
