<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CHAPLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANCOR OVER SELECTION OF CHAPLAIN BUILDS IN THE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of all the political trapdoors House Republicans
have tried to tiptoe around this election year, the selection of
the House chaplain, the man who delivers the morning prayer on the
floor, was one few members ever thought would catch them by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Now, five months after a Roman Catholic priest was passed over
by Republican leaders in favor of a Presbyterian minister, the tiff
has turned into a furor that is dogging Republicans both here in
Congress and, at least in a few cases, back home in their
districts. In its 210 years, the House has never had a Catholic
chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has led a group of Catholic Republicans to
express dismay over how the speaker of the House, Dennis Hastert of
Illinois, has handled the matter, allowing it to languish. And it
has stoked Democratic fervor on the question of whether
Republicans, dominated by Protestants, are insensitive to
Catholics. The accusation first roiled the party in the
presidential campaign when Gov. George W. Bush of Texas visited Bob
Jones University, a Christian fundamentalist school with
anti-Catholic teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just this incident, it was also Bob Jones,'' said
Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa, a Catholic who made a speech on the House
floor urging the Presbyterian minister, the Rev. Charles Parker
Wright, to remove himself from consideration. ``You put the two
together, and it's like throwing gasoline on a fire, and they just
fed on each other,'' Ganske said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ought to be dealt with sooner rather than later,'' he said,
adding that he and about three dozen other Catholic Republicans
have pressed Hastert to resolve the matter. ``I have had
constituents back in my district ask me, No. 1, how did we get into
this mess, and why wasn't it taken care of a few months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fade with time, the controversy seems to be growing.
On Wednesday, after staying silent on the matter, Rep. Dick
Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democratic leader, entered the
fray, further escalating the strain.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Hastert, Gephardt wrote that the selection
``process has gone seriously off-track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is the way in which a process ostensibly
designed to result in a chaplain selected by a bipartisan cross
section of the House appears to have gone awry, and how it can be
corrected,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of the chaplain has handed Democrats an
opportunity not only to paint Republicans as anti-Catholic but to
ridicule them for bungling something as straightforward as choosing
a chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   It is a subject that has caused heartache for Hastert,
personally and politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``What distresses me is that there are some people on that side
of the aisle who have seen they can get political gain on this
issue, and that's exactly what they are doing in an election
year,'' Hastert said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert had broken with tradition and had created a bipartisan
committee to help choose the chaplain instead of simply making the
selection himself. After the committee of 18 _ nine Democrats and
nine Republicans _ winnowed the list to three candidates, the names
were forwarded, in alphabetical order, to Hastert, Rep. Dick Armey
of Texas, the majority leader, and Gephardt. At that point, the
decision rested with the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and Armey, after interviewing the candidates, chose
Wright, a Presbyterian who is associated with the National Prayer
Breakfast. Gephardt was inclined to support a different candidate,
the Rev. Robert Dvorak, the regional director of the Evangelical
Covenant Church, but eventually allowed his name to be used on the
announcement about Wright.
</P>
<P>
   None of them initially supported the Catholic priest, the Rev.
Timothy O'Brien, a political science professor at Marquette
University in Milwaukee, although Gephardt later backed him.
O'Brien, however, received the most votes in committee, followed by
Dvorak and then Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats demanded to know why the first choice, O'Brien, was
overlooked. Hastert said he had never received, nor did he need to
know, the vote tally. The final decision belonged to the leaders,
and he said Wright impressed him the most.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was exacerbated when O'Brien complained about
anti-Catholic bias. He also objected to questions from committee
members about his collar and whether he was qualified to counsel
married people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all stunned, really stunned,'' said Rep. Anna Eshoo,
D-Calif., a Catholic who was on the committee. ``I do think there
is some anti-Catholic bias in this.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one Catholic leader, William Donohue, the president of
the Catholic League of Civil and Religious Rights, has not let
Hastert off the hook. He has turned the fracas into an effort to
root out the anti-Catholic bias he said still exists among
Protestants, especially Christian evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a segment of the evangelical Protestant community
that is anti-Catholic,'' Donohue said. ``It has been there for a
long, long time. Everyone is saying, `Let's not talk about it.' I
don't want a strain between Catholics and Protestants, but I'm not
going to paper this over.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue's vehemence has led to criticism from other Catholic
leaders who say he is needlessly inflaming passions. It has also
upset evangelical Christians in Congress, who have pressured
Hastert not to back down, further complicating the issue.
</P>
<P>
   To blunt the political fallout, Republican leaders have
instructed members to remind constituents that many Republicans
have voted to outlaw abortion and to send more children to
parochial schools. They have also passed a resolution praising
Catholic schools and granting Cardinal John O'Connor of New York
the Congressional Medal of Honor. Democrats wondered whether it was
coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said he was debating what to do because Democrats are
likely to oppose the selection of Wright on the House floor. ``It's
not fair to ask someone to come in and be chaplain when half of the
House won't even talk to him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Catholics, already shaken by the Bob Jones University
incident, want him to hurry up and put the issue to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been festering,'' said Rep. Paul Ryan, R-Wis., a
Catholic who represents O'Brien's district. He called the attacks
``disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It did restoke those old Catholic fears,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 2144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
