<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-DRAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINCINNATI COACH IS UPSET THAT HIS TEAM IS NOT A NO. 1 SEED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The top seeds are vulnerable; at least one No. 2 seed believes
it should be a No. 1 seed, and surging St. John's will try to
capture a wide-open National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament from the sunshine of the West. Such are the perceptions
and truths when the NCAA selection committee paired the nation's 64
best teams against one another Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Two teams from last year's Final Four, Duke (27-4) and Michigan
State (26-7), were awarded No. 1 seeds in the East and Midwest
regions, and two West Coast teams were deemed the strongest in the
other two regions: Arizona (26-6) stays in the West and Stanford
(26-3) was shipped South as the top seed for the first time in the
school's history.
</P>
<P>
   And that did not sit well with Cincinnati Coach Bob Huggins. His
Bearcats (28-3), who were ranked No. 1 in the polls for 12 weeks,
were sent South as a No. 2 after their star, Kenyon Martin,
suffered a broken leg in the Conference USA tournament last week.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins did not like that his team's power ratings that quantify
strength of schedule lost out a medically-tinged crystal ball.
``It's ridiculous, totally ridiculous,'' Huggins said, basing his
argument on the ratings power index. ``We must be the first team in
history to be No. 1 in the RPI and not get a No. 1 seed. That's a
historical thing those guys just did. How do they know how good
we'll be without Kenyon?''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Thompson, chairman of the NCAA selection committee,
conceded that the Martin injury was the only reason Cincinnati was
not seeded No. 1. ``We try to project what the loss of an
All-America-caliber player like Kenyon Martin would do to a team,''
said Thompson, commissioner of the Mountain West Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Temple (26-5) could also have made a case for a top seed and,
Coach John Chaney made it clear during the weekend that the Owls
were talented enough to take him to his first Final Four ``if we
didn't run across Duke.'' On paper, at least, Temple, the second
seed in the East, would need to beat the Blue Devils in the final.
The Owls will play Lafayette (24-6) on Friday in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which bracket doesn't matter,'' said Chaney, whose teams have
lost four times in the regional finals. ``Everybody will try to be
as good as they can possibly be. Win one, you buy one. Lose, it's
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's Coach Mike Jarvis also did not mind that the
committee moved his team West as the No. 2 seed. The Red Storm
(24-7) have won 11 of their last 12 games and will play Northern
Arizona (20-10) on Thursday in Tucson, Ariz. In 1993, Jarvis took
George Washington to the West Regional and almost upset eventual
tournament runner-up Michigan, who had Chris Webber and Jalen Rose
among its ``Fab Five.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis called the McKale Center, where Arizona plays its home
games, a ``mini-Madison Square Garden,'' and he thoroughly enjoyed
how his team was highly regarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams that going in worrying about their seed or worrying
about being upset have a pretty good chance of being upset,''
Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's was one of five Big East teams to make the field _
Connecticut is seeded No. 5 and Miami No. 6 in the South; Syracuse
was sent to the Midwest as a No. 4 and Seton Hall stayed in the
East as No. 10. But the conference was denied a sixth team when
Notre Dame (18-14) failed to make the field despite upsets of
Connecticut twice, Ohio State and St. John's. The Irish, Arizona
State and Virginia were among 12 winning teams to feel the
heartbreak of not being selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very tough decision,'' Thompson said of Notre Dame.
``We measure quality wins and the unfortunate losses. They didn't
have a winning record in the Big East.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten, Big 12 and Southeastern conferences were deemed the
strongest by the selection committee, and each placed six teams
each in the field. Conference USA and the Pacific-10 eah had four
teams, and the Atlantic Coast Conference had only three teams
selected for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's welcomed the selection as the school's highest seed
since the 1985 team with Chris Mullins and Walter Berry made the
Final Four. If the Red Storm beat Northern Arizona, the Red Storm
will play the winner of the game between No. 7 Louisville (19-11)
and No. 10 Gonzaga (24-8) on Saturday. The region's top seed,
Arizona (26-6), the Pac-10 champion, will play No. 16 Jackson State
(16-15) on Thursday in Salt Lake City
</P>
<P>
   Erick Barkley, the Red Storm's embattled guard who recently came
under N.C.A.A. scrutiny, said he would approach the first-round
game as he had all the others in his difficult season. ``From the
beginning, I've played every game like my last,'' Barkley said.
``I'm only going to be satisfied if we're in the Final Four or
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
