<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MURDER-DNA-620&AMP;ADD     03-12 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MURDER-DNA-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA DATABASE SAID TO LINK INMATE TO 1979 MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prosecutors in Westchester County say they have
solved the 1979 murder of a young Mount Vernon mother by analyzing
DNA evidence collected along a blood trail from the woman's
apartment and comparing it with the state's database of DNA
profiles of convicted felons.
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence, which is expected to result in charges being
filed Monday against Walter Gill, 49, an inmate at Sing Sing
Correctional Facility in Ossining, provides state officials with
the first DNA match in a cold case since legislation was passed
last fall to expand the state's database of criminal offenders.
Gill is serving a prison term for robbery, an offense that did not
require DNA sampling until December.
</P>
<P>
   The Westchester County district attorney, Jeanine F. Pirro, said
Sunday that based on the DNA match, her office would charge Gill
with the murder of Diane Gregory, 22, whose body was found in the
living room of her fourth-floor Mount Vernon apartment in August
1979. Gregory, who had a 2-year-old daughter, had been stabbed four
times. Her case was reopened this year at the request of her
family, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro said the match was a powerful illustration that the
database is maturing as a law-enforcement tool. She predicted that
more old murder cases would be solved as police departments and
prosecutors around the state scoured their files for cases in which
biological evidence had been preserved and could be analyzed and
submitted for comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, I think, the beginning of our solving a number of
crimes,'' Pirro said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into Gregory's slaying was renewed this year
after Carolyn Gregory, the dead woman's sister, asked a member of
the Mount Vernon City Council if DNA might be used to glean fresh
clues in the case, Pirro said. The councilman approached the Mount
Vernon Police Department, which then reviewed its files to see if
old evidence existed.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, biological evidence abounded. Gregory's apartment
had been splattered with blood, as had a pillowcase that had been
pressed against her head, a piece of jagged glass and a sheet found
at the end of a bloody trail that began at her body and continued
outdoors. Some of this blood, detectives had long believed, came
from her attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a law-enforcement official who is involved in the
investigation said the Mount Vernon detectives' original case files
indicated that Gill had known Gregory and had been a suspect from
the beginning, but that investigators had lacked evidence powerful
enough to file a charge or to get a court order to draw his blood
for testing. Under the new state law, however, Gill had to submit a
DNA sample as an inmate, and did so in January.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing this, investigators retrieved the sheet, pillowcase and
glass shard from storage and sent them to the Westchester County
forensic lab, which was able to extract, amplify and analyze DNA
from the blood on the sheet and pillowcase. Once entered into the
state database, the DNA profile extracted from the sheet was found
to match Gill's profile, Pirro said. Gregory's blood was on the
sheet also.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro described discovery of the DNA match as ``like the finger
of God pointing 21 years later, saying, `You can't get away with
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``This evidence shows that he was at the murder scene while she
was bleeding,'' Pirro said. ``Obviously we will still have to go to
trial and prove it beyond a reasonable doubt, and I believe that we
can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pirro said that after her office charged Gill with second-degree
murder, prosecutors would present the DNA evidence to a grand jury.
Gill is eligible for parole on his robbery conviction in May.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The cold-case DNA match is not the first in the state. Earlier
this year, the DNA of Jonathan Williams, 33, an inmate being held
at Rikers Island jail on a murder charge, was found to match a
sample in a New York City database of DNA derived from rape
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Safir, the New York police commissioner, said the match
conclusively linked Williams to semen taken from a Harlem rape
victim in 1998. And the city medical examiner's office, which
maintains that database, said it had had as many as three so-called
hits since last year. The case against Williams has been under
grand-jury review, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gregory's case was seized upon Sunday by Gov. George
Pataki, who described Gill as a career criminal who has been
convicted of nine felonies and eight misdemeanors since 1969. The
convictions include multiple counts of robbery, grand larceny,
possession of stolen property and criminal trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   The governor plans to call a news conference Monday to say that
Gregory's case illustrates that his two recent proposals for
greater use of forensic DNA _ one to expand the database to include
anyone convicted of any state crime, another to eliminate statutes
of limitation for 16 felonies _ are sound.
</P>
<P>
   Civil libertarians have expressed opposition to elements of both
bills, saying that the expanded DNA sampling would be an
unnecessary invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   They also say that many of the felonies for which Pataki would
abolish the statutes of limitation, including second-degree arson,
criminal sale of a weapon and aggravated assault on a police
officer, do not typically yield DNA evidence, and thus should not
have their prosecution deadlines abolished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
