<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4840 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CIA-NYT &LR;      03-12 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REDEMPTION AT THE CIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, March 13:
</P>
<P>
   The CIA's Cold War entanglements in Guatemala are like a
malignant tumor that cannot be eradicated.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 the agency seemed to deal belatedly but decisively with
its misdeeds. John Deutch, the CIA director, dismissed two senior
officers and disciplined several others for mishandling relations
with the Guatemalan military and failing to keep Congress
adequately informed about operations in the Central American
nation.
</P>
<P>
   But now all seems forgiven, as the agency prepares to award a
distinguished career medal to the highest-ranking official who was
fired.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA contends that the award to Terry Ward, who was once
chief of covert operations in Latin America, is intended to honor
his achievements over a long career and should not be read as a
nullification of Deutch's action.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials note that even as he sacked Ward, Deutch said
his decision did not preclude recognition of Ward's previous
service. But the unmistakable message of the award is that George
Tenet, Deutch's successor, does not think Ward's behavior was all
that reprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   The Guatemala matter was not a minor mistake. It involved a
breach of the most basic covenant that must govern the operations
of an intelligence agency in a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Ward failed to ensure that Congress, as required by law, was
kept fully and currently informed about the abusive conduct of
Guatemalan officers who were on the agency payroll. This included
allegations that one of the men had condoned the murder of an
American innkeeper in Guatemala and the killing of a Guatemalan
guerrilla married to an American lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet, who has worked for the White House and the Senate and
served as Deutch's deputy, is wise in the ways of Washington.
Surely he knows that an award like this tells agency employees that
the boss is repudiating the decision of Deutch and is more
interested in befriending the CIA's operations division than in
insisting on the highest standards of conduct. It is no secret that
Ward's dismissal outraged many members of the espionage service.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is just a coincidence, but the rehabilitation of Ward
comes just as Deutch's stature has been diminished by new
disclosures that he mishandled classified information when he ran
the CIA, and that some of his top aides, including Tenet, may have
tried to shield him from investigation after he left the agency. In
the spy business, accounts tend to get settled eventually, though
often in opaque ways.
</P>
<P>
   If Tenet did not want to create the impression that the agency
was absolving Ward, he could have quietly overruled the decision of
his operations chief, James Pavitt, to grant the award. At the
least, when the award is presented later this month, Tenet or
Pavitt should say that in honoring Ward, the CIA is not excusing or
belittling his transgressions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-BALLOT-NYT &LR;      03-12 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BALLOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WHIFFS OF REFORM IN ALBANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it was the springlike weather, or the angry complaints of
Republican voters who had to squint hard to find their presidential
candidate listed in small print on New York's presidential primary
ballot. But the past week saw encouraging signs that the breezes of
political reform may finally be reaching Albany.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Republican leader of the State Senate, Joseph
Bruno, denounced as ``absolute nonsense'' the Republican ballot
rules that nearly blocked Sen. John McCain from competing here and
subjected New York to national ridicule. Even more refreshing,
Bruno promised ``to move diligently'' on a thorough overhaul of
those rules to make it easier for candidates to get on the ballot.
He also pledged to simplify the ballot itself. That would
presumably mean discarding the state GOP's frustrating practice of
showing delegates' names in large type, with the names of the
presidential candidates those delegates support listed in tiny type
below.
</P>
<P>
   In making these pledges, Bruno was elaborating on the general
promise of change that he made two weeks ago, when he was trying to
perfume a party-line vote by Senate Republicans to block a solid
reform bill proposed by Senate Democrats. In the interim, the sour
reaction of many Republican voters to last Tuesday's convoluted
ballot apparently strengthened Bruno's resolve to get out in front
on the issue rather than wait for leadership from Gov. George
Pataki, a fellow Republican with whom he has been feuding these
past several months.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been a long wait. Until Bruno's announcement, and
even right afterward, the governor's office was dismissing calls
for prompt action on reform, saying there was no urgency as the
next presidential election is still four years away. But confronted
by Bruno's promise to take action independently, Pataki changed his
tune. A spokesman denied reacting to Bruno's push but said the
governor would make his own reform proposal, and that it would come
``sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki was an architect of the disgraceful and ultimately
unsuccessful effort to prevent McCain and other Republican
candidates from competing against Gov. George W. Bush in the
state's primary. The fact that Bush ultimately prevailed over
McCain in the contest does not make the governor's ballot scheming
look any better. Pataki owes it to New Yorkers to rise above his
petty squabbling with Bruno to achieve permanent changes in the law
that ease the rules for ballot access and that otherwise advance
principles of democracy and fair competition.
</P>
<P>
   There is no excuse for delay. The latest ballot fiasco has
created a window for reform that is fated to close as memories of
this year's ballot manipulation fade and party leaders again become
preoccupied with crafting rules to help their particular candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 2212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
