<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-WAGE-NYT &LR;      03-12 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A POISONED MINIMUM WAGE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, March 13:
</P>
<P>
   The House has passed a much-needed $1 minimum-wage increase over
two years, but the bill is fatally tainted by $123 billion in tax
cuts that mostly benefit the wealthy. President Clinton has vowed
to veto the bill unless Congress strips away the tax cuts.
Republican leaders have resisted increasing the minimum wage, which
at $5.15 an hour is well below its buying power in 1980. But now
they have modified their game plan, trying instead to hold a wage
increase hostage for tax breaks for high-income individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans claim that the tax cuts are intended to help
small businesses, which would have to pay their lowest-wage workers
more. But in fact, more than $78 billion of the tax cuts over 10
years comes from reductions in estate and gift taxes. Only $19
billion of the cuts counts as small-business tax relief, according
to the Congressional Joint Committee on Taxation. Other provisions
in the bill could reduce employer-paid pension coverage for
low-paid workers.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens for Tax Justice, a liberal research group, estimates
that nearly 90 percent of the tax benefits would go to the
wealthiest 5 percent of taxpayers. The House bill will now have to
be reconciled with a Senate bill that raised the minimum wage by $1
dollar over three years and included an equally objectionable,
though smaller package of tax cuts. The minimum wage should be
raised, without tax cuts for the rich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 2218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4844 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-PEREZ-CORRECTION-     03-12 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PEREZ-CORRECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' PEREZ CHARGED WITH DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Fixing ninth graph) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Carlos Perez's on-field problems spilled off
the field once again when he was arrested and charged with driving
under the influence late Saturday night, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who pitched earlier in the day against St. Louis in
Jupiter, Fla., was arrested at 11:03 p.m. He spent eight hours in
county jail before posting $500 bond, according to a statement
released by the Vero Beach Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, 29, was on his way back from dinner at the Riverside
Cafe, police said, when he stopped at a traffic light at the
beachfront intersection of Ocean Drive and Beachland Boulevard. He
put his car in park and fell asleep, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A concerned motorist called police after witnessing the car go
through a complete cycle of the traffic light without moving,
according to the police statement.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, still owed $12.6 million over the next two seasons, was
released from jail approximately 7 a.m. and was in uniform by 10
a.m. for the day's workout. Afterward, Perez met with Los Angeles
Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone and managing partner and CEO
Bob Daly for approximately 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm not happy,'' Daly said. ``He said he had a
couple of drinks, got to the light and fell asleep. I'm very happy
that nobody got hurt and nothing else happened, but it's not
exactly what I would have liked to have with my eggs this
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly said Perez ``seems to be remorseful about (the incident).''
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he's not going to do it again. We'll see. I don't
know. I want to get the rest of the facts,'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's legal limit for driving under the influence is .08.
Perez failed a field roadside physical performance test but refused
a breathalyzer test, according to Vero Beach Police Lt. Kevin
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the officer's opinion, he was impaired and over the legal
limit,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The arresting officer, Charles McFarland, could not be reached
for comment. Perez was charged with a first-degree misdemeanor,
Martin said. The maxium penalty is one year in prison and a $1,000
fine. Martin also said Florida law mandates the suspension of
Perez's driver's license for six months for failing to take a
breathalyzer test.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter to me if they want to do it (administer a
breathalyzer), if I say no,'' Perez said. ``Nobody got hurt, nobody
got hit. I was sleeping at the light, and that's it. I was just
kind of tired. I don't think this kind of stuff is going to happen.
Only thing I can say is I'll be more careful next time and hope it
doesn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to upset my mind. I'm still working hard and
I'm not going to keep nothing in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   A hearing date was not set. However, Adam Katz, Perez's agent,
is scheduled to fly here today to meet with the player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake,'' Perez said. ``Everyone can make a mistake.
It's the first time it happened, but I can guarantee it's not going
to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said that since he doesn't know all the facts of the
incident, and with litigation looming, it would be unfair to
address how this affects Perez's status on the Dodgers. Perez
remains in the hunt for a spot in the starting rotation, but team
officials were steaming about this incident.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson opted not to comment on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   This is a another in a series of off-the-field incidents
involving the well-compensated Perez, who is trying to rebound from
the worst year of his career. He was 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA last
season, and has a 14.40 ERA this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The problems began for Perez the moment he was acquired from the
Montreal Expos in a July 1998 trade. He made his first start with
cotton stuck in his nose, the remnants of a one-car collision he
was involved in days before the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Perez missed a start in Montreal when he
mysteriously injured his knee. Perez said he hurt it shagging balls
on the hard Olympic Stadium turf, but Malone acknowledged hearing a
story that Perez was injured the night before his start when he
fell and banged his knee during a night on the town.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the infamous scene of Perez repeatedly bashing a
water cooler with a bat in the Dodgers' dugout after a poor outing
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers management also was not happy about Perez swearing near
spectators after making poor pitches during spring training games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed that there is even a hint of something
improper occurred,'' Malone said. ``He needs to show us he's
serious and make a commitment for us to help him return to the form
of old when he was one of the best left-handed pitchers in the
National League. We're there to help him, not only as a pitcher but
as a person, but he's going to have to make a decision this is what
he wants. We're here to help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
