<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000312.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PSI-NET-1STLD-WRITETH     03-12 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSI-NET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: day one.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Schrader reserves his deepest ire, however, for local telephone
incumbents, which he says are monopolists holding back the digital
future. Bashing the Bell companies is hardly unusual among smaller
communications carriers, but Schrader's company must also deal with
the Bells on a daily basis, renting their local communications
lines in order to reach customers.
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly outspoken about Bell Atlantic, the East Coast
giant with which PSINet does a significant amount of business. ``I
call them `Bell Atlantis,''' Schrader said, still dishing as he
drove. ``Bell Atlantis is dead. They cannot exist in tomorrow. We
know the customer better than they do and they can't keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   Why lash out at a such an important supplier?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm honest,'' Schrader said. Referring to Bell
Atlantic's chairman, he said, ``It's not in my best interest to
tell you that Ivan Seidenberg is a poor manager of a
multibillion-dollar company, because they're our major supplier.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for a corporate response, Susan Kraus, a Bell Atlantic
spokeswoman, replied: ``This is not even worth commenting on but
I'll say this. Consider the source. It's hard to take anything he
says seriously. This guy has a long history of making irrational
statements and taking gratuitous potshots at his competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most remarkable aspect of Schrader's blunt style is
that it has not prevented him from garnering the deep respect of
his peers, even those he does not treat gently. As someone who
spoke up for and invested in the Internet early and often, Schrader
is often considered one of the handful of true Internet
visionaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has enormous courage and he's as smart as a fox,'' said
George H. Conrades, chairman of Akamai Technologies Inc. and former
chairman of BBN, one of the big three early independent Internet
companies, along with UUNet and PSINet. ``I admire him,'' Conrades
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sidgmore, of UUNet, also offered a compliment of sorts. ``I'm a
big supporter of Bill's, as wacky as he is,'' Sidgmore said.
``Whatever else you say, good or bad, he is steadfastly committed
to his vision for the company.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sidgmore said, ``I would not be surprised if you read
soon that we will do some investments together.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of all he has built, Schrader has been reluctant
to sell it, despite the hundreds of millions or billions of dollars
such a deal could bring him, considering his personal 7.45 percent
stake in PSINet.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, Internet providers of all size and
description have been snatched up by more traditional
communications companies. UUNet agreed to be acquired by MFS
Communications in 1996 just before MFS itself was acquired by
Worldcom Inc. In 1997, BBN was acquired by GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   That has essentially left PSINet as the last of the Mohicans,
holding out against assimilation with the communications giants.
Deutsche Telekom, for instance, has explored acquiring PSInet, but
those discussions were strictly preliminary. Far more likely
suitors are the new breed of communications carrier in the United
States, companies like Level 3, Qwest, Broadwing and Nextlink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to buy PSINet at least 10 times over the last few
years,'' Sidgmore said. ``Right after MFS bought us we tried to buy
him. I tried after Worldcom. I tried a bunch of times and he would
never sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, it comes down to Schrader being Schrader. ``He
always had the opinion that PSInet is worth 10 times whatever his
stock price is,'' Sidgmore said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that other Internet companies have sold out _ beyond
the financial incentives _ has been their executives' notion that
integrating into a bigger company can give them access to a broader
set of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Wills, PSINet's No. 2 executive, takes a slightly more pragmatic
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some day, they will buy us and we will be sold, and my job is
to make it more expensive for them every day that they wait,''
Wills said. ``What they could have bought for $200 million, they
will now probably have to pay $20 billion for.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Schrader about selling his company _ well, maybe it's better
not to ask. ``Why should I sell the company?'' he said, bristling.
``Tell me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
