   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- March 12, 2000 -- HEADE-PROFILE-2 -- A
Martin Johnson Heade retrospective, at the National Gallery of Art
in Washington through May 7, is the first major survey of his work
in 30 years and only the second ever assembled. ``Approaching
Thunderstorm'' (1859), is among the works in the exhibition.
(Museum of Fine Arts Boston/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 12, 2000 -- HUDSON-VALLEY-INDUSTRY --
Decades after smokestack industries largely disappeared from the
Hudson River valley, leaving behind an environmental and economic
mess that took years to reverse, plans are afoot to build more than
a dozen industrial plants in the region. The St. Lawrence Cement
Company wants to reopen its former barge loading zone on the Hudson
River to serve a proposed new factory. Albert Cook, below, of
Hudson, N.Y., who operated a crane for Atlas Cement in the area for
24 years, says a proposed new factory in the area would hurt the
town's tourism. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
