   (NYT9) DUNEDIN, Fla. -- March 12, 2000 --
YANKS-SPRINGTRAINING-FLOATER -- The World Champion New York Yankees
during batting practice in Dundein, Fla., before a game against the
Toronto Blue Jays, Sunday. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DUNEDIN, Fla. -- March 12, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-PITCHING --
The Yankees' winter theory was that they could afford to trade
Ramiro Mendoza because they have enough pitching talent to replace
him. But after a month of spring training, the Yankees have
ascertained they that they do not have as much depth as they first
thought. No candidate to replace Mendoza in relief has developed so
far. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 12, 2000 -- NY-THEATERS -- In the late
1970s when Times Square belonged to the prostitutes and peep shows,
a collection of theater companies moved into a handful of stages
carved out of shuttered massage parlors on West 42nd Street. Now,
the local development corporation that helped create the strip now
known as Theater Row is closing four of the playhouses as it
prepares to break ground on an apartment tower and collection of
new stages on West 42nd Street. Performers of the show
``Countless'': Anita Keal, left, Jy Murphy, center standing, and
Mike Finesilver, center, sitting, during a break in the backyard of
the Samuel Beckett Theatre. The theater is scheduled to be closed
soon to make way for a redevelopment project in Times Square.
(Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- March 12, 2000 -- REAL-SIMPLE-MEDIA -- Real
Simple, a new magazine, is ``about streamlining, refining and
distilling your life to the essence of what pleases you.'' Susan
Wyland, managing editor, and publisher Alexander Sareyan of Time
Inc., with displays of Real Simple. The magazine is a hybrid,
combining the lifestyle approach of Martha Stewart Living, the
common-sense housekeeping guidelines of Good Housekeeping, the
shopping opportunities of In Style and and the Internet service
articles of PC Magazine. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
