<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4857 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     03-12 1602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYWEATHER'S TOUGHEST FOE _ HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Only a few years ago, the boxing world was as
excited about the future of immensely talented Floyd Mayweather Jr.
as that of any other young fighter. Today, many would like to see
him get his head knocked off.
</P>
<P>
   What changed? Floyd Mayweather Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those close to the WBC super featherweight champion will
point to two decisions he made and shake their heads: His rejection
of a multi-million-dollar contract offer from HBO - which he called
``slave wages'' - and the hiring of rap promoter Jay Prince to
replace his father/trainer, Floyd Sr., as his manager. The latter
is part of what has caused a heavyweight feud in one of boxing's
first families.
</P>
<P>
   Mayweather, 23, counters by saying he's a grown man and is only
trying to make the right business decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever is most accurate, a once-happy camp is now in turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   `'He's out of control,'' said Jeff Mayweather, Floyd Jr.'s uncle
and former member of his team.
</P>
<P>
   The boxing world was disgusted when Mayweather turned down a
six-fight, $11.5 million contract extension with HBO, which
would've made him one of the highest-paid fighters in the world,
and his use of the term ``slave wages'' certainly cost him fans.
</P>
<P>
   Things got so bad at one point that HBO officials refused to
speak with him.
</P>
<P>
   The offer remains on the table but Mayweather - whose title
defense against Goyo Vargas on Saturday is his last under contract
- has yet to accept it and won't say whether he plans to do so.
He'll leave that up to Prince.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mayweather did defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   He insists he was misquoted. He claims he said something along
the lines of, ``Compared to Prince (Naseem) Hamed's contract, this
is a slave contract'' and doesn't regret saying it. He simply
believes he should be paid the kind of money earned by the likes of
Hamed, Roy Jones Jr. and Oscar De La Hoya, and he is not inclined
to accept anything less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm up there with those guys,'' he said. ``I feel I should get
closer to what they get.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I was seen as a good guy when I did everything everyone
asked. Then, when I didn't want to accept the contract, I'm a bad
guy. It doesn't even bother me. I feel good about my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he shouldn't earn the same as Hamed and Co.
Mayweather, while as talented as anyone, does not have the drawing
power of any of the above. At least, not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are Jay Prince will have Mayweather fix the immediate
problem by accepting HBO's offer and continuing to build his name
by winning fights in spectacular fashion. Normally, that's how it's
done in this business.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he can fix the damage done to his personal relationships
is another story.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Mayweather, a former fighter who worked in tandem with
Floyd Sr. guiding Floyd Jr.'s career, took the biggest hit: He was
fired by his nephew and now the two barely speak.
</P>
<P>
   The result, Jeff said, is a rift between the fighter and several
members of his extended family that might never be rectified.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's burned so many bridges,'' Jeff said. ``He's turned
everyone off, everyone in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Jr. said he realized that his uncle doesn't have the
expertise to handle his business affairs and asked himself: Why am
I paying this guy? He also claims that Jeff stole money from him,
an accusation his uncle denies.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Sr., who remains as trainer, seems to be the most hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Mayweather said his nephew and brother ``no longer have a
father-and-son relationship. It's strictly business now.'' That
might be an exaggeration but there's some truth to it.
</P>
<P>
   That's sad. The former fighter had to watch from prison as his
son fought in the 1996 Olympics but was released in time to take
over his son' training early in his professional career. The two
comprised a winning and vibrant team and seemed to be tight.
</P>
<P>
   Then Floyd Jr. refused the HBO offer - against his father's
advice - and Hamed has been criticized for lack of legitimate
competition. And while Bungu is a good fighter, he moved up in
weight to fight Hamed and certainly isn't in the class of an Erik
Morales, the type of opponent Hamed must beat if he hopes to lure
back the fans he has alienated....
</P>
<P>
   Floyd senior refused to comment in detail. But it's clear he
feels he was betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone has done something wrong to an individual, I feel
that person should apologize,'' he said. ``Sometimes apologies do
mend things, sometimes you can be forgiven for things.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on: ``I'm a true believer in God and there is one thing
I'm sure about: You gotta be good to your parents. That's the way
life is.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Jr. has no regrets about letting his uncle go. However, he
is committed to his father and tried to explain hsi position.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Price, the successful founder of Rap-A-Lot Records in
Houston, because he wanted a businessman with a track record to
handle his money. In a way, he feels his team failed him because
they did not stay behind him when it came time to make a tough
decision.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, he wants his father to remain at his
side as trainer - assuming that's what Floyd Sr. also wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my father,'' said Floyd Jr. ``And he's the best trainer
in the world, he really is. If he doesn't want to train me, he can
go. It's not like I have handcuffs on him. If he is not happy, he
should leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, if my dad left me it would hurt me, it would
take a piece of my heart. Everyone else can leave but not my dad.
If it takes stress off him, then that's what he should do.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Sr. won't say what he plans to do. He only hinted that the
difficult situation will be rectified soon without providing
details.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's the trainer of one of the most talented fighters
in the world and will make a very good living as long as he remains
with him. He earns 10 percent of his son's purses, as he has all
along, while Prince claims 20 percent (Jeff received three
percent).
</P>
<P>
   However, Floyd Sr. made it clear that no matter what happens
he'll always love his son and want the best for him - even when he
makes mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it can be very, very costly to an individual who
doesn't listen to those close to him, to those who live him,'' he
said. ``But Floyd's a very good man now and I'm his father. I'll be
his father until the day one of us dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Jr. swears he is content. He believes in Prince and is as
confident as ever in his son's ability. He even sees a silver
lining in all that surrounds him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, controversy sells,''aid Floyd Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there's plenty of that.
</P>
<P>
   Staples deal off: The fact that Staples Center and Arum have
agreed to share the cost if the state refuses to cap its live-gate
tax at $50,000 for the tentative De La Hoya-Shane Mosley fight on
June 17 was predictable.
</P>
<P>
   What's an estimated $350,000 among friends when all parties
stand to make much, much more?
</P>
<P>
   However, it's the long term that concerns both parties. State
officials probably will have to agree to the cap - as opposed to 5
percent of the gate - if California is going to compete against New
York and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   And why shouldn't the cap be implemented? Money generated by
big- money fights will cover any loss as a result of the cap. It's
as simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it will be interesting to see exactly how big
this fight will be.
</P>
<P>
   The seating capacity at the new arena will be 19,000-plus. It's
difficult to imagine a sellout even with an expected marketing
blitz: Boxing, even at this level, remains a difficult sell despite
the fact few sports can match its electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers will be surprised if the paid crowd exceeds
15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Lou Savarase, set to fight Mike Tyson on May 20
in Milan, Italy, has little chance of beating the former two-time
world champion.
</P>
<P>
   However, he's a legitimate fighter. That could not be said for
Tyson's last opponent, Julius Francis, who can hardly box.
</P>
<P>
   Savarase isn't a great test for Tyson - but he is a test....
</P>
<P>
   Hamed announced before his bout with Vuyani Bungu that we would
see a more focused, more business-like fighter and he proceeded to
knock out the South African in four rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed has been criticized for lack of legitimate competition.
And while Bungu is a good fighter, he moved up in weight to fight
Hamed and certainly is not in the class of an Erik Morales, the
type of opponent Hamed must beat if he hopes to lure back the fans
he has alienated....
</P>
<P>
   Arturo Gatti, whose brutal knockout of Joey Gamache on Feb. 26
in New York pumped added life into his career, is scheduled to
fight on the undercard of the Lennox Lewis-Michael Grant fight on
April 29 in New York. His opponent has yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Camache, 33, has the reputation as one of the smartest people
ever to lace up gloves, and he demonstrated why last week - by
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Camache was lucky to survive the Gatti fight without serious
injuries and he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky I'm not dead,'' he said. ``When you get that close,
it's a sign from God that it's time to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Camache will make a fine television analyst....
</P>
<P>
   Diego Corales defends his IBF junior lightweight title against
slick Derrick Gainer on the undercard of the Mayweather-Vargas
fight....
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Lopez reportedly is training in Las Vegas and is
trying to break his contract with Main Events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
