<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MOZAMBIQUE-NYT &LR;      03-12 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MOZAMBIQUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE TRIBULATIONS OF MOZAMBIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, March 13:
</P>
<P>
   The floodwaters in Mozambique have subsided, but the need to
provide for the victims is by no means diminished. The United
States and other wealthy nations should be generous in providing
aid. Nearly a million of Mozambique's 17 million people have lost
their homes, farms or food supplies. The official death toll of 400
is expected to rise into the thousands. Tens of thousands of
villagers have fled their homes for the safety of high ground. The
United Nations says 250,000 Mozambicans are now living in makeshift
camps, and another 250,000 remain in ruined villages around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The most urgent immediate needs are food, tents, medicine and
plastic sheeting and blankets. The U.N. estimates that a third of
the country's corn, the staple crop, has been destroyed. More than
40,000 head of cattle have drowned, and 141 schools have been
obliterated.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term economic consequences could be devastating for a
country that is still struggling to rebuild from a 16-year civil
war that ended in 1992. Mozambique remains one of the poorest
countries in the world, with a per capita annual income of barely
$150. But it had made impressive gains in recent years. The
government of Joaquim Chissano had embraced economic reform,
encouraging foreign investment, increasing exports and boosting
economic growth to close to 10 percent a year, one of the highest
rates in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But flood damage could reduce the country's domestic product by
as much as a third. After the first floods in early February, the
government and the United Nations issued an urgent appeal for $65
million in foreign aid. They are expected to double or even triple
that request in the coming weeks. So far, foreign donors have
pledged more than $100 million. Debt relief would also help.
Washington has said that it will forgive Mozambique's remaining
debt. Britain, Italy, Spain and Portugal will do the same. The
World Bank has accelerated its debt relief program and diverted
money from long-term infrastructure to emergency road-building.
These are welcome expressions of support for a country that could
take years to recover from this disaster.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-00 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
