<SLUG> BC-BK-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JARVIS EMBARKING ON A SPIRITUAL JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Jarvis passed through a thick, noisy crowd of
well-wishers Sunday evening as he led his St. John's players to
their seats, from where they would watch the traditional National
Collegiate Athletic Association men's basketball selection show.
Jarvis made his way through clusters packed three- and four-deep at
the ESPN Zone on Times Square, the place sizzling with the
electricity of college basketball in March. The well-wishers
hollered, ``Congratulations, Coach,'' ``Way to go, Mike,'' and
``Good job, Coach.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city dominated by professional sports and professional
sports issues _ hirings, firings, trades _ St. John's for the
second straight season has managed to ignite a passion for college
basketball. Jarvis, a coach some wondered about and grumbled about,
is quickly winning. In this city, winning takes off the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very good about coming to New York before we ever
played a game,'' Jarvis said. ``I felt that there were a lot of
people who were very excited about us being here. What they told me
was that they would judge me as much on how our team played as much
as how our team won.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there are a lot of people who are excited about how
you perform. They love the underdog; we're going to have to find a
way to remain the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``New Yorkers say, `Great job, Coach,' but they always
end it with `this year' or `so far.' But that's New York and I love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis is the architect of a toughness that allowed St. John's
to defeat Duke at Duke last month, then beat Connecticut, the
defending national champion, not once, not twice, but three times.
At George Washington, where he was forced to recruit foreign
players, Jarvis said his greatest challenge, ``was getting players
to understand me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tough,'' Jarvis said, ``but what I want to emphasize is
that we're mentally tough. What I look for, are players who have
not just won all their lives, but who have been through some type
of adversity and who have found a way to come through it.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's discovered it was going West. To Tucson, Ariz., as
the second-seeded team, the highest seeding it had received since
1985, when St. John's was placed first in the West and wound up
reaching the Final Four. Still, Jarvis would not call this his most
satisfying season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly been one of the most interesting years,'' he
said. ``But it's really too early. We're still on a journey. I
don't know where it's going to take us. I'm just enjoying the
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Erick Barkley arrived late Sunday and sat by himself on a sofa
away from the team. For the past month, Barkley has been the target
of a National Collegiate Athletic Association investigation into
activities including the administration of his Scholastic
Assessment Test before he enrolled at St. John's, as well as other
perceived special benefits. The pressure became so intense that
Barkley stunned his team and the administration by announcing
Friday night that he was leaving the team.
</P>
<P>
   He returned Saturday night and had brilliant game as St. John's
beat Connecticut for the Big East title. This is Barkley's second
season under Jarvis. He said the difference between the first and
second seasons has been miniscule.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still wants you to run the offense to perfection,'' Barkley
said. ``He runs a pro offense, but over all if you follow his rules
you don't have anything to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's has six games left to win, beginning Thursday against
15th-seeded Northern Arizona. This gets to the heart of a story
that has been lost beneath the drama of the season: the precise
teachings of Mike Jarvis. Last season St. John's was a turnover
from reaching the Final Four. Last season, St. John's had more
weapons: every player could take the opposition off the dribble.
This season passing has had to be crisper. The passing is
exquisite. The team runs, pushes the tempo, forces the pace and
does it with an iron-man rotation of seven players. Is this enough
to advance?
</P>
<P>
   St. John's has not reached the Final Four since 1985. In some
ways the NCAA's worst nightmare might be for the Red Storm to
advance. In each successive tournament game, Barkley could become,
if not a more sympathetic figure, a lightning rod to discuss the
merits of NCAA regulations, the intensity and intent of
enforcement. Everyone knows about Barkley; let's find out about the
enforcement officers who are going after him.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA needs to be exposed. Who orders the investigations?
Through what prisms does the NCAA filter its investigations? An
entire tournament is needed to ferret it out. Let's play the
investigation game on an open court.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis is not sure that he wants to carry a campaign through the
tournament. He would prefer to concentrate on basketball. ``But I
probably won't have that option,'' he said. ``That could be a
positive and a negative.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been rumored for several NBA head-coaching jobs. He has
only reiterated that he keeps all options open. At heart he says he
is an educator. A college coach.
</P>
<P>
   On his way through the crowd Sunday evening, a man whispered to
a friend: ``Next year this time he's going to be in the NBA.'' When
told of the exchange that some might consider a compliment, Jarvis
only smiled. ``To some people it might be,'' he said, and he left
it at that. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
