<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN SNOW BIRDS TRY NEW SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MAUREEN WEST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Canadian snowbirds always come back to Arizona like
swallows returning to Capistrano.
</P>
<P>
   Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   The slow business in Phoenix's East Valley winter visitor RV
parks this year is blamed in part on the change in the migratory
pattern of Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   Some are traveling past Arizona to newer and cheaper places in
Mexico while others are staying in Canada and migrating to British
Columbia, where the weather is moderate, Canadians remain covered
by Canada's public health-care system and there's no devaluation of
currency as occurs across the U.S. line.
</P>
<P>
   Small British Columbia communities are even considering building
RV parks, according to Doug Gray of Vancouver, British Columbia, an
author and lawyer considered the foremost authority on Canadian
snowbird patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``While western Canadians would prefer to winter in Arizona, an
increasing number can't because of medical-insurance problems,''
Gray said during a visit to Apache Junction this month. ``That's a
bigger problem to many people than the poor exchange rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, when Gray publishes his fourth edition of his
Canadian bestseller The Canadian Snowbird Guide, it will include a
chapter on snowbirding in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver Island and Vancouver's Fraser Valley have moderate
climates and plentiful campgrounds. Informal winter retirement
communities are emerging there.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 15 to 20 percent of Arizona's 300,000 snowbirds
normally come from Canada. But the numbers have been down the past
few years. Canadians who stay away from home for more than six
months a year lose their health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of money is at stake between competing retirement
regions, Gray said, explaining that the aging population is growing
at a faster rate in Canada than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   By 2026, according to Canadian government statistics, 7 million
people, or 18 percent of the Canadian population, will be 65 or
older, compared with 16 percent of Americans. By 2041, Canada will
have 10 million seniors, making up 23 percent of the population. As
in the United States, they are far healthier and more active than
previous retirees.
</P>
<P>
   There is a multiplier effect that increases the value of winter
visitors, according to Gray. He cites a study showing that the
average Canadian snowbird hosts additional visitors, for an average
of 49 days during their seasonal stay. ``Those are a lot of tourist
dollars for the communities where they land,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Canadians love Arizona and all their friends here and will
be loyal, although many will shorten their traditional six-month
stay here by half, according to Gray. Many East Valley RV park
owners say they have noticed that trend over the past two years,
with some Canadians arriving later and leaving earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there are about 55 companies offering
health-insurance policies, some older Canadians can't purchase them
because of pre-existing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The current edition of Gray's book has information on part-time
living in Mexico, which is becoming increasingly popular with
younger Canadians. Costa Rica also has appeal to some Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   Younger retirees are also being lured to Mexico by airlines
offering cheap packages, said Gray. In January, one round-trip
flight from Canada was advertised for $150. Mexico's rich culture
and cheap rent also are attracting some Canadians. About 95 percent
of Canadians visiting Mexico are 45 and older and have not yet
tried Arizona or other U.S. winter destinations, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians Guy Couture, 57, and his 56-year-old wife, Tharcycle,
of Quebec, who spent six weeks, including a few weeks in Arizona,
on the road in a small van this year, are planning a trip to Mexico
next winter.
</P>
<P>
   Al and Pat Lynch of British Columbia regularly return to Mesa
for the winter, but each year they have to weigh the costs of food
and rent, which have become more expensive over the past seven
winters here.
</P>
<P>
   As do other repeat visitors from Canada, they make the decision
about whether to come back one season at a time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Maureen &QL; 
.West(at)ArizonaRepublic.com &QL; 
or (602) 444-8167. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mexico and cities in British Columbia have their eyes on attracting
Canadian winter visitors who in the past have stayed for months at
a time in sunny Arizona. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
