<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-SOUTHERN-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI SOUTHERN STATE COLLEGE ADOPTS INTERNATIONAL ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOPLIN, Mo. _ When Missouri Southern State College's president
told people in the early 1990s that the college was adopting an
``international mission,'' many thought it could never happen.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``cosmopolitan'' didn't come to mind to describe this
former junior college in a southwest Missouri city better known for
its two dozen trucking firms.
</P>
<P>
   But on the campus, evidence abounds that the college has
embraced the world.
</P>
<P>
   In one classroom, a video camera, television screen and
satellite connection let French-language students talk to a group
of English-language students at a university in Orleans, France.
They debate topics from movies to the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In another class, Terry Marion lectures onways a human resources
manager can help employees adjust to living in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   In the office of Chad Stebbins, who heads the Institute of
International Studies, masks he bought while traveling in Africa
adorn the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Students swap tales of time spent studying or working in
countries such as Austria, Mexico, and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Many colleges offer students a chance to study abroad, learn
foreign languages and take classes in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But at Missouri Southern, which has about 5,500 students,
thinking globally is a mission that permeates the campus, rather
than being an isolated program.
</P>
<P>
   Campus leaders say the international mission prepares students
for work at companies that are increasingly multinational.
</P>
<P>
   John Wittstruck, Missouri's deputy commissioner for higher
education, remembers the early skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't seem to fit. (Becoming) a center of excellence
in the transportation industry _ trucking _ made more sense,'' he
said. ``But I think they really have made believers out of some of
the skeptics. If one were to ask why an international mission at
Missouri Southern, one would come back with, `Why not?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Opening students and professors to the world is the goal of the
new international focus.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of them have begun going overseas to study everything
from art and biology to music and journalism. Students can major in
international studies and international business, or learn to speak
Russian or Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Campus visits by global notables such as former Costa Rica
President Oscar Arias and the Zambian Boys Choir have lent an
international flair to Joplin, a place where, for many, New York
and Los Angeles were once considered exotic.
</P>
<P>
   At Southern, located near the junction of Kansas, Missouri,
Oklahoma and Arkansas, more than 9 in 10 students are white, most
of them from small to medium-sized towns in the area. Graduates
usually have stayed around Joplin as teachers or nurses,
journalists or business people.
</P>
<P>
   Now, students who have studied abroad think it's natural to want
to work in Chicago or San Francisco, maybe even Madrid or Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Business has become more global, even in this corner of
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Leggett &AMP; Platt Inc., a bedding components manufacturer in
nearby Carthage, has plants in Belgium, Germany, Sweden, China and
other countries. Several area firms recently were bought by
international conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world's a much smaller place than it used to be and the
Internet has made it smaller,'' said John Hale, Leggett &AMP; Platt's
vice president for human resources. ``Southern was early among
smaller colleges in undertaking an international mission and was
very wise to have done it.''  &LR; brk:Quiet change  &LR; tx:The
international mission began slowly and quietly in the early 1990s
under the leadership of President Julio Leon.
</P>
<P>
   Leon, a native of Chile who is of Chinese descent, arrived at
Southern 31 years ago to teach business classes. He earned a
doctorate at the University of Arkansas-Fayetteville, and later
became dean of Southern's business school. He began his term as
president in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   During his time on campus and in Joplin, Leon came to believe
that Southern's students and professors could benefit from
understanding more of the world than what they could reach in their
car.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted students and professors to know the world, not just
through words in a textbook, but in the sights, smells and sounds
of an open-air market in San Jose, Costa Rica, or a Hong Kong
street crammed with cars, pedestrians and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
