r a BC-MISSOURI-SOUTHERN-2ND     03-12 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-SOUTHERN-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI SOUTHERN STATE COLLEGE ADOPTS INTERNATIONAL ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... pedestrians and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our students tend to be a little provincial in their
views. Some of them have never been out of the county, let alone
the country,'' Leon said. ``When they travel they have to get a
passport, cross the ocean, deal with different languages. When
these students return, they are transformed in the way they see
themselves. Their horizons are expanded.''
</P>
<P>
   About 100 students go abroad each year, some for weeklong
conferences, others for a semester or year or to study or intern
for a company.
</P>
<P>
   The move to an international mission began when a handful of
students went abroad and a few professors introduced international
content to their classes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Missouri Coordinating Board for Higher Education
began ``mission review,'' which required Missouri's public colleges
to choose a mission. Board members wanted the state's public
colleges to differentiate themselves from each other and to focus
their efforts, not try to be all things to all people.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri General Assembly decided to give colleges money to
enhance those missions. Many colleges chose missions that reflected
the strengths they had had for years. For example, the University
of Missouri's four campuses wanted to strengthen graduate programs
and the life and health sciences.
</P>
<P>
   But Southern decided to stretch. It has received almost $6
million over the past five years in mission enhancement money, and
uses about $300,000 each year to send students abroad, and almost
$100,000 to send professors abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international mission has put us on the map and made us a
player around the state,'' said Stebbins, a Joplin native. ``(Other
colleges) are doing more of what they did before. We're doing
something completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   In the words of one graduate: it practically ``defies logic''
that his alma mater has successfully adopted a cosmopolitan
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   There have been obstacles along Southern's path toward being a
global campus. Many people on campus and in the community were
suspicious of the change. Some still are.
</P>
<P>
   People have questioned whether the school really needs to focus
on what's happening in Hong Kong or Africa. Who cares, they ask,
how England educates its kids or Mexico handles environmental
problems?
</P>
<P>
   Some area residents heard ``international mission'' and
envisioned a flood of foreign students taking classroom spots from
local kids.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what the mission is about.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly more foreign students study in Joplin now, but the
number still is minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the international focus lets students and professors
experience the world themselves, with many overseas trips paid for
by the college. Similar programs at most colleges help students
find private scholarships to go overseas, but don't pay for the
trips.
</P>
<P>
   And the international mission lets Southern students debate
important issues in other nations that have a ripple effect
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier, people would say, `Why an international mission? Kids
grow up in southwest Missouri. They go to school here, work here
and die here,' '' said Richard Massa, a southwest Missouri native
who began the school's Institute of International Studies in 1996.
``But my response is, `Your children deserve the very best
education possible.' ''  &LR; brk:Different attitude  &LR; tx:As a member of
the college's governing board, alum Steve Carlton endorses the
change. When he was a student, ``the big thing was a trip (to
Bolivar, Mo.) to play Southwest Baptist in baseball. Going to
college was a big deal, let alone Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not true for today's students.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Rogers graduated in December and now edits /{The Carthage
Press./} The highlight of his time at Southern was a three-week
trip to Hong Kong and China. He and another student worked side by
side with journalists from around the world covering Britain's
handover of Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get the impression the Chinese are reserved and serious,
but I got to see more sides of the Chinese people,'' Rogers
recalls. ``We went to the Guangzhou zoo. We were the main
attraction. Everybody was following us around. They are enamored of
the American culture, but I hadn't realized that before.''
</P>
<P>
   The college also has worked to share its new identity with
people off campus.
</P>
<P>
   Southern students teach after-school classes in Spanish and
Russian at area elementary schools. Joplin area residents attend
the school's annual International Piano Competition and campus
performances by international cultural groups. The college offers
an International Trade and Quality Center as a resource for local
businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
   But the mission's primary goal is to mold Southern students into
world-ready young people who understand themselves and others.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny Andrews, a mass communication major, traveled to Germany
on a fellowship and to Croatia for an international journalism
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel extremely well equipped,'' she said. ``It's a great
college, but on top of that, their dedication to the international
mission has really enhanced my education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
