<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4872 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-GOLDEN-DOLLAR-KAN &LR;      03-12 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-DOLLAR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T WORRY, THOSE NEW GOLDEN DOLLARS ARE COMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 EDWARD M. EVELD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Those new golden dollars, the ones featuring
Indian guide Sacagawea, seem to have vanished as quickly as they
appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Have they already gone the way of the ill-fated Susan B. Anthony
dollar?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. In fact, people gobbled up the first 200 million so fast
that the folks at the U.S. Mint wished they had twice as many for
the first distribution. Hey, 200 million (BEGIN ITALICS)seemed(END
ITALICS) like a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The mint shipped 100 million to the Federal Reserve, which
distributed them to banks, and 100 million to Wal-Mart stores,
where they landed in their cash registers. The nationwide shipment
got under way at the end of January.
</P>
<P>
   Some area Wal-Mart stores are still making change with the new
dollars, but don't be surprised if bank tellers and checkout clerks
have trouble coming up with one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a shortage because of the surprising demand,'' said
Diane Raley at the Federal Reserve Bank in Kansas City. ``We will
eventually catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael White at the U.S. Mint in Washington hopes to be caught
up by the end of March. The Philadelphia mint is cranking them out
at high speed, he said, and the Denver mint will join in soon.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Commerce Bank got an initial shipment of 2,000 and UMB
Bank received 4,000, not enough to keep up with requests.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who got some of the first batch of coins held onto
them as collector's items _ a typical reaction to a new coin, White
said. But soon there will be enough in circulation that consumers
will use them like the rest of their coins, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks the new dollars shouldn't be so scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we hit the 14-week mark of production, about mid-April,
we expect to be up around 500 million coins,'' said White. ``It
took the Susan B. Anthony coin 14 years to get to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the mint, in fact, like to talk about how different
the new dollar is from the Susan B. Anthony, a coin that never
caught on in part because it looked and felt too much like a
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The chief difference, of course, is the new coin is golden,
although not actually gold. It is manganese brass, a mixture of
copper, zinc, manganese and nickel.
</P>
<P>
   The new coin is the same size as the Susan B. Anthony, but it
has an extra-wide border and a smooth edge like a nickel, rather
than a reeded edge. And through the miracle of electromagnetic
properties, says the mint, vending machines that recognized the
Susan B. Anthony as a dollar coin also will recognize the new
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   While the coin has gotten some good reviews, it wasn't launched
without controversy. Some retailers didn't appreciate the mint's
idea to get the coin to consumers quickly by selling them to
Wal-Mart. Plenty of small store owners already struggle against
Wal-Mart competition.
</P>
<P>
   And some banks complained that Wal-Mart got the coins before
they did, although the mint maintains the coins were shipped at the
same time. Some smaller community banks complained they were
shortchanged in the distribution, and the mint recently launched a
new distribution directly to them.
</P>
<P>
   Many have applauded the choice of Sacagawea as the image on the
new coin. Sacagawea was the Shoshone interpreter who accompanied
Lewis and Clark on their expedition west between 1804 and 1806.
Interestingly, she seems to peer directly at the holder.
</P>
<P>
   But a small brouhaha arose over the way Sacagawea is pictured
carrying her baby. Sacagawea gave birth to a son, Jean Baptiste, on
the trip and would likely have placed him on a cradleboard, facing
backward, according to Shoshone custom. But the image shows the
baby facing forward, wrapped in a pouch on her back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically there was a little artistic license there,'' said
White.
</P>
<P>
   With such a small image, it would have been difficult to picture
the baby on a cradleboard. And the mint checked with Shoshone
representatives and historians who said that it was possible that
as a matter of convenience at times Sacagawea would have wrapped
the baby and carried him on her back as depicted.
</P>
<P>
   For the success of the coin itself, the question remains whether
Americans will take to it in everyday transactions. Some people are
skeptical, especially as long as the dollar bill is around.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be a plot to do away with the $1 denomination in
paper money?
</P>
<P>
   In a recent speech to the National Press Club in Washington,
Philip N. Diehl, director of the U.S. Mint, said there were no
plans to retire the dollar bill. The new coin, so long in coming,
he said, was a response to a market demand for a new dollar coin,
especially in the vending industry.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers in the next few months will decide if Diehl was
correct in calling the response to the coin a ``grand slam home
run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
