<HEADER>
A4873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT &LR;      03-12 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' comments about life in the
Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to New Orleans, I was boarding a tour bus when
the guide asked everyone his or her place of origin. There were
visitors from Tennessee, Oklahoma, California, France, Italy and
Germany, and the guide's reply was always the same: ``How nice!
Welcome to New Orleans!'' When he came to me, I answered ``New
York.'' ``Welcome to America,'' he replied. Are we really viewed as
that different?
</P>
<P>
   _ DALIA LIEBERSOHN
</P>
<P>
   When she returned from Paris recently, Susan Rappaport brought
two charming and basic French books for Alexandra Hall, her
5-year-old granddaughter. She explained that Alex might enjoy
beginning to learn French now, in preparation for future visits.
Alex listened attentively and then placed her hands firmly on her
hips. ``Thanks for the books, but I can't learn French,'' she said.
``Listen, I don't even know all the words in New York City yet.''
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make one wonder, according to Norman I. Reisman.
He was among the crowd on the subway platform waiting to push onto
the uptown local at Lexington Avenue and 59th Street when the
following announcement came over the loudspeaker: ``Please step
fully into the train and watch the closing doors. There really is
another train right behind this one.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTHING IS FOREVER
</P>
<P>
   Still winter's captive.
</P>
<P>
   After repeated flurries
</P>
<P>
   Of deep standing snow
</P>
<P>
   And howling winds
</P>
<P>
   That threaten to upend and transport me
</P>
<P>
   Whereas I would not go.
</P>
<P>
   I hear a gentle voice
</P>
<P>
   Saying ``nice day is it not?''
</P>
<P>
   I feel a tickle at my heart
</P>
<P>
   That turns into a titter
</P>
<P>
   And then a laugh that roars
</P>
<P>
   Until I imagine I have encircled the globe
</P>
<P>
   And everybody is out dancing
</P>
<P>
   And clapping their hands with glee
</P>
<P>
   To welcome a sunny day at last.
</P>
<P>
   _ ISIDORE ELFMAN
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I was driving on the Upper East Side when a pedestrian pointed
to my front wheel, indicating something was wrong. I pulled up next
to the curb. He bent over, examined the tire and asked me to pull
up about a foot and then back up so he could show me what had
caused the flat tire.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing that I was annoyed at the prospect of changing the tire,
he offered to give me a hand. By pure good luck, he had a plug and
the glue necessary to fix it. He quickly yanked out the sharp screw
that had caused the damage, inserted the plug and in two minutes
had executed a perfect repair. I offered him $5 but he said he
wanted $15. I gave him $10, but felt he had earned the money.
</P>
<P>
   On my way home, I pulled into a gas station to check the tire
pressure. As the attendant checked the tires, I recounted my story.
</P>
<P>
   He roared with laughter. ``I told Charlie to cut that stuff out.
He'll ruin the neighborhood reputation,'' he said. Of course, what
Charlie did when he bent over was to place a screw on the road and
ask me to rock the car back and forth until I had given myself a
flat tire.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Charlie doesn't feel he's ready to give up his repair
work. Soon after, he did the same thing to a good friend of mine,
but was paid twice since he was able to put two holes in the tire.
</P>
<P>
   _ JAMES M. STEWART
</P>
<P>
   Harold R. Rainin and his grandson Robbie were crossing a parking
lot to a Manhattan restaurant when it began raining. One of the
members of a group leaving the restaurant commented, ``Look, it's
rainin'.'' Robbie looked up at his grandfather. ``Pop, does
everyone know you?'' he asked. Rainin didn't affirm or deny, he
just fudged. ``Not quite,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thelma Mielke recently recalled an unusual encounter with a
woman visiting from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mielke was across from Saks Fifth Avenue, trying to hail a taxi.
As she raised her arm, she felt a foreign object in her right hand
and without even looking at it, flung it into the street. The next
thing she knew, a man was yelling, ``For God's sake, get out of the
street'' as he pulled a woman back to the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic light changed and the man ran into the road himself
and retrieved a woman's wig. It was the foreign object Mielke had
tossed away. She had swept it off the woman's head with the curled
finger of her upraised, taxi-hailing arm.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Going online is perfectly fine
</P>
<P>
   When you need to search for stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But have a care, for hackers are there,
</P>
<P>
   And surfing is sometimes rough.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps your fate is discovering too late
</P>
<P>
   An occasional crash is the norm,
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo!'' you say, and maybe ``eBay!''
</P>
<P>
   It's the dot-com before the storm.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERT H. NUTT &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Kim Corcoran recently spotted this sign in an East Village
delicatessen:
</P>
<P>
   ``LOST CHIHUAHUA
</P>
<P>
   REWARD
</P>
<P>
   Name: Walter (also answers to Don't You Ever Shut Up!)
</P>
<P>
   This is a horrible, horrible dog who will make your life a
living hell. Bring him back so I can beat him and give you money.''
</P>
<P>
   A man in a crowded subway car going uptown managed to extricate
his large saxophone from its case. He then proceeded to play very
loudly and not very well, drowning out even the usual screeching
and creaking. ``Blissfully he then stopped,'' said the Rev. Roger
John Callan, who was among the passengers, but it was only to
announce to his captive audience that, for a small fee, he would
play no more. Callan reported that the nearby passengers
contributed to the ransom with enthusiasm. Silence prevailed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
