<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNICKS STAND TALL AGAINST THE SPURS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston sneered right back
at their demons Sunday night by attacking their fears. Instead of
flinching at the sight of Tim Duncan and David Robinson, they began
the game by smartly driving right under the chins of San Antonio's
exceptional big men.
</P>
<P>
   They used reverse layups and backdoor cuts and devised a detour
system around the wingspan of Duncan and Robinson. In the process,
they left the looming duo that devastated them in the finals last
June in foul trouble. With a little help from the Knicks' missing
piece in that championship series _ Patrick Ewing _ they barged
their way to a 93-80 confidence builder at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   It did not make up for the last time the Spurs were at the
Garden, when they danced around after winning the league
championship, but it helped soothe any anxiety the Knicks may have
had about whether they could compete against Robinson and Duncan if
they meet again.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' star trio dominated. Sprewell ended with 24 points,
Houston scored 20 and Ewing had 21 points and 15 rebounds. Held
down by Larry Johnson, Duncan scored just 15 points, while Robinson
added 22. The Knicks held the Spurs to 38.6 percent shooting from
the field and shot 48.6 percent themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' hold on this game slipped just a bit in the opening
four minutes of the fourth quarter, when the Spurs cut a 17-point
third-quarter deficit to 9 points after Duncan's hook shot over
Kurt Thomas. But the Knicks did not repeat their pattern of coming
unglued under pressure this season and fought back with some smart
defense to take the ball out of Duncan's hands. A 3-pointer by
Johnson with 6 minutes 53 seconds left put his team back up, 87-73.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few nervous moments when the Spurs cut the Knicks'
lead to 89-80 with two minutes left. But the attack theme
prevailed. After a miss by Robinson, Chris Childs scored on a
driving layup with 1:23 remaining to increase the margin to 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs were not the dominating force they were the last time
they came to the Garden. A month later, Sean Elliott had a kidney
transplant. That he was sitting on the bench in a suit Sunday
night, awaiting the green light to play again, was a medical
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs were also without the injured Terry Porter. But they
did have Duncan and Robinson to torture the Knicks. Last June, they
devastated the Knicks in the paint, coming up with points and
blocked shots. By the end of the finals, the Knicks were flinching
as they drove the lane and helpless to defend against the bank-shot
artist, Duncan. In January, it was the same.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Knicks took a different approach. Instead of
shying from contact, they reveled in it as Sprewell and Houston
drove inside, using their bodies and reverse layups to avoid having
their shots blocked. In the process, they also drew fouls on
Robinson and Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter was a blueprint followed to perfection.
Johnson played physically on Duncan _ and was aided by a few double
teams _ to hold him to 1-for-7 shooting. On offense, the Knicks
worked the ball inside and ended the first quarter going to the
free-throw line on their final five possessions to take a 34-22
lead.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Knicks went into a lull. Once again, as soon as
Coach Jeff Van Gundy began to put reserves like John Wallace and
Childs into the game, the rhythm was lost. Quickly, the Spurs
capitalized and went on a 12-0 run to cut the Knicks' lead to
36-34. The Knicks turned the ball over three times in that span.
And when they doubled Duncan, he passed the ball to set up Jaren
Jackson and Mario Elie for 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Knicks, perhaps because they had been the aggressors,
got the benefit of a key call with 4:41 remaining and their lead
down to 42-41. It appeared Sprewell bumped Robinson out of the way
on a reverse layup attempt. But Referee Hugh Evans saw it
differently and slapped Robinson with his third foul.
</P>
<P>
   A livid Spurs Coach Gregg Popovich went storming up the sideline
and was hit with a technical foul. After the free throw for the
technical, plus the two free throws by Sprewell, the Knicks grabbed
a 4-point lead and crushed the Spurs' momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks plodded ahead from there and ended the first half
with an exclamation mark. After a steal by Wallace, Childs came
streaking up the court, pulled up from 26 feet and knocked down a
3-pointer at the buzzer to give them a 54-47 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Their plan to attack the Spurs' big men was working, even though
the Spurs were shooting 51.2 percent. By the end of the half, the
Knicks had gone to the free-throw line 16 times, while the Spurs
had just four attempts.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sprewell guiding the way. He was masterminding the
Knicks' plan on every level _ coming up with four assists and six
rebounds to go with his 16 first-half points _ while providing
inspiration with his hustle.
</P>
<P>
   He did not let down in the third quarter. He picked up two quick
assists, including a slick feed to Johnson for a layup, and had the
Knicks up 64-52 with eight minutes left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's unselfishness was contagious. Ewing got into the act
of giving when he drove through the lane and spotted Houston wide
open on the perimeter. In midstride, Ewing flung the ball outside.
And as the crowd cheered the unselfishness, Houston lived up to
their excitement by drilling the 3-pointer. One possession later,
Houston made another 3-pointer and gave the Knicks a 71-55 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The evening crowd could not help but be impressed and cheered
wildly as the Spurs were forced to take another timeout to stop the
bleeding. The Knicks' lead ballooned to 17 points after another
assist from Sprewell and some tough defense by Johnson on Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs had their pride, and the Knicks had a couple of
sloppy moments. Those lapses gave the Spurs a chance to cut the
Knicks' lead to 79-67 entering the fourth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
