<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNCLAIMED-FUNDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME OFFICIALS SAY THEY CAN'T GIVE AWAY UNCLAIMED FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ While thousands of folks hound the Kansas Revenue
Department for their income tax refunds, some people turn up their
noses at huge checks another state agency has waiting for them.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being told that the state holds a big chunk of your
money, perhaps hundreds of thousands of dollars, but refusing to
accept it, even after the state has tracked you down and told you
it's available.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Wilson, a former Johnson County state representative who
runs the unclaimed property operation for state Treasurer Tim
Shallenburger, shakes his head at it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people on one hand who can't get it fast enough, and
others, when you have it in hand, you can't give it to them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's program in the treasurer's office is charged with
returning as much as $80 million to about 375,000 missing owners.
Last year, $5.8 million was returned.
</P>
<P>
   It's like being a debt collector in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   He finds people and tries to return money to them that has been
held in bank accounts, stocks, bonds, insurance policies and even
utility deposits that are considered abandoned. When the owners
can't be found, the money is given to the state treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Wilson about returning big-time amounts and he'll quickly
come up with a handful of stories. He says he can't release
information that would allow the potential recipients to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of a person whose name was culled from the
unclaimed property records last March. The person was tracked down
and letters were sent urging the person to make a claim, but Wilson
has heard nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Shallenburger and I could not raise the person on the
phone. We went to the person's door and knocked on the door,''
Wilson said. ``The person came to the door without opening it and
said, `Who is it? What do you want?'''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he explained that a number of letters had been sent
and there had been no response. Did you know, Wilson asked the
person, that there is $224,000 in unclaimed property in your name?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do,'' the person said. ``Go away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day,'' Wilson said, ``we have not heard from this
person.''
</P>
<P>
   In another case, Wilson traced someone entitled to $255,000 from
the unclaimed property account, but found that the person had moved
to Georgia. Unclaimed property authorities there said they were
trying to give the same person $2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The person moved again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent two registered letters to the home,'' Wilson said.
``That's been seven months ago, and the person's not collected or
had anything to do with me.''
</P>
<P>
   He's had the same luck trying to reunite people with two claims
of $65,000 each and with one of $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the Missouri treasurer's office, officials in the unclaimed
property section used to be baffled by the refusal of people to
accept money owed to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not anymore,'' said Monica Boone, a spokeswoman. ``I
usually send them a claim form and say it's up to them whether they
send it back or not. There's not a thing we can do if they don't
want their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri is holding about $135 million worth of unclaimed
property owned by more than 900,000 individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in both states say they don't know why some people are
unwilling to accept such large amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, of course, turns down the windfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson returned about $145,000 to an individual who had no idea
the cash was waiting from an old real estate deal and some old
shares of stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable. This is unbelievable service because I
had no idea that either one of those existed,'' the person told
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The largest I've actually given away since I've been here is
$405,000,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Checks in the range of $50,000 or $60,000 aren't that unusual.
Wilson has one case worth more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson routinely writes letters explaining that he may have
missing money for a person. He makes phone calls, sometimes
multiple calls. He's like a persistent salesman trying to close the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   What does he think about when he's standing on a stranger's
porch?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I worry about is my safety,'' he said.
``People are pretty jumpy about opening the door for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he tries to persuade people that he is really from the
treasurer's office, that he's not selling something or trying to
scam someone.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, he has been fairly successful at returning money to
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one function of government that is good,'' he said.
``This is one function of government that works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
