<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRAC-RECORDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 U.S. HIGH SCHOOL RECORDS SET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM J. MILLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three United States high school records were set, and
Shalane Flanagan and Damion Drummond lost in upsets Sunday in the
final day of the New Balance National Scholastic Indoor
Championships at the Armory Track and Field Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The national records were registered by Brooklyn's Boys and
Girls High School in the girls' 4x800-meterrelay in 9 minutes 7.57
seconds; Leevan Sands of Melbourne, Fla., in the boys' triple jump
at 52 feet 8 inches; and Sanya Richards of Pembroke Pines, Fla., in
the girls' 200 in 23.64 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, a 15-year-old sophomore, also won the 60 in 7.43 in
her first career indoor meet. Sands, a senior, also took the long
jump Saturday at 24-3}.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan, one of the top milers, from Marblehead, Mass., was
leading in the mile Sunday until five meters from the finish, when
Emily Kroshus of Calgary, Alberta, came on to nip her at the tape
in 4:46.79, just 12-hundredths of a second ahead. The two seniors
will meet again next week in Portugal at the world junior
cross-country championships.
</P>
<P>
   Kroshus, a 5-foot-6-inch, 120-pound smooth-striding runner who
has trained 80 miles a week for the cross-country meet with little
speed work, returned to the track 90 minutes after the mile Sunday
and destroyed the competition in the two-mile run with a sparkling
10:09.36, winning by more than 100 meters. She had splits of 5:02
for one mile and 9:32 at the 3,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Drummond, a senior at Brooklyn's Paul Robeson High, took the
lead in the 800 and held it until Paul Joyce, a senior at Rockland
County's Clarkstown South, put on a blistering kick over the final
80 meters to win in 1:52.23, with Drummond second in 1:53.39. Joyce
had defeated Drummond in the 800 in the Eastern States meet two
weeks ago in a national-leading time of 1:51.96.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Thomas, a senior at Northwest High School in Burtonville,
Md., put on gritty winning performances in the 60 and the 60 high
hurdles. Suffering since January from a badly sprained left ankle
that had curtailed his training, he won the 60 dash in 6.73, which
came as no surprise since he is one of the best in the country at
the sprint. But he raised eyebrows with his hurdles victory, in
7.92, which came 10 minutes after his dash victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the meet officials Monday and asked if I could be in
the hurdles even though I hadn't hurdled since outdoor season last
year,'' the 6-1, 180-pound Thomas said. ``I just wanted to see if I
could do something in the hurdles.'' He ran two races in each of
these events before the finals Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Other outstanding performances Sunday in boys' events were
recorded by Carlos Bedoya of White Plains, N.Y., in the 200
(21.44); Jonte Buhl of Austin, Tex., in the 400 (47.78); Justin
Romaniuk of Suffern, N.Y., in the mile (4:14.09); Camden, N.J., in
the 4x200 relay (1:28.81); Lenape, N.J., in the 4x400 relay
(3:16.40); and Joshua McCaughey of West Kingston, R.I., in the
25-pound weight throw at 78-8\.
</P>
<P>
   Notable winners in girls' events included Priscilla Lopes of
Whitby, Ontario, in the 60 hurdles (8.29); William Penn of
Philadelphia in the 4x400 relay (3:50.82); and Berkeley of
California in the 4x200 relay (1:38.73).
</P>
</TEXT>
