<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-SCHEDULING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOCK SCHEDULING IN SCHOOLS GAINS POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ERICA WOOD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kay Lunsford belongs to the old guard.
</P>
<P>
   The former head of the North Kansas City High School English
department was among the veteran teachers who fought to stop the
school from going to longer class periods in the fall of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But Lunsford, now the writing-lab manager, has since joined the
parade of administrators, teachers and students who praise what is
known as block scheduling. Though some districts balk at the
format, the concept has steadily gained popularity in the last
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Lunsford said the change had forced her to become aware of
different learning styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to stop being the great purveyor of education,''
Lunsford said. ``My kids told me it wasn't going to work for me to
talk to them for 85 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Several variations of block scheduling exist, but most schools
use modified versions of the straight ``4//4'' block or the
alternating ``A//B'' model.
</P>
<P>
   On the straight block, classes meet every day, and students do a
school year's worth of work in a semester.
</P>
<P>
   The other version alternates two daily schedules, so that four
classes meet on the ``A'' day and four on the following ``B'' day.
Students take eight courses each semester.
</P>
<P>
   The A//B model is the most popular.
</P>
<P>
   Area schools from Independence to Kansas City, Kan., have
switched to the longer periods. Others, such as Center and Shawnee
Mission South, aren't convinced block scheduling is the best
method.
</P>
<P>
   They've stuck with the more traditional schedule, which
encompasses six to eight class periods daily, each lasting 45 to 50
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Though studies have reported conflicting results on the academic
benefits, block scheduling appears to be more than a fad.
</P>
<P>
   Jim King, executive director of the Missouri Association of
Secondary School Principals, said he knew of no Missouri schools
that had tried the block format and then reverted to the
traditional schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, a 1997 survey of 77 percent of Virginia schools
found block scheduling had created a more relaxed environment that
had resulted in fewer discipline referrals and improved teacher
morale.
</P>
<P>
   Area school officials and students say teachers now have more
time to go in-depth than with the traditional schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been extremely positive about it,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   North Kansas City High School was one of the area's first to
switch to the ``A//B'' schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study there showed that students now have more time to
study for tests.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Durham, school-improvement coordinator for North Kansas
City High School, said academically there hadn't been a measurable
difference. But officials have seen fewer discipline problems.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Cannon, a North Kansas City High School freshman, said that
with all the rushing around under the old format, he didn't know
how students got anything done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel as bogged down,'' Cannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Area schools have learned to compromise on the controversial
aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Math and music teachers traditionally have balked at block
scheduling. They want students in class every day, lest they forget
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin Middle School in the Hickman Mills School District solved
the problem by instituting a seminar period common to most block
formats. Seminars enable students to receive tutoring, attend club
meetings or go to assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   At Ervin, students attend their band, orchestra or choir
practice for the first 45 minutes of seminar. They attend class the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin Principal Darryl Cobb said officials found that most music
students were doing OK academically, so they didn't need the extra
help others get during seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Marching-band members at Shawnee Mission West also can work with
their teachers during seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not everybody's a fan of block scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   Visits to Shawnee Mission West and several other high schools
with block scheduling weren't enough to sell the program to Shawnee
Mission South's faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Principal Corky Jacobs said officials couldn't see where block
scheduling would benefit students, since they already had strong
test scores. A committee is studying the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Schumann, Center High School principal, said the
district's main focus was to raise test scores so that it could
regain full accreditation in the spring of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Because no proof exists that block scheduling helps that,
Schumann said, switching schedules is not a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the seminar period gives students too much freedom.
The report on North Kansas City's program suggests that many
students don't fully utilize the period.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day at North Kansas City High School, some students
practiced dance routines or received academic help. Others
congregated in the hallways, sitting or leaning against lockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (seminar) great for the one-third to one-half of students
who will take it seriously,'' King said. ``For those not really
committed to school to begin with, it provides an opportunity for
them to waste that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Each district, he said, has to look at what's best for its
students in deciding whether to switch to block scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever schedule you're on, you have to learn to live with
it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
