<HEADLINE>
UNDER HARRY'S SPELL, KIDS IN DULGE IN READ ING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY DAVE WALKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: ALSO MOVING IN THE ``A'' CATEGORY) (PHOENIX) -
Phoenix fifth-grader Tony Marino has been forbidden to read - by
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, mom Lynne Marino won't let her 11-year-old son
reread - again - any of his three Harry Potter books.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly four months until the release of the fourth book in
J.K. Rowling's mystical, magical, megaselling series, Tony has been
encouraged to explore books by other authors.
</P>
<P>
   Other Phoenix area kids, parents, librarians and booksellers are
employing a similar strategy to fill the long days between now and
July 8, when the next Potter book is expected to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, kids section staples such as Brian Jacques' Redwall
series and C.S. Lewis' Chronicles of Narnia recently have surged in
popularity around the country. In fact, sales for many Harry Potter
surrogate books have doubled or tripled in the past year. (Talk
about legs: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe - the first book
in the Narnia series - was originally published 50 years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   With proven page-turning appeal to both kids and their elders,
the three-book Potter series has sold more than 18 million copies
since its first title, Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone, was
published in September 1998 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter's most powerful magic is his ability to sell
hardcover books to 11-year-old boys. The juvenile market is
primarily a paperback business, and middle school boys don't
typically read much outside of class, preferring athletic and
electronic distractions instead.
</P>
<P>
   A Harry Potter book is ``the type of book that kids who hated to
read have just fallen in love with,'' said Marty Rice, children's
book specialist at Borders Books &AMP; Music in Phoenix. ``For some of
them, it has gotten them excited enough to start reading other
authors.''
</P>
<P>
   Local booksellers and librarians (who have been forced by
limited Potter titles to steer suddenly eager readers to alternate
authors) said they focus on a few key attributes when recommending
surrogates: fast pace, serial form and fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling's books are ``fast-moving,'' said Kitty Jazwinski,
librarian at Glendale American Elementary School. ``You never read
a chapter and say, `Oh well, nothing happened there.''
</P>
<P>
   Serials appeal to kids who identify with characters and want to
follow continuing adventures, said Joyce Dooley, librarian and
media specialist at Landmark Middle School in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   ``So often when we read a book, we don't want it to end,'' she
said. ``That's the appeal of a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students want to read them all and are quick to tell me if I'm
missing one of the books in the series.''
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy stories encourage young readers to stretch their
imaginations - sometimes too far, allege some parents who dislike
the books because of their supernatural content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter has just enough of the weirdness - the witchy
part - to make it almost naughty but not really,'' said Sue
Sjostrom, a former schoolteacher who now operates Annie's Book Stop
in Phoenix. ``There's just enough `should my kid be reading this?'
to make it that much more special and delicious for the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on prerelease orders, the Harry Potter series' fourth
installment, Harry Potter and the Doomspell Tournament, already
occupies the No. 1 slot on Internet bookseller Amazon.com's sales
list.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Marino, who has his copy of the next Harry Potter reserved
at a local bookstore, is making do till July with the Redwall
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome,'' he said. ``But it's not as good as Harry
Potter.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Dave. &QL; 
Walker(at)ArizonaRepublic.com &QL; 
or (602) 444-8625. &QL; 
 &QL; 
With nearly three months till the new Harry Potter book is
released, kids, parents, librarians and booksellers are dimming
their hunger-for-Harry gangs by exploring other books in the
juvenile-fantasy genre. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
