<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICKSON OPTIMISTIC, DESPITE BEING ROCKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Starting pitcher Jason Dickson took a one-hopper
off his left forearm, had a bat thrown at him and gave up seven
runs in 11/3 innings, but one wouldn't have known it talking to the
right-hander afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson remains optimistic because: A) the ball off his forearm
caused only a minor bruise; B) he was able to dodge the bat that
slipped out of a hitter's hands; and C) four of the seven runs he
allowed were unearned runs, a result of three errors behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson is coming back from shoulder surgery and says he feels
fine physically. His problem has been with the command of his
pitches, but he said Sunday after the Anaheim Angels' 18-9 loss to
the Mariners he was able to hit his spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here and the last time out against Oakland I was far from
perfect but I can see where it's getting back to where I want it to
be,'' Dickson said. ``I'm unhappy with the results but I'm happy
with the quality of the stuff I had today.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson is competing for a spot in the starting rotation, but in
two games is 0-2 with a 12.46 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was my first big league season you could be really
worried because you look at the numbers and say I'm not doing
well,'' Dickson said. ``But I've thrown the ball good enough to get
myself through a big league game. When you know your stuff, you
know if things are going to be fine, and that the numbers at this
point in the season don't mean that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, he had better command today and threw a lot of balls
down in the zone,'' Scioscia said. ``It was a step in the right
direction. And we gave him six outs in that first inning (because
of the errors). I think he threw a lot better than what's going to
show up in the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Edmonds, Mo Vaughn, Garret Anderson and Gary DiSarcina did
not make the 40-minute trip to Peoria, instead working out at the
club's complex in Tempe. In doing so, they missed a bad display of
defense put on by the Angels, and it wasn't just the four errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible,'' Scioscia said. ``Some plays weren't made,
they didn't throw to the right bases and those errors in the first
inning gave them extra outs. Some of it you can chalk up to spring
training, but part of it you shouldn't see at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Angels were fine, getting 13 hits. Tim Salmon
had three hits, including his team-leading third home run of the
spring, and Benji Gil, a leading candidate to win a job as a
utility player, also homered. Scott Spiezio and Larry Barnes had
two hits apiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
