<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HEAD EAST FOR IMPORTANT TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's too early to say the Los Angeles Lakers have
reached the stretch run of the season, but they are entering their
last uphill leg today as they begin an eight-day, five-game road
trip.
</P>
<P>
   It's the last extended trip of the season and their last through
the East, concluding with back-to-back games against two of that
conference's powers, New York and Miami, next Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The trip starts in Denver tonight, followed by back-to-back
games at Washington and Detroit on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson has pointed to previous road trips as
barometers, but attached no grand significance this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're out so far, the chimney sweep is coming, and the
guy that does the roofing is coming in and the cleaners are there,
etc.,'' Jackson said wryly, ``so I'm looking forward to a clean
house when I get back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, it has no more significance than when we play
New York and Miami back-to-back at the end of this thing....
Hopefully, we can surmount the Detroit, Washington games, which
will be tough enough as it is, back-to-back, to go in and have the
energy to play New York and Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the weaker opponents should present a challenge as the
Lakers try to extend a nine-game road winning streak. All but the
Wizards have impressive records at home: Denver 20-12, Washington
13-19, Detroit 22-10, New York 25-7 and Miami 23-6.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, the Lakers would fly home from Denver tonight, then
leave for D.C. on Wednesday, but Jackson said the quick turnaround
and long flight East would make it impossible to hold practices in
L.A. (they'll practice twice in Denver instead).
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson, who once took his Chicago Bulls to the Statue of
Liberty for some team-building, also considered taking the Lakers
on a field trip in D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had the scheduling to do all over again,'' he said,
``but I couldn't get the plane to reroute and get us on to
Washington, because we could have done something in Washington....
I was going to play that by ear, but that went by the wayside about
two weeks ago, when it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   By George: Jackson indicated he wants to give little-used rookie
swingman Devean George a longer look over the last month and a half
of the season, figuring he might provide an added dimension in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great 3-point shooting threat and is going to get, I
think, some major time down the stretch before the playoffs start,
so he can get ready to play more minutes,'' Jackson said. ``I'm
looing for time that's important time, not just time that's at the
end of the game.... I definitely think he's got a chance to help
us. I like to have shooters in at the end of quarters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
