<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-12 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4997 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN     03-12 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE CAN NOW REST EASY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Some of the Pepperdine players passed time
Sunday afternoon playing dominoes on a patio overlooking the
Pacific Ocean. Others nervously munched on food inside the home of
Dr. Andy Benton, the school's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves were at Benton's home to watch the NCAA Tournament
selection show and finally learn whether they were one of the 35
teams earning at-large berths.
</P>
<P>
   They kept saying they were confident they belonged in the field
of 64, that the selection committee felt the same way. But until
they knew for sure, well, these were anxious moments.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Waves' long wait - it began last Monday after a
69-65 loss to Gonzaga in the West Coast Conference final - came to
a swift, happy conclusion when they learned they were an 11th seed
in the East Region, the first region announced. Pepperdine (24-8)
opens against sixth-seed Indiana in Buffalo, N.Y., on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The moment their name scrolled across the television screen, the
Waves erupted with joy, sharing high-fives, hugs and laughs.
</P>
<P>
   The wait was over. Pepperdine was in. It was time to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always tough being on the bubble, you're never really
sure if you're going to get in or not,'' said Pepperdine guard
Craig Lewis. ``Anything can happen with the (selection) committee
while they're in the room trying to figure out who's in or not.
We're just happy we came up early, on the first bracket. That eased
a lot of stress that we had.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the stress was unwarranted. Pepperdine was on
solid ground after winning the regular-season WCC crown, then
advancing to the conference tournament final. Even though the Waves
lost in overtime, their strong nonconference schedule and wins
against Fresno State, Louisiana-Lafayette and Gonzaga were too
impressive to overlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember beating Frenso State the second game of the season
and telling the team this was an NCAA win,'' Pepperdine coach Jan
van Breda Kolff said. ``To go on the road and beat a team that's
had a good tradition like a Fresno State, in a hostile environment.
That's the type of game that's going to help us come tournament
time. We used that word (NCAA Tournament) the second game of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine was immediately back at work Sunday night, practicing
and preparing for Indiana, which finished fifth in the Big Ten,
then bowed out of the conference tournament in a 72-69 loss to
Illinois in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves don't seem too concerned with the Hoosiers' (20-8)
historic standing among the elite teams in the country. They look
forward to the challenge, but are not intimidated. Bob Knight, A.J.
Guyton and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a team like we were before, just hoping to win,''
Tommie Prince said. ``We're one of the teams looking to win and put
the program back on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Tezale Archie agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter who we played,'' Archie said. ``We played
UCLA this year, stepped into Pauley Pavilion with all that
tradition. We went to Kansas. So we're past that stage of we're
just happy to be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
